the victim of a 1983 traffic accident would not want to be kept alive in the helpless state in which she has been maintained, the woman's older sister testified at a right-to-die trial thursday
last year, the parents of 30-year-old nancy cruzan, who is in what doctors call a ``persistent vegetative state,'' sued the state to force doctors to allow her to die by removing a feeding tube from her stomach
it is the first case in missouri to address the question of whether food and water can be denied patients like ms. cruzan
assistant attorney general robert presson contends missouri law prohibits such a step. staff members at the state rehabilitation center at mount vernon said removing the feeding tube would violate their medical mission
doctors say ms. cruzan's brain stem was nearly the only part of her brain left intact after she was deprived of oxygen for several minutes after the accident
on thursday, the second day of trial in jasper county probate court, her older sister, christy white, testified that ms. cruzan was a vital, sometimes headstrong, woman who had said on at least two occasions that she would not want to live if she could not do so independently
her father, joe cruzan of carterville, said he could ``see no purpose in forcing her to go through the indignities she's going through now.''
when she has a bowel movement, they have to change her diaper,'' he said. ``i know the hospital does the best it can, but nancy drools. sometimes ... her hair will be wet, the pillow, her gown. i just feel like it's beneath her dignity to continue like this.''
lisa perrin, a nurse at the rehabilitation center who said she has seen ms. cruzan daily for the past three years, testified: ``i was trained to preserve life and i don't want to enhance death.''
dr. james c. davis, ms. cruzan's physician, said that a legal ruling would help him make a decision but that he still would hesitate to counsel the cruzan's to pursue their plan
mentally, they're going to have problems somewhere down the line that they brought about the death of their daughter,'' he said. ``and if they don't do it, they will have the same problem with her continued suffering. either way, they're going to have problems.''
the people of afghanistan continued to suffer human rights abuses at the hands of both government and rebel forces last year, according to a report by two groups that monitor human rights
the march report of the u.s. helsinki watch committee and the asia watch committee is based on a september-october fact-finding mission to pakistan, afghanistan's neighbor to the south and a base for opposition forces fighting the soviet-backed government
the report's authors said all requests to visit kabul or other cities under the government's control went unanswered
afghanistan has been the scene of some of the most serious human rights violations on record,'' the report said. ``about one-half of the country's prewar population ... is either in emigration, or internally displaced, or dead.''
the report, the committees' fourth on human rights violations in afghanistan since 1984, noted that most abuses reported previously had continued. the government is guilty of most of the abuses, it said
indiscriminate warfare in the countryside combined with totalitarian controls in the cities have brought incalculable suffering to the afghan people,'' it said
resistance groups also were accused of violations, as in previous reports
we continue to deplore the execution of prisoners of war by the resistance, often after a trial that is lacking in most aspects of what we consider due process,'' the report said
it specifically mentioned abuses by the hezb-i-islami resistance group, led by gulbaddin hekmatyar
abuses by this group seem to have become even more extreme in the past year and reportedly include politically motivated assassinations, the taking of hostages,'' the committees said
if a settlement is reached in afghanistan's civil war, the committees said, the hezb-i-islami and other groups ``guilty of gross human rights violations'' should not be given much influence in a new government
the report noted ``seemingly positive developments'' in 1987, including the government's call for refugees to return to afghanistan and amnesty declarations for thousands of prisoners
the new york-based u.s. helsinki watch committee was founded in 1979 to promote domestic and international compliance with human rights provisions of the 1975 helsinki accords
the washington-based asia watch committee was founded in 1985 to promote internationally recognized human rights in asia. both are private, non-profit groups
a page of notes jotted by president john f. kennedy during the 1962 cuban missile crisis sold for $10,000 at auction thursday
the unsigned page includes the words ``bombers'' and ``alpha-66,'' code for a group of cuban exiles who conducted commando raids on the country, said auctioneer herman darvik
at the bottom of the note is the start of a draft of a letter to soviet leader nikita khruschev, darvik said
the note, which had been owned by a private dealer, was purchased by the american museum of historical documents, a private dealer in las vegas that has a large kennedy collection, he said
other items sold thursday by herman darvik autograph auctions were a signed photograph of sitting bull, which brought $3,500; a signature of george washington clipped from a document, $2,750, and a letter from marilyn monroe to her lawyer, $1,650
a photo of air force one signed by presidents ronald reagan, richard nixon, jimmy carter and gerald ford went for $2,750, darvik said
about 35 percent of smokers die prematurely because of tobacco, the american cancer society estimates
if smokers could just think of those odds as twice as bad as those for russian roulette, they might understand how dangerous the cigarette habit really is,'' harmon eyre, national society president, said in a statement
the estimate refers to all tobacco-related causes of death, such as lung cancer and heart disease, a cancer society spokesman said
it appears in the society's new publication, ``cancer facts &amp; figures _ 1988.''
some 40 percent of male smokers and 28 percent of female smokers die prematurely, the society said
the estimate is derived from population data, and the higher percentage for men reflects the fact that men have historically smoked longer and in greater amounts than women, rather than any significant sex-based difference in risk for individual smokers, the society spokesman said
the society estimates that smoking is related to 320,000 deaths a year, including 30 percent of all cancer deaths. it blames cigarettes for 85 percent of lung cancer cases among men and 75 percent among women
among males, smokers run more than twice the rate of non-smokers for cancer death, while among women the difference is 67 percent, the society says
the society also said lung cancer remains the nation's leading cancer killer within each sex. some 152,000 new cases are expected this year, with 139,000 deaths. found</head>
the government fired the director of the treasury police after authorities found his agents in a truck believed to have been used in several recent kidnappings, authorities said friday
six of those abducted in the ``panel truck of death'' were killed, a human rights group said
the firing of oscar diaz urquizu, a former security chief for president vinicio cerezo, came after the truck was discovered by national police
army col. julio caballeros seigne, the national police director, said he and members of his personal security guard found the truck thursday parked eight miles east of the city
the six men inside were wearing treasury police uniforms, caballeros seigne said
baudilio hichos, third in command of the treasury police, arrived at the scene to try to free his men
the dispute continued at a downtown guatemala city police station, where about 100 treasury policemen arrived to defend the six. after arguing with national police for an hour, they left
interior minister juan rodil peralta announced the firing friday after meetings with heads of both security groups. he named miguel equizabal, second in command, as his interim replacement
the six treasury policemen were in custody for questioning on friday but had not been charged. their names were not disclosed
treasury police are assigned to deal with customs matters, but are said to be involved in other operations. diaz urquizu was chief of security for the campaign of cerezo, who took office jan. 14, 1986 as the first civilian president since 1970
the mutual support group, an organization of relatives of people who disappeared in political violence, says six of nine people known to have been abducted this year by men using a white panel truck with darkly tinted glass were killed
three others were released, said herlindo hicho, a spokesman for the group
it called the vehicle ``the panel truck of death.'' authorities had said for several weeks that they were looking for the truck and had seized or stopped several of the same description
police said they believed the truck stopped friday night was the one they had been seeking
the number of disappearances and political killings in guatemala has declined from the early 1980s when there were as many as 500 killings a month, but cases continue to occur
left-wing insurgents have been fighting the government sporadically for 25 years. report arafat also rejects u.s. plan. pick up 12th graf: in cairo ...</note>
prime minister yitzhak shamir on friday attacked u.s. peace proposals for the first time in public, saying they were ``fraught with danger'' and incapable of bringing peace to the region
u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz shuttled through the region last week to urge arab and israeli acceptance of the plan
the only word i agree with in the u.s. plan is the name shultz,'' shamir was quoted as saying by the israeli daily newspaper haaretz
shamir previously has criticized elements of the u.s. proposal in private meetings with party officials, but statements published friday in a series of interviews constituted his first rejection of the plan as a whole
shamir's comments on the plan were criticized by a high-ranking official in israel's left-of-center labor party, which shares power in a shaky coalition with shamir's rightist likud bloc
it would be extremely artificial if the american people hear only one unauthorized version,'' former foreign minister abba eban told israel radio
foreign minister shimon peres, shamir's rival and a leader of the labor party, supports the plan
yasser arafat, chairman of the palestine liberation organization, has rejected the u.s. plan, the new york times reported in its saturday editions. it said that in an interview thursday in tunis, tunisia, where the plo has its headquarters, arafat said the plo would no longer settle for indirect representation through a joint jordanian-palestinian delegation as suggested by shultz
earlier this week, arafat's fatah branch of the plo had criticized the u.s. plan
israel and the united states consider the plo a terrorist organization. israel has declared it will never negotiate with the plo but would consider talks with a combined delegation of jordanians and non-plo palestinians
in cairo, president hosni mubarak of egypt and jordan's king hussein said friday that shamir would pit himself against world opinion if he rejects the u.s. peace plan
i don't think that this (shamir's comments) will lead to a comprehensive settlement or a comprehensive peace which is very important for the whole area and the whole world,'' mubarak told reporters after a 3{-hour meeting with the jordanian leader
i agree,'' hussein said
shultz has requested an israeli decision on the plan by the time shamir arrives in washington on monday and has publicly complained that both the arabs and the israelis are unwilling to compromise
the plan calls for israel to give up land in the occupied west bank and gaza strip in exchange for peace in the region
shamir said he was particularly disturbed by the part of the u.s. proposal that calls for kicking off direct negotiations with an international conference
that, he told the english-language jerusalem post, ``obligates me to resist ... with all my power. and my power to resist is very great.''
he said the united states had changed its position on the convening of such a conference without reason and he warned the proposal was ``fraught with danger.''
shamir told haaretz that while the united states is undeniably a friend to israel, ``every bit of it (the u.s. plan) was an attempt to satisfy the arabs.''
the right-wing leader has twice blocked cabinet votes on whether israel should approve the plan
the issue is expected to come up a final time before the shamir trip during a cabinet meeting sunday
eban, a member of peres' labor party, announced friday he would travel to the united states hours before shamir to explain labor's position on the peace plan to the americans
the fact is that mr. shamir did not get any authorization to refuse the peace plan. no parliament, and no cabinet agreed to this refusal,'' eban said on israel radio
speaking on israel radio, shamir said he would explain to shultz ``that his plan, as it is seen today, can't solve the problem of peace in our area and can't guarantee the safety and security of the state of israel.''
despite shamir's tough stand, u.s. officials are still hopeful that shultz and reagan may be able to persuade the prime minister to change his mind, diplomatic sources said
shamir, however, stressed that he will bring the americans his own suggestions on how to make the plan more acceptable
this paper (the plan) given to us is not moses' commandments from mt. sinai,'' shamir said on the radio
shamir aide yossi ahimeir told the associated press the prime minister would suggest implementing palestinian self-rule in the territories on a step-by-step basis, testing the idea in a single city, for example
in addition, the prime minister will suggest that instead of an international conference, peace talks be held under soviet-american auspices, ahimeir said
finally, ahimeir said, the prime minister wants a more flexible timetable than that sought by washington, which has called for starting talks on an interim solution in the territories by may and opening negotiations on the final status of the west bank and gaza by december
shamir wants to delay talks on the final status until self-rule is implemented throughout the territories, his aide said
japan's latest comic book heros are emperor hirohito and former prime minister yasuhiro nakasone
comic books, widely read in japan by both children and adults, often are used as teaching aids for such topics as history, economics or etiquette and even to explain frictions with the united states over trade
the hirohito comic book, which is in hard cover and is titled ``tenno heika'' (emperor), follows the 86-year-old monarch from childhood through world war ii, including his historic surrender broadcast in 1945, and into his quiet retirement in tokyo's imperial palace
the book on nakasone is called ``yatchan's,'' which was the former prime minister's childhood nickname. it is published quarterly by nakasone's office and sent to supporters and constituents
japanese prime ministers, once they step down, traditionally fade into the political background and take the role of party elder, occasionally seen but seldom heard
but nakasone, whose term in office ended this past november, has stayed in the news through trips abroad and the establishment of a think-tank group. ``yatchan's'' helps keep attention focused on him
the idea for a cartoon newsletter has been gestating for a long time, and it just happens that it was produced after nakasone-san left office,'' said masaki donji, a private secretary to nakasone. ``there was no deliberate timing to keep him in the news.''
while purporting to depict faithfully the characters' lives and careers, the comic books seem overly flattering
hirohito is shown as barrel-chested and cheerful rather than the aged and stooped man he is now
nakasone, now 67, is shown as burly, with round eyes and a uncharacteristic full head of hair
but the comic book presents little-known facets of nakasone's life
an essay by nakasone's wife tsutako says that, in his younger days when he was known as yatchan, nakasone pranced about in his underwear after baths, humming music from swan lake. and on state visits abroad as prime minister, he grudgingly allowed his wife off elevators first, but upon returning to japanese soil, would instantly declare, ``ladies first is over.''
yatchan's'' opens with nakasone's return from the 1987 summit in venice, italy, with photos of the six in-flight meals he was served on his special jet. it then flashes back to the beginning: a fiery-eyed nakasone resigning from tokyo's metropolitan police department in 1946 to work toward japan's postwar reconstruction
he reveals himself as an idealist who patterns himself after sakura sogo, a 17th-century village headman who was executed for seeking reduced taxes for poor peasants
he eats potatoes for lunch _ an expression of humility _ and chooses a white bicycle for his first political campaign because hirohito rode a white horse
subscriptions to ``yatchan's'' are 2,000 yen ($15.50) a year. the booklet also includes reproductions of nakasone's paintings, and samples of his haiku poetry
the hirohito book divulges some imperial trivia: the emperor has no surname, reached adulthood at age 18 (20 for ordinary japanese), and cannot adopt children or vote
it also explains that his duties include opening sessions of the diet (parliament), closing sessions of the house of representatives, receiving foreign ambassadors, and formally approving laws, government decrees, amendments to the constitution and treaties
hirohito, once regarded as a living god, remains a sensitive subject in modern japan, and ribbing of royalty by the press is neither tolerated nor attempted
but the comic book touches on some sensitive points in the emperor's life, including an assassination attempt, the great kanto earthquake of 1923 for which hirohito was later criticized for not doing enough for his people, and a 1936 military rebellion that led to the death of one of his favored ministers
it also touches briefly on his role in world war ii, although it reveals little about his activities or motivations during the conflict, and portrays hirohito's famed speech imploring the nation in august 1945 to bear the unbearable _ surrender
the emperor's trips to europe and the united states are shown, including protesters waving signs saying ``go home'' and ``fascist hirohito.'' it ends with him enjoying his favorite pastimes, walking along the beach and studying marine biology
an official of the imperial household agency, which tends to the imperial family's duties and needs, said the agency had nothing to do with the comic book and extended neither approval or assistance in its production
graffiti, the ubiquitous writing that is spray-painted on mosques, schools and shops, is a guide to political happenings in the occupied west bank and gaza strip
from the mount of olives in jerusalem to the farmlands of gaza, the walls are a bulletin board for political groups to proclaim their ideologies and issue public appeals
let the gaza strip be in flames for shultz,'' said a wall in gaza city shortly before the recent middle east shuttle of secretary of state george p. shultz
a slogan in black paint on the wall of the beit al may refugee camp in the west bank declared: ``disgrace will face collaborators. glory to our heroic martyrs.''
it was signed by the united national leadership of the uprising, a name used by supporters of yasser arafat's palestine liberation organization
a more religious tone was struck nearby: ``paradise for our martyrs'' and ``god is great. victory to islam.''
this was signed by hamas, arabic for zeal, the signature of the moslem brotherhood, a fundamentalist sunni moslem group that opposes plo support for a negotiated settlement
islam is the solution and the alternative,'' said a slogan signed by the ``islamic resistance,'' also believed to be the work of moslem brothers
other wall decorations in the occupied territories were signed by ``shaabiya,'' george habash's popular front for the liberation of palestine, and ``democratia,'' nayef hawatmeh's democratic front for the liberation of palestine
one was the work of supporters of abul abbas, the mastermind of the hijacking of the italian cruise ship achille lauro in 1985
on the mount of olives, a wall declared, ``palestinian-arab solidarity lives on.''
this slogan, possibly written by supporters of jordan, is a rarity because sentiment in the west bank and gaza has been strongly against arab states
the feeling is that arab states have failed to support the rebellion against israeli occupation and some, notably jordan, fear that the revolutionary fervor will cross its borders
as a result, slogans supporting syria, damascus-based palestinian groups and jordan's king hussein, are noticeably absent
in gaza city, residents of the well-to-do ramali neighborhood were chastized by a piece of graffito scrawled on the mosque in palestine square: ``courage to the people of the ramali quarter,'' it said, mocking the inaction of the middle class
some wall-writing has called for specific action, such as ones in gaza that demanded the resignation of arab tax collectors and arab police officers
arab employes of the income tax and value added department must resign. otherwise we will,'' said the chilling warning in downtown gaza city
forty taxmen quit their jobs as directed and new graffiti written in blue spray paint replaced the old: ``yes, yes for the step taken by our honorable brothers in resigning from the tax department ... and yes to the resignation of the police.''
moderates have also come in for a pounding on the walls, which tend to reflect more hardline views. ``down with hanna siniora and fayez abu rahme,'' declared a slogan attacking the two palestinians who met with shultz in washington last month
israel's army has periodically tried to censor the wall writing
in nablus, a reporter saw arab prisoners watched by armed israeli soldiers using black paint to blot out slogans such as ``death to israel'' written in red on the metal shutters of shops
the political graffiti has also spread to israel, where the division between left and right is played out on the walls of the beachfront ``tayellet,'' or promenade in tel aviv
arabs: go to the arab world,'' said one declaration, reflecting the extreme right-wing view that arabs should leave israeli-held territory
enough of the occupation,'' countered another, reflecting the left-wing viewpoint that israel should withdraw from the west bank and gaza strip
the discovery in spain of a car bomb destined for gibraltar was a relief to the british government, helping ease political embarrassment by proving a tragedy had been averted by the killing of three unarmed ira members
thwarting the irish republican army operation in the british colony through pooled british, irish and spanish intelligence was a triumph for international cooperation against terrorism, but the circumstances raised questions:
was it necessary to shoot the guerrillas dead when they were unarmed? why did britain wait 24 hours to declare the falsity of official reports that a car bomb already had been parked at the gibraltar governor's residence?
the guerrillas were shot sunday. on tuesday, spanish police found a car laden with explosives in a parking lot at marbella, a resort about 45 miles up the coast of southern spain from the fortress colony
prime minister margaret thatcher's supporters said the discovery vindicated the army in the shootings
i am delighted,'' said lawmaker ivor stanbrook, who heads a parliament committee on nothern ireland. ``this confirms all the evidence which showed that the actions of the british security services were absolutely justified.''
two men and a woman were shot down at midday sunday as they walked from a car they had parked at the governor's residence, called the convent. a public changing of the guard ceremony was scheduled for tuesday morning, involving a british army unit just transferred from northern ireland
men dressed in jeans did the shooting, and were said to be members of the elite special air services undercover unit. the sas has been involved in several operations against the outlawed ira, a mainly roman catholic group fighting to drive the british from protestant-dominated northern ireland
protests came from the irish republic and from inside britain
the mass-circulation press backed mrs. thatcher but the daily telegraph, usually pro-government in irish matters, said britain should ``give ill-wishers no further grounds to suggest that the authorities operate a `shoot-to-kill' policy against terrorists.''
in dublin, the respected irish times commented: ``there is emerging a profound difference between british and irish attitudes on the proper response which is demanded by terrorism.''
immediately after the shootings, spanish police and british officials in gibraltar spoke of a ``gun battle'' and a ``car bomb.''
then the ira said early monday the slain trio were in gibraltar ``on active service,'' reinforcing britain's contention that the bomb was in place
britain's armed forces minister, ian stanley, described the car parked near the governor's residence as a ``car bomb'' and british press reports spoke of hundreds of pounds of explosives
not until monday afternoon did sir geoffrey howe, the foreign secretary, tell a surprised house of commons there were no explosives in the car and police were searching for another vehicle
official british sources say confusion arose because of assumptions based on spanish intelligence and underlined by the ira reference to ``active service.''
why the immediate resort to gunfire? the response was that security forces could not be sure the guerrillas were not armed
reporters in london were told mairead farrell, an ira veteran, ``fumbled in her handbag,'' and ``could have been going for a gun, for some explosive device, anything.''
on tuesday, the irish government said it was ``gravely perturbed'' that unarmed irish people ``should have been shot dead ... when it appears they could have been arrested.''
this enraged british officials and one said privately: ``a lot of british people are beginning to wonder if they (the irish) are serious about combating terrorism.''
british officials said the 145 pounds of explosives packed into the car found at marbella, timed to explode during the military ceremony tuesday, could have killed more than 100 people. the guerrillas apparently parked the first vehicle to secure a space for the car bomb when arrived later
the shooting came at an awkward moment in anglo-irish relations
tensions arose in january when britain announced it would not prosecute northern ireland police officers involved in killing six roman catholics, five of them guerrillas but unarmed, in three incidents at the end of 1982
those shootings had ``remarkable similarities'' to that in gibraltar, the irish times said
soon after the government announcement, a british soldier in a watchtower shot an unarmed catholic civilian dead at a checkpoint on the irish border. the soldier, who is in custody, said it was an accident but the irish government ordered its own inquiry
eastern airlines says it will appeal a contempt-of-court citation imposed by a judge who ruled that plans to transfer the airlines' shuttle operations to a new corporate entity violate a 1987 injunction
u.s. district judge john h. pratt ruled thursday that the miami-based airline was in contempt of his july 2, 1987 order that it maintain the status quo in working conditions for 12,000 employees represented by the international association of machinists and aerospace workers
although the preliminary injunction issued last summer dealt with a separate labor dispute, pratt said his order also applied to any plans to change the working conditions of union workers that would create a major dispute as defined by the railway labor act
the judge scheduled a march 18 hearing to determine what sanctions to impose against eastern. the judge could impose a daily fine to force eastern to halt its plans to transfer the shuttle to a new corporate entity under its parent, texas air corp
in a complicated financial deal announced last month, texas air will purchase the shuttle operation for $225 million. the federal aviation administration must approve the transaction and give an operating certificate to the new operator to take over the shuttle, which operates between washington, new york and boston
airline spokesman robin matell said ``eastern's view is that the court's ruling is incorrect and we intend to file an expedited appeal in the u.s. court of appeals for the district of columbia. we are confident the court will rule in our favor.''
the union, meanwhile, said in a statement that ``the court's order today sends a message to texas air that it is not above the law and it too must comply with the railway labor act.''
pratt found that the ``proposed transfer to texas air significantly changes the working conditions of iam members.''
we find that the proposed `spin off' of eastern's air shuttle operations to the new air shuttle is not fundamentally different from the proposed `spin off' of eastern's fleet services employees to air ground services,'' the judge's opinion said
that spinoff, which was barred last summer, involved plans to transfer ground crews and baggage handlers to a new subsidiary called air ground services inc
eastern's serious financial problems ``do not change the fact that it proposed a `spin off' of the air shuttle ... is in clear violation of our july 2, 1987 order, which, whatever doubts eastern had as to its meaning and application, it made no attempt to have clarified or modified,'' the judge said
the judge noted that eastern announced the deal a day after it dropped its appeal of the preliminary injunction in the air ground case
pratt accepted the union's contention that spinning off the air shuttle could undermine the machinists' bargaining position with the company. if fewer than 50 percent of the air shuttle's employees opt to join the iam, machinists who transferred to the new subsidiary from eastern would be without union representation, the judge noted
the decision is the latest in a series of complicated and often bitter legal fights eastern is having with its union
in a separate action, the air line pilots association is trying to bar eastern from contracting with an air freight hauler to train pilots to operate the company's planes in the event of a strike this spring
the pilots' union has asked another federal judge here to issue a temporary restraining order to prevent the use of eastern aircraft by orion air inc
so far, one plane has been leased to orion to train pilots who would fly eastern aircraft in the event the pilots honor a strike by the machinists union, according to court testimony. the union contends this arrangement circumvents the labor contract that specifies that only its members can operate eastern planes
eastern contends that the labor agreement does not prevent it from leasing its aircraft to other companies
president reagan has released a symbolic wish list of projects he wants congress to strike from its spending plan, but there appears little chance capitol hill will pay much attention
james c. miller iii, director of the office of management and budget, said that if the list were adopted the savings for fiscal 1988 alone would amount to $1.15 billion
miller, who released the list thursday, said the money saved could be used either to reduce the deficit or pay for more meaningful projects
the items were included in the $600 billion catch-all spending bill approved at the end of last year's congressional session
i'm hopeful congress will respond to it,'' miller said when asked whether the cuts had any chance of gaining congressional attention
the list, which has no legal power, has no effect unless congress moves to adopt it. the president's request was not in the form of legislation and even when he has made such requests formally, they have received little support in congress
reagan's effort appears to fall short of the pledge he made in his state of the union address in january
in his speech, reagan repeated his longstanding request for the line-item veto, which would allow him to delete specific items from congress' spending bills
in lieu of such power, reagan said he intended to send back to congress, ``in 30 days ... those items, as rescissions, which if i had the authority to line them out, i would do so.''
instead of sending the formal rescissions to congress, reagan sent the informal list
miller explained that the president decided not to send the formal rescission list because many members of congress had argued such an action would upset the bipartisan agreement on the budget reached last year by the white house and congress
this is not an ordinary year,'' miller said, referring to the lengthy negotiations that produced the budget agreement
gop sources on capitol hill, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the strategy was adopted to avoid election-year clashes with republican lawmakers who won spending projects for their home districts last year
in proposing a formal rescission, reagan freezes spending on those items for 45 days and gives procedural advantages to those in congress supporting the effort. after the 45-day period, the spending would be restored unless the rescissions were approved
in his 46-page informal list, reagan cited a myriad of projects from around the country, including the construction of a ski lift in idaho, 15 building projects at universities or medical schools and even a program to establish a fund to preserve lighthouses
sen. james mcclure, r-idaho, won approval for $6.4 million for a kellogg, idaho, gondola in the $600 billion spending bill approved late last year. the money was in appropriations for a forest service program that is supposed to pay for development and management of forests
the 15 construction projects included $4 million for a cancer research center at the medical university of south carolina and $7.5 million for a pediatric research center at the children's hospital of pittsburgh
the list also included historic preservation grants with the national park service that would establish a bicentennial lighthouse fund to distribute matching grants for the preservation of lighthouses. the list did not give an exact amount for the item, saying only that it amounted to ``less than $50,000.''
army bases across the country are running out of tuition assistance funds for soldiers because of a $30 million cut in the army's education budget, according to college groups
the army has put new restrictions on its tuition assistance, which helped 188,000 soldiers and officers pay for college and graduate school last year
allan w. ostar, president of the american association of state colleges and universities, said the cutbacks ``will have a direct impact on thousands of individuals who want to take college classes.''
it will only hurt us all if individuals enlisted in the army do not have the opportunity to get the education they need,'' he said
frank mensel, vice president of federal relations for the american association of community and junior colleges, said the army has shifted ``education funds into recruiting.''
lt. col. greg rixon, an army spokesman, said the cutbacks were triggered by pentagon budget reductions that congress and the reagan administration recently ordered to hold down the federal deficit
the education budget was cut to $96.6 million. originally, $35 million of the army's $126 million education budget for fiscal 1988 was targeted for tuition assistance
rixon said army's personnel chief did have the option ``to move money around'' among his education, civilian training and recruiting accounts, ``but there was a relatively uniform reduction across the board.''
the college groups are lobbying to get at least $11 million restored for tuition assistance. even at that level, ostar said, ``a number of programs would still come to a grinding halt, but at least it is a more realistic and equitable approach to budget reduction.'''
the army has requested a total education budget of $104 million for fiscal 1989, which starts oct. 1
many soldiers pursue their college or graduate studies at state campuses and community colleges near military bases
the army once covered 90 percent of a g.i.'s cost of taking classes. rixon said it now pays 75 percent of tuition costs, up to $80 a semester hour for undergraduate study and $165 for graduate study
he said area commanders are being allowed to tailor the program to meet their local needs
but the army has ruled out providing tuition assistance for soldiers who are entitled to vietnam-era g.i. bill benefits for college, and it will not pay for a degree that is lower or lateral to one a soldier already has
in general, subject to the area commanders' discretion, the army is not paying any tuition for lieutenant colonels or above, or paying for graduate school for enlisted soldiers or warrant officers, rixon said
this is one of a series of periodic reports on how the u.s. presidential election campaign is viewed abroad
while vice president george bush is drawing most of the comment in the foreign press after his super tuesday victories, the showing of democrat jesse jackson also is attracting attention. this is what commentators abroad had to say about jackson and bush:
_basler zeitung of basel (independent): ``there is only one charismatic personality among the candidates and his triumph will resound longest after this super tuesday: jesse jackson has pushed open doors in the `deep south' that can never be closed again. even if _ as is expected _ he will be neither nominated nor become a candidate for vice president, he has changed fundamentally the political world for america's blacks.''
_xinhua news agency (government): ``jackson, the only black candidate, has the least campaign funds. his influence, however, has increased greatly compared with his campaign in 1984, when he won only one state in the south. this time he got five southern states on tuesday. ... it is obvious that the american people are not as open-minded as to select a black to be their president. it is also impossible for the democratic party to nominate a black as its candidate for the presidency.''
_the independent of london (independent): ``the rejection of the rev. pat robertson as a serious presidential candidate in tuesday's republican primaries was cheering news, while the relative success of the rev. jesse jackson in the democratic race engenders a more ambiguous mood. neither man's foreign policy inspires confidence. but their styles, in a campaign which is being fought almost entirely on domestic issues, are very different. mr. robertson looks inward while mr. jackson, for all his faults, reaches out. . .. mr. jackson ... is a serious figure in a way that mr. robertson is not.''
_the financial times of london (independent): the ... assumption, on the democratic side, is that the rev. jesse jackson remains a containable political force. ... in policy terms, mr. jackson is of the left of the democratic party, and on super tuesday better aggregate, if not individual, results were achieved by gov. michael dukakis and sen. albert gore, very much men of the middle.''
_politiken of copenhagen (liberal): ``like a second muhammad ali before a title fight the otherwise colorless george bush has declared himself as the next president of the united states. ... he is a conservative pragmatist _ some would say, an opportunist _ without strong views
as far as foreign policy goes he is clearly the most experienced of all the candidates. if he becomes president, one can expect a continuation of recent years' improvement in american-soviet relations as well as foreign trade policies of a more liberal sort that certain young turks among the democrats have avowed.''
_the guardian (liberal): ``bush ... has the money and the machine to cover the country. in some parts of america _ like the south _ they like the continuity with ronald reagan that the vice president seems to offer. better the devil you've seen around a lot. ... but no one, examining the attitude and exit polls from the south, should too blithely assume that old george has roses all the way to next november's real vote. he still isn't seen as much of a leader by four-fifths of those who chose him. his views are regarded as fuzzy; his trustiness is much in question.''
_the daily telegraph of london (conservative): ``at this early stage in the process by which america selects a president, vice president george bush looks the most likely republican contender. . .. the prospect of mr. bush securing the final nomination is held in some quarters to be good news for the democrats; he carries handicaps as well as the aura of the vice presidency
_der bund of bern (right of center): ``bush takes the floor as the administrator of the estate left by reagan whose economic policy appears to be successful to many americans despite the enormous increase of the debt burden. the whole thing recalls the well-orchestrated campaign by mondale in 1984 who won the nomination without new ideas, without emotional appeal to the voters, only to be badly beaten by reagan.''
_la suisse of geneva (independent): ``from now on, the possibility of george bush becoming president must be regarded as a serious possibility. against a democratic party from which genuine contenders _ if there are any _ have not yet emerged, the race seems almost easy for the vice president. the `super tuesday' mountain has given birth to a mouse, and that one is feared to be rather mousy.''
comedian george burns may be 92, but it's not slowing him down _ he's doing stand-up routines at casinos, has just finished a movie and is working on a new book
there isn't anything i can't do now that i couldn't do when i was 18 _ which shows you how pathetic i was at 18,'' he said during a recent one-hour performance at caesars palace on the strip
burns is a regular at the palace and other caesars properties in lake tahoe, nev., and atlantic city, n.j. his new movie, ``18 again,'' opens april 9
burns' newest book is about the one true love of his life, gracie allen, his stage partner and wife of 38 years until her death in 1964
i've written six books. that's pretty good for a guy who only read two,'' he told the audience at caesars
his formula for acting?
if the director wants me to cry, i think of my sex life,'' he said. ``if the director wants me to laugh, i think of my sex life
i'd go out with women my age, but there are no women my age.''
burns smokes 15 to 20 cigars and drinks several martinis daily
what do his doctors think of that?
they're all dead.''
comedian bob newhart says he watches every episode of his ``newhart'' televison show, but not the way the average viewer would
i check to see what jokes we left out and what works and what doesn't,'' he said in an interview published in the april issue of good housekeeping
newhart, 58, said his 1978 decision to end his role as psychologist dr. bob hartley on ``the bob newhart show'' was the result of ``burnout.''
i thought we were beginning to repeat some of the situations and the jokes,'' newhart said. ``after 24 shows a year for six years, i wasn't sure where the characters were going. i was proud of the series, and didn't want to see it copying itself.''
despite the tiresome schedule of the earlier show, he said it was inevitable that he would return to tv
boxing great archie moore wants americans down for the count _ the 1990 u.s. census
people, in the black community especially, have not been counted,'' moore, 74, said at a u.s. census bureau open house thursday. ``count your people. stand up and be counted.''
he said young people ought to help the census so people ``can benefit from the programs in washington they are eligible for.''
st. louis, one of three areas across the nation selected for a 1990 census dress rehearsal this month, was moore's boyhood home and the place where he won the light-heavyweight boxing championship in 1952
moore held the title until it was vacated in 1961. he failed twice to win the heavyweight crown, losing to rocky marciano and floyd patterson, but compiled a 183-22-9 career record including 129 knockouts. he now lives in san diego
broadway star chita rivera, who still feels pain from the auto accident that shattered her left leg two years ago, says she wants to do more dancing in the revival of ``can-can'' she's touring in
i'm not a pollyanna; it hurts to dance,'' rivera, 55, said in an interview being published in sunday's parade magazine. ``but you don't keep telling yourself that.''
rivera, whose left leg is held together by 12 screws, said she asked the road show's producers for more dancing
the actress said that after her accident she never doubted she'd dance again one day
she said she sometimes felt like quitting during physical therapy, when ``i would feel like i was going to hit the ceiling.'' but her positive side prevailed
the spirit is the strongest thing there is,'' rivera said
tipper gore, wife of democratic presidential contender albert gore jr. and opponent of obscene rock lyrics, has gotten a tip of the hat from pop star george michael, performer of ``i want your sex.''
michael said thursday he had been notified that his ``faith'' album, which includes the hit ``sex'' single, has sold more than 10 million copies worldwide
no doubt a few of those american sales came from tipper gore's efforts,'' michael said in a statement released by his publicist, phil lobel
perhaps now she can help sell a few thousand more records since her husband won big in the primaries,'' michael said in perth, australia, where he is performing
the tennessee senator won in six states during the super tuesday primaries
the chicago tribune, illinois' largest newspaper, endorsed republican bob dole in the state's presidential primary even as the kansas senator's campaign appeared to falter
in an editorial titled ``why illinois should pick dole,'' the newspaper said in its friday editions that dole needs a big primary win to stay alive in his race against vice president george bush for the gop presidential nomination
the vice president's impressive qualifications and his commanding lead notwithstanding, the tribune hopes that sen. dole gets that big win, and endorses him in the illinois republican primary on tuesday,'' the editorial said
dole's campaign has been reeling from its dismal showing in the super tuesday primaries. he pulled television commercials off the air in illinois and laid off more than half his staff thursday
campaign spokeswoman dale tate said thursday that dole intended to remain a candidate, but a campaign aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said campaign officials were discussing whether the senate minority leader should withdraw from the illinois contest
the very lead that bush amassed on super tuesday was cited by the tribune as one of its reasons for endorsing dole
the combination of mr. bush's incumbency and the personal popularity of president reagan has brought the vice president to the brink of nomination without the kind of campaign test both he and the republican party need to have a chance in november,'' the editorial said
so far, the fight for the 1988 republican nomination has been a replay of the 1984 democratic one, in which former vice president walter mondale muscled out all the challengers early and sailed on to a mighty debacle in the general election.''
while saying that bush's identification with the administration and policies of president reagan gives him strength among republican primary voters, the tribune suggested that identification with reagan might backfire in the general election
nowhere have the republican candidates asked or answered the kind of harsh questions the democrats surely will raise in november about the reagan administration, whose colors mr. bush has been able to wave more furiously than anyone else,'' the editorial continued
yet voter concern over these issues shows up in opinion polls that often reflect sen. dole as a stronger party standard-bearer than mr. bush in match-ups with democrats,'' it said
the two home-state favorites in the democratic presidential fields got the most applause thursday as five of the party's presidential contenders appeared at an illinois democratic party dinner a few days before the state's critical primary
right after the dinner they participated in a low-key forum sponsored by the roosevelt center for american policy studies
unlike in the candidates debates held throughout the campaign, there was no byplay between the contenders and not a cross word about each other's positions
during both events, the candidates stuck closely to their standard stump speeches
at the dinner, illinois sen. paul simon, known for his trademark bow ties and horn-rimmed glasses, drew laughter and applause when he said, ``i want your vote in a beauty contest, believe it or not.''
simon went on to say, ``i offer you not a 30-second commercial but 30 years service to the people of this state and this nation.''
you will not meet me through a commercial,'' said jackson, the other illinois resident in the presidential race
both simon and jackson and running bare-bones campaigns with little or no money left for advertising. dukakis is the only democrat with the funds to run a full-scale advertising campaign directed at illinois voters
simon, who bypassed the super tuesday contests earlier this week, is hoping to get back into contention with a strong vote from his home state
jackson did well on super tuesday and is regarded as a storng contender in illinois
gov. michael dukakis of massachusetts, rep. richard gephardt of missouri and sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee also are bidding for support in the primary
at the forum, gore called for ``an all-out war on drugs'' and repeated his new campaign theme that he wants to bring ``the democratic party back to the neighborhoods.''
dukakis described himself at the forum as ``a full-employment democrat.''
on foreign policy, he said, ``we've got to get a lot tougher on south africa,'' saying that ought to include tougher sanctions to press that country to do away with its racial segregation policies
frederic remington, the painter and sculptor best known for his depiction of the wild west, deserves recognition as an american master, say the curators of a traveling exhibit of his work that opens here today
remington has been seen superficially,'' says michael edward shapiro, chief curator at the st. louis art museum. ``he's been stereotyped as a cowboy artist when he was a very sophisticated new yorker who drew from a lot of sources and created his own style, which has astonishingly imprinted itself on the conscience of our country.''
shapiro and peter h. hassrick, director of the buffalo bill historical center in cody, wyo., organized ``frederic remington: the masterworks,'' the first major traveling exhibit of remington's work
the exhibition consists of 46 paintings and drawings and 20 bronze sculptures remington created from 1889, when he was 28, until he died in 1909 at age 48 of complications from appendicitis
among the works are ``a dash for the timber,'' an 1889 painting acknowledged as remington's first masterpiece, and ``the bronco buster,'' possibly the best-known american bronze sculpture of the 19th century
remington began his art career as an illustrator, with his wild west scenes turning up in several popular magazines, including harper's weekly. his work illustrated what shapiro describes as the forces of nature and man and the risk of death and danger in the west in the action and energy of remington's horses and horsemen
he was especially successful at capturing the image of the horse _ bucking, rearing, lunging, running at breakneck speed. ``there was never a more vivid depiction of the american horse,'' shapiro adds
indeed, remington once told a drinking companion that if he could have one thing written on his tombstone, it would be: ``he knew the horse.''
his subject was always the horse and its rider _ the indian-fighting soldier or the cowboy. but the west of the homesteader, the farmer and the frontier-ending railroads held no interest for him
while the rest of the country spoke of the advance of the frontier, the `taming of the west,' as a positive force in the building of american civilization, to remington the frontier was receding and, in the end, a tragic loss,'' historian david mccullough writes in the show's catalog
remington was born oct. 4, 1861, in canton, n.y., the son of a newspaper proprietor. he grew up in canton and ogdensburg, n.y., then enrolled in the school of fine arts and joined the football team at yale university
he dropped out of yale after a year and a half when his father died and, at the age of 21, he headed west to make his fortune, plunking down part of his inheritance on a sheep ranch near peabody, kan
the sheep ranch failed, and remington bought into a kansas city saloon, which also failed. his new wife had left him to go back to new york. remington headed west again to sketch his way through new mexico and arizona
but by 1885, remington was back in new york, reunited with his wife and establishing himself as a magazine illustrator. in 1887, harper's weekly carried 39 of his sketches and drawings, and the next year more than 70
remington's drawings also began to appear in st. nicholas and outing magazines. he was commissioned by century illustrated magazine to illustrate a series of articles by a young theodore roosevelt. the series later was made into a book titled ``ranch life and the hunting trail.''
despite his popular success, remington was never a critical success, says shapiro
his work was ``just seen as cowboys and indians,'' he says, ``and there was a belief that cowboys and indians wasn't serious subject matter.''
the exhibit goes next to the buffalo bill historical center in cody, wyo., the museum of fine arts in houston and closes at the metropolitan museum of art in new york
a ruptured pipeline feb. 17 spilled nearly twice as much of a toxic chemical as thought, sun pipe line co. said thursday
in a statement from its tulsa, okla., headquarters, sun said that 176,000 gallons of toluene were missing after the break in the pipeline, which leads from a sun refinery in toledo to one in marcus hook, pa
earlier, officials estimated that between 80,000 and 100,000 gallons had leaked into a marshy area and made its way into the sandusky river
the spill forced the city of fremont to evacuate 5,000 people and impose a water emergency for several days until a method was devised to filter the chemical out of the drinking water the city draws from the river
sun said a significant share of the additional amount that spilled evaporated. up 6th graf pvs, `in view ...'</note>
talks aimed at ending a four-day strike by film and tv scriptwriters broke off thursday
in new york, meanwhile, two unions representing 100,000 actors set a march 21 deadline for a strike against makers of tv and radio commercials
talks between the alliance of motion picture and television producers and the striking writers guild of america had gone on here under the auspices of a federal mediator
marty waldman, a guild spokesman, said the producers broke off the talks
a spokesman for the producers, herb steinberg, said the scriptwriters' demands are so unrealistic that ``further talks would be fruitless. ... they're not even in the same neighborhood in an assessment of the economics involved.''
no new negotiations were set. the 9,000 scriptwriters walked out sunday over creative control and royalties from reruns
in view of the seriousness of the strike and its impact on the industry, we had hoped that continued talks might bring us better results,'' said mona mangan, executive director of the writers guild of america-east
we deeply regret that the companies do not view these talks as moving us closer together,'' she said
the strike, in its fourth day thursday, has not yet had a widespread effect on the movie and tv industry, but has delayed the debut of at least two series and has forced the david letterman and johnny carson shows into reruns
it could shorten the tv season if producers failed to stock enough scripts or discovered the need for extensive rewriting
in new york, leaders of the screen actors guild and the american federation of television and radio artists announced a march 21 deadline for a strike against the american association of advertising agencies and the association of national advertisers
union members voted 93 percent to 7 percent march 2 to authorize a walkout, according to a statement from the unions. the last strike of its kind lasted seven weeks in 1978-79
the current contract expired feb. 6 but was extended while negotiations continued over such key issues as the industry's insistence on removing cost-of-living increases, and the union's demand for higher compensation for commercials shown on cable television, the union said
there was no answer thursday night at the new york offices of the american association of advertising agencies. the unions negotiate in the field of tv commercials. radio commercials are under aftra's jurisdiction
in a strike, sag and aftra members would be asked not to perform or audition for commerciials, and to terminate the producers' right to use any commercial beyond its maximum period of use, the unions said
some of the most popular shows were near the end of their work schedules when the scriptwriters went on strike. the episode closing out the popular eight-year run of ``magnum p.i.'' has been written
i have a lot of projects that are jeopardized now,'' said executive producer jennifer alward. ``there are options on books that will run out if the scripts aren't delivered on time. if the strike goes three months, what do i do?''
wes kenney, executive producer of the abc soap opera ``general hospital'' said: ``i have enough scripts to last me through any strike.''
writers working on the academy awards ceremonies slated for worldwide broadcast april 11 said they left its script half written when they walked out. but producer samuel goldwyn jr. said: ``the show must go on, and it will.''
a former government employee, once responsible for $1.3 million a year in pentagon clothing contracts, was sentenced thursday to 10 years in prison for taking at least $331,000 in bribes from manufacturers
frank coccia, for 15 years head of the clothing and textile directorate at the defense personnel support center, also was fined $50,000 by u.s. district judge edmund ludwig
the 55-year-old resident of medford, n.j., had pleaded guilty to racketeering and conspiracy in a plea bargain under which he also agreed to forfeit $331,000 in bribe money
coccia, whose crimes began in 1976 and continued for 10 yeras, was charged in a corruption investigation, begun four years ago, that has resulted in the conviction of nine companies and 15 individuals
among them was former new jersey legislator joseph chinnici, 68, of bridgeton, n.j., who faces sentencing april 8. he was convicted of paying coccia thousands of dollars to get contracts for his clothing firm
coccia influenced the awarding of hundreds of millions of dollars in military contacts to corrupt companies'' in exchange for cash, money orders, gold coins and securities he hid in his home, said assistant u.s. attorney linda hoffa
coccia's crimes began in 1976 and continued for 10 years
the damage to the integrity of the military apparel procurement system is incalculable,'' ms. hoffa said. ``it is impossible to know whether the product or the integrity of the product being purchased by the government was compromised.''
coccia told the judge: ``my one and only objective in my job was to support the armed forces and i think i did that very well. i did not compromise the quality of any product that was brought in.''
the military regime of gen. manuel antonio noriega made its army payroll, but panama's deposed president and economists predicted it will not be able to pay civil servants next week
that could further erode support for the general, chief of the 15,000-strong panama defense forces and considered the real power behind panama's civilian government
the government had to withdraw substantial funds from the central national bank of panama and divert receipts from state-owned utilities in order to back the army payroll thursday, diplomatic sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity
in other developments thursday, panama's banks defied a government order to reopen on a limited scale, saying there simply wasn't enough cash available to do business
in washington, the house voted overwhelmingly to demand noriega's ouster, and the reagan administration considered imposing sanctions on panama, including withholding payments for panama canal operations due by march 15
also, the panamanian government ordered five private television stations to close indefinitely, but did not say why
eric arturo delvalle, whose noriega-orchestrated removal from the presidency feb. 26 led to u.s. economic pressure, predicted the government would not be able to meet its mid-march payrolls for public employees
the government will not be able to pay all civil servants and that will create another problem,'' delvalle said
delvalle, who has been in hiding since his ouster, made the statement in a tape-recorded response to written questions from the chicago tribune
he was dismissed hours after he tried to fire noriega, who is under federal indictment in the united states on charges of trafficking in colombian cocaine and money laundering
attorneys representing delvalle, who still is recognized by the united states as panama's legitimate president, have blocked the transfer of an estimated $50 million in panamanian government funds held in u.s. banks
popular resentment toward noriega's regime could rise if it cannot meet its obligations to workers after paying the military
public school teachers and other government workers are scheduled to receive their semimonthly paychecks monday and tuesday. the total payroll, including the military's, is estimated at more than $38 million, about six times the amount of money the government reportedly has on hand
private economists estimated the government's reserves at about $5 million, making it unlikely it will be able to meet next week's payroll
the national banking association, which represents 97 of the 118 financial institutions that make panama a major international banking center, said thursday that its members ``are in no condition to resume'' operations
the association on wednesday had ordered its members to reopen, but only to accept deposits and make transfers of funds between banks, calling the move a ``first step'' toward resumption of full banking services
but in a statement the following day, it said the government still had not been able to guarantee its members enough money. a run on deposits that began with opposition demonstrations last summer and accelerated after delvalle's ouster prompted the banks to close on march 1
the government ordered the banks to close last week, saying it could not provide them with enough money because of the legal action in the united states
panama's currency is the u.s. dollar
in an interview shown thursday on the caracol television chain in colombia, noriega again denied drug trafficking charges and said his accusers were paid $1.5 million to make their claims. he did not elaborate
noriega rejected ``for reasons of sovereignty and dignity'' the possibility of his going to florida to respond to the indictments
he said ``the north american assistant secretary of state for latin american affairs (elliott abrams) would not come to panama to confront a trial here for his confabulation against the panamanian state.''
energy secretary john herrington says foreign money may pay for up to half the $4.4 billion superconducting super collider project, and house committee members want the international commitments before approving u.s. funds
japan, taiwan, south korea, france, italy and canada are interested in investing in the project, herrington said thursday in testimony before the house appropriations committee's energy and water development subcommittee
i fully expect you to see 40 (percent) to 50 percent of this project will be international financing,'' herrington said. ``i think the money is there and the interest is there. it is an international project.''
herrington's estimate of foreign participation was about double the 25 percent level previously stated by department officials
the subcommittee's chairman, rep. tom bevill, d-ala., said foreign money would help win congressional funding for the physics research complex, which would include a 53-mile-round atom smasher
but he and herrington differed on who should commit money first, congress or foreign investors
it seems to me this is the only way under our present budget situation that we would even start this project, with the participation of the countries,'' bevill said
herrington replied: ``it is not in the interests of the united states government to say to the world, `we are the leaders in high-energy physics and we are ready to take the next step, ... but we are not willing to do that until we get foreign commitments.' that's not leadership.''
bevill said he was considering how to pay for the project, while herrington was thinking of the united states being first in physics
unless we can get allocated another billion dollars pretty soon and start it ... we could not possibly initiate the funding,'' bevill said. ``but if we had assurance 50 percent or 75 percent would be contributed by other countries, it would be a whole new game.''
the reagan administration has proposed spending $363 million for super-collider construction in 1989, but critics in congress say that would divert money from other important research projects
seven states have sites competing for the project, which will produce 3,000 jobs and have an annual operating budget of $279 million
the states are arizona, colorado, illinois, michigan, north carolina, tennessee and texas
