a strong earthquake shook costa rica late thursday, breaking windows in houses in southern cities near the border with panama, a fire department official said
there were no immediate reports of injuries
firefighters in the panamanian city of david said the tremor was felt strongly in panama's western provinces of chiriqui and boca del toro, both bordering costa rica, but there were no reports of damage or injuries there either
the temblor was not felt in panama city
the quake registered 5.6 on the richter scale, said an official in the communications office of san jose's fire department. he refused to be further identified
no one answered telephones at the seismology institute
the red cross said no damage was reported in san jose, the capital
the fire department official said the quake occured at 9:45 p.m. (10:45 p.m. est) and was centered near buenos aires, 70 miles southeast of san jose and 26 miles from the border with panama
we have reports that the glass windows of many homes broke in the towns of buenos aires, ciudad neily and san isidro ... and we are expecting possible reports of damage in puerto jimenez, near buenos aires,'' the official said
san isidro is 48 miles southeast of san jose and ciudad neily is seven miles from the panamanian border
he said the quake also was felt strongly in the city of golfito, also near the border, but communications were poor and there was no word of damage, he said
the people ran into the streets terrified in the cities of buenos aires and ciudad neily, since the temblor was really strong,'' johnny zamora of the red cross in san jose said
in san jose, tall buildings swayed
definitely the quake was felt practically in all the country,'' the fire department official said
the richter scale is a measure of the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. every increase of one number indicates an increase of 10 times in ground motion
an earthquake of magnitude 5 can cause considerable damage. one measuring 6 can cause severe damage, while a reading of 8 indicates a quake capable of tremendous damage
president reagan says he will try to persuade israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir to drop objections to an american peace plan for the middle east
reagan said thursday that ``a great element'' of israel's coalition government supports the plan. he said the plan offers ``a pretty good solution that would remove some of the problems besetting the people in the occupied territories.''
i believe that peace is inevitable,'' reagan said. ``we may have some differences there as to how to achieve it but i don't think anyone believes that we can go on just with a constant state of warfare and unrest (in the middle east).''
the president conducted four separate interviews in the white house map room with television journalists from france, britain, italy and west germany. transcripts of the remarks were released by the white house
he criticized israel's ban on press coverage of unrest and the military's response in the occupied west bank and gaza strip
more than 80 arabs have been killed by israeli troops or settlers since the demonstrations began late last year. israeli officials concerned about the negative publicity have now restricted press access to the areas involved
i'm a great believer in a free press and the right of the people to know ... so i would have to be opposed to it _ thinking that they want to conduct operations in which they would rather not have public knowledge of them.''
next week, shamir will meet at the white house with reagan to discuss the administration's proposals. the prime minister has blocked efforts to force a vote within israel's government on how to respond to the american plan
shamir rejects the u.s. plan because it sets a timetable for negotiations between israel and the arabs on the future of the west bank and gaza strip. thirty u.s. senators have criticized shamir for rejecting an exchange of ``territory for peace.''
reagan, asked what kind of pressure he would put on shamir, said, ``well, i don't think it's so much pressure as it is just an attempt at persuasion
but also, i'd like to point out that his cabinet is pretty evenly split on the solution,'' reagan said. ``so it isn't a case of outside pressure there. he has a great element in his own government that sees merit in the proposals that we've made.''
part of the u.s. plan calls for an international peace conference whose members would include the soviet union
reagan said moscow has not recognized israel as a nation and added, ``that's very difficult to have someone participating in a conference of that kind who doesn't even believe in the right of statehood of the other country.''
he said the conference would not be empowered to impose a settlement, but would try ``to be helpful and see if we could not join in helping arrive at a solution that would once and for all end the hostilities.''
on other subjects, reagan:
_said the united states has made gains in talks with the soviet union. ``there has been a softening in their position on human rights and they have freed political prisoners and so forth,'' reagan said. ``we think they have a long way to go to meet our standard of human rights.''
_denied that his wife, nancy, is his main adviser. ``no, and she's very embarrassed about the press stories that for some reason continue to say that. no, she has been a good and faithful wife, and i share secrets with her and my problems and all of that.''
elisabeth ann zinser resigned her position early friday as president of gallaudet university, only five days after her selection to lead the school for the deaf touched off a storm of protest from students who demanded a hearing-impaired president
the university's board of trustees said it had regretfully accepted zinser's resignation and would resume its search for a new president
gallaudet board chairman jane bassett spilman called the resignation a tragic loss to the university
we selected dr. zinser as president in recognition of her superior academic, administrative and research skills. her strengths and accomplishments were precisely in those areas most critical for the growth of the university,'' spilman said
on thursday, students capped the fourth day of protests by declaring zinser _ is not deaf and does not know sign language _ unelcome on campus and vowing to keep her out
jerry covell, a leader of the protests, hailed the resignation, but said early friday that students were still angry with spilman, who had resisted the push to oust zinser, who is vice chancellor for academic affairs at the university of north carolina-greensboro
we are glad that she resigned but we are still waiting for spilman,'' covell said
in submitting her resignation shortly after midnight, zinser emphasized her concern that the very governance of gallaudet had been called into question by the week's events
the campus was virtually shut down for four days while a large majority of the 124-year-old institution's 2,200 students protested. the students had attracted members of congress and presidential candidates to their cause
zinser had been named to head the university, the nation's only liberal arts college for the deaf, on sunday
i accepted the presidency when the board and i agreed that my values, talents and experiences were well suited to the growth of gallaudet university in the higher education community as well as the deaf community. this remains the challenge for the future of gallaudet,'' zinser said in a statement released through a public relations firm
she said her decision to resign was reached ``with great difficulty as i came to understand how deeply some see the social stature of deaf persons reflected in the presidency of this university.''
students on thursday threatened to seize the president's campus house and office if zinser made her way past students blocking entrances to the school. the doors to the administration building were chained shut, and no administrators were seen on campus
in other action on thursday, one of the two deaf finalists for the school presidency withdrew his support for zinser and said he would back the student protesters
a day earlier, i. king jordan, dean of the school's college of arts and sciences, had said he was supporting zinser ``for the good of the school.'' but jordan told a student rally on thursday that he could no longer support the new leader
rep. david bonior, d-mich., who is a member of gallaudet's board of trustees, said in a statement thursday he suggested to zinser that in the next few days she consult with the faculty, students, staff and alumni ``to experience the passion with which they view the appointment of hearing president.''
the time is long overdue for gallaudet university to have a deaf president,'' bonior said. ``the university has for generations been an international mecca for excellence and opportunity in deaf education
the question before us is _ how long will it be able to sustain this important role without a deaf president?''
earlier, in an interview with the washington post, bonior said he told zinser that federal aid for the school may be jeopardized if she refuses to leave the post she was named to sunday night
about 75 percent of the school's $76 million operating budget comes from federal funds. the rest comes from tuition and grants
meanwhile, the house education and labor subcommittee on select education, which oversees gallaudet's budget, scheduled hearings for tuesday on the controversy over the president and the makeup of the board of trustees
zinser had said wednesday she was assuming her post immediately instead of waiting until the original july starting date
she also lamented that campus protests have disrupted classes, and said she would take unspecified steps to restore order if the protests, which have been peaceful so far, took a violent turn
besides calling for zinser's ouster, the students want spilman's resignation, and a deaf majority on the 20-member trustees board, which now has four deaf members
as zinser attempted to start her job, support for the protesters grew
late wednesday, democratic presidential candidate jesse jackson issued a statement supporting the students, and called on gallaudet's board of trustees to ``resolve this dispute equitably
the problem is not that the students do not hear. the problem is that the hearing world does not listen,'' jackson said
sen. paul simon, d-ill., another democratic presidential hopeful, on thursday called for zinser's resignation
simon, a longtime member of the senate labor and human resources subcommittee on the handicapped, which has jurisdiction over funding for gallaudet, said zinser's appointment was a ``slap in the face to the entire purpose of the university.''
vince dollard, a spokesman for the national technical institute for the deaf, in rochester, n.y., said two buses and several cars, carrying at least 100 students from the school, were to leave at midnight for washington to join the gallaudet protest
a rally was held on the rochester campus in support of gallaudet thursday afternoon
in addition, some east coast leaders of the national association of the deaf, a 20,000-member deaf rights group based in silver spring, md., were planning to gather in washington on friday, spokesman fred weiner said
and activist abbie hoffman, who lectures to universities on student protests, said, ``what's happening at gallaudet is obviously right there in the front,'' he said, ``and they're going to win their battle.''
he said he has urged members of three electronic bulletin-board networks, with a total of 16,000 members, to support the students' efforts by tying up gallaudet's switchboards with calls of support for the students
frederic remington, the painter and sculptor best known for his depiction of the wild west, deserves recognition as an american master, say the curators of a traveling exhibit of his work that opens here today
remington has been seen superficially,'' says michael edward shapiro, chief curator at the st. louis art museum. ``he's been stereotyped as a cowboy artist when he was a very sophisticated new yorker who drew from a lot of sources and created his own style, which has astonishingly imprinted itself on the conscience of our country.''
shapiro and peter h. hassrick, director of the buffalo bill historical center in cody, wyo., organized ``frederic remington: the masterworks,'' the first major traveling exhibit of remington's work
the exhibition consists of 46 paintings and drawings and 20 bronze sculptures remington created from 1889, when he was 28, until he died in 1909 at age 48 of complications from appendicitis
among the works are ``a dash for the timber,'' an 1889 painting acknowledged as remington's first masterpiece, and ``the bronco buster,'' possibly the best-known american bronze sculpture of the 19th century
remington began his art career as an illustrator, with his wild west scenes turning up in several popular magazines, including harper's weekly. his work illustrated what shapiro describes as the forces of nature and man and the risk of death and danger in the west in the action and energy of remington's horses and horsemen
he was especially successful at capturing the image of the horse _ bucking, rearing, lunging, running at breakneck speed. ``there was never a more vivid depiction of the american horse,'' shapiro adds
indeed, remington once told a drinking companion that if he could have one thing written on his tombstone, it would be: ``he knew the horse.''
his subject was always the horse and its rider _ the indian-fighting soldier or the cowboy. but the west of the homesteader, the farmer and the frontier-ending railroads held no interest for him
while the rest of the country spoke of the advance of the frontier, the `taming of the west,' as a positive force in the building of american civilization, to remington the frontier was receding and, in the end, a tragic loss,'' historian david mccullough writes in the show's catalog
remington was born oct. 4, 1861, in canton, n.y., the son of a newspaper proprietor. he grew up in canton and ogdensburg, n.y., then enrolled in the school of fine arts and joined the football team at yale university
he dropped out of yale after a year and a half when his father died and, at the age of 21, he headed west to make his fortune, plunking down part of his inheritance on a sheep ranch near peabody, kan
the sheep ranch failed, and remington bought into a kansas city saloon, which also failed. his new wife had left him to go back to new york. remington headed west again to sketch his way through new mexico and arizona
but by 1885, remington was back in new york, reunited with his wife and establishing himself as a magazine illustrator. in 1887, harper's weekly carried 39 of his sketches and drawings, and the next year more than 70
remington's drawings also began to appear in st. nicholas and outing magazines. he was commissioned by century illustrated magazine to illustrate a series of articles by a young theodore roosevelt. the series later was made into a book titled ``ranch life and the hunting trail.''
despite his popular success, remington was never a critical success, says shapiro
his work was ``just seen as cowboys and indians,'' he says, ``and there was a belief that cowboys and indians wasn't serious subject matter.''
the exhibit goes next to the buffalo bill historical center in cody, wyo., the museum of fine arts in houston and closes at the metropolitan museum of art in new york
environmental cleanup at the nation's nuclear weapons production plants could cost as much as $100 billion, department of energy officials told a congressional panel
cleaning up doe's nuclear facilities may be the federal government's biggest challenge,'' j. dexter peach, an assistant comptroller general of the general accounting office, said in testimony thursday before the house energy and commerce hazardous materials subcommittee
joseph salgado, undersecretary at the energy department, told the panel that $100 billion in cleanup costs for all of the federal facilities ``is probably in the ballpark.''
the subcommittee is considering a number of bills designed to strengthen enforcement of environmental laws at the nation's weapons production plants, which are operated for the department by private contractors
in a related development, the new york times quoted energy department officials in today's editions as saying the department would sharply scale back the amount of radioactive material it plans to bury in the nation's first permanent nuclear waste repository
department engineers said in interviews with the newspaper that the department would entomb less than a quarter of the 125,000 barrels of plutonium-contaminated wastes the government earlier intended to place in the planned $700 million repository in new mexico over the next five years
the decision came four months after scientists told a congressional committee that enough water was seeping into the repository to threaten its ability to safely store wastes that would remain radioactive for hundreds of thousands of years
last week, a panel of experts from the national academy of sciences confirmed that water was entering the chamber and recommended that the energy department entomb only enough waste for experiments to determine the significance of the seepage
the water leaks are to be studied further to determine whether current plans for the repository to receive even more waste can be put into effect. the repository is being dug from salt beds 26 miles east of carlsbad, n.m. and is to open next october
winston porter, assistant administrator for the u.s. environmental protection agency, acknowledged thursday in the hearing that the epa has lost one of its levers in forcing facilities to comply with environmental laws. the reason, he said, is that the justice department has prevented the agency from using its authority to go to court or issue unilateral orders
he said the administration has brought no court suits, issued no unilateral orders, and entered into a handful of consent orders, two enforceable compliance agreements and three unenforceable agreements as part of its cleanup efforts
but salgado told the subcommittee that the energy department has recently made significant progress toward addressing environmental contamination and has increased funding for cleanup by 62 percent in fiscal 1989
salgado said he has been told it will likely cost $1 billion to begin cleanup at the feed materials production center in fernald, ohio. the aging foundry processes uranium for use in nuclear weapons
joseph legrone, the energy department's operations manager at oak ridge, tenn., said $105 million was budgeted for environmental work at fernald in fiscal 1988, more than the $102 million for production. and he said $145 million has been earmarked for fiscal 1989
legrone told rep. thomas luken, d-ohio, he hopes to be able to assure that there is no leakage from fernald's waste pits into groundwater within a year and a half
richard nixon in a new book criticizes the american military establishment for ``preparing for the big war that will probably never be fought'' and ignoring the possibility of smaller wars
moscow is most likely to seek to outflank europe and japan with aggression in the third world, where our nuclear power is useless,'' he writes in ``1999: victory without war.'' ``if we fail to develop the capability to parry soviet thrusts in the third world, we will find ourselves unable to compete with moscow.''
nixon's book, the sixth he has written since he resigned the presidency in 1974, is to be published this spring by simon and schuster. like the last four, it deals with foreign policy. his first post-white house book was his memoirs
he writes that moscow is outspending washington 4-to-1 in providing military aid to other countries and that america must continue providing ``tons of weapons'' to its allies to head off the soviet challenge
it is not philanthropy but expansionism that drives the soviet union to pump weapons into the third world,'' nixon says. ``its goal in exporting arms is exporting communism. ... we must do at least as much for our allies as the soviets do for theirs.''
he adds: ``americans instinctively cringe at the thought of shipping off tons of weapons and military equipment to countries around the world; they do not want to think of themselves as arms merchants. but military aid is often the best way to protect our interests and those of our friends and allies.''
the united states, nixon says, ``must not fall into the trap of thinking that a reduction in u.s.-soviet tensions means the end of the conflict. if (mikhail s.) gorbachev stresses the need to solve his internal problems, we should not be conned into thinking that the system has changed or that the threat has ended.''
gorbachev, the current soviet leader, nixon says ``more than his predecessors is a powerful reminder that we underestimate the soviets at our peril.''
washington ``lost its collective senses'' when gorbachev applied his public relations talents last december at the superpower summit, the former president writes, saying that gorbachev ``is so confident of his strengths that he is not afraid to talk about his weaknesses.''
nixon also makes these points:
_``in 1999, when we look back over the 20th century, we will have to face the fact that mankind's advances in military power and material progress have dwarfed his progress in developing the political skills and institutions to preserve peace and capitalize on our technological advances. it will be our task in the 21st century to end the mismatch between our technological skill and our woefully lagging political skill.''
_the united states has a greater competitive edge in foreign economic assistance than in military aid. this country has spent more than $134 billion in economic aid since world war ii compared with less than $50 billion by the soviet union, yet has failed to capitalize on the advantage
_``if we are to compete, it must be on their side of the iron courtain as well as ours. if we compete only on moscow's terms, soviet leaders will take what we give them and come back for more.''
_although the united states holds good cards in ideological competition with the soviets ``they have done a good job of selling a poor case and we have done a poor job of selling a good case.'' he writes of ``the pap that passes for programming on the voice of america'' and of professional diplomats who ``reflexively treat disputes as if they were simply great misunderstandings rather than imsurmountable differences.''
_the war powers act, which limits a president's power to take military action overseas without congressional approval and was passed over nixon's veto in 1973, is not only unconstitutional but unsound. ``given the realities of the world, the united states will sometimes need to use force in actions short of all-out war and will have to be able to act quickly and decisively. while 535 would be commanders in chief (the number of representatives and senators) dissect the merits and demerits of the intervention, the president will have to keep glancing over his shoulder to check the clock while fighting to defend american interests.''
discovery of a gene that produces a brain protein from the chromosome segment responsible for down's syndrome puts researchers ``on the trail'' of the genetic basis for the most common form of mental retardation
in a study published today in the journal science, researchers from canada and california report that they have identified a brain protein gene in a part of chromosome 21 that relates to down's syndrome, a discovery that other experts said may be an important first step toward a genetic understanding of the birth defect
it puts bloodhounds on the trail, but it's still a distant scent,'' said dr. david r. cox of the university of california, san francisco, one of seven scientists who conducted the research. he cautioned that more study is required because ``we don't know what it's relative importance will be'' in the cause of down's
dr. sigfried pueschel, head of a down's syndrome research program at brown university and a nationally recognized authority, said the finding is a ``significant advance.''
it is a first step and an important step,'' pueschel said
down's syndrome is a congenital defect that includes mental retardation and bowel and heart abnormalities. down's babies have broad features and slanted eyes, characteristics that led the syndrome to once be identified by the now-obsolete term of ``mongoloidism.''
down's syndrome is the most common form of mental retardation. about 4,000 down's babies are born annually in the united states. the syndrome affects one in every 800 to 1,000 live births
the birth defect is caused by the presence of three copies of chromosome 21, instead of the normal pair. it is believed that this so-called ``trisomy'' leads to the genetic expression of proteins which in turn lead to the development of down's
in the science magazine report, cox said that his co-investigators found a gene in chromosome 21 that expresses a protein, called s100, that is primarily found in the brain
this is the first time that a brain protein has been mapped into the down's syndrome region of chromosome 21,'' he said. ``previously there had been some genes that were expressed primarily in the brain,'' but those were mapped to other portions of the chromosome, said cox
our results say that this is a potential candidate gene that may play a major or minor role in mental retardation,'' he said. ``it can now be studied to test this hypothesis.''
cox emphasized that the discovery offers no immediate promise for treatment and that it will take additional study to determine the precise effect of the gene
but it provides the first clue that allows one to start looking into that,'' he said
i think to uncover any gene on chromosome 21 with a specific function is a significant advance,'' pueschel said. ``it might in the future provide us with information on how to treat these individuals.''
cox said the researchers isolated portions of chromosome 21 and then conducted tests to determine which part produced s100. the gene that expressed the protein was found in a band called 21q22. it is one of perhaps 1,000 genes in that portion of chromosome 21, but cox said it is the first found there that expresses a brain protein
in addition to cox, members of the research team were robert allore, karen neilson, h.f. willard, r.j. dunn, david o'hanlon and alexander marks, all of the university of toronto in canada, and e.r. price of the university of california, san francisco
science is the journal of the american association for the advancement of science
a hand grenade exploded thursday night in an apartment, injuring three of about a dozen people who had gathered to watch a pro basketball game on television, police said
an unidentified man apparently pulled a pin from a grenade while the group was watching the chicago bulls play the los angeles lakes, said police sgt. david schweiger
the blast injured the man who pulled the pin, a teen-ager and a 28-year-old woman, carolyn dyson of chicago, who was hospitalized in good condition with shrapnel in her eyes, authorities said
the man and the teen-ager, whose names were not immediately available, were listed in serious condition at loyola university medical center in suburban maywood, said spokeswoman carol prevatt
police didn't know why the man had the grenade, but thought it was ``either real old or homemade,'' said schweiger
the explosion didn't cause extensive damage to the apartment, he said
sen. donald riegle has returned campaign contributions made by employees and officers of an arizona company on whose behalf he met with federal bank regulators conducting an investigation
riegle said thursday he wanted to avoid the appearance of a conflict of interest and so was giving back $76,100 in contributions from people associated with american continental co. of phoenix, ariz., and its subsidiaries
three other senators present at the meeting last year said through aides they saw no reason to return the money. an aide to a fourth senator was unable to say whether the contributions would be returned
while there was no conflict of interest involved, before or after these contributions, even the appearance of such a personal conflict should be enough to warrant the return of these contributions, and that is what i have done,'' said riegle, a michigan democrat up for re-election this year who sits on the senate banking committee
riegle and sens. dennis deconcini, d-ariz.; alan cranston, d-calif.; john glenn, d-ohio; and john mccain, r-ariz., met last april 9 with federal home loan bank board examiners and discussed the investigation of an american continental subsidiary, lincoln savings and loan association of irvine, calif
there was no connection between the meeting and the agency's decision to end its probe of high-risk investments made by the subsidiary, riegle said last month
the meeting was called by deconcini, said riegle's press secretary, mike russell. deconcini had received $43,000 in campaign contributions from american continental officers and employees
cranston received $41,900 in contributions; glenn, $34,000; and mccain, $112,000
it is foolishness to assume that just because employees of a company make a contribution to a deconcini campaign, that that company can no longer go to sen. deconcini and request the same kind of constitutent service that any other individual or company would expect,'' said deconcini's press secretary, bob maynes
aides to mccain and glenn also said the senators would not return the contributions because they saw no reason to do so
cranston's press secretary, victoria lion, said the senator was out of the country and she was unable to determine whether he had or intended to return his american continental campaign contributions
the contributions were legal under federal election laws
russell said riegle believed returning the contributions would put to rest questions about the propriety of his having accepted the money
he made a personal decision last weekend,'' russell said. ``this was the first time in his 22 years of public service that a conflict of interest had been raised.''
american continental owns detroit's pontchartrain hotel
drug and alcohol testing of the nation's railroad workers is resuming following a court order that has temporarily boosted reagan administration efforts to make the examinations more common
the administrator of the federal railroad administration, john riley, told congress on thursday that he had ordered railroads to begin conducting the urine and blood tests once again, less than a month after a federal court in san francisco declared them illegal
his order was a response to a stay issued last friday that temporarily lifts the ban on testing
if an accident were to occur tomorrow, the crew would be tested,'' riley told the house transportation appropriations subcommittee
riley said that without last friday's court ruling, ``our testing program would be terminated.''
the reagan administration has been trying to perform more and more drug and alcohol tests on employees in the transportation industry
on feb. 11, the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals in san francisco struck down the fra's 2-year-old program that required railroads to check the members of train crews involved in serious accidents for drug or alcohol use. the court stated that such tests were unconstitutional unless there was a suspicion that an individual worker was under the influence of drugs or alcohol
but last friday, u.s. circuit judge thomas tang granted a request by the government to stay the order until april 2. tang was in the 2-1 majority that originally voted to invalidate the testing
riley said that under federal judicial procedures, if the government files its appeal by april 2 _ which officials say they will _ the stay would automatically remain in effect until the supreme court issues a decision in the case. that would probably take months
but a spokesman for the country's railroad unions said the stay would not be automatically extended beyond april 2. edward wytkind, spokesman for the railway labor executives association, said that after april 2, the supreme court could decide to allow the tests to resume at any time
we don't view the stay as any sort of attack on employees,'' wytkind said. ``it's just on an interim basis.''
as a result of the decision, the government had also halted drug and alcohol testing of railroad workers performed for what it called ``reasonable cause'' in which a supervisor noticed unusual behavior by a worker
such tests also will be resumed, riley said
the four-month tab for storing midwest grain on river barges to help make room in country elevators for the new 1986 harvest came to $62 million, or nearly a dollar a bushel, the general accounting office says
overall, the cost to taxpayers was sharply higher than the storage fees normally paid by the government for grain inventories in elevators and farm bins. the program was announced in august 1986 as one of a number of emergency measures to help relieve pressure on elevators getting ready for another bumper corn harvest
the gao, an investigative agency of congress, said in a recent report to rep. bill alexander, d-ark., that the agriculture department awarded storage contracts to a dozen grain companies. a total of about 64.9 million bushels of grain _ 98 percent corn and 2 percent soybeans _ was loaded on 1,253 barges along the illinois, mississippi, missouri and ohio rivers
all of the barge grain originated from the corn belt states of illinois, indiana, iowa, michigan, minnesota, missouri, nebraska, ohio and wisconsin, the gao said. most had been in country and terminal elevators in those states, but some had been stored by producers on their farms
eventually, the department's kansas city commodity office, which handled the program, disposed of most of the barge grain by trading it to the contractors for grain they had stored in inland elevators. the remainder was sold, redeemed by farmers or returned to storage elsewhere
we estimate that the additional cost of the special barge storage program, over and above the normal costs for shipping, storing and disposing of the grain, was about $44.8 million, or an additional cost of 69 cents per bushel to store the grain for an average of four months,'' the gao said
the estimate by gao was made because the department's agricultural stabilization and conservation service ``did not separately accumulate total cost data for the program.'' however, gao said its estimates were based on reviews of contracts and other information provided by the agency
the estimated cost of storing the 64.9 million bushels of grain was about $62.2 million, or 96 cents per bushel,'' the gao said. ``this includes the additional cost of the program (about $44.8 million) and the cost that would have been incurred in the normal course of storage (more than $17.3 million).''
corn market prices nationally averaged $1.73 per bushel when the program was announced and dropped to $1.40 in october 1986, the peak of the new harvest
investigators said they estimated the department's kansas city commodity office paid the 12 contractors about $45.5 million and that an additional $16.7 million went to others for charges related to the barge-stored grain
the gao said the kansas city office ``agreed with our methodology and results'' in estimating the payments
the agriculture department's new crackdown on illegally high traces of a suspected cancer-causing drug found in hog carcasses has eased concern in japan that pork imports from the united states may be tainted, officials said
japan had initiated a program to hold and test all u.s. pork imports, which american livestock interests feared might jeopardize foreign sales. the drug involved is sulfamethazine, commonly used by swine producers to prevent certain kinds of disease and as a feed additive to promote faster growth
lester m. crawford, administrator of the department's food safety and inspection service, said thursday that usda and japanese officials have agreed on testing requirements for pork shipped to japan
crawford said japanese officials ``have been favorably impressed with u.s. efforts'' initiated on march 7 to increase testing of pork products for sulfamethazine residues in the 100 largest u.s. pork plants
u.s. pork produced after march 7 must carry a statement on the export certificate that the product originated from one of the 100 plants undergoing increased residue testing,'' he said. ``japan will not further test these products for sulfamethazine residues.''
pork exported before the new controls went into effect will be tested further for the drug, either in japan or the united states, he said
the agriculture department reports the soviet union has bought an additional 100,000 metric tons of u.s. corn for delivery this year under a long-term supply agreement between the two countries
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. the 100,000 tons of corn would be about 3.94 million bushels
corn prices recently have been averaging about $1.84 per bushel at the farm level, meaning that the sale could have a farm value of around $7.25 million
officials said thursday the latest sale involved 50,000 tons that had been reported by exporters as headed for japan, and 50,000 tons for ``unknown destinations.''
the corn is part of the grain the soviet union is committed to buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of u.s. grain. the pact expires sept. 30
according to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. the soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent
with the latest purchases, the soviets now have bought 3.27 million tons of corn and more than 6.9 million tons of wheat, plus 1.3 million tons of soybean meal and 813,300 tons of soybeans
congress will begin another long fight with the white house if it passes a bill requiring president reagan to tell capitol hill about all covert operations within 48 hours after they start, says defense secretary frank c. carlucci
reagan would veto the bill because he believes it is unconstitutional, the defense secretary said thursday in testimony before a house intelligence subcommittee. he added that enactment of the measure over reagan's objection would touch off another fight similar to the ongoing dispute over the war powers act
the war powers act, a 1973 law restricting a president's authority to send u.s. troops into dangerous situations, is the subject of a federal court fight over its constitutionality. the white house claims it is unconstitutional
the intelligence notification bills arise from the iran-contra affair, when u.s. weapons were secretly sold to iran and some of the profits were diverted to the nicaraguan contra guerrillas. reagan withheld notification from congress for 10 months in 1986
current laws require that congress be told about covert actions except in extraordinary circumstances, when only ``timely notice'' is required. but the phrase is not defined and the proposed legislation would mandate notice within 48 hours
carlucci, who was reagan's national security adviser after the iran-contra affair became public, said the administration has put procedures into place to avoid another iran-contra situation
at some point, we have to rely on trust,'' he told the legislation subcommittee. ``if a future president sets out to deceive a congress, no amount of statutes will stop him.''
rep. henry hyde, r-ill., said the bill is ``one more battle between the imperial congress and the imperial presidency.''
carlucci agreed, saying, ``i can think of no step by the congress which would do more harm to the process of rebuilding an atmosphere of trust and candor between the branches than unilaterally to lay claim to prerogatives which the president firmly believes are vested in the executive by the constitution.''
but rep. matt mchugh, d-n.y., chairman of the subcommittee, said the legislation is needed
in the case of the arms sales to iran, the president construed current law as permitting him to withhold notice for more than 10 months after the covert sales had been authorized,'' mchugh said
if he had done (as the law generally requires), he would surely have heard some strong objections and might have spared the country a serious foreign policy setback and himself a major political embarrassment.''
carlucci's argument was that ``the failures of the iran affair were human and managerial. no statute can prevent these mistakes. ... we will not put the mistrust which caused the iran-contra affair behind us until we trust each other again.''
the bill was also opposed by brent scowcroft, national security adviser to president ford
scowcroft said ``the excessively restrictive language proposed seems a case of throwing out the baby with the bath. it is not possible to eliminate every opportunity for abuse by the executive without at the same time paralyzing the ability to act.''
he said the bills arise from the view that notification to congress about the arms sales would have been met with opposition that would have derailed the plan
scowcroft disputed that. ``there is no evidence to support this assumption. indeed, as it was, the president was confronted, by his principal advisers, with views strongly in opposition to the iranian arms sales.''
the dollar dipped against the japanese yen in trading in tokyo friday, while stock prices fell following an overnight decline on wall street
the dollar opened at 127.85 yen, down 0.35 yen from thursday's close of 128.20 yen, and closed for the day at 127.80, down 0.40 yen from thursday
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, which gained 12.43 points thursday, lost 74.09 points or 0.02 percent to close at 25,543.73
although nothing has changed in regard to japan's improved investment environment, a 48.24-point fall in the dow jones industrial average dampened the mood of investors,'' said masahiro umemori of nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage
a dealer at a major commercial bank in tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the currency market ``generally remained listless.'' he said the market was waiting for the release of u.s. retail sales and producer price figures, due out friday in washington
vice president george bush leads senate gop leader bob dole by a wide margin among republicans likely to vote in illinois' presidential primary, according to survey results published today
the washington post-abc news telephone poll conducted wednesday, six days before the primary election, showed bush with the support of 58 percent of 395 likely republican voters, while dole, of kansas, was backed by 31 percent
former television evangelist pat robertson was the choice of 6 percent while rep. jack kemp of new york, who dropped out of the race on thursday, had 4 percent, according to the survey, which was published in today's editions of the post
in the democratic race, native sons sen. paul simon of illinois and civil rights leader jesse jackson of chicago led with 38 percent and 33 percent, respectively, among 402 likely democratic voters. the difference between the two was within the poll's margin of error
massachussets gov. michael dukakis trailed with 16 percent and rep. richard gephardt of missouri had 6 percent. former sen. gary hart of colorado, who was expected to withdraw from the contest today, was picked by 3 percent of the respondents and sen. albert gore of tennessee was chosen by 2 percent
the newspaper said the survey had a margin of error of plus or minus eight percentage points. limit</head>
pat robertson, the biggest-spending candidate of the presidential race so far, says he'll use his federal matching funds after all, even though he has said he is philosophically opposed to the idea
robertson said thursday that ``short of what would amount to an absolute miracle in the state (of illinois), it looks as if i'll have to use them.''
he also said at a news conference that he is within about $2 million of the $27 million spending cap that election rules set for those who get matching funds. that could pose serious strategy problems for him, because it means he will be unable to continue the kind of high-spending campaign he has conducted so far and will be forced to skimp along for the remainder of the primary season
it's going to mean that it's going to be me the candidate and not a lot of travel and everything else the volunteers,'' he said
robertson said he had made deep cuts in his national staff, but he declined to give specific numbers. he said the reductions had cut deeply into his press and office staff
everybody is bucking up around the federal (spending) limit ... so we want to stay lean and mean,'' he said
robertson has received $7.2 million in federal matching funds, more than any other candidate, including vice president george bush, who has received $6.6 million
robertson's campaign has put the money into an escrow account and was keeping open the option of not using the money and later giving it back to the government. in that case, campaign attorney marion harrison had contended, robertson would not be bound by the spending limits imposed on those who accept matching funds
whether the federal election commission would have accepted that point of view is now moot since robertson has indicated he will not try that approach
fec officials had pointed out that the law requires a candidate to sign an agreement to abide by the limits at the time of application for matching funds. there is no language in the regulations that addresses whether a candidate actually spends the money
robertson had used the money as collateral for a $5.5 million loan in january, and a $1.5 million loan in december
we put the (matching) funds in escrow and borrowed against them. we're still trying to keep our options open, but the options, i might say, narrowed considerably after super tuesday,'' robertson said in an interview following a brief chicago news conference kicking off his effort in illinois
robertson said that the matching funds are, ``in a sense, already spent
that money would just go to pay off loans. the truth is, in my estimation, that all the major campaigns are bumped up against the limit. there is not much money left for anybody,'' said robertson
we're trying to husband our resources as hard as we can and hold on through june,'' he continued
robertson said cash problems would not deter him from continuing the gop fight
i am more and more being urged by conservatives to stay in the race as a rallying point for conservatives and conservative principles,'' he said
as of the most recent campaign financial reports, through jan. 31, robertson had spent more against the limit than any other candidate _ more than $22 million. that was before the most intensive spending period began for the super tuesday primaries and caucuses in 20 states on march 8
by contrast, bush had spent $15.3 million and sen. bob dole, r-kan., $18.1 million
the matching funds are provided from a fund supported by the $1 voluntary checkoff on individual income tax returns. each donation of $250 or less that a candidate raises is matched by the public fund. to qualify initially, a candidate must raise at least $100,000 across 20 states in contributions of $250 or less
robertson had said he was not in favor of the publicly supported campaign finance system
talks with movie and television producers aimed at ending a five-day scriptwriters strike broke down, with no new meeting scheduled, officials of both sides said
the writers and producers were meeting thursday with a federal mediator when the producers decided the talks weren't going anywhere, said mona mangan, executive director of the writers guild of america's east coast unit
in view of the seriousness of the strike and its impact on the industry, we had hoped that continued talks might bring us better results. we deeply regret that the companies do not view these talks as moving us closer together,'' ms. mangan said
a spokesman for the alliance of motion picture and television producers, herb steinberg, said the scriptwriters' demands were so unrealistic that ``further talks would be fruitless. ... they're not even in the same neighborhood in an assessment of the economics involved.''
meanwhile, in new york, two unions representing 100,000 actors set a march 21 deadline for a strike against makers of tv and radio commercials
federal mediator leonard farrell recessed the scriptwriters talks subject to his calling another meeting, but no date was agreed to, ms. mangan said
daily variety, an industry newspaper, reported thursday that the guild is preparing interim contracts for independent producers, a tactic used last summer by the directors guild before its contract with producers ended
the strike has yet to have a widespread effect on the motion picture and television industry, but has delayed the debut of at least two series and has forced the david letterman and johnny carson shows into reruns
a long strike by the 9,000 writers could affect some movies and the fall television season, and could shorten the current television season if producers failed to stock enough scripts or discover extensive rewriting is needed
the union struck sunday, demanding an increase in residuals from movies and television shows distributed in foreign countries and rejecting a producers' offer to reformulate residuals from the syndication of one-hour tv shows
in new york, the screen actors guild and the american federation of television and radio artists announced a march 21 strike deadline for the american association of advertising agencies and the association of national advertisers
union members, working under a contract extension, voted march 2 to authorize a walkout. the last strike of its kind lasted seven weeks in 1978-79
there was no answer thursday night at the new york offices of the american association of advertising agencies
the complicated relationship between the ethereal blanche du bois and the earthy stanley kowalski in tennessee williams' ``a streetcar named desire'' is one of the most fascinating in the american theater
blanche, the epitome of neurotic southern gentility, flutters to her doom at the hands of stanley, her crude but practical brother-in-law. it's a destructive flight, one that she resists until the very end of the play but then accepts almost willingly
that strange bond between the two is ignored in the new, straightforward revival of williams' classic drama that opened thursday at broadway's circle in the square theater
this ``streetcar'' is riding on one rail _ blythe danner's dangerous, on-the-edge performance as the desperate blanche. just when you think she may veer out of control, miss danner takes charge
the actress recites williams' poetry _ and that's what much of his dialogue is _ with an intensity that is very moving. she also can handle the more lurid permutations of the plot, bringing a conviction to melodramatic moments such as as the story of the death of her young husband. it's a commanding portrait
that conviction is lacking in aidan quinn who plays stanley. quinn is an intelligent actor but he's miscast, both physically and vocally
his stanley is brash rather than brutish, more wise guy than tough guy. that approach works when he's playing poker with his pals, but when he comes up against an aggressive blanche, quinn falters
blanche keeps referring to stanley as ape-like, but quinn's characterization is anything but animalistic. he's too boyish and bears more than a passing resemblance to the young newsboy blanche attempts to seduce late in the first act
blanche and stanley become little more than a bickering couple. their lack of electricity doesn't ruin the production, but it does make this revival a lopsided, unsurprising evening of theater
danner works better with frank converse, who projects an innate decency as mitch, stanley's good friend and blanche's one last chance. there's a genuine regret about their inability to make something of their relationship. equally appealing is frances mcdormand, a ripe, voluptuous stella who gamely puts up with stanley's crudeness because she loves him
nikos psacharopoulos, the country's foremost interpreter of williams' plays, directs at a leisurely pace. between scenes, there are a lot of saxophone moans in the night. designer john conklin spills a french quarter setting, much of it wrought iron, across the elongated stage to create an evocative new orleans apartment
the set is tantalizing and so is miss danner. she just doesn't have anyone to go up against
in other reviews:
frank rich of the new york times called the production ``a staging that may not deface williams's masterpiece but often sanitizes it. ..
what is most absent from the evening, and not just in blanche and stanley's showdown, is sex. miss danner and mr. quinn _ both fine actors, both erotic figures in other circumstances _ shed no sparks here.''
in the daily news, howard kissel writes that the production lacks ``a sense of an old world decaying, of desire hanging palpably, urgently in the air. ... without this tangled undergrowth of anxiety and nervous longing, the play loses its force.'' case</head>
the prosecutor who handled the big dan's pool-table rape trial says he hopes a state supreme court ruling affirming the convictions will end the furor touched off by the case
it was a worldwide case. literally the whole world was watching,'' bristol county district attorney ronald pina said thursday after the high court affirmed the convictions of four men in the 1984 trial
if anything, it has heightened the awareness of rape victims that they can come forward and testify. they now know that they should report rapes,'' he said
in a pair of unanimous rulings, the massachusetts supreme court turned aside defense objections on pina's handling of evidence, judge william g. young's decision to avert television cameras from the victim and other issues
the victim's dramatic account of the barroom rape and the lengthy televised trial in superior court drew national attention to the working-class neighborhoods of new bedford, where the attack occurred, and sparked an intense debate over rape
the case also brought agony to new bedford's large portuguese-american community. the six young men charged in the case were of portuguese descent, as was the victim
the high court upheld the punishments handed out to daniel silvia, john cordeiro and victor raposo, who were sentenced to nine to 12 years in the state maximum-security prison at walpole, and joseph vieira, who drew six to eight years. the two other defendants were acquitted
the victim died in a car crash outside miami in december 1986 at age 25
according to court records, she entered big dan's tavern on march 6, 1983, to buy cigarettes. she ordered a drink, spoke with another woman and watched a game of pool. when she declined an offer of a ride from cordeiro and raposo, the court said, she was knocked down, dragged to the pool table and raped
prices on the tokyo stock exchange fell 74.09 points in heavy trading today, while the u.s. dollar fell slightly against the yen
traders said most of the 1.8 billion shares traded involved the top 10 stocks, prompting concern that investors were again turning to speculation to fuel the market
the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues fell 0.02 percent to close at 25,543.73, after gaining 12.43 points on thursday
the dollar closed at 127.80 yen, down 0.40 yen from thursday's close
stephen jennings, a salesman for kleinwort benson, said trading today was concentrated in two stocks, nippon steel and ihi, accounting for a half a billion shares
there is a fear that quality is deteriorating,'' and that much of today's trading was based on speculation, jennings said
he said investors are now looking toward the u.s. trade figures to be released later this month
another dealer at a major commercial bank in tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the currency market ``generally remained listless'' and said the market is waiting for the release of u.s. retail sales and producer price figures. ^by michael west</byline>
newspapers clamored today for prince charles and other royals to abandon dangerous pursuits after the 39-year-old heir to the british throne narrowly escaped an avalanche that killed a close friend
charles is the next king .... that means he must be ... safeguarded, if need be from himself,'' the daily mirror admonished in an editorial
it said charles as well as prince andrew and his wife, the duchess of york, took ``unnecessary risks.''
the royals have a duty to play it safe,'' the newspaper added
charles' 28-year-old brother, andrew, was catapaulted off the deck of the u.s. carrier nimitz in a jet fighter when he and the 28-year-old duchess visited the united states last week
the duchess, the former sarah ferguson, is expecting the couple's first child in august. she was on a skiing holiday with charles and his wife, princess diana, 26, and friends at klosters in the swiss alps when the avalanche occurred thursday. all are good skiers
sarah, who fell skiing earlier thursday and was advised to rest, was with diana in a chalet when the avalanche struck
andrew, a royal navy helicopter co-pilot in the 1982 falklands war and now a helicopter instructor, missed the holiday because of duties at portland naval based in southwest england
the avalanche killed maj. hugh lindsay, 34, and injured another friend of the royals, patricia palmer-tomkinson
charles, the lead skier, and the rest of his party managed to evade the avalanche. he helped rescue the unconscious mrs. palmer-tomkinson, both of whose legs were broken, and then helped free lindsay's body from under the snow
another tabloid, the sun, demanded: ``why was he there?''
daredevil charles has a passion for pushing himself to the limit on the snow. each time he dons his skis he likes to shake off his tag of pampered prince and prove he is a real man ... charles has consistently risked his life by going on increasingly deadly slopes,'' the sun said
swiss authorities had warned that the area where the royal party was skiing was prone to avalanches
the sun quoted alex broggi, a klosters ski club owner, as calling charles ``incredibly brave.'' broggi added, ``many locals are amazed by the runs he attempts. they wouldn't go anywhere near them.''
the star said in an editorial: ``we don't want our royals to be wimps ... but advisers who should know better must never again lead the heir to the throne into such deadly danger.''
the royals and many of their friends have a pronounced taste for danger and charles once asserted: ``if you occasionally live dangerously it helps you appreciate life.''
the daily mail said: ``the question asked by well-wishers of the royal family is: why do so many of them go in for such perilous sports?'' it urged queen elizabeth ii to ``ask your offspring, for the nation's sake, to show just a little more care.''
charles' other sports include polo and fox hunting. he has injured himself several times in falls from his horse at polo
his father, prince philip, 66, played polo until recently while the 61-year-old queen is an accomplished horsewoman
princess anne, 37, the queen's only daughter, goes fox hunting and occasionally rides in horse races, where accidents are numerous
vice president george bush says he will continue to campaign hard in the illinois primary despite a poll putting him comfortably ahead of gop rival bob dole
i'm not going to be out-hustled as we prepare to go the polls tuesday in illinois,'' bush told a republican dinner on thursday night
a washington post-abc news poll published in today's editions of the post said bush led dole, 58 percent to 31 percent
bush had little to say about major staff cutbacks by the dole campaign, coupled with a move by the dole forces to pull television spots off the air in the state. dole campaign sources said the kansas senator had talked about the possibility of pulling out of the race, but had decided to stay in at least through tuesday's primary here
bush's chief of staff, craig fuller, said the vice president's reaction to reports about dole was: ``we'll go about our business, do our job.''
dole, reeling from a dismal showing on super tuesday, insisted thursday night that he was ``not a dropout'' and would continue to campaign
meanwhile, bush appealed to more than 700 republicans at the champaign county dinner to help him win the state's primary and the 82 gop delegates at stake
he also urged party factions to prepare to put their differences aside
it's important to remember that we are all republicans,'' said bush. ``we shouldn't get so negative we can't close ranks in the fall.''
bush, speaking in one of the nation's top agricultural counties, said as president he would ask that a world economic summit scheduled in france focus on agriculture
he said he would fight for open markets and fair trade so u.s. farmers could sell their products abroad
bush said he would not use food ``as a foreign policy weapon'' as the carter administration did with its 1980 grain embargo, and he said he would oppose protectionist legislation
if you protect a textile industry, the first thing to be retaliated against is american agriculture,'' said bush
earlier, during an appearance in chicago, bush said he was ``tired of being embarrassed'' by scandals surrounding public officials and unethical behavior by high government officials _ though he named no names
he pledged to create a special white house ethics panel and give it ``a new and specific code of ethics.''
when a congressman goes bad or someone in the executive branch violates the public trust, it hurts,'' bush told the governor's club luncheon at the chicago hilton. ``i'm tired of being embarrassed. people at all levels of government should come to serve, not to profit.''
bush has steadfastly refused to critize any reagan administration officials, including attorney general edwin meese, who is under investigation by several grand juries
former top white house aides michael k. deaver and lyn nofziger have been convicted in court cases involving their lobbying activities after leaving the administration
bush, asked at a news conference whether he was criticizing the reagan administration, said he was not. he added that no one ``has a higher standard of personal ethics than the president _ always above any possible conflict of interest.''
relief worker peter coleridge, released after six days of questioning by palestinian gunmen in lebanon, returned and said the long-term hostages there must be going through something ``very close to hell.''
it was thoughts of my family which kept me going,'' coleridge told a news conference after he was reunited with his wife and three children at heathrow airport on thursday, two days after his captors freed him
coleridge, 44, middle east coordinator of the british charity and relief organization oxfam, was seized in sidon march 3 after taking photographs at the ein el-hilweh refugee camp there
also captured was his syrian aide, omar traboulsi, 31. after daily interrogations, they were both released tuesday
i was very much aware that i was arguing for my life,'' said coleridge. ``if they were in any way not convinced, it wold not have turned out as well as it has.''
i developed quite an interesting kind of relationship with those interrogating me,'' coleridge said. ``i felt that by the end, we had reached quite a level of understanding of what my organization does and the kind of work we get involved in.''
coleridge said the ordeal gave him an insight into what other hostages must be experiencing
they must be going through something very, very close to hell. i wouldn't wish it on anyone at all _ and i had only six days of it.''
i was kept in one room with a blanket and bucket and fed adequately, although i didn't have much of an appetite,'' he said
twenty-two foreigners, including nine americans, are known to be missing in lebanon after being kidnapped
terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, is the longest-held hostage. he was kidnapped march 16, 1985
democratic presidential candidate jesse jackson is calling for a 71 percent increase in spending on drug interdiction and treatment over the 1989 reagan administration proposal
jackson released a detailed position paper thursday saying the government should spend $6.7 billion to fight drugs, a topic which has emerged at the top of his list of campaign issues
it's overrunning our borders, it's undermining our productivity, it's killing our children, it's corrupting our government,'' he said at a campaign stop at wheaton college. ``we must stop the flow of drugs into our country.''
his spending program includes increases in the interdiction budgets of the justice department, customs operations, coast guard, pentagon, and state department, and prevention and treatment programs
for treatment, according to jackson's position paper, he would spend $1.7 billion, compared to $425 million proposed by president reagan
jackson contends the drug issue is a hidden benefit for him in his presidential campaign, because it strikes a responsive chord wherever he speaks about it. he said in an interview last week that the media and political analysts have failed to take note of how important the drug issue is to the american people
jackson tells his audiences that the drug problem is the nation's no. 1 threat to national security, killing young people, corrupting police departments and making banks into partners with drug kingpins
he often asks members of the audience to stand if they know someone who has died because of drugs, who is in jail because of drugs, or who has tried drugs
jackson has previously said he had no specific numbers on how to implement his suggestions to fight drugs. but his new position paper breaks down totals for each government agency
it is time to put up the necessary resources to meet this national security threat head on,'' he said in his statement
we have 325,000 troops in europe but only 269 drug enforcement agents overseas to fight the war on drugs.''
he would tie u.s. foreign and trade policy to the drug problem, persuading drug-producing allies to install new anti-drug programs or face trade and diplomatic penalties. these countries should be rewarded with crop diversification plans and increased u.s. training, equipment and material assistance. he said
jackson proposed a western hemisphere summit on drugs, and said ``international troops may be needed in countries like colombia to deal with the crisis
jackson also would name a cabinet-level ``drug czar.'' and he would beef up the border patrol and other agencies to stop drugs at the border, he said
jackson also proposed a school-based education and prevention program, led by the secretary of education, and a public awareness campaign similar to the one that warns people about the danger of smoking cigarettes
the reagan administration has asked an appeals court to overturn a judge's order barring federal regulations that would cut off funding to family planning clinics that offer abortions or abortion counseling
the administration said it was seeking a reversal from the 1st u.s. circuit court of appeals in u.s. district judge walter ray skinner's march 3 ruling, which declared the regulations unconstitutional
skinner's ruling was announced the day the new guidelines were to have taken effect, and forced the u.s. department of health and human services to order regional offices to suspend enforcing them
that order will remain in effect while the appeal is considered, said hhs spokeswoman lucy eddinger
in a memo accompanying his ruling, skinner said the regulations violated a woman's right to choose to have an abortion and her first amendment rights to free speech
federal judges in colorado and new york had issued temporary injunctions against the regulations, but skinner was the first to rule on their constitutionality, and said his order applied nationwide
he granted an injunction requested by the state of massachusetts, the national family planning and reproductive health association and 13 other local and national family planning groups
about 5 million low- and moderate-income women receive services at 4,000 clinics nationwide which would have been affected by the regulations announced last month by hhs secretary otis r. bowen
the new rules would have prevented federally funded family planning programs from providing abortion counseling, abortion referrals, and engaging in lobbying or legal action to increase the availability of abortions
if a clinic performed abortions, it would have been forced to maintain separate facilities for each type of patient if it wanted to continue to receive funding under title x of the public health service act of 1970. panama</head>
japanese banks will ``wait for the time being'' for overdue interest and principal payments by panama of $40.6 million in bonds, a japanese banking official said today
panama missed thursday's deadline for the payments owed to an unspecified number of japanese commercial banks _ $39.06 million in principal and $1.56 million in interest, said a bank of tokyo official who insisted on anonymity
the bank of tokyo, along with yamaichi securities co., are the lead agents for the 10-year bonds, which panama issued in march 1978
we will wait for the time being as the panamanian side has recently confirmed it is delaying the payments'' because of a freeze on panamanian assets held by u.s. banks, the official said
according to japanese banking sources, panama earlier told its japanese creditors a freeze in u.s. aid money to the country in the wake of a confrontation between washington and the military regime of gen. manuel antonio noriega would make it difficult to honor the transaction
the united states is attempting to oust noriega, who has been indicted in florida on drug trafficking charges
doctors continue to perform ``archaic'' circumcisions on newborn males, forsaking anesthetics because of misguided notions that their tiny patients do not feel pain, a new study concludes
dr. howard stang, a minneapolis pediatrician, said the findings were not new, ``but the most important thing is this _ if it's going to be done, it ought to be done humanely.''
about 3{ million children, roughly half of them males, are born in the united states each year
stang and four colleagues, whose study was reported in today's journal of the american medical association, estimate that between 60 percent and 80 percent of the male infants are circumcised within days of their births _ and that virtually all of those children are circumcised without anesthesia
years and years ago, there was a feeling in the (medical) community that infants don't suffer,'' stang said. ``we now know that just isn't true. as pediatricians, we're trying to get this across to the obstetricians and family practitioners who handle the bulk of these surgeries
i guess it's custom, and customs die hard,'' he added in a telephone interview. ``the sad thing is that the law requires animals, for example, to have anesthesia before surgery, but we don't extend that same humanity to our own kids.''
in the study, 60 newborns who were to be circumcised were randomly divided into three groups of 20 each
the first group received lidocaine as a local anesthetic in a 10-year-old procedure known as a dorsal penile block. the second group also received an injection, but the solution was a placebo. the third group received no injections
researchers found newborns in the lidocaine group cried 23 percent of the time, while babies in the saline and control groups cried 68 percent and 71 percent of the time, respectively, during circumcision
additionally, the study measured how the surgery affected blood levels of cortisol, a chemical secreted by the adrenal gland that shows how much stress the individual is under
the infants given lidocaine showed significantly lower levels throughout the surgery, said stang
stang noted that during the circumcisions of jewish children, infants are given wine as a general anesthetic
that's a start,'' he said, ``but a local anesthetic is better because it's more easily controlled and there are no complications
using the block has been proven to be safe,'' he said, ``but what will make it commonplace is for parents to demand that their doctors do it.''
stang said doctors also may be resisting the procedure because they fear a lack of complications may lead to an increasing number of circumcisions
he said the current rate has held steady since 1970, when both the american academy of pediatrics and the american college of obstetrics and gynecology issued statements that circumcision has no medical value
since then, some insurance companies have classified the surgery as cosmetic and will not reimburse clients
but some new studies may be shifting the tide back,'' stang said. he said there are indications that uncircumcised males may be more prone to urinary tract infections
an earthquake that shook most of costa rica swayed tall buildings in the capital and sent people fleeing from their homes as windows shattered in southern cities, authorities said
there were no immediate reports of injuries in thursday night's quake, which was centered near the panamanian border
the quake occurred at 9:46 p.m. and registered 5.6 on the richter scale, said a san jose's fire official, adding that it was centered near buenos aires _ 70 miles southeast of the capital and 26 miles from panama
the glass windows of many homes broke in the towns of buenos aires, ciudad neily and san isidro,'' said the official, who refused to be further identified. san isidro is 48 miles southeast of san jose. ciudad neily is seven miles from the panamanian border
firefighters in the panamanian city of david said the tremor was felt strongly in the western border provinces of chiriqui and boca del toro, but there were no reports of damage or injuries
the temblor was not felt in panama city
the people ran into the streets terrified in the cities of buenos aires and ciudad neily,'' johnny zamora of the red cross in san jose said
in san jose, tall buildings swayed
definitely the quake was felt practically in all the country,'' the fire official said
the richter scale is a measure of the energy released by an earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. every increase of one number indicates an increase of 10 times in ground motion
an earthquake of magnitude 5 can cause considerable damage. one measuring 6 can cause severe damage, while a reading of 8 indicates a quake capable of tremendous damage
former president jimmy carter says this year's democratic national convention will help produce a strong presidential ticket, unlike recent ``circus'' atmosphere conventions that weakened the nominee
carter, who spent thursday at the u.s. coast guard academy as a hedrick fellow, said he emerged from both conventions that nominated him for president ``weaker than i went in'' because too many delegates used the occasions as platforms for their own issues
democratic conventions were a circus,'' he said at a news conference after conducting an informal class for cadets majoring in international relations and government
we had nominees wounded and bleeding,'' he said, praising the current party leadership for ``making sure delegates are committed to winning _ not just highlighting their own individual causes.''
carter said he can't tell who will prevail at the convention, but it will be difficult for any candidate to get 50 percent of the delegates on the first ballot
i've got an open mind about it,'' he said. ``what happens during the campaign will be an indication of who will do well in november when they run against george bush.''
as if stopping the momentum of his rival democrats wasn't enough to worry about, presidential contender richard gephardt was hard-pressed just to get on the road for a day of campaigning
secret service agents and chicago police struggled for more than 45 minutes thursday to open a burgundy cadillac inside which a gephardt aide had locked the keys
the car was parked at midway airport, where the missouri congressman arrived in the late afternoon in preparation for thursday night's democratic unity dinner
while the agents and police worked on the parked car, gephardt was taken to a nearby office where he had to fend off reporters asking whether his campaign had run out of gas
we're campaigning as hard as we can in illinois, in michigan and in all the other states,'' he said
gephardt, eventually taken away in a second car, declined to predict his finish in illinois' primary on tuesday, but added, ``we're going to do well.''
three days after super tuesday, republican officials say human error skewed the reported results of washington state's precinct-level gop caucuses, but not enough to change the order of finish that put pat robertson on top
robertson won 39 percent of the republican delegates picked tuesday night to attend county or legislative district conventions where another slate of delegates will be picked for the state convention. sen. bob dole won 26 percent and vice president george bush, 24 percent
john meyers, executive director of the state gop, said reporting errors occurred when precinct caucus results were phoned in to the news election service, and that these errors first were noted by the dole campaign
meyers said most involved precinct chairmen reporting straw vote totals rather than the number of pledged delegates they would send to their next convention. others reported delegates and alternates together, he said
the mistakes weren't enough to change the overall results,'' meyers said. ``when you've got almost 4,000 precincts some mistakes are going to be made.''
the result was that nes reported more delegates committed than possible for the 71 percent sample of tuesday night. some precincts didn't report
vance noted that it would be the july 15 state convention when delegates would be allocated and until then, ``no one won here on super tuesday.''
new york gov. mario cuomo is repeating his pledge not to run for president and calling on democratic candidates to support the man who takes the most delegates into the convention
whoever it is, make him the candidate,'' cuomo said thursday. ``if mike dukakis has 41 percent, get everybody together in a room and say, `jesse, gore, gephardt, you came close, but mike's the candidate
why is 51 percent the magic number? let's pick the guy who's ahead after california,'' cuomo said at a news conference in his manhattan office
during a visit to long island earlier thursday, the governor said he won't run for president this year because of a promise he made when he ran for re-election in 1986
he also shot down any ideas of drafting him at the democratic convention in july, saying leaving that option open would be divisive
you're saying, `but then there's no role for you, governor.' that's right. i shouldn't be part of it,'' cuomo said at the world trade center. ``i should've been in the primaries like everybody else if i wanted it.''
cuomo said he has probably missed his chance to become president
since i can't be a candidate this year,'' cuomo reasoned, ``and the democrats are going to win for sure, the democrats will be in office for eight years. that's the end of cuomo.'' concessions</head>
fifty union activists demanding higher pay and reinstatement of fired workers occupied the interior ministry for nine tense hours, then left the police-ringed building under church protection
the roman catholic church was able to mediate the evacuation thursday after a judge inspected the building and confirmed the workers were neither armed nor holding hostages, said monsignor gregorio rosa chavez, the metropolitan auxiliary bishop
the workers solidary coordinate protesters were unable to win any concessions and took a bus, under military escort, to a local church office for the night
officials with the national salvadoran workers unity, the largest opposition union, said soldiers captured and beat their leader, humberto centeno, when he arrived to seek an end to the occupation
both unions are leading opponents of the government of president jose napoleon duarte, who claimed the ministry takeover was part of a recently-discovered guerrilla plan to stir up mass protests in the country
the 50 unionists took over the building to demand a $60 monthly wage hike, reinstatement of dismissed workers and other conditions. they spoke with labor minister lazaro tadeo bernal, but he gave them no satisfaction, said gerardo diaz henriquez, the coordinate's director
centeno had arrived on a bus with several other union activists, who soldiers forced back onto the vehicle before shooting out its window, said guillermo rojas, a workers unity official
one worker was injured by flying glass, he said
duarte, at a news conference with bernal, said the government did not talk with the protesters, who he said would be jailed if captured
the president said the incident confirmed the existence of a rebel plan to widen the scopeof its leftist insurgency by having urban-based mass organizations engage in disruptive activity
the government has said the plan calls for constructing barricades, occupying public buildings, provoking riot police and burning buses and other government vehicles
a soviet envoy rejected a u.s. demand that moscow cut off military aid to afghanistan if washington stops aiding afghan rebels after a soviet troop pullout
moscow's ties to afghanistan are seven decades old and the u.s. demand is tantamount to the soviets calling for an end to u.s. aid to pakistan, said nikolay kozyrev, ambassador-at-large and senior soviet specialist in asian affairs
kozyrev, who spoke to reporters at a news conference thursday, heads a visiting team of soviet specialists to follow the latest round of the peace talks in geneva between pakistan and afghanistan
u.n. undersecretary-general diego cordovez is mediating the 6-year-old peace talks, the latest round of which began march 2
pakistan is representing afghan guerrillas who have been fighting for nine years against the government in kabul, the afghan capital. soviet troops were sent into afghanistan in 1979 to prop up the marxist government
robert peck, assistant deputy secretary of state, is also in geneva to follow the talks and has been in touch with kozyrev. a u.s. mission spokesman said peck had no immediate comment on the soviet's comments
the united states has given the afghan rebels millions of dollars in aid, including ground-to-air stinger missiles claimed to have downed more than 200 soviet and afghan aircraft
kozyrev said the talks ``bogged down'' of pakistan's insistence that an interim government replace the one headed by soviet-backed president najib
he said islamabad will bear the responsibility if there is no final agreement despite completion of all main elements of the ``peace package.''
the interim government, pakistan argues, could guarantee implementation of the settlement and ensure the safe return of more than 5 million afghan refugees from pakistan and iran
kozyrev said the draft agreements from the peace talks do not commit his country to halt aid to the kabul government, except to stipulate that no new troops must be sent to afghanistan after the withdrawal of the estimated 115,000-strong ``limited soviet contingent.''
kozryev avoided a direct answer when asked whether negotiations would continue after next tuesday, the target date set by mikhail gorbachev last month. the soviet leader said that moscow will begin the troop withdrawal may 15 if the settlement is signed by march 15
sources close to the talks said the date was not considered a deadline after which the kabul representatives would walk out
the u.s. demand for ``symmetrical cessation'' of military aid was spelled out at a state department briefing on march 4. it was the latest of seemingly uncoordinated signals from washington concerning the issue
it followed a non-binding resolution, unanimously adopted by the u.s. senate last week, urging the white house to continue such aid until all soviet troops have left
peck said before his departure from washington that a decision on the timing of the cut-off should be left to president reagan
we must not forget that many of the worst nazi hangmen were austrians. there were austrians who were victims and others who were perpetrators.'' _ austrian president kurt waldheim, in a speech marking the 50th anniversary of austria's annexation by nazi germany, apologizing for war crimes committed by his countrymen
my decision to resign was reached with great difficulty as i came to understand how deeply some see the social stature of deaf persons reflected in the presidency of this university,'' elisabeth ann zinser, the newly appointed president of gallaudet university in washington, d.c., resigning after students demanded a hearing-impaired leader for the nation's only liberal arts college for the deaf
we must not go on as if nothing has happened if the initiative is rejected against our will. we must bring it to a decision in elections. we may not succeed in this but it is our moral duty to do so.'' _ israeli defense minister yitzhak rabin, urging fellow labor party officials to demand new elections if conservative prime minister yitzhak shamir rejects the u.s. peace initiative in the middle east
in a dramatic speech in parliament, an independent deputy demanded the truth be told about the world war ii massacre of 4,000 polish officers in a forest in the soviet union
the official version is that nazi troops committed the katyn forest massacre, but many poles blame the soviet union
deputy ryszard bender, raising the taboo issue for the first time in parliament, said thursday that full disclosure is needed if poland and the soviet union are to have genuinely friendly relations
the word `katyn' must be spoken out in this high chamber,'' said bender, addressing foreign minister marian orzechowski. ``this is required by the honor of the polish people, by its martyrdom throughout'' the war
bender spoke after orzechowski praised a soviet-polish agreement on ideological cooperation signed last year that stresses the need for a more truthful history of polish-soviet relations
bender said soviet interests were not served by ``making poland a dependent nation'' but by having ``a sovereign, self-governing, economically strong poland'' as its neighbor
he said the friendly relations between poland and the soviet union ``must be genuine ... not just facade-like propaganda.''
on tuesday, 59 polish opposition activists and intellectuals, including solidarity leader lech walesa, issued an open letter appealing to soviet intellectuals to speak out about katyn
bender called on communist authorities to open up to historians archives of classified documents so ``blank spots'' in polish-soviet relations can be filled. he said these included the 1939 non-aggression pact through which the soviet union and germany divided poland
that september, the nazis invaded from the west and the soviets from the east. tens of thousands of poles were deported to siberia
there are persons in this chamber with painful experiences of those deportations,'' said bender
the phrase ``blank spots'' has become shorthand in poland for topics so controversial that go unmentioned or are distorted in official histories
last week, a joint soviet-polish commission of communist party historians met in warsaw to review research on the ``blank spots.''
the panel discussed such sensitive topics as the fate of poles deported to the soviet union in 1939-41, but reported no progress in elucidating all the circumstances behind the katyn massacre
polish and soviet official versions of the massacre say the 4,000 officers whose bodies were found in the forest near smolensk were murdered by the nazis in 1941 after they invaded the soviet union
most poles and western historians maintain the officers were slain in 1940 on orders of soviet dictator josef stalin
the 4,000 were among 15,000 polish officers detained after the soviets invaded poland and held in three separate camps in western russia. the fate of the remaining 11,000 officers has never been revealed, and the issue remains a sensitive point in polish-soviet relations
in his speech, orzechowski said the ideological cooperation agreement ``will be conducive to overcoming the negative phenomena which have accumulated in history'' between two countries
he said poland fully supported the ``revolutionary changes'' being introduced by soviet leader mikhail gorbachev, adding that polish-soviet relations are ``closer than ever before.''
peace corps officials they're anxious to begin negotiations with the chinese to set up the terms of a program under which agency volunteers for the first time will serve in that nation
arlen erdahl, directing of recruiting for the peace corps, said thursday that applicants started phoning the corps within hours of the announcement a day earlier that china would begin accepting peace corps volunteers
though the concentration is likely to be on english teachers, china still must decide what special skills it wants the volunteers to have, where they will serve and how large the peace corps program would be
erdahl said the agency will have to put volunteers for the program through a rigorous testing program that rejects four out of five applicants
cpl. arnold bracy, a marine embassy guard who for a time figured prominently in last year's moscow spy scandal is leaving the military next month, and a source said he would be honorably discharged
the marine corps announced thursday that bracy, 22, of woodside queens, new york city, will be formally discharged on april 4. a marine official who asked not to be named said bracy would receive an honorable discharge
bracy served as an embassy guard in moscow with sgt. clayton j. lonetree, 26, who was convicted last august of passing classified information to soviet agents after becoming involved with a russian woman
for a time last spring, bracy also faced a military court-martial because navy and federal agents were convinced he had conspired with lonetree and allowed russian kgb agents inside the embassy late at night to roam at will
those allegations were based in part on a confession signed by bracy after a lengthy interrogation. bracy later recanted that statement, saying it had been coerced, and all charges against him were dropped when military lawyers concluded they did not have any corroborating evidence to prosecute
the retiring head of nasa's space station program is warning that the program could be destroyed if money budgeted for that purpose is diverted to pay for an unmanned scientific and manufacturing facility in space
andrew stofan told a house subcommittee thursday he would oppose any attempt to take money from the space station budget to pay for a commercially developed ``industrial space facility.''
i see no use for it (the isf) as far as developing the space station is concerned,'' said stofan, who is retiring after 30 years at the national aeronautics and space administration
meanwhile, rep. edward p. boland, d-mass., told a house appropriations subcommittee that more money is needed for housing programs next year and that if the money is not allocated, then congress will ``kiss goodbye to the space station.''
boland's subcommittee handles financing for housing programs as well as independent agencies including nasa
the chairman of a house subcommittee says fraud, overcharging and kickbacks are rampant among clinical laboratories, and witnesses at a hearing called for better federal oversight
rep. john dingell, a michigan democrat who chairs the house energy and commerce subcommittee on oversight and investigations, said at a hearing thursday that problems are ``rampant in this industry and federal oversight has been non-existent.''
witnesses at the hearing said unregulated laboratory procedures have resulted in problems such as a 20 to 40 percent error rate in pap tests used to detect cervical cancer in women
other problems include piecework pay systems that encourage production at the expense of careful diagnosis and pressure to accept inadequate specimens and call them negative so doctors won't send their business elsewhere, said shirley greening, representing the american society for cytotechnology
she and others recommended mandatory proficiency testing for all diagnostic lab technicians, workload limits, more federal money to monitor labs through the medicare and medicaid programs, and required public disclosure of lab caseload volume, staffing, fees, quality control methods and results
the rev. jerry falwell says scandals involving tv preachers jim bakker and jimmy swaggart have strengthened broadcast evangelism and made christianity stronger, more mature and more committed
christian television ministries that put their financial and doctrinal houses in order will survive and prosoper, falwell told the national association of evangelicals on thursday
in five years, ``most of the evangelical ministers that are playing on top of the table will be stronger than they are today,'' the fundamentalist preacher said in his first appearance before the group, which represents 50,000 churches in 72 denominations. falwell is not a member of the nae
you need not be embarrassed by what has happened ... just more sensitive,'' he told hundreds of applauding delegates. ``this is a time to regroup, judge ourselves and march on with a greater intensity than before
the cause of christ is now better off'' because of bakker and swaggart's problems, falwell said, comparing the scandals with watergate and politics
in the days ahead, it is going to be tougher for national leaders (of tv ministries) to misbehave,'' just as the watergate crisis resulted in governmental and political reforms, he said
bakker, who admitted a tryst with a church secretary and who has been accused of financial improprieties, was expelled from the assemblies of god church. after bakker resigned as head of ptl, falwell headed the ministry for several months before stepping aside
swaggart, who has been accused of paying a prostitute to perform lewd acts, was suspended by the denomination and expects to return to the pulpit
the scandals have led to a new code of moral and financial ethics for religious broadcasters
i think the days of the rolls royces and rolexes ... the days in which social status is gauged by financial trappings are over,'' said falwell, whose ``old time gospel hour'' is broadcast worldwide on 350 television stations
he said the swaggart controversy had little effect on his own ministry, and he didn't believe that it had the more serious impact of the bakker revelations on the religious broadcast industry
however, he said that if the events surrounding swaggart and bakker had involved him, billy graham or other more conservative ministers ``we would be out looking for other employment.''
i'd rather be dead'' than be immoral, said falwell, a founder of the moral majority and pastor of the 21,000-member thomas road baptist church in lynchburg, va
falwell praised former television evangelist pat robertson, but said he endorsed vice president george bush for the presidency even though falwell advised president reagan not choose bush as his vice president
the preacher said he would like to see u.s. rep. jack kemp run for vice president. the republican new york congressman pulled out of the presidential race thursday after a poor showing in primary and caucus races
falwell is a registered democrat, but said, ``i can't think of a single democrat running this year who i could hold my nose and vote for.''
