glenn cunningham, who overcame a crippling childhood injury to become america's premier middle distance runner in the 1930s, is dead at age 78
cunningham died thursday at his exotic animal preserve near menifee, which he maintained as a retreat for troubled youngsters
as long as you believe you can do things, they're not impossible,'' cunningham said in an interview 10 years ago. ``you place limits on yourself mentally, not physically
people say something's never been done, so it can't be done. but that's not so. it's never been done because no one has set about the task of doing it.''
cunningham's greatest task was to walk after the severe injuries he received in a 1917 schoolhouse fire that killed his older brother, floyd. doctors feared the extensive damage to the 7-year-old cunningham's legs might require amputation and surely would prevent him from walking
cunningham proved them wrong. not only did he walk, he ran as fast as any miler of his generation, persevering through almost constant pain
i was 179 pounds, too heavy for a runner,'' he recalled a few years ago. ``i also had broken-down arches, bad legs and such badly abscessed teeth _ eight of them _ that doctors didn't see how i could walk. i never knew when my teeth would cause me great pain. but i just knew i could do it _ run and win.''
he set a world outdoor record of 4 minutes, 6.7 seconds in the mile at princeton, n.j., in 1938. his indoor best of 4:04.4 wasn't recognized as a record because it was considered a paced race, a practice which became acceptable only after cunningham had retired
cunningham, a native of elkhart, kan., who later attended kansas university ran the 1,500 in two olympics, finishing fourth in the 1932 games at los angeles and winning the silver medal in the 1936 games at berlin
cunningham six times won the prestigious wanamaker mile in the indoor millrose games at new york. he won it the first time in 1933, the year he was voted the sullivan award as the best amateur athlete in the united states
he won 21 of his 31 races at madison square garden, set six world records at 1,500 meters or one mile and another at 1,000 yards
in 1979, cunningham was voted best track athlete in the 100-year history of madison square garden, and on feb. 28 returned to the millrose games to run a lap during a commemorative ceremony
after a tour with the navy in world war ii, cunningham and his wife, ruth, bought an 840-acre ranch near wichita, kan. cunningham tended exotic animals and he and his wife cared for any wayward or troubled child sent his way
we have worked 18 hours a day, seven days a week, to rehabilitate 9,000 wayward or orphaned youths who passed through our care,'' said cunningham, who had 12 children of his own
funeral arrangments were incomplete
retired air force maj. gen. richard secord, a key figure in the iran-contra scandal, denied any knowledge of an alleged reagan administration plot to infiltrate the organizations of political extremist lyndon larouche
secord said thursday he was relaying a message from an associate when, in a memo to former national security council aide oliver north, he mentioned an apparent effort to collect information against larouche
secord, a principal in north's private contra supply network, said in a telephone interview that he was not aware of any government plot to infiltrate larouche organizations
defense lawyers for larouche and his supporters, on trial here on fraud and conspiracy charges, contend larouche was a target of the fbi and cia. they cite the north-secord memo and other documents as support for the claim
the defense lawyers contend that north, the marine lieutenant colonel fired for his role in the iran-contra scandal, supported the cia and fbi infiltration as part of a reagan administration plot to ruin larouche because he opposed aid to the contra rebels in nicaragua
in addition to the secord-north memo, larouche defense lawyers have been given an fbi document, declassified wednesday, that quotes three intelligence operatives as saying they were directed by top fbi and cia officials to infiltrate larouche groups
u.s. district judge robert e. keeton halted trial testimony this week because of the newly discovered documents
he ordered assistant u.s. attorney john markham to review classified fbi files from which the declassified material was taken and determine if additional information should be given to defense lawyers
in a may 1986 memo to north that was declassified this week, secord said he was told by ``our man here'' that retired army sgt. maj. fred lewis ``has collected info against larouche.''
defense lawyers have said the prosecutor in the case told them ``our man'' referred to fbi executive assistant director oliver revell. but secord said he was referring to john cupp, who worked for a company that provided clandestine air transport for government operations, including the contra resupply effort
cupp on thursday agreed with secord's characterization that ``our man'' referred to him, but defense lawyers maintained their position that the reference was to revell
cupp said he had relayed to secord details of a conversation he had with lewis, whom cupp described as a longtime friend
fred came to me and said he had been approached by mr. larouche to conduct some very questionable activities and he kind of went along with it to get information because he thought he was a froot loop,'' cupp said in a telephone interview
he knew i was working in washington and looked me up because he thought i would be able to get the information to an authority who would be able to take some kind of action,'' cupp said
cupp said lewis told him that larouche wanted to rescue dissidents from the soviet union, including andrei sakharov and his wife, yelena bonner
lewis hung around for a while to check him out and see what he was doing but he wasn't doing anything official,'' cupp said
cupp said he agreed to discuss the matter as a favor to secord
the three operatives quoted in the declassified fbi material are lewis, gary howard and ron tucker
larouche, six aides and five larouche political organizations are charged with conspiring to obstruct a grand jury investigation of alleged credit card and loan fraud by larouche followers during his 1984 presidential campaign. four of the organizations also are charged with fraud
defense attorneys claim evidence of the fraud was fabricated by fbi and cia plants in the organizations
a powerful storm system centered near the nebraska-wyoming line churned up snow and wind from the western dakotas across western nebraska and much of wyoming and colorado today
blizzard warnings continued today in eastern wyoming and were issued today for northeast colorado, northwest nebraska and western south dakota
many roads were closed in central and eastern wyoming, where up to a foot of snow was on the ground, winds of 20 to 40 mph gusted to around 50 mph, visibility was near zero at times, and subzero wind chills were reported
in nebraska, the blizzard buffeted kimball, alliance, chadron and sidney, with snow totals ranging to 8 inches southwest of scottsbluff and up to a foot near the wyoming state line
in western south dakota, there were 10 inches of snow on the ground in deadwood. more than 18 inches of snow was expected in the black hills by tonight, and 4 to 8 inches elsewhere in western south dakota
the high country of colorado and utah also received heavy snow, including up to 3 feet thursday at elevations above 6,500 feet in utah
the storm system was expected to move east, spreading snow across much of the northern half of the plains. its effects, however, were felt as far west as southern california, where northerly winds of 25 to 35 mph and gusts to 45 mph occurred in higher elevations
elsewhere, a few snow showers lingered in the mountains of montana and idaho. rain extended from eastern north dakota into northwest minnesota, with snow over northeast minnesota
dry weather prevailed east of the mississippi river, across the southern third of the country, and west of the rockies
late night temperatures were mostly in the teens and 20s over the northern and central rockies and northern nevada. readings in the 20s were also common in the northern and central high plains, and from the lower great lakes across the northern and central appalachians
today's forecast called for strong winds and locally heavy snow across the northern plains and minnesota. strong, gusty winds also were expected in the texas panhandle and the lower and middle mississippi valley. snow showers should linger over the northern and central rockies, and scattered snow was predicted in northern wisconsin and upper michigan
high temperatures were forecast in the 40s, 50s or 60s, except for 20s and 30s from the northern and central rockies across the northern plains into upper michigan, and in western and upstate new york and northern new england. temperatures should reach the 70s in the lower mississippi valley, alabama, florida and the southwest deserts, and 70s and 80s across much of the southern plains
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from 11 at yellowstone park, wyo., to 67 at laredo, texas, and key west, fla
