san juan capistrano, which welcomes migrating swallows every year, has some competition from another southern california city, but the winged creatures returning here buzz instead of flap
the city advisory council recently proclaimed april 1 the ``80th anniversary of the day the flies return to yucaipa,'' according to chairman burrell woodring
in san juan capistrano, the swallows are greeted as they return to an old spanish mission. in this city about 75 miles east of downtown los angeles, some people have suggested an april fools day welcoming ceremony for the flies at an old dump
many blame chicken and horse ranches for attracting the pesky insects, which make their comeback as spring temperatures rise
i think i'd rather have the swallows,'' said council member gary pitts, who also sits on the san bernardino county fly abatement and appeals board. ``you open your door and you're inundated.''
henry miller's typescript of ``tropic of cancer'' sold for $165,000, so aspiring author alan rosenberg figures a manuscript of his new novel should fetch at least $2.75
rosenberg's 415-page bound manuscript of ``run red riding hood run'' is one of 17 items to be placed on the block next month at a new york auction billed as ``the first futures market in literary memorabilia.''
acknowledging that authors whose memorabilia are considered worthy of sale are already famous and usually dead, the 34-year-old portland writer said thursday an investment in a rosenberg memento would give potential buyers ``a chance to get in on the ground floor.''
the items to be offered for auction april 7 include rosenberg's dog-eared dictionary, photos and letters, tapes of his dictated notes, manuscripts of two previous, unpublished books _ and 30 rejection letters from publishers
bids for all items open at $2.75, except for the portable computer on which he wrote his latest work, rosenberg said
the author, who hired a new york publicist and an auctioneer specializing in rare books and manuscripts, admits the event is intended to draw publishers' attention to his new novel
i don't expect to make enough here to cover my costs,'' the author said. ``i do expect to make a point. it's tough to break in, no matter how much talent, determination and patience you have.''
organizers of this mississippi river city's annual barbecue contest say it's time the cookoff was officially titled the world's largest, and they're going whole hog for the billing
the may 12-14 competition is called the world championship barbecue contest, but that title has no independent verfication
the national pork producers council is mounting a cooking contest june 12 in des moines, iowa, and is seeking a nod from the guinness book of world records for the most pork barbecue cooked in a day, said ida eleazer, a program director for the memphis in may festival
the pork producers hope to attract 300 cooking teams and crank out 20,000 pounds of pork barbecue, she said
i guess we've been challenged,'' said becky landers, an organizer of memphis' cookoff
in an informal survey two years ago, the memphis barbecuers cooked 75,000 pounds of pork in two days, ms. landers said
this year, participants will be required to keep records of how much pork they cook
we never really felt like it was an issue before. we knew we were the largest barbecue contest in the world,'' ms. landers said
defense attorneys expressed disbelief after a judge convicted two 13-year-old girls of being accessories in the death of a 12-year-old boy forced to drink lighter fluid and suffocated with a plastic bag
montgomery county juvenile court judge arthur o. fisher on thursday found the girls guilty of involuntary manslaughter and grand theft because they helped two 15-year-old boys get into the apartment of victim antonio r. cooley
i had never envisioned her as anything but a material witness,'' defense attorney daniel o'brien said of his client, whose name, like that of the other youngsters in the case, was not released because of their age
attorney risa mccray, who represented the second girl, said fisher ignored the girls' claims they tried to warn the victim and testimony by a 13-year-old boy backing them up
he even ignored the state's own evidence,'' ms. mccray said
the defense attorneys contended the 13-year-old boy kept the girls in a back room while two older boys killed cooley feb. 8
o'brien said the two older boys had threatened the girls with harm even while in the county detention center
cooley was sprayed with insecticide and forced to drink charcoal lighter fluid before being suffocated with a plastic bag, according to a deputy coroner
fisher said the girls did nothing to alert authorities, although they knew the boys were angry because cooley had denied them use of his videocassette recorder, and knew they intended to beat cooley and steal several items, including the vcr and a stereo
o'brien said he would consider an appeal based on the sentence fisher is to impose on the girls at an unspecified date
fisher could order them held for a year, and state officials then could decide to continue to hold them until age 21, assistant prosecutor debra armanini said
the 13-year-old boy has pleaded guilty to deliquency involuntary manslaughter and theft, and will be sentenced later
the 15-year-old boys face delinquency charges of aggravated murder, aggravated robbery, child endangerment and intimidation, and may be tried as adults
i think the verdict sends a message across this city that the courts are not going to permit anyone, no matter what their age, to take part in a scheme or plan to snuff out another life,'' assistant prosecutor mathias heck jr. said
the girls' mothers sobbed, and one called the verdict unfair
i know she didn't do it,'' the woman said. ``he (fisher) was against them in the very beginning, regardless.'' background on ritalin.</note>
a 15-year-old boy convicted of killing a classmate with a baseball bat ``to know what it was like'' has been sentenced to life in prison, becoming the state's youngest prison inmate
rod matthews could be paroled in 15 years under the mandatory sentence he received thursday after being found guilty of second-degree murder in the nov. 20, 1986, slaying of 14-year-old shaun ouillette
two former friends of matthews testified he told them of planning the killing and took them to see ouillette's body, which police did not find until nearly four weeks later in woods in canton, a suburb 15 miles south of boston
matthews showed no emotion when the verdict, reached after almost 10 hours of deliberations over two days by the norfolk county superior court jury, was announced. throughout the trial he had been expressionless, eyes downcast
the decision satisfied neither the victim's mother, jeanne quinn, nor the defendants' parents
mrs. quinn, carrying a portrait of her son and choking back tears, told reporters she had hoped matthews would be convicted of first-degree murder, which carries a mandatory life sentence without parole
he planned this,'' she said. ``fifteen years. no, i'm sorry, that's wrong. shaun is not coming home in 15 years, is he? he's not ever coming home.''
it's terrible,'' matthews' mother, janice, said on the courthouse steps hours after the verdict. ``a child shouldn't be persecuted and forced to go through something like this
god only knows how much worse it's (prison) going to make his condition,'' she said
matthews takes ritalin for hyperactivity, and defense attorney john philip white argued for acquittal by reason of insanity
ritalin, taken by an estimated 800,000 children, has been a standard treatment for hyperactivity and attention problems for the past 30 years. but the stimulant drug has its critics, including those who say it can cause serious side effects including facial tics, extreme lethargy and stunted growth
white portrayed matthews as a mentally unstable child whose pleas for help were ignored by teachers and friends and whose irrational behavior was possibly exacerbated by ritalin
he was overlooked,'' said mrs. matthews. ``he was overlooked in the third grade, junior high school. we overlooked him because we didn't think there was a problem.''
white, expressing concern for matthews' safety and the possiblity the youth might attempt suicide, said he will try to have the boy moved from prison to a mental health center while considering whether to appeal
an appeal must be made within 30 days, said superior court judge roger donahue
matthews is the youngest of more than 6,500 massachusetts prison inmates, said correction department spokeswoman mary mcgeown
it just doesn't make any sense because there's no treatment facility there,'' said matthews' father, kenneth
prosecutor peter casey, a norfolk county assistant district attorney, called the decision an ``appropriate, well-counseled verdict.''
the case has been compared to that of anthony broussard, 18, sentenced to 25 years to life in 1982, in san jose, calif., for killing his girlfriend in 1981. broussard, who was also tried as an adult, took at least 13 schoolmates to see the body. the movie ``the river's edge'' was based on that case
matthews' trial, which began march 2, was broadcast on a canton cable television station. it was highlighted by graphic descriptions of the slaying and testimony by matthews' former friends, rob peterson and jonathan cash, who said he told them of his desire to kill in the fall of 1986
he said he wanted to know what it was like to kill somebody,'' peterson said
after rejecting two possible victims, matthews chose ouillete, an overweight high school freshman relatively new to canton, because he felt he would not be missed, the youngsters testified
ouillette was lured to the woods after school by the promise of fireworks before being hit at least three times in the head with the baseball bat
matthews took peterson to see the body several hours after the slaying, and they hid a knife matthews planned to use to cut off ouillette's arms and legs, peterson said
several days later, peterson and cash went with matthews to see the body, then went to a pizzeria
police found the body dec. 15, 1986, after receiving an anonymous letter from cash
matthews told a psychiatric counselor after the slaying that he first decided to kill someone after viewing the videotape ``faces of death,'' which shows animal and human deaths.  military involvement. picks up 3rd graf pvs, `the mission...' ^an ap extra</note>
the use of u.s. military personnel to help in anti-drug operations has bolstered bolivia's ability to foil trafficking, but also has shown the difficulties of curtailing a billion dollar industry
there are 30 u.s. military trainers and advisers, sent from the u.s. southern command in panama, now working with bolivian anti-narcotics police units and air force pilots, according to the interior ministry
there have been recent calls in the united states for the military to be deployed in the war on drugs and bolivia is a country in which the use of u.s. soldiers is being tried
the mission is a follow-up to the presence of 175 u.s. soldiers and six black hawk helicopters in july 1986 for a three-month operation known as blast furnace, says david greenly, chief of mission at the u.s. embassy in la paz
blast furnace demostrated that a concerted u.s.-bolivian effort could make a difference in bolivia, that bolivian operations could have a similar impact and we are beginning to see such an impact is possible,'' greenly told the associated press
during the 1986 operation, 22 major cocaine processing labs were destroyed and cocaine shipment and processing were seriously disrupted. farmers could not sell their coca leaves because processing was snarled, and prices dropped from $1.20 a pound of coca leaf to 40 cents, the estimated cost of production
cocaine is processed from the leaves of the coca plant, which peasants in bolivia grow for its profitability
after the troops pulled out in november, coca leaf prices shot up and trafficking operations returned to normal, bolivian and u.s. drug officials say
since then, the u.s. trainers have prepared 720 elite anti-drug police and taught pilots to fly five huey helicopters on loan from the united states. the helicopters, carrying bolivian police, now fly regular missions in the tropical lowlands where cocaine labs are located
bolivian police are disrupting operations in the chapare coca-growing region, where most of the cocaine is processed into paste
this is reflected in a drop in coca leaf prices, the u.s. drug enforcement agency says. it says prices are down to 30 cents a pound of coca leaf, even lower than blast furnace days
the volume of cocaine reaching u.s. and european markets has not decreased and the price of cocaine has dropped, evidence of a glut
bolivian cocaine production, which accounts for one third of what reaches u.s. and european markets, has increased 10 percent a year to an estimated 80 metric tons in 1987, according to a report from the u.s. state department
the cocaine produced in bolivia has a u.s. street value in the billons of dollars, the dea says
despite the concerted effort by bolivian and u.s. forces, traffickers have moved their operations to remote and hidden jungle areas that are difficult to reach by road or even helicopter
the u.s. government, with all its military might, could only make a dent on cocaine operations in bolivia during blast furnace,'' said information minister herman antelo
but he said that dent was important because it showed bolivia was serious about combating cocaine despite political problems that blast furnace caused for the government
during blast furnace, marches were held to protest the u.s. presence and opposition congressmen and political leaders attacked the government, describing the u.s. military presence as an interference in the internal affairs of bolivia
when bolivian police, dea agents and pilots took over the village of santa ananin in october 1986 looking for traffickers, almost the entire town of 5,000 joined in forcing them to leave under threat of death. townspeople knew in advance about their arrival, although officials say the planning was handled with utmost secrecy
bolivian and u.s. officials hope the presence of the 30 trainers, who are based near the city of trinidad in the chapare region, will reduce corruption of officers by traffickers and increase the effectiveness of bolivian police and pilots
two scientists set a world record for concentrating the sun's energy with a homemade silver device that could help make a practical, solar-powered laser, officials said
we consider this a breakthrough because it just hasn't been achieved before,'' said bimleshwar gupta of the u.s. energy department's solar energy research institute in golden, colo., which paid for the $150,000 project
roland winston, a university of chicago physics professor, and philip gleckman, a graduate physics student, used a borrowed mirror and their solar concentrator to focus sunlight to 60,000 times its normal intensity on earth, the university announced thursday
that concentration is about three times the previously achieved range of 16,000 to 20,000 times normal intensity, said gupta, the institute's program manager for solar thermal research
this work opens whole new areas for applications of solar energy,'' he said. ``perhaps the solar concentrator could be used to power lasers.''
most conventional lasers run on electricity, he said. there are no commercially available solar-powered lasers because the technology hasn't been developed to harness the sun's rays efficiently
in theory, gupta said, a solar-powered laser would be cheaper to operate because conventional lasers require large amounts of expensive electricity
and those advantages would be greater in space, he said, where solar energy isn't weakened by clouds and is more accessible than electricity or other types of energy
gleckman, 26, who helped design the solar concentrator on a computer, said scientists have used sunlight to power lasers before, ``but not very efficiently.''
we believe this solar concentrator we've built has the potential to make a more efficient solar-powered laser. ... it would be less costly and more practical,'' said gleckman
the solar concentrator he helped design was made from an ounce of silver in a university machine shop. it is hollow and cone-shaped, about half an inch high and a half-inch wide at the base, he said
it has a one-centimeter opening at the wide end and a smaller opening, measuring about one millimeter, at the tip, gleckman said
the device is fitted with a lens and contains a special oil that boosts light refraction, he said
the 16-inch diameter mirror _ a standard astronomical telescope mirror _ was borrowed from the university's yerkes observatory, gleckman said
the solar concentrator's design was based on the principle of ``non-imaging optics'' developed by winston nearly 15 years ago, the university said
in a test feb. 12 on the roof of a university physics building, the solar concentrator achieved an intensity of six kilowatts per square centimeter, the statement said. the previous record was less than one kilowatt per square centimeter, it said
for the second time in a year, harvard university president derek bok has gone against a majority of tenured law professors and will not recommend tenure for a professor who is an adherent of critical legal studies
the critical studies philosophy _ that the legal system is biased in favor of the rich and powerful _ is an issue that has divided harvard law school
bok, who was dean of the law school before he became president of the university in 1971, announced his decision thursday in the case of clare dalton, 37, who has taught for seven years
my record was strong enough for tenure, and there was political and gender discrimination involved in my being denied,'' she told the boston globe thursday night
bok would not answer questions about the decision, and the prepared statement he issued did not give a specific reason for his action, the newspaper said
the american association of university professors will investigate, according to a spokeswoman in washington. the american association of law schools also has been asked to investigate
last may, bok went against the law school faculty in not recommending tenure for professor david trubek
tenured members of the law school faculty voted 29-20 last spring in favor of granting ms. dalton tenure, four votes short of the two-thirds needed under a rule change earlier in the year
some faculty members say the rule is used by conservative professors to block tenure for faculty with whom they disagree politically. daniel tarullo, who also was recommended by a majority but not a two-thirds vote, was denied tenure then
last october, ms. dalton filed complaints against harvard with the massachusetts commission against discrimination and the federal equal employment opportunity commission
she and a representative of the university asked the state commission not to investigate until bok completed a review of the case. her lawyer, nancy gertner, said ms. dalton has ``an extremely strong gender discrimination case and an extremely strong political discrimination case.''
last december, bok appointed an outside committee to review the case
the globe said that according to a letter bok reportedly sent to law school faculty thursday, the committee and harvard law school dean james vorenberg and two harvard law professors met for seven hours sunday, reviewed ms. dalton's scholarship, and decided that her ``record was not sufficient to merit tenure.''
defense secretary george younger defended british soldiers who shot dead three unarmed ira guerrillas in gibraltar as violence over the slayings erupted in belfast for a fourth night
younger said on the british broadcasting corp.'s television program ``question time'' broadcast from belfast thursday night that the soldiers challenged the three guerrillas before opening fire on sunday
they were challenged, we understand. if you challenge somebody, in that second they convince you that they are about to kill you, my goodness you have a right to defend yourself and my goodness you always should,'' younger said
the killing of the guerrillas, who authorities say were plotting a huge car bomb explosion in the british colony, enraged ira supporters. the irish government has complained about the alleged lack of any attempt to arrest them
on the british mainland, 60 legislators of the opposition labor party and some newspapers have also questioned the slayings
foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe said monday that the guerrillas _ a woman and two men _ were shot when they made movements that made the soldiers involved think their own lives were in danger
witnesses said the soldiers were wearing jeans
the ira said the three guerrrillas were ``on active service,'' a euphemism for a bombing or shooting attack as part of the outlawed group's guerrilla war to end british rule in northern ireland
the mainly catholic ira wants to unite the predominantly protestant province with the overwhelmingly catholic irish republic under socialist rule
the ira commandos were shot in the street by the british soldiers believed to belong to the crack special air services regiment after parking a car near the governor's residence
police said they believed the car was parked to reserve a space for a car bomb that was later found outside the fortress colony on spain territory
violence erupted in roman catholic areas of belfast for the fourth straight night thursday. a press officer at belfast police headquarters said it was markedly lighter than on the previous three nights of rioting
he said an army patrol escaped injury in a bomb attack in west belfast and two vans and a car were stolen and set on fire
he also reported some shooting and a gasoline bomb attack on an ambulance, but said nobody was hurt in any of the attacks and that army explosives experts safely defused two bombs found in the city
the officer, by regulation speaking on condition of anonymity, said that in londonderry, northern ireland's second largest city, catholic youths hurled gasoline bombs at a joint army and police patrol but again nobody was hurt
by friday, 60 of labor's 229 legislators in the 650-seat commons denounced the killings in a motion as ``an act of terrorism.... tantamount to capital punishment without trial.''
the motion charged: ``there was no attempt to apprehend or arrest these people before killing them.''
labor's foreign affairs spokesman, gerald kaufman, has written to howe repeating labor's demand for an inquiry
