six of the nation's nine goals for reducing fatalities from injuries by 1990 will probably be achieved, federal health officials predict
the national centers for disease control reported thursday that the fatality rates from many types of injuries, including car accidents, house fires and drownings, have dropped since 1979, when the u.s. department of health and human services announced its 1990 goals for the nation
however, some rates have not fallen as far as the government had hoped, the cdc said. although some of the 1990 injury-related goals _ reducing deaths from car crashes, childhood household accidents, house fires and gun accidents _ will be met, others _ such as reducing deaths from falls and drownings _ won't
achieving the 1990 objectives ... will require the coordinated efforts of federal, state and local agencies ... academic institutions, professional associations and private entities,'' the atlanta-based cdc said in its weekly report
here, from the cdc report, is a look at the nation's 1990 goals for reducing deaths from injuries, and the progress being made:
_reducing the nation's annual motor vehicle fatality rate, from 23.6 such deaths per 100,000 americans in 1978 to 18 per 100,000 in 1990. by 1984, the rate had fallen to 19.6, and the goal is projected to be met, in part because of a reduction in alcohol-related fatalities
_reducing the motor vehicle fatality rate for children under 15, from nine per 100,000 in 1978 to 5.5. by 1984, the rate had fallen to 6.6, and the goal is projected to be met
_reducing the death rate from falls from 6.2 per 100,000 in 1978 to two. the rate had fallen only to 5.1 by 1984, and the goal is not expected to be reached. people over 65 continue to have high death rates from falls _ for example, in 1984, 10.2 such deaths per 100,000 people age 65-74, and 147 per 100,000 people over 84
_reducing the death rate for children under 15 in home injuries from six per 100,000 in 1978 to five. the 1984 rate was 4.9, already meeting the objective
_reducing the drowning rate from 3.2 per 100,000 in 1978 to 1.5. the rate had fallen only to 2.3 in 1984, and the goal is not expected to be met
_reducing the number of deaths in residential fires from 5,401 in 1978 to 4,500. the objective was reached in 1984, when 4,466 americans died in such fires
_reducing the number of deaths in firearm accidents from 1,806 in 1978 to 1,700. the goal was met in 1984, when 1,668 such deaths were reported
_reducing the suicide rate among 15- to 24-year-olds from 12.1 per 100,000 in 1978 to 11. the rate is going up, not down; it was 12.2 per 100,000 in 1984, up slightly from 1978 and up about 200 percent from 1950. cdc noted that various suicide prevention approaches have been tried in u.s. communities, but their effectiveness is not known
_reducing the homicide rate among black males aged 15-24 from 70.7 per 100,000 in 1978 to 60. this goal will probably be met, according to cdc researcher dr. richard sattin; the rate had fallen in 1984 to 61.5. this goal was set recognizing the high homicide rate among young black men, sattin said, noting that the national homicide rate in 1984 was 8.4 per 100,000 americans
