a haitian colonel accused of conspiring to import 100 kilograms of cocaine into the united states is unlikely to come to trial, u.s. officials have conceded
at present there is no extradition treaty between the united states and haiti,'' ana barnett, an executive assistant to u.s. attorney leon kellner, said thursday after the indictment accusing col. jean-claude paul was unsealed
this leaves a substantial question of how the extradition of colonel paul could be accomplished,'' she said
a statement haiti's president leslie manigat issued thursday through a washington public relations firm called the indictment ``a matter of concern'' that will be handled in haiti by military courts
paul, head of a battalion in the haitian capital of port-au-prince, is accused of conspiring to import 100 kilograms of cocaine into the united states. his brother, antonio paul, and his former wife, marie merielle delinois, also were named as defendants in the indictment
jean-claude paul, 40, had close ties to the military-dominated ruling junta that replaced president jean-claude ``baby doc'' duvalier after he fled the impoverished island nation in february 1986. the officer seldom appeared in public during the junta's two-year rule, which ended when manigat was inaugurated last feb. 7
when he did, it often was to serve as bodyguard for lt. gen. henri namphy, the junta president and now military chief, and brig. gen. williams regala, now defense minister
the indictment charged that in december 1986 the accused traffickers used a landing strip on paul's farm 90 miles from haiti's capital to load and fly the cocaine shipment to the bahamas, where it was lost or stolen
both men named in the indictment are charged with conspiracy to distribute, distribution and attempted importation of cocaine. they could face up to 45 years in prison and $375,000 in fines
ms. delinois, already a federal fugitive after jumping bond on a related march 1987 indictment in miami, faces the same three counts, plus charges of jumping bond and attempting to extort a fellow conspirator with violence. she faces up to 75 years in prison and $410,000 in fines
the extortion count grows out of the unexplained loss of the cocaine shipment on spanish key in the bahamas, where it allegedly was flown from haiti for shipment to the united states
osvaldo quintana, a conspirator and now a principal government witness, went to spanish key in an attempt to locate the cocaine, the indictment said
when he failed to find it, according to the indictment, ms. delinois told him ``his family would be killed if he did not pay at least $250,000 of the money owed for the lost shipment.''
quintana, in a news conference here last month, said there were two attempts on his life by armed haitians, but no shots were fired
quintana has testified for the government at previous drug trials. in january, outside of a federal courtroom, he told reporters he had once seen 9,000 kilograms of cocaine stuffed into duffel bags in the haitian presidential palace during the administration of duvalier. suharto and sudharmono</note>
the parliament today elected a close aide of president suharto as vice president despite opposition from a moslem faction and some members of the military
the five factions in the 1,000-member people's consultative assembly reached a consensus to elect state secretary sudharmono, 61, to the post after the moslem united development party dropped its candidate, jailani naro, who is party chairman
the moslem party had opposed sudharmono
sudharmono's election came hours after suharto was sworn in as president for a fifth five-year term. suharto has been president of indonesia for 22 years
the assembly, the nation's highest policymaking body, unanimously reelected suharto on thursday. he was the only candidate
suharto, 66, reportedly told party members late last month the next vice president should be able to lead the nation should he become incapacitated
sudharmono was nominated by the ruling golkar party, an acronym for the indonesian words ``golongan karya'' or functional group
he was also supported by three other factions in the assembly _ the government-nominated military faction, the government-nominated provincial faction and the nationalist christian indonesian democratic party faction
military sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said some members of the army had opposed sudharmono's nomination and wanted to nominate the newly appointed armed forces commander, gen. try sutrisno, 52, a popular figure and a former suharto aide
the assembly meets every five years to elect a president and vice president and issue a decree on the guidelines for state policies
sudharmono, 61, a retired army lieutenant general, is a military lawyer. he is one of the country's leading bureaucrats after years of government apprenticeship, first under the late president sukarno and then as a founding member of the suharto administration
suharto is expected later this month to form a new cabinet, which will have to tackle economic development and cope with a hefty foreign debt of $42.1 billion
the country's economy was hit hard by the collapse of oil prices, a drop in prices in commodities and the 1983 economic recession
