u.s. military bases here are essential for both nations' defenses, but difficult negotiations are ahead on how much washington will pay the philippines to keep them, a senior american diplomat said today
also today, the military said about 200 communist rebels dressed in fatigues raided a police station, killing three policemen and a civilian before making off with weapons and a radio
the rebels attacked thursday afternoon in the town of st. nicholas in pangasinan province, 100 miles northeast of the capital
in manila, kenneth quinn, the u.s. deputy chief of mission, denied allegations by the philippines' foreign secretary that the united states will step up political pressure on president corazon aquino to extend the current bases agreement
quinn told a civic club that the u.s. installations, including clark air base and the subic bay naval base, contributed to global security and played a major role not only in the defense of the philippines but in providing jobs to filipinos
the bases are important because they provide for our bilateral protection and for the external defense of the philippines,'' quinn said
we think they're important because they make an enormous contribution to the economy of the philippines in terms of the 68,000-plus filipinos who are hired there and the $500 million a year which is spent in your economy,'' he added
quinn described as ``absolutely false'' a claim by foreign secretary raul manglapus that the united states was pressuring mrs. aquino to say whether she wants the bases agreement extended
on thursday, manglapus, who spent more than 10 years as a political refugee in the united states, accused the americans of ``arm-twisting'' mrs. aquino ``because they have decided to stay.''
the current agreement provides that after sept. 16, 1991, the philippines can order the bases closed within one year. mrs. aquino has said she will honor the current agreement but refuses to say whether she will agree to an extension
under the new constitution, any extension must be approved by two-thirds of the 23-member senate and may be subject to a national referendum
the u.s. and philippine governments are to begin reviewing the current agreement within the next two months. filipino officials are expected to demand a substantial increase in the $180 million a year which the manila government receives in aid for use of the bases
quinn said he expected a ``full and frank discussion'' on the issue of compensation, using diplomatic language which refers to tough bargaining
some filipino congressmen have suggested that the united states agree to pay off the country's nearly $29 billion foreign debt as the price for keeping the bases
about 70 members of the radical league of filipino students rallied in front of the senate building today demanding the bases be closed
they carried placards reading: ``save the earth from nuclear destruction; dismantle all u.s. bases.''
on thursday, rep. lorna yap, a member of the house foreign affairs committee, said the panel reached a consensus to enforce a provision of the constitution against nuclear weapons
the constitution states that: ``the philippines, consistent with the national interest, adopts and pursues a policy of freedom from nuclear weapons in its territory.''
some government officials argue the phrase ``consistent with the national interest'' would give mrs. aquino flexibility to allow such weapons at the american bases. others see it as a ban on such weapons
the united states refuses to say whether it maintains nuclear weapons at the installations here
