johnny welch, who has called for a manned space flight to saturn and a requirement that every american perform civil service, captured 34 percent of the vote in the 6th congressional district primary tuesday
he faces an april 12 runoff against n.p. ``pat'' kendrick, and the winner of that race will take on republican incumbent u.s. rep. joe barton
but kendrick and ousted candidate w. alton parish think they've been the victims of some sort of republican conspiracy. registered republicans can vote in either party's primary, as long as they don't cast ballots in both
they did it intentionally,'' charged parish, a fort worth economics professor
there's something very suspicious here,'' he said. ``mr. kendrick and i worked very hard on this campaign. we never took him (welch) seriously. kendrick thought i was his opponent, and i thought he was mine.''
gary koops, barton's press secretary, denied that republicans were behind the voting for welch, and he noted that barton had worked with local officials throughout the district to produce a record-breaking gop turnout tuesday
there was some speculation that perhaps voters confused welch with louie welch, the former longtime mayor of houston who twice waged a high-profile campaign against incumbent kathy whitmire
johnny welch's address and home phone number are listed with the secretary of state's office, and a check with both the telephone book and directory assistance confirmed the number is correct
but calls to the home address have gone unanswered; there is no campaign office listed, and party activists in two districts say they have never heard of welch
welch's three-point platform called for launching a manned space flight to saturn, mandating that every american participate in civil service unless they pay a fee to the government, and feeding and sheltering the hungry and homeless. graf, `the mufti ...' inserts 3 grafs after 15th graf ` in nablus ...,' to update with details of unrest. picks up 16th graf `in gaza ...'</note>
the army blocked off some cities in the occupied territories to media coverage during moslem noon prayers today after destroying at least four homes of suspected palestinian activists
at least five palestinians were wounded during protests in the west bank and gaza, hospital officials and arab reports said
the mufti of jerusalem, the city's top moslem religious leader, issued a statement lashing out at israel for blocking some mosques from worshippers, raiding others and confiscating loudspeakers used to summon palestinians to prayer
the mufti, sheik said adin alami, called on worshippers ``to defend the mosques by all possible means despite the attackers.''
prime minister yitzhak shamir, meanwhile, reiterated his opposition to a u.s. peace plan for the region in the strongest statement he has made so far
shamir, speaking on israel radio, said when he arrives in washington next week he would ``explain to our friend secretary of state george shultz that his plan, as it's seen today, can't solve the problem of peace in our area.''
the army destroyed one home overnight in hebron, 20 miles south of jerusalem in the occupied west bank, and three others in biddya, 30 miles northwest of jerusalem
in hebron, the destroyed home where 22 palestinians live belonged to ahmed mahmoud abdullah kawasmeh, 57, whose 22-year-old son is accused of stabbing an israeli settler from nearby kiryat arba five months ago in jerusalem
the soldiers came. they woke us about 11:30 at night and ordered us out of the house,'' kawasmeh, wearing an arab headdress and wrapped in a ragged blanket, told the associated press
i said, `but my son has not even been tried yet.' but it did not make any difference,'' he said
the latest demolitions brought to 14 the number of palestinian homes destroyed by israeli troops since the unrest began in the territories more than three months ago, the palestine press service said
at least 87 palestinians have been killed by israeli gunfire or beatings during the unrest, and hundreds have been wounded
the army turned back journalists from hebron and nablus, but the clampdown was not as severe as last friday, when roadblocks prevented journalists from entering nearly all major cities, towns and refugee camps in the west bank
friday is the moslem sabbath
in hebron, about 10 israeli settlers with rifles slung over their shoulders patrolled a jewish neighborhood near al ibrahimi mosque during noon prayers
in nablus, the west bank's largest city, noon prayers passed without incident and israeli soldiers kept largely out of sight, although an army helicopter circled overhead
in the southern district of the west bank, 60 of 250 arab policemen resigned after being urged by plo leaflets to quit working for the israelis
in ramallah, about 200 protesters threw rocks at soldiers after noon prayers. soldiers fired rubber bullets and tear gas to quell the demonstrators
the jerusalem post reported, meanwhile, that the army is currently holding about 2,600 palestinian prisoners
in gaza city, the army closed the main al amari mosque for the first time, creating what palestinian residents said was ``deep anger'' in the city. some 2,500 worshipers usually pray at the mosque
in other mosques in gaza city, special ``salat al ghaib'' or ``prayers for the missing'' were held at the order of the plo to honor the palestinians who have been killed by israelis since the uprising began
in jerusalem, about 200 palestinians protested after noon prayers at the dome of the rock and al aqsa mosques, raising several palestinian flags, which have been outlawed by israel
on thursday, foreign minister shimon peres said the jewish state would lose an opportunity to make peace by passing up the shultz initiative
peres, head of the left-centrist labor party, said upon receiving an honorary doctorate from hebrew union college in jerusalem that israel would be making a fateful decision in the next few weeks
in 40 days time there is a chance that direct negotiations may start between a jordanian-palestinian delegation and an israeli delegation,'' he said. ``in 40 days we may lose the opportunity as well, and the grayness of hesitation, of suspicion, of postponement may cover our skies again for time to come.''
shamir flies to washington next week to discuss the initiative one more time before announcing whether he accepts it or not
the plan calls for negotiations on the final status of the occupied lands to begin in december, elections for palestinian self-rule in the west bank and gaza strip by late 1988 and implementation of self-rule for palestinians in three years. parliament. corrects spelling of fascism. edits to tighten. no pickup.</note>
austria today marked the 50th anniversary of its annexation by nazi germany, capping a bitter two-year debate about its world war ii past that has polarized politics at home and tarnished its image abroad
about 60 protesters gathered outside the chancellery to demand the resignation of president kurt waldheim. members of the liberal greens party boycotted a special parliamentary session marking the annexation, known as the anschluss
during world war ii, waldheim served as a lieutenant in a german army unit in the balkans that has been linked to nazi atrocities. he has denied any wrongdoing
fewer than 100 people turned out in a light rain as waldheim and other political leaders laid wreaths in separate ceremonies at monuments honoring austria's unknown soldiers and victims of fascism
during the ceremonies a dozen protesters gathered outside the chancellory building 500 yards away, carrying a banner that asked: ``who will make waldheim resign?''
until two years ago, waldheim had not admitted that he served in the balkans unit. since then, he has resisted mounting pressure to resign
greens delegates handed out pamphlets saying they were protesting waldheim's presence at the hour-long session. the pamphlets said waldheim ``is not representative of the austria that we want to commemorate.''
the greens said they would instead travel to mauthausen, site of a former nazi concentration camp near the city of linz, to honor the victims of nazi germany
chancellor franz vranitzky told a special cabinet session that the events of 1938, when this alpine nation was forcibly annexed to adolf hitler's third reich, were a central theme of austrian politics today
the events of 50 years ago pose relevant, fundamental questions about the essence of politics,'' vranitzky said. ``if one attempts to avoid them, they sooner or later return with greater emphasis.''
vranitzky said austrians must recognize that crimes were committed by their countrymen during world war ii
we must recognize the fact of historical guilt ... because as politicians we must draw lessons from the past failures of society,'' he said
vranitzky did not mention the waldheim controversy
waldheim, originally to speak at a hofburg palace ceremony, was to remain out of the spotlight throughout the day
instead, waldheim commemorated the annexation with a nationally televised speech thursday in which for the first time he apologized for crimes committed by austrian nazis during the war. but he ignored the debate surrounding him
we must not forget that many of the worst nazi hangmen were austrians,'' waldheim said in the 12-minute speech. ``there were austrians who were victims and others who were perpetrators.''
the president added that ``as head of state of the republic of austria, i wish to apologize for nazi crimes committed by austrians.''
austria's nazi past _ largely suppressed here over the past four decades _ has dogged this country since the disclosure in march 1986 of waldheim's wartime service in the balkans
as a result, the u.s. justice department last year placed waldheim on a list that effectively bars him from entering the country
in april 1938, the nazis said 99 percent of austrians approved of the anschluss in a nationwide vote widely believed to have been rigged
more than half a million austrians joined the nazi party, and 250,000 turned out to cheer hitler when he came to vienna shortly after the anschluss
last month, an international panel of historians found that waldheim had been in ``close proximity'' to war crimes during world war ii, knew they were going on and made no attempt to prevent them
the panel's report did not support allegations waldheim committed atrocities, but left open the question of whether he was guilty of any crime. waldheim claimed the report vindicated him
a violent jamaican crack ring that operated in new york, philadelphia and washington and was responsible for a series of murders and other brutal crimes has been smashed by the arrests of several alleged drug dealers, authorities say
the arrests were the result of an intensive investigation focusing on an epidemic of murders and shootings by jamaican drug rings in brooklyn, said u.s. attorney andrew maloney on thursday
the alleged ringleader, described as ``one of the most feared crack organization enforcers in the nation,'' and six others were named in federal complaints, maloney said. one defendant remains at large
the level of trafficking has risen and the level of violence by jamaican posses is very high,'' said robert stutman, head of the federal drug enforcement agency's new york office
the 50-member drug ring dealt up to $100,000 of crack, a highly addictive cocaine derivative, each day in brooklyn alone, maloney said. the ring, which had been in operation since 1983, also allegedly ran less extensive operations in philadelphia and washington
the complaint alleged the defendants were responsible for five murders, 15 shootings, one abduction and one beating
the leader was identified as delroy ``uzi'' edwards, 29, of brooklyn, who is a jamaican national. edwards, who drove a mercedes, got his nickname because he used to carry a submachine gun under his trenchcoat, authorities said
edwards allegedly murdered two of his dealers in washington because one of them had stolen money from the organization, the complaint said. he also allegedly shot and injured three new york members for the same reason
another grisly murder described in the complaint was that of a man who was beaten with baseball bats and then tied with chains to the ceiling of a crack location. the next morning the man was found dead, his body wrapped in garbage bags and dropped off on a street
after his arrest on a brooklyn street corner wednesday, edwards was turned over to the brooklyn district attorney's office, where he was wanted on an outstanding warrant for an unrelated murder
the other defendants were identified as patrick williams, erroll thorpe and ricky nelson, all jamaicans; and john barry russell, conroy green and stanley mccall, who were said to be u.s. citizens
assistant u.s. attorney jonny frank said there was only sketchy information about the defendants, but that most were in their 20s and they all lived in brooklyn
mccall is the only defendant still at large, frank said
stutman said violent jamaican drug rings known as ``posses'' can be found in many eastern cities
they are constantly seeking out new weapons or tactics,'' he said. ``more and more, especially the jamaicans, are starting to shoot back at police.'' iran. picks up 9th graf, `the agency ...' edits to tighten thereafter.</note>
iraq said it fired 11 missiles today into tehran and qom, seat of iran's religious hierarchy, undermining efforts to halt the 12-day-old bloody ``war of the cities.''
the official iraqi news agency also said iraqi warplanes bombed a tanker off the iranian coast
the news agency, monitored in nicosia, reported that the 11th missile was fired at the iranian capital at 3:44 p.m., 16 minutes before baghdad had said it would stop its deadly barrages on iranian cities
iraq had offered to end the bombardments if iran halted its barrages on baghdad and other iraqi cities. baghdad also demanded that it be allowed to fire the last shot
in all, the iraqi agency said eight missiles were fired into tehran today and three into qom, 60 miles south of the iranian capital
iran's islamic republic news agency confirmed five of the attacks and said there were numerous casualties
the agency said that in one attack, homes of two jewish families surnamed odishiv and roshan were demolished, killing and wounding women and children
there were no reports of iranian attacks on baghdad. but the iraqi news agency said iranian f-4 phantom jets struck hard at residential targets in the northern iraqi city of sulaymaniya, killing and wounding several civilians
it also said basra, in southern iraq, and a cluster of towns along the border were shelled by iranian long-range artillery, but gave no precise casualty figures
iraq said that during the night its warplanes bombed a ``large maritime target,'' a reference to an oil tanker, off the iranian coast, and seven iranian cities today _ baneh and ardabil in the north, kermanshah and hamadan in the west; arak and broujerd in central iran; and dezful in the southwest
the agency did not identify the stricken ship, but said the planes ``scored accurate and effective blows'' on all their targets
iran's agency confirmed the raids on the cities, saying they were aimed at civilian targets
this is a further proof to the tehran rulers, who are filled with evil intentions and hatred, that they should not have started the war of the cities,'' the iraqi news agency said
it said the attacks ``were designed to avenge the innocent blood shed in baghdad'' and other iraqi cities in the unprecedented missile duel
before today, iran and iraq had claimed firing 78 missiles at each other's capitals since feb. 29. fifty-one were fired by iraq at tehran and 27 by iran at baghdad
according to the iranian agency, the previous attacks on tehran have killed at least 157 civilians and wounded more than 420. iraq has not provided exact casualty figures
several missiles have struck other iranian cities, including qom and central isfahan, while iranian gunners kept up a steady barrage of artillery fire on iraqi border communities
turkish prime minister turgut ozal said in ankara that iran and iraq had agreed to halt the duels at his request
iraq announced thursday that it would stop attacking iranian cities at 4 p.m. baghdad time today, which is 4:30 p.m. tehran time
iran gave two times thursday when it said it would stop its attacks, but both deadlines passed with continued attacks. today, however, iran has not reported firing any missiles
iran's u.n. envoy, mohammad ja'afar mahallati, offered to honor an unconditional truce if the u.n. chief called for one
mahallati told a news conference in new york that iran would not fire back if iraq got in the last shot before any deadline set by u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar
perez de cuellar had no immediate comment. retail sales reports, picking up 3rd graf pvs, `declining issues ....'</note>
declines in the costs of food and energy pushed wholesale prices downward last month, while retail sales were boosted by strength in autos, the government said today
wholesale prices fell 0.2 percent in february, the labor department said as it released its monthly producer price index
food prices fell 1.1 percent and energy prices declined 0.8 percent, the department said
for the first two months of 1988, prices rose at an annual rate of 1.1 percent, half the modest 2.2 percent rate for all of last year. prices rose 0.4 percent in january after a 0.4 percent decline in december
meanwhile, the commerce department said retail sales rose 0.6 percent in february. the increase was generally in line with expectations
the government also revised its january retail sales report to show a small decline of 0.2 percent instead of an originally reported increase of 0.5 percent
even with the january decline, analysts said the sales report generally reflected that the october stock market crash has had little effect on consumer buying plans
since consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of overall economic activity, any significant faltering in this area could topple the country into a recession
on thursday, nervousness over wall street's strength yanked down stock prices, but pessimism disappeared in the energy markets, where oil futures rose sharply over expectations that opec will take steps to avert another 1986-style price collapse
the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 48.24 points to 2,026.03, its largest loss since falling 57.20 on jan. 20. broader market indicators also declined
declining issues outnumbered advancers by nearly 3 to 1 on the new york stock exchange, and the wilshire 5000 equity index measuring the value of 5,000 u.s. stocks fell nearly $40 billion
analysts said the selloff reflected continued anxiety about the aftermath of the oct. 19 market crash, which persistently has undermined investor confidence
the mood contrasted sharply with a buying spree on the new york mercantile exchange, where contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the main u.s. crude, rose 51 cents to close at $16.00 a barrel. refined products traded on the exchange also rose sharply
petroleum analysts linked the oil rally to reports that the organization of petroleum exporting countries _ aware it can't sustain relentless price discounting and excessive output _ will shave 5 percent off the production of all members except iraq, which has resisted cartel discipline
the reports reflected hopes that after three months of price erosion reminiscent of the cataclysmic market plunge two years ago, opec and non-opec producers were taking steps to avoid another uncontrollable drop
since january, prices for persian gulf oil have fallen as low as $13 per 42-gallon barrel, compared with opec's official price of $18. west texas intermediate has dropped from about $18 to as low as $15
in other financial markets, gold prices rose sharply in reaction to the sudden strength in the oil market, which could portend higher inflation. gold is considered a good hedge against rising prices
in the bond market, a barometer of interest rate trends, prices fell in reaction to higher oil and metal prices. the treasury's 30-year issue fell $5 per $1,000 in face amount and its yield rose from 8.51 percent to 8.55 percent. aboard</head> statements from portuguese officials. no pickup.</note>
two men were killed when a british royal navy helicopter crashed off the portuguese coast after taking off from a warship that prince andrew was aboard, portuguese and british officials said today
commandante antonio monteiro coelho, a portuguese navy spokesman, said the lynx helicopter crashed thursday night less than three-fourths of a mile from the training ship engadine, where andrew was on duty as a helicopter warship instructor
andrew, 28, is the third eldest of queen elizabeth ii's four children and a naval helicopter pilot
a british defense ministry spokesman identified the dead pilots as lt. cmdr. anthony peter gardiner davies, 37, and acting sub. lt. richard alan hand cawthorne, 23
an informal lunch that president mario soares was to have put on for andrew today was canceled because of the accident, the president's office said
on thursday, prince charles, andrew's brother and heir to the british throne, narrowly escaped an avalanche that killed a close friend skiing with him in switzerland. the accident prompted calls in the british press for the royal family to abandon dangerous pursuits
the defense ministry spokesman, who was not indentified in keeping with british custom, refused to say whether andrew was involved in the planning of the helicopter's test flight
it is normal practice not to reveal who is involved in the planning of operations,'' he said. ``the whole thing will go before the board of inquiry.''
monteiro coelho said the helicopter crashed into the sea around 9 p.m., 50 miles west of the cabo da roca, a cape west of lisbon
he said the cause of the crash was unknown. ``the sea was calm and weather conditions were not adverse,'' he told the associated press
the helicopter was badly damaged by its impact with the water, but it did not sink, he said. the portuguese navy answered a distress call from the engadine and sent the portuguese corvette batista de andrade from lisbon to assist, he added
the spokesman said portuguese naval divers helped recover the bodies
monteiro coelho said portuguese naval authorities had been told that because of the crash, andrew's ship would not put into lisbon for the weekend as scheduled. he said he did not know whether the vessel would return to britain or remain at sea
monteiro coelho said the helicopter was too far from the engadine went it crashed for those aboard the ship to have witnessed the accident
andrew, a combat helicopter pilot who saw action in the falklands war, was on regular sea duty as a helicopter instructor aboard the engadine, british officials said
the 6,500-ton helicopter support ship used for training was carrying 73 crew members of the royal fleet auxiliary, the logistical support arm of the navy, and an unspecified number of royal navy personnel. ....'</note>
telephone transcripts casting doubt on former minister walker railey's actions the night his wife was almost choked to death were released by a prosecutor who said he wanted to ``fill in the blanks.''
the transcripts of two calls railey made to his home answering machine the night of the attack and a note he wrote before attempting suicide 11 days later were made public thursday by dallas county assistant district attorney norman kinne
in the transcripts, railey describes his whereabouts in detail, gives times and warns his wife, margaret ``peggy'' railey, to lock the garage door
railey, 40, told police he found his wife unconscious in the garage with a cord wrapped around her neck when he came home early april 21. mrs. railey remains in a coma
railey, senior pastor at first united methodist church and a rising star in the united methodist church, took an overdose of pills in an unsuccessful suicide attempt may 2, the day police said they planned to interview him
after reportedly refusing 43 times to testify before a grand jury, he resigned and moved to san francisco, leaving his wife and children, ages 2 and 5, in texas
kinne said he didn't have the evidence to bring railey to trial
i feel like this may very well be the last anyone is hearing of this, and i want to fill in the blanks as much as i can,'' the prosecutor said
the answering machine transcripts point out a number of discrepancies
in one call, railey said he was phoning around 10:30 p.m. and had a couple more hours of research to do at a southern methodist university library
however, telephone company records indicate railey made the call from his mobile phone at 12:04 a.m., and library employees couldn't recall seeing railey when he claimed he was there, kinne said
railey explained he had to leave the library when it closed and was on his way to another, and later called to say he was on his way home
i'm not calling on the private line because i know you're already asleep,' he said in that message, ``but in case you get up with the kids, i just wanted you to know that i'm on my way home. it's 12:30. i'll be home by about 12:45. love you, dear. bye bye.''
railey called police about 15 minutes later to report he had found his wife unconscious
in the four-page suicide note, he described himself as ``the weakest of the weak ... the baddest of the bad ... and the lowest of the low.''
he said he was taking his life because ``a demon inside my soul ... has finally gotten the upper hand ... (and) lured me into doing things i do not want to do.''
other parts of the note were published earlier. railey has said the letter reflected his despondency
kinne also said he discovered that railey spent more than an hour that night at the home of psychologist lucy papillon, who reportedly told grand jurors she and railey were having an affair
there's a big gap between saying the man is not telling the truth about some things and saying therefore he strangled his wife,'' the prosecutor said. ``i'm not saying that.''
kinne initially refused to release the transcripts, prompting abc news to file suit. the suit failed but kinne decided to release the material after an appeals court ruled it was up to local officials to decide the issue
the telephone at railey's san francisco apartment is unlisted, and railey could not be reached for comment thursday. railey leased the apartment with ms. papillon
mrs. railey's mother and legal guardian, billy jo nicolai, has filed a civil suit against railey accusing him of the attack on her daughter
an american woman who championed the cause of soviet citizens seeking to emigrate to the united states to join their spouses has been divorced from her russian husband
district judge kenneth bronson agreed with sandra gubin's contention that her husband, aleksei lodisev, married her solely to enter the united states
the defendant's entire testimony is shot through with evasiveness and contradictions,'' said bronson, who heard the case as a visiting judge in washtenaw county circuit court
the only reason lodisev married gubin, bronson said, was to leave the soviet union. ``that's the only conclusion i can reach,'' he said. ``he planned his moves. he thought it out. the plan was of long duration.''
gubin and lodisev were married in the soviet union in 1981, while gubin was studying in kiev. she returned to the united states and spent several years trying to get an exit visa for lodisev
she became nationally known as a spokeswoman for the divided spouse coalition, americans whose spouses have been denied exit visas
in january 1986, lodisev arrived in new york. eleven months later, gubin filed for divorce, saying that he married her only to come to the united states
gubin was awarded $113,087 for lost wages, expenses for writing to political figures and medical expenses. ``there is scant likelihood of collection on the judgment,'' because of debts pending against lodisev, bronson said in his ruling tuesday
lodisev, he said, had run up about $22,000 in bills before leaving last summer for a visit to the soviet union, which showed ``a pattern not just of stiffing the plaintiff, but of stiffing everyone else in this country,'' bronson said
lodisev's lawyer, craig mckinnon, said he was unsure whether his client wanted to appeal. lodisev, who works for a computer company, had no comment after the ruling
gubin, 40, a doctoral student in political science at the university of michigan, said she felt vindicated, but sorry for lodisev
i care for him,'' she said. ``i know he doesn't believe it, but i do.''
guerrillas sprayed a police station with submachine-gun and rocket fire, wounding two officers and three civilians in the most serious of several nighttime attacks, police said
the attacks late thursday came hours before president augusto pinochet was to address the nation in a speech marking the seventh anniversary of his controversial constitution, which allows him to seek re-election this year for another eight-year term
police said they believed the guerrillas were leftists
security was stepped up today in this capital city of 4.5 million people. army patrols in full combat gear occupied strategic points
in the most serious attack, according to police, guerrillas launched two rockets and shot submachine guns at a suburban police station in southern santiago
two officers and three civilians were wounded. police said one of the officers was in ``extremely serious condition,'' wounded in the stomach by rocket shrapnel
another station and a patrol car were also attacked during the night, but no victims were reported
at least three bombs damaged electric power installations during the night and blacked out some sectors of the city, police said
pinochet, who has ruled chile since a bloody 1973 coup, has so far refused to confirm whether he is running for re-election, but he appears to be seeking the nomination
a woman convicted of killing three people during a 1985 shooting spree at a shopping mall has been sent to prison for life after psychiatrists said they could do nothing more to treat her mental illness
sylvia seegrist, 27, was transferred from a state hospital to the state correctional institution at muncy on thursday to begin serving three consecutive life sentences for the random shooting at the springfield mall, said prison spokeswoman anne forgacs
under state law, ms. seegrist will not be eligible for parole unless the governor commutes her sentence
hospital psychiatrists and a psychiatrist hired by ms. seegrist's attorney ruled that ``her coherence level has improved and she is more cooperative,'' said delaware county assistant district attorney dennis mcandrews
in june 1986, ms. seegrist was judged guilty but mentally ill on three counts of murder and seven counts of attempted murder stemming from the oct. 30, 1985, shootings
ms. seegrist opened fire on shoppers with a .22-caliber semi-automatic rifle at the crowded shopping mall
mcandrews met tuesday with ms. seegrist's attorney, ruth shafer, and delaware coutny court judge joseph t. labrum jr., who ordered wednesday that ms. seegrist be transferred to the medium-security women's prison
her dangerous tendencies are in remission at this time,'' mcandrews said
commuters on a subway route plagued by problems today refused to leave a train that was delayed after a man fell under the wheels. it was the fourth such revolt in two weeks
london underground officials demanded an end to mutinies on its northern line, where passengers staged three sit-ins last week
subway staff asked passengers to leave the train at the old street station after the unidentified man was taken to the hospital with multiple injuries, underground officials said. most passengers left but a dozen refused to do so until police arrived
the action of passengers didn't delay the removal of the man from underneath the train,'' said london underground spokesman roger shire. ``but it's extremely disturbing that a dozen people wouldn't get off
i can understand their frustration in being delayed, but not in these circumstances,'' he said. ``they're not doing anyone any good. sit-ins are not the answer.''
spokesman derek salter said the man fell from the platform onto the tracks just after 8 a.m. as the train was pulling into the station
after the man was taken to st. bartholomew's hospital, a station guard walked through the crowded train telling passengers they had to get off and could take another waiting just behind
the (halted) train had to be taken out of service. we have to check for damage after such incidents for obvious reasons,'' shire said
passengers complain of rudeness by staff, breakdowns, delays, dirt, crime and crowds on the london underground, which carries 2.5 million people a day
the sit-ins on the northern line, among the most antiquated and inefficient routes, began on march 1. pickup.</note>
a regional train derailed near the brussels suburb of lot today, killing one person and injuring 25, the railroad said
the electrical wiring over the train was cut as a result of the accident, and all service between brussels and paris was temporarily suspended
police were investigating the cause of the derailment on the southern schaarbeek-to-binche run, said spokesman louis gilliaux of the sncb railroad company
gilliaux said five people were seriously injured and about 20 suffered minor injuries. he did not have the identity of the dead person
the injured were taken to several hospitals in the area
rail traffic between paris and brussels was later rerouted, but delays were reported
twelve percent of u.s.-made condoms and 21 percent of foreign-made ones failed in recent testing, say federal researchers. the prophylactics have been advocated as a means of slowing the spread of aids
as of february, the centers for disease control reported thursday, the food and drug administration had tested samples from 430 batches of condoms _ 165 batches manufactured in america, and 265 manufactured abroad
the fda reported previously that as many as one in five batches of latex condoms it tested fail to meet federal standards
the fda rejects a batch of condoms if more than four per 1,000 fail in water-leakage tests. if two or more batches from a foreign manufacturer fail, future shipments from that manufacturer are stopped at their port of entry into the united states
the cdc in its report on condoms and sexually transmitted diseases stressed that condoms can help prevent such diseases, but that they don't always work
individuals likely to become infected or known to be infected with (aids) should be aware that condom use cannot completely eliminate the risk of transmission,'' the atlanta-based agency said
lab tests have shown that latex condoms are effective barriers to the spread of aids, hepatitis b, gonorrhea, chlamydia and other sexually transmitted diseases. however, breakage or other mishaps during use can negate their disease-fighting effectiveness
the cdc said condoms ``should be made more widely available'' through std clinics, family planning clinics and drug treatment centers
those clinics and centers should ``become more assertive'' in warning clients about stds, and ``emphasize that the risk of infection is most effectively reduced through abstinence or sexual intercourse with a mutually faithful, uninfected partner.''
aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer
it is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring. with china warning tibetans to turn selves in. picks up 4th graf, `she said ...'</note>
