the tourist, speaking on condition of anonymity, reported seeing 20 armed police in central lhasa in front of the jokhang temple, the holiest site of tibetan buddhism. she said seven armed police were also seen on the roof of a police station in the central market square
the western tourist, who speaks tibetan, said she was told up to 200 people may have been arrested since thousands of tibetans rioted saturday to protest chinese rule
chinese authorities broadcast warnings to tibetan rebels today to turn themselves in by march 20 or face punishment, the traveler said
the tourist said vans with loudspeakers were driving through the city every hour repeating the message
they're warning people to do their duty, report troublemakers. they'll be rewarded if they give information,'' she said in a telephone interview. she said one announcement called ``for people to surrender _ people who were involved in the disturbances _ before the 20th, otherwise they would be punished.''
she said tibetans reported mass arrests, beatings and torture. she was told details of the arrests of 10 people, but she was unable to confirm other arrests
most arrests were made saturday and sunday as chinese police pulled people from their homes during the night and beat them as they were dragged away, she said
other westerners in lhasa earlier reported at least 300 arrests since saturday's all-day clash between police and tibetans demanding independence. monks and lay tibetans stoned and knifed chinese police and lit bonfires throughout the city on the last day of a major prayer festival, the reports said
