republican sen. bob dole today denied he was dropping out of the presidential race, and he criticized the news media for concentrating on such matters as his campaign staff cuts, saying, ``i never thought that a campaign was a jobs program.''
i am running for president,'' dole told a group of illinois farm bureau leaders, trying to stop rumors that he was about to pull out after suffering crushing defeats to vice president george bush on super tuesday
however, he told reporters after the speech, ``we will reassess after illinois. i am going to be very realistic about this.''
dole said the question of pulling out of the illinois primary was not discussed by him and his aides, but he conceded they did discuss canceling some campaign activities ``to heighten whatever we're going to do later.''
he said his campaign had more than $1 million on hand to finance its illinois efforts. his problem, he said, ``is not money. we've got the staff we need. what we need is to slow down this super tuesday momentum.''
it's hard to focus on the issues sometimes because the press won't let us do that,'' he said. ``they would rather write about how many staff you reduced your numbers by.''
news reports also have noted that he has taken his television ads off the air in illinois
dole made his remarks at the start of a day-long trip across central and western illinois to shore up his support in farm country, which is considered his strongest territory
in a statement issued thursday night in illinois and washington, dole had ``categorically denied rumors'' that he was about to drop out in the face of bush's big delegate lead and polls that show bush ahead in illinois, which has its primary next tuesday. dole has taken all his tv ads off the air in illinois
i'm not a dropout. i'm a candidate,'' dole told a suburban chicago veterans group thursday night
we're going to be in this race all the way to new orleans. and now we're looking for an upset next tuesday in illinois.''
although dole sought to shoot down reports that his presidential quest was ending, several campaign sources said that option had been discussed
the sources, speaking on condition that they not be identified, said dole met with campaign manager bill brock and other aides in the past few days in illinois and talked about the possibility of abandoning the race because of bush's commanding lead in delegates for the gop nomination
dole, however, decided to press on in illinois
i'm the underdog. the odds are great, but i've tackled great odds before and i'm still here,'' dole said
bush's sweep of 16 super tuesday primaries has clearly wounded dole's campaign
one dole aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said dole's private polls indicated bush held a lead of between 15 and 20 percentage points in illinois. that was described as a significant increase for the vice president in the 48 hours following his victories on super tuesday
a washington post-abc news poll published today said bush led dole in illinois by a wide margin _ 58 percent to 31 percent
although dole had not said whether he would remain in the race if he lost illinois next tuesday, one aide said: ``i think it's clear to dole that it's do or die.''
i'm a fighter. i'm also a realist. i've looked at the delegate count, and i've got to do well in illinois,'' dole said at one chicago stop thursday
and i'm not in this race to see how long we can extend it. i'm in this race to win.''
mari maseng, dole's press secretary, said 130 staff members in super tuesday states were being cut because the campaign no longer needed them. in addition, she said more than half of the staff in the campaign national headquarters was laid off to provide money for ``media and essential travel'' for the illinois effort
there were no staff cuts in states with primaries after next tuesday
maseng confirmed dole had ordered his television ads stopped in illinois because ``we've changed our media strategy.'' dole had planned to spend about $500,000 on tv spots in the state
maseng said campaign advisers were trying to draft a new advertising battle plan to ``draw the contrast between bob dole and george bush as dramatically as we can.''
the campaign, according to one source, is considering a 30-minute paid broadcast near the end of the illinois campaign
a band of men wielding guns, swords and daggers ambushed a bus carrying tamils today and killed at least 16 people, officials said
police believe the attack was in retaliation for the killings of sinhalese by tamil guerrillas last week
today's killings occurred in the northeastern district of trincomalee and the victims all were believed to be tamils, said a military official. he could not be identified under military regulations
the official said the attackers stopped the bus near the village of horawapatana, 28 miles west of the port city of trincomalee, and attacked the passengers
our reports are that eight passengers were shot and butchered, seven more were forced to remain inside the bus when it was torched. another died on the way to a nearby hospital
we have unconfirmed reports that the total dead could be more than 22,'' the official said. ``all of them are reported to be tamils.''
police investigating the bus attack believe it was carried out by sinhalese in retaliation for the killings last week of 45 sinhalese and moslem villagers
twenty-seven people, most of them sinhalese, died when a truck was blown up saturday near sitaru, and 18 more sinhalese were killed when tamil rebels raided the morawewa village wednesday. both villages are in trincomalee
militant tamils have been fighting since the summer of 1983 for a separate state in northern and eastern sri lanka, where most tamils live
india has an estimated 45,000 soldiers in sri lanka to try to enforce an indian-sponsored peace accord signed last july to try to end the war
tamils, most of whom are hindus, make up 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million population. they claim they are discriminated against by the majority sinhalese buddhists, who control the government and the military
india has become involved because it has 60 million ethnic tamils in its southern states
a court-appointed guardian for a 48-year-old comatose woman is supporting her family's request to remove a feeding tube that is keeping the woman alive
boston college law professor paul r. tremblay concluded that although tube feeding was once considered an ``ordinary measure'' that a patient could not refuse, a considerable body of legal and medical expertise suggests that is no longer true
doctors for the family of marcia v. gray and the state, which is fighting the family's request, say the woman will die within a period of days to a few weeks if the feeding tube is removed
in a similar case, a family in carthage, mo., is suing the state to force doctors to disconnect nancy cruzan, 30, from a feeding tube because she would not want to live in a hopeless state. her parents rested their case today after they and another daughter testified
the woman was left in what doctors call a ``persistent vegetative state'' after a 1983 automobile accident. she is being cared for at the state rehabilitation center at mount vernon
mrs. gray has been in a coma since suffering a cerebral hemorrhage in january 1986. last january, the roman catholic bishop of providence, louis e. gelineau, said it would be morally permissible to withdraw nutrition from mrs. gray, who is a catholic
it is in marcia gray's best interest that the feeding tube be removed, once the benefits of continued feeding are weighed against the burdens of that treatment,'' tremblay said in a report submitted thursday to u.s. district judge francis j. boyle
tremblay concluded that if state officials at general hospital continue to oppose allowing mrs. gray to die, they should quickly transfer her to a hospital that would grant the family's request
if no hospital were found, tremblay said, the court should order state officials to comply
the state asserts that honoring the family's request would be tantamount to sanctioning euthanasia
family members, tremblay said, have provided ``adequate data ... to satisfy the standards that courts have used'' to permit the discontinuance of life-support systems for terminally ill patients
she was very persistent in her wishes, and insisted that i promise not to keep her alive in a coma where there was no hope of recovery,'' her husband, university of rhode island professor h. glenn gray, said in an affidavit
a minor earthquake shook an area about 10 miles southeast of tacoma today, but apparently did no damage, officials said
the temblor was recorded at 2:01 a.m. pst, according to the u.s. geological survey's national earthquake information center in golden, colo. it measured 3.5 on the richter scale, said the center's bruce presgrave
there were no reports of damage or injury
for a quake this size, i really would not expect any,'' presgrave said
residents of fife, federal way, tacoma and auburn called local radio stations to report the quake
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude. thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times stronger than one of 6.5
an earthquake of 3.5 on the richter scale can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage. a 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of tremendous damage
the government kicked off the wedtech racketeering trial today by accusing rep. mario biaggi and his six co-defendants of theft from the defunct bronx defense contractor
this is a case about corruption and greed,'' howard wilson, an assistant u.s. attorney, told the 12-person jury in u.s. district court
it is a case about public officials who want to get paid twice.''
wilson pointed to biaggi and former bronx borough president stanley simon at the defense table and said they and the others stole from wedtech. some had been promised more money, he said
at the trial's opening, judge constance baker motley told the jury: ``an indictment is simply a series of charges. ... a defendant on trial is presumed innocent and this presumption of innocence is presumed throughout the trial.''
the case involving the defense contractor includes charges that the seven defendants looted millions of dollars in cash and stocks from the company
the trial is expected to last several months
in addition to biaggi, 70, and simon, 57, the defendants are: bernard g. ehrlich, 59, biaggi's former law partner and a former major general in the new york national guard; biaggi's eldest son, richard, 38; peter neglia, 39, the former regional administrator of the small business administration; former wedtech chairman john mariotta, 57; and ronald betso, 39, a former city police officer and close friend of neglia's
they are charged with racketeering and conspiracy, which each carry maximum 20-year penalties upon conviction, as well as various other alleged crimes. biaggi is also accused of extortion, bribe-receiving, wire fraud, perjury and filing false tax returns. update with highway closings in n.d. and colo.</note>
a powerful late-winter blizzard lashed the western plains with up to two feet of snow today, closing hundreds of miles of highway in nebraska, wyoming, colorado and the dakotas and stranding hundreds of travelers
up to 33 inches fell in the mountains of utah
in southwestern nebraska, the snow pileup cut off the town of kimball, whose residents opened their doors to about 600 stranded motorists. and in an adjacent section of colorado, several hundred students had to spend the night in their school
the storm occurred 100 years to the day after the start of the four-day great blizzard of 1888 in the eastern united states. that storm claimed 400 lives
the storm, stalled near the nebraska-wyoming line before moving east, pumped heavy snow and winds gusting up to 40 mph from the western dakotas across western nebraska and much of wyoming and colorado
in nebraska, the storm was not expected to abate until late tonight, deputy civil defense coordinator john jenson said early today
we've still got a good 12 hours of this to go,'' he said
it's going to continue to pack quite a punch as it spreads across nebraska and south dakota particularly,'' said meteorologist pete reynolds of the national weather service's severe storm forecast center in kansas city, mo
blizzard warnings were posted today over eastern wyoming, northeastern colorado, western nebraska and western south dakota, and winter storm warnings were posted through tonight for east-central south dakota, much of north dakota and southwestern minnesota
in utah, southeast of salt lake city, the alta ski resort had accumulated 33 inches of snow since wednesday and snowbird counted 31 inches. freezing rain fell in the valleys and a 12-car pileup blocked part of interstate 215 thursday evening near salt lake
authorities closed 112 miles of interstate 80 in western nebraska and eastern wyoming early today due to snowpacked roads and blowing snow, forcing hundreds of stranded motorists to find shelter. almost 100 miles of other nebraska roads also were closed
i think i could have stayed home because i'm not going to have any business, '' said kelly cheshire, 22, a cashier at a major truck stop west of cheyenne, wyo. ``it's bad.''
about 100 miles of interstate 90 was closed overnight in western south dakota between spearfish and wall, but police said there were few reports of stranded motorists. two feet of snow was reported today in deadwood, with 15 to 20 inches in sturgis and 12 to 18 inches in spearfish
sections of interstate 94 were closed today in north dakota and the bismarck municipal airport was shut down. the state pulled snow plows off highways because of poor visibility
several highways were closed in northeastern colorado. ``at one point we were receiving one accident every 60 seconds,'' maj. john kammerzell of the larimer county sheriff's office said
up to 14 inches of snow and buffeting winds kept almost 140 miles of interstate 25 closed in wyoming. an average of 6-12 inches of snow accumulated in the eastern third of the state
wyoming highway patrol officers spent most of thursday searching for motorists on snow-closed roads, a patrol dispatcher said
no major traffic accidents were reported in wyoming or nebraska, though the storm triggered scores of minor ones, authorities said
we've mostly had people sliding off the road. we're not even pulling them out. we're just getting people out of the vehicles,'' said nebraska state patrol dispatcher alex haberkorn in scottsbluff
when people call and ask what it's like out here, i'm suggesting they stay home,'' he said
all roads into kimball were closed thursday night, stranding at least 600 motorists in the town of 3,800, said region 21 civil defense director dan jenson
he said residents were opening their homes to the stranded and overnight accommodations were found for hundreds by midevening, but the kimball county courthouse remained packed with people at 8:30 p.m
i've never seen so many gosh-dang people,'' jenson said. ``i really appreciate the citizens of the city of kimball for opening their homes to strangers.''
in nearby colorado, several hundred students in the weld county school district re3j made themselves comfortable for the night in school buildings when district buses couldn't get them home thursday
we just have some awfully bad weather, just a whiteout (and) some of our roads now are plugging with drifts,'' said superintendent bob gudka, who had 250 to 300 of the district's 1,200 students kept overnight in several schools
the kids are having a ball,'' he said. as for the teachers, he joked, ``we may have to get psychological help for them later on.''
the weather threatened hundreds of newborn calves, and ranchers in the nebraska sandhills region worked around the clock to get animals to shelter
the men are just exhausted'' said marianne beel, whose family ranches in the area. ``we've got about 600 head of cows calving. we worked all night long.''
we had 300 calves born yesterday,'' she said. ``we're dragging them in, separating them from their mothers.''
roads across northern and eastern colorado remained closed early today. the storm struck suddenly thursday, dropping 6 inches of snow in fort collins in just two hours. about 16 inches of snow fell in estes park, colo
i didn't expect this one,'' said truck driver mike brock of reading, pa., who planned to check into a motel at rapid city, s.d. ``i pulled off the interstate because a four-wheeler did a doughnut in front of me and i decided that was close enough.''
betty flosky might never have learned the truth about her life if she hadn't developed leukemia
the suburban detroit woman learned late last month that her parents were really an adoptive aunt and uncle and that her supposed brothers were cousins
everyone just held the secret all these years,'' said gene wise, one of her cousins. ``i'm glad it's out. i wish it was under better circumstances.''
she also learned she had three brothers and a sister, all unknown to her, who might be able to help her undergo a life-saving bone marrow transplant
i'm shaking like a leaf,'' flosky, 32, said after meeting lynne kern, the sister who had just arrived from denver
flosky's mother died four days after giving birth to her. she was taken in by an aunt and an uncle and never told about her mother or father, who later died
last month, doctors told flosky about her leukemia, which could be fatal within three years. she also learned that a bone marrow transplant from a sibling was her best chance at survival
wise and his brother, norm, told her they would be tested to see if they could donate marrow, despite knowing that cousins don't make the best donors. then on feb. 25, joe flosky told his wife she had been adopted
when he told me i sat there and said, `is that it?''' she said. ``i said, `i thought you were going to tell me i was going to die.'''
since then, her brothers and sister have been contacted and are being tested to see whether they can donate marrow. if any of them tests positive, flosky and the donor are ready to fly to a seattle hospital that frequently performs bone marrow transplants
it's like `the twilight zone' or something, isn't it?'' flosky said. ``instead of my family shrinking, it's growing.''
federal investigators say an air force bomb expert who had been absent without leave for several weeks apparently set off a blast in his pickup truck that killed him and damaged a motel where he was staying
but officials said it was unknown if staff sgt. donald lawrence lunger detonated the bomb intentionally or accidentally march 4
forensic psychologists will study lunger's medical records and talk with family and friends to determine why he placed a 10-pound to 15-pound package of explosives behind the seat of his pickup truck and attached it to a blasting cap, said willi ellison, agent in charge of the jacksonville office of the bureau of alcohol, tobacco and firearms
the explosives, wires and other materials found at the blast scene indicated they were the type used at eglin air force base, where lunger was stationed. an investigation at the base was under way to determine if any explosive materials were missing, ellison said thursday
it has been determined that the explosion that resulted in the death of lunger was a deliberate act initiated by actions intentionally or unintentionally taken by him,'' officials said
the charge could have been electrically detonated by the cigarette lighter in the truck or flashlight components, ellison said
he said there was no indication that lunger was involved in any criminal activity, narcotics or espionage. he said he could not speculate on whether lunger was under mental distress at the time of the blast
lunger, 30, had been staying at the southern inn motel for several days before the explosion, motel employees said. he was reported awol from eglin on feb. 22
lunger, originally of endicott, n.y., had been in the air force 13 years. he was married and had two children
a national team of investigators was dispatched the day after the blast, which smashed about 65 windows at the motel and caused minor damage to railings and other exterior structures at the two-story motel. there were no other reported injuries
the state naacp president and 13 other black lawmakers argued today that they were protected by legislative immunity when they tried to remove the confederate battle flag from atop the alabama capitol
the trespassing arrests of the legislators raised ``serious constitutional questions and serious questions of state law,'' said fred gray, who represents thomas reed, head of the state national association for the advancement of colored people
gray also said at the court hearing that gov. guy hunt lacked the right to instruct officers to arrest anyone who attempted to enter the capitol grounds through a locked, chain-link fence since the building is under the control of the alabama historical commission. the building is closed for renovation
prosecutors from the district attorney's office did not comment on the defense motions
district judge craig miller granted defense attorneys' request to file briefs and gave the district attorney's office 10 days to respond. he said he would set a trial date later
reed, speaking with reporters before the brief hearing began, repeated his contention that the state should not fly the flag over the capitol. reed and the other legislators maintain that the confederate banner represents racial oppression and slavery
people can fly it on their pickup trucks _ i have no problem with that,'' said reed, a state representative from tuskegee
reed and his co-defendants were arrested feb. 2, minutes after the legislature's opening gavel
capitol police and state troopers pulled down reed and the others as they made at least symbolic efforts to scale the 8-foot fence. the lawmakers never got near the building and the dixie flag still flies atop the capitol dome. some merely put their hand on the chain-link fence when they were arrested
each lawmaker was charged with second-degree criminal trespassing and released from the county jail on $300 bond. conviction on the misdemeanor count carries a maximum penalty of three months in jail and a $500 fine
reed had vowed for weeks to remove the flag. hundreds of people _ ranging from ku klux klansmen carrying rebel flags to black students singing ``we shall overcome'' _ gathered outside the capitol for reed's attempt
hunt, who contends the flag is historic and not a symbol of racism, has refused to remove the standard, saying the legislature should decide the issue. hours after reed and the other democrats were arrested, the state house defeated a resolution to remove the flag
the naacp also is trying to remove the banner above south carolina's statehouse and change the state flags of georgia and mississippi, which bear versions of the confederate battle flag in their designs
kidnappers of u.s. marine lt. col. william r. higgins have pledged to free him but set no specific date for the release, the beirut magazine ash-shiraa said today
the weekly quoted unidentified knowledgeable sources in south lebanon as saying the kidnappers made the pledge ``in secret contacts undertaken by more than local and regional parties.''
there was no way to verify the report independently
ash-shiraa gained international fame for disclosing the secret u.s. arms sales to iran in november 1986. but many of its reports about foreign hostages held in lebanon have proved inaccurate
higgins, 44, of danville, kentucky, who served with a u.n. observers group in south lebanon, was kidnapped near the ancient southern port of tyre on feb. 17
a pro-iranian shiite group, the organization of the oppressed on earth, claimed responsibility for his abduction, charging he was a spy for the u.s. central intelligence agency. u.s. and u.n. officials have denied the charge
the sources did not reveal an approximate date for higgins' release, saying this has been left for the kidnappers to set,'' the magazine said
the sources have said that the important thing in this regard is that a decision has been taken by the kidnappers to free higgins, such as what happened with (former) west german hostage ralph schray, who was freed last week,'' ash-shiraa added
schray, an industrial engineer who was abducted in moslem west beirut jan. 27, was released by his pro-iranian shiite moslem captors march 3 in west beirut
syrian troops in charge of security in west beirut's whisked him the same day to the syrian capital of damascus, where he was handed over to the west german embassy. he returned to resume his life in west beirut two days later
twenty-two foreigners, including nine americans, are missing and believed kidnapped in lebanon. the longest held is american terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press. he was kidnapped march 16, 1985
