authorities on friday would not identify the site or specify what they might find
this site has possibilities but no certainties,'' marathon county sheriff's lt. elwood mason said friday
authorities believe 500 to 700 cubic yards of material will be removed, mason said. he would not comment on whether that material might be dirt or concrete
it is not on land that is owned or under control by any suspect in this case,'' mason said, adding that was one reason for choosing to dig at this site rather than any others under consideration
four members of the kunz family were found shot to death and a fifth family member disappeared from their rural athens home last july
circumstances and events surrounding july 4 and 5 give this site some probabilities but by no means create a certainty that there would be something there,'' mason said
district attorney rand krueger said thursday he did not plan to file charges in the case this week and no one was in custody. he said the number of suspects, which he had described earlier as more than one but fewer than 12, remained the same
helen kunz, 70, has been missing since her relatives' bodies were discovered in the family home. ms. kunz's brother, clarence kunz, 76; their sisters, irene, 81, and marie, 72; and helen kunz's son, randy, 30, were shot dead
krueger would not comment on whether a murder weapon had been recovered
a german restaurant violated the civil rights of three patrons by refusing them service for wearing nazi swastika lapel pins, a superior court judge ruled
but judge kurt lewin said thursday it would be up to a jury to determine whether alpine village restaurant in torrance was wrong in refusing the three service in october 1985 after they caused a disturbance when told to leave
lewin said state law prevented the restaurant from refusing service because of what the men wore
the suit, on behalf of joe fields, 24, of san pedro; stanley witek, 54, of los angeles; and harold follin, 28, of anaheim had sought unspecified damages as well as an injunction preventing the restaurant from refusing service to customers based on their political views. damages would only be awarded if the jury sides with the plaintiffs
attorney julia tachikawa, who represented the restaurant, said she didn't know if alpine village would want to appeal
she expressed disappointment that the judge ruled against the restaurant's contention that it did not have to serve the men if they wore things patrons might find offensive
ms. tachikawa said lewin failed to take into account the restaurant's constitutional right of freedom of association
in this case i was trying to argue that it was a german restaurant, and the association was so obvious, the restaurant was compelled to speak up that we don't hold that view,'' she said
the swastika was the emblem of adolf hitler's national socialist party
ms. tachikawa said the restaurant contended the men were thrown out not because of the pins but because they caused trouble after being asked to either remove the pins or leave
american civil liberties union attorney carol sobel, who represented the men, said it didn't matter whether they created a disturbance after they were refused service
she argued that the only issue to be resolved was whether a restaurant could exclude someone because it disapproved of what the person was wearing
judging by what israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir had to say in his letter to skeptical senators, this tough-minded middle eastern leader may climb aboard secretary of state george p. shultz's peace shuttle after all
shamir reaffirmed his commitment to the 1978 camp david approach to negotiations over the west bank and gaza. the way shultz has structured the talks that would suffice for the first stage
but shamir's resistance to the concept of trading the territories or even part of them for arab recognition is a potential roadblock. so is the refusal of king hussein of jordan to commit himself to recognizing israel until the territories are vacated
shamir, who will be here monday to see president reagan, shultz and members of congress, has a reputation for intransigence. so did menachem begin, the last leader of the likud coalition to serve as prime minister of israel
but begin turned every inch of sinai over to egypt, stripping israel in the meantime of all its oil resources, dismantling a first-class military airfield and uprooting jewish settlers. begin gave it all away in exchange for a 1979 peace treaty with the most formidable arab country
the treaty was based on the camp david agreements former president jimmy carter worked out with begin and the late egyptian president anwar sadat in the catoctin mountains of maryland
israel offered self-rule, or autonomy, to the 1.5 million palestinian arabs who live on the west bank and in gaza as an interim arrangement. all options, including statehood, would be open during a second stage of negotiations
the first round ended in 1981 in failure. jordan and the palestinians did not participate. the arab world shunned sadat for his treaty with israel and only lately has begun to repair relations with cairo
sens. carl levin, d-mich., rudy boschwitz, r-minn., and 28 other senators criticized shamir for not being willing to give up portions of the territories in exchange for arab recognition of israel
but the prime minister, in his reply, left the option open _ as the camp david agreements do. he said the formula begin and sadat devised ``would grant the palestinian arabs self-rule, following which the sides would negotiate the final status of the territories in question in a vastly improved setting of coexistence and cooperation between jordan, israel and the palestinian arabs.''
in other words, shamir still wants a trial period of palestinian autonomy before taking up a final settlement. he may harbor hopes the palestinians would elect to remain under israel's security control while running their own daily affairs
in a letter to shultz in january, the israeli leader excluded only security and foreign relations as functions of autonomous palestinian arabs
the scheme shultz presented to shamir and hussein in jerusalem and london envisions a three-year interim arrangement. that should be attractive to the prime minister
also, negotiations for an overall settlement would begin only if israel and a mixed jordanian-palestinian delegation succeeded in working out interim arrangements
that means shamir could say ``yes'' next week to the president and the secretary of state without committing himself to yielding the territory israel won in the 1967 six-day war
the prime minister's letter to levin and boschwitz suggests getting him to give up even parts of the west bank and gaza would be more difficult than persuading begin to yield the sinai
shamir reminded the senators that jordan's occupation of the west bank from 1950 to 1967 was never recognized internationally. egypt held gaza during the same period, but unlike sinai, the strip along the mediterranean was occupied ``militarily and illegally,'' shamir said
we have sought peace relentlessly, but our arab neighbors, except egypt, still have to prove in deeds that they are willing to negotiate peace with us,'' the israeli leader said
shultz tried to pierce hussein's decades-long resistance by proposing to hold the negotiations in an international setting. this is designed to give the king the support he seeks
but shultz obviously could not guarantee hussein that israel would withdraw from the west bank and gaza. so there's a big question mark over hussein's participation in the peace talks as well
barry schweid has covered u.s.-middle east diplomacy over the past 15 years
a federal appeals court ruled today that prosecutors illegally obtained statements from a former fbi agent charged with lying about his role in handling teamster president jackie presser as an informant
the u.s. court of appeals upheld a lower court's decision that suppresses as evidence the statements that former fbi agent robert s. friederick made to government prosecutors in early 1986
the statements that friedrick made to federal prosecutors constituted the linchpin of the government's case against him. the former cleveland fbi agent is charged with five counts of making false statements to federal agents
the appeals court panel upheld a finding by u.s. district judge george revercomb that federal prosecutors failed to inform friederick that unlike previous interviews in 1985, statements he made to them during the january 1986 session could be used as evidence against him
friederick's lawyer, william beyer, said the decision eliminates the only evidence that prosecutors have against his client
i don't know of any other evidence that they have to support their claim,'' beyer said in a telephone inteview from cleveland
friederick is charged with lying by telling fbi agents and prosecutors that he was aware that presser had been authorized by the cleveland fbi office to put ghost employees on the payroll of a local teamsters union
the case stems from an fbi investigation of payroll padding in teamsters local 507 in cleveland that resulted in convictions of jack nardi and allen friedman in 1983
presser has been indicted on charges that he authorized the payment of union funds to so-called ``phantom employees.'' as a defense, presser claims he was acting under the authority of cleveland fbi agents as an informant
friederick, who was head of the cleveland fbi's organized crime squad, was questioned in 1984 and again in 1985 about his handling of presser as an informant
it was during a 1984 interview with friederick and other cleveland agents that the fbi learned that presser was an informant. during a june 26, 1985, interview at fbi headquarters in washington, friederick signed an fbi form that said he was required to answer questions but that the government could not use his statements against him in a criminal prosecution
friederick was questioned on two other occasions that summer in connection with the fbi's internal investigation of the handling of presser as an informant
the appellate court upheld revercomb's finding that friederick was not warned during a jan. 6, 1986, interview that statements he made could be used against him
the prosecutors ``made a conscious decision prior to the interview not to furnish friederick with or even mention (the fbi form); indeed they hoped that friederick would make incriminating statements that they could use against him in a subsequent prosecution,'' the court said in an opinion by judge kenneth starr
during the january interview, friederick made statements contradicting his previous assertion that he was aware that presser had been authorized to put ghost employees on the local's payroll. the next day he failed a lie detector test
the state textbook commission has rejected american indians' pleas to remove from elementary schools a book containing stories by washington irving and john smith that depict indians as blood-thirsty savages
the commission refused thursday to withdraw approval for ``what joy awaits you'' by open court publishing co., and said teachers can offset negative images by teaching children to think critically
an open court representative said a supplemental text is being prepared to help teachers discuss how perceptions of native americans have changed. the company also will revise the text in 1989 to include treaty violations and atrocities against native americans, but will not remove classical writings
the company said 10 other states have approved the book, including idaho and california
commission member clark cox, superintendent of alpine school district, said removing or deleting offensive passages would ``make pablum of literature.''
wil numkena, education specialist at the state office of education, said irving's derogatory story of indians may be considered a classic, but ``at whose expense?''
numkena recalled that as a boy a teacher told his class that indians were bad, raided white people and took away white people's land
thanks to my mother and father who reinforced my understanding of who i am, i was able to continue my education, understand my identity and build self-esteem,'' he said. ``but many children don't have that support system.''
the expense account was filed about 400 years late and the government dispensed tea instead of money as a group of people dressed as elizabethans tried to recover the costs incurred by sir francis drake
five devonions from drake's hometown, tavistock, recited his rhyming claim thursday for 914 pounds, 17 shillings and 4 pence from the british treasury, to cover payments to officers and crew aboard the revenge
the five say drake never got the money because lord burghley, who conducted the war against spain, thought he was being overcharged. the expense papers were found in a museum in plymouth, devon
at his office in whitehall, the seat of government, treasury chief secretary john major listened to the plea for repayment:
and this, good sirs, a tidy sum, was never paid to me
so we have come to you this day to settle up my fee,'' quoth john sterne, a shopkeeper dressed as drake
come up to my office for a cup of tea,'' responded major, the no. 2 man in charge of the nation's finances
after 400 years' inflation, this must be worth about 100,000 pounds ($184,000) now,'' he said. ``but i think it's out of time _ legally unenforceable.''
after tea, sterne, wearing doublet and hose, a tall hat and carrying a sword, said, ``it seems that's all we're going to get.''
asked if his sword was real, sterne, said: ``oh, yes, you can see it is _ it's my mother's.''
asked if he needed a permit to wear the sword, sterne said: ``no, i wrapped it up until i got here.''
the tavistock five said they were happy to dress for the occasion
pat mildren was dressed as queen elizabeth i, emma nicholson as drake's second wife, and pat murray and lis lee as courtiers
mrs. mildren wore a crown, a floor-length green dress over a hoop and lots of beads
i feel very good in this, but quite hot,'' she said. ``excuse me, my hoop is slipping.''
the five said they will wear their costumes for most of this year to celebrate the 400th anniversary of england's defeat of the spanish armada
i'll do anything for my constituency, and drake was my constituent,'' said mrs. nicholson, legislator for tavistock in the house of commons
shopowner mary thompson said mrs. nicholson's costume took two weeks and nearly $370 to make
the outfit, mostly from a brocade curtain, had one overskirt, three underskirts, a roll to keep everything up above a hoop, a stomacher with embroidered sleeves, lots of padding and a lace ruff and cap
it's enormously comfortable. i'm laced in, stayed up and covered in whalebone and i'm warm and wonderful,'' mrs. nicholson said
wholesale prices dipped 0.2 percent in feburary as both energy and food costs declined, including a dramatic 70 percent tumble in the price of lettuce, the government reported friday
the decline in the labor department's producer price index partially erased a 0.4 percent increase in january. analysts said it provided further evidence that inflation remains tame
for the first two months of 1988, wholesale prices have been increasing at an annual rate of 1.1 percent _ just half of last year's 2.2 percent rise
however, the producer index does not show two categories in which price increases have been the most pronounced _ services and imported goods. these items are included in the companion consumer price index, which was up 4.4 percent in 1987
at the wholesale level, food prices overall fell 1.1 percent after a 1.7 percent rise a month earlier. energy prices were also down, but the 0.8 percent decline trailed january's 4.5 percent drop
gasoline prices fell 0.5 percent after an 8.4 percent plunge in january. home heating oil costs were off 4.2 percent after a 6.2 percent drop. natural gas prices, up 0.8 percent in january, fell 1.4 percent
as for food, vegetable prices, which had increased 16.2 percent in january, dropped 26.3 percent, a decline largely driven by the drop in lettuce prices. the price of lettuce had tripled between october and november because of shortages and crop infestation in california
fruits, down 3.0 percent in january, fell an additional 3.5 percent
beef and veal prices were up 0.3 percent after a 3.4 percent rise in january. pork costs, up 13.2 percent in the previous month, rose just 0.2 percent
coffee prices fell 0.8 percent for the second consecutive month. alcoholic beverage costs were up 0.8 percent after rising 0.1 percent in the preceding month
subtracting the usually volatile energy and food categories, wholesale prices for all other goods increased a relatively sedate 0.3 percent
the stability which we continue to see in the (producer) index is very good news,'' said dirk van dorgen, president of the national association of wholesaler-distributors. ``we don't need to have to cope with a vexing inflation problem on top of all the other basic economic problems we've got to deal with.''
the producer index had declined as recently as last december, when it was down 0.4 percent. the 0.2 percent february decline, if continued for 12 consecutive months, would yield an annual price-change rate of minus 2.2 percent
the teaming up of lower energy and food costs in february ``really was a break for the consumer,'' said sandra shaber, senior economist for the futures group, a management consulting company. ``but there have been some strong increases in some services, medical care, housing costs, which are not in the ppi.''
we can't anticipate a continuing decline in lettuce prices, unfortunately,' she added
friday's report again showed there was little justification for worries of a resurgence in inflation, analysts agreed
the news is clearly that we have very stable inflation rates,'' said david wyss, chief financial economist for data resources inc. ``we think energy prices will come back a little bit in the next few months because they have dropped so far. but the base inflation rate is going to remain very stable.''
other wholesale price activity in february included:
_prices for new automobiles fell 0.2 percent after a 0.2 percent gain in january
_capital equipment costs were up 0.2 percent for the third month in a row
_children's clothing prices fell 2.2 percent. men's clothing costs fell 0.1 percent. men's apparel prices gained 0.5 percent
_tobacco prices gained 0.9 percent after a 1.2 percent drop in january
february's decline brought the overall wholesale price index to 105.9. this means that a selection of wholesale goods costing $100 during a 1982 base period would have cost $105.90 last month. the index itself is not adjusted for seasonal variations, as are other figures in the report
the labor department recently switched from a 1967 base period for both its producer and consumer price index figures
using the 1967 base, the february index would have been 297.3. that compares to a 292.3 index in february 1988. in other words, goods costing $100 in 1967 would have cost $292.30 in february 1987 and $297.30 in february 1988. picking up 5th graf pvs, `he launched ....'</note>
merrill k. riddick, a colorful and quixotic figure who campaigned for president three times as the candidate of the puritan ethic and epic, magnetohydrodynamics and prohibition party, has died at the age of 93
riddick, who died wednesday of cancer, also was a world war i aviator and 1920s barnstormer before moving to montana to prospect for gold
he ran for president in 1976, 1980 and 1984, campaigning across the country on the greyhound buses where he also slept
i live on the bus,'' he said in 1981. ``i can get the bus passes for less than $12 a day. it's cheaper than living in a hotel.''
he lost his presidential bids, obviously. but that was nothing new for riddick. he had been running for office since 1960 and losing spectacularly just as long
but politics was a relatively late interest for riddick, also known as one of the nation's earliest aviators
he was a graduate of the army air corps' first pilot class in san diego in 1917 and flew reconnaissance missions over europe in world war i. he became one of the nation's first airmail pilots and instructed at the nation's first private flight school, alongside fellow instructor eddie rickenbacker
riddick also was a 1920s barnstormer, an itinerant pilot who made a living giving air shows and selling rides, before moving to montana as a gold prospector
he launched his political career with a bid for the montana democratic gubernatorial nomination in 1960. he finished sixth in a field of six. he tried again in 1968 with the same result
he switched parties to run for the senate in 1972. he finished fourth among four republicans
and with that long political background, he launched his bids for the presidency
his party was his own creation. the puritan ethic and epic in the title stood for moral values. magnetohydrodynamics is a high-tech process for turning coal into electricity. prohibition marked his personal belief
perennial losing candidates are not unusual in american politics. but riddick's quests earned him a place in the hearts of many in montana, a state proud of its individualists
a restaurant freqented by politicians in helena, the state capital, named a private dining room after riddick. the airport in philipsburg, his home, was named for him. and the 341st strategic wing at malmstrom air force base in great falls named him an honorary missileman
he had a long, full life,'' said his sister, ruth mcclain. ``his mind was clear to the end.''
mrs. mcclain said he probably would be buried in annapolis, md., near the grave of his father, former u.s. rep. carl riddick
a georgia power co. worker was electrocuted friday when he came into contact with a low voltage cable, and electricity was shut off to some downtown office buildings, the company said
georgia power spokeswoman meg reggie said johnny lane, a lead cable splicer, was working in an underground vault behind the offices of the atlanta newspapers inc., when he came in contact with the cable and was knocked unconscious
lane, 35, died shortly before 10 a.m., grady memorial hospital spokeswoman beverly thomas said
power was then shut off to allow rescue workers to reach him, she said
the 90-minute outage interrupted power to cnn center, which includes studios of cable news network and offices of the associated press, and to offices of the atlanta journal and the atlanta constitution. cnn was knocked off the air for about four seconds before emergency power kicked in, a producer said
a man who held a teen-age girl captive in a motel room and fired at fbi agents has been sentenced to 25 years in prison on extortion, assault and firearms violations
richard lee brown received the maximum sentences in federal court thursday for charges stemming from the siege in september in lake city, about 50 miles west of here. brown held 17-year-old stacey ann sapp of savannah, ga., hostage during the siege
brown, who had been traveling around the country with miss sapp for several weeks, called her father and threatened to harm her unless the father paid $30,000 in ransom. but authorities intervened after miss sapp's father called the fbi, and a 21-hour standoff followed at the motel
in january, brown pleaded guilty to two charges of assaulting a federal officer with a deadly weapon, as well as one count each of using a firearm in a violent crime and transmitting an extortion demand across state lines
brown, of tallahassee, had told officials he was possessed by demons and had angels inside his body. a court-appointed psychiatrist said he suffered from several personality disorders
he was judged competent to stand trial, however, after the psychiatrist said he understood right from wrong and the charges against him
brown also had been charged with extortion in georgia, but those were dropped as part of his plea-bargain agreement
gary hart ended his on-again, off-again bid for the 1988 democratic presidential nomination today, saying, ``the people have decided and now i should not go forward.''
it was the second withdrawal for the man who once was the prohibitive front-runner for his party's nomination, coming 10 months after he quit because of questions concerning his relationship with miami model donna rice
flanked by members of his family, hart told a news conference that when he rejoined the race last december, he wanted to ``let the people decide.''
i got a fair hearing and the people have decided and now i should not go forward,'' he declared
the former colorado senator departed with words of praise for the surviving democratic contenders, but with thinly veiled criticism, as well
he said democrats have won only a single presidential election since 1964, and added, ``those who cling to the past mask their lack of direction with caution and platitudes. we can only be prepared to govern if we challenge the future with bold new ideas.''
he said the contenders must offer detailed budget proposals and learn the details of military reform _ two points he made repeatedly in his rerun for the nomination
hart second exit contained only a trace of the defiance that marked his departure in may, but he struck one similar note
to those of you in and out of politics who may face setbacks, failures or defeats _ who are told to give up, accommodate or compromise _ i hope you will simply say as i do _ `hell no,''' hart said
hart also stepped back from the criticism of reporters that marked his second try for the nomination, saying, ``i want to thank members of the media who were fair and balanced.''
hart's announcement capped a story as bizarre as any in modern presidential politics
he was the overwhelming favorite for the nomination when he announced his bid a year ago, but his campaign self-destructed in the springtime scandal
he plunged back into the campaign last december and briefly soared in the polls, but it quickly became clear the voters were deciding he wasn't their man, relegating him to the back of the pack in the early primaries and caucuses
hart failed to garner a single delegate to the 1988 democratic national convention, and his vote percentage never reached double digits in any contest. when the dust settled from this week's 20-state super tuesday contests, the federal election commission announced that hart was no longer eligible for federal campaign matching funds
hart's undoing in his initial bid came when the miami herald newspaper staked out his washington townhouse and reported that rice, 29, a part-time model, spent a night there
there were questions about that, because the paper admitted it did not have every entrance monitored all night. but then photos of rice sitting on hart's knee aboard a yacht called the monkey business on a trip to bimini surfaced
hart, however, repeatedly refused to discuss specifics of his relationship with rice, saying it was his personal business
later he admitted: ``i never should have been on a boat with a woman who was not my wife, but that's not the issue. it's complicated. it's the system. it's all of us.''
after seven months on the sidelines, he announced in december in new hampshire _ in a dramatic steps-of-the-statehouse news conference _ that he was back in the race and would ``let the people decide.''
he could not, he said, withhold his views on public policy and issues during this presidential campaign. he vowed to run a grassroots campaign, with little money and an informal organization
however, he sustained another serious blow in january when there were reports that hollywood video producer stuart karl improperly bankrolled his campaigns
when we needed fliers printed or a chartered plane, stuart managed to get it done,'' one source told the associated press. ``(dennis) walto was a full-time advance man for hart and he was on karl's payroll. ...stuart picked up a variety of other things.''
hart said he was unaware of any wrongdoing, but: ``i will hold myself responsible for whatever happened and not shift any blame to anyone else. obviously a candidate cannot know every detail.''
he later acknowledged that several contributions from employees of karl were illegal and he was returning the money
the united states told secretary-general javier perez de cuellar today it will move next week to close the plo's observer mission at the united nations
perez de cuellar replied with a ``strong'' protest to u.s. ambassador herbert okun, according to u.n. spokesman francois giulaini
okun's letter to the u.n. chief says the justice department will initiate legal action to close the palestine liberation organization mission around march 21
it also says the united states will not try to close the mission until the litigation is resolved
giuliani said perez de cuellar's legal staff is ``studying options,'' but he refused to describe them or say if the united nations would join the litigation on behalf of the plo
the united nations released copies of okun's letter to the secretary-general during a press briefing after the two diplomats met this morning
giuliani said perez de cuellar ``strongly protested this violation of the headquarters agreement'' during the meeting
the letter also says that the united states refuses binding arbitration of the dispute over the mission, the worst confrontation ever between the united nations and its host country
the 159-nation general assembly, in a special meeting last month, asked the world court in the hague to rule on whether the united states must agree to arbitration. oral arguments are scheduled for april 11
u.n. officials and diplomats regard the threat to the plo mission as a challenge to the independence of the united nations
they and the state department have said the 1947 treaty under which new york became u.n. headquarters obliges the united states to let all accredited missions operate
even the united states' closest allies have denounced the attempt to close the mission and several arab diplomats have suggested that the general assembly move to geneva if the mission here is closed
it was not clear if the assembly would convene again to consider the dispute
last year, the state department closed down the only other plo office in the united states, an information office in washington, in what turned out to be a futile attempt to head off legislation ordering the u.n. mission closed
despite this and despite the headquarters treaty, congress passed an anti-terrorism law in december ordering the mission closed by march 21
the united states and israel consider the plo a terrorist organization. but the united nations recognizes it as the only legitimate spokesman for palestinians. picking up 5th graf pvs, `sparks and ....'</note>
two people who claim they have information that could clear a condemned murderer said today they were disappointed the governor refused to meet with them to discuss the case, which has become a rallying point for death penalty opponents
the rev. sam sparks, a baptist minister, and christine bass, a lakeland secretary, appeared at a news conference with amnesty international officials to discuss about information they believe might clear willie jasper darden of murder
darden is under his seventh death warrant and is scheduled for electrocution tuesday for the 1973 slaying of a furniture store owner
no other florida inmate has survived as many death warrants and only one other prisoner has been on florida's death row longer
i know willie darden is innocent. it is not a belief; it is a knowledge,'' said ms. bass, who said her attempts to give vital information to darden's trial attorney 14 years ago were rebuffed
gov. bob martinez refused to meet with the two, and an aide said the governor is satisfied that the evidence sparks and ms. bass were talking about had been considered and rejected by the courts
this is not about public sentiment. it's about the law and carrying out the law,'' press secretary jon peck said in explaining why martinez decided against the meeting
i think a lot of people in florida are wondering why he won't sit down for even 15 minutes with ms. bass and me. that seems reasonable,'' sparks said at the news conference
sparks and ms. bass, who have signed affidavits that raise questions about whether darden could have committed the crime, have appeared on television news programs to repeat those statements
supporters say darden, who is black, was the victim of racial prejudice in his trial
he was convicted of killing lakeland store owner james turman during a robbery that netted $15. a store employee also was shot and permanently disabled, while turman's wife had to fend off a sexual attack as her husband lay dying
sparks said turman's wife had told him that all blacks looked alike to her and that her identification of darden was unimportant because the lawyers had told her that darden committed the crime
helen baum, formerly helen turman, recently denied having made that statement to sparks and reaffirmed her identification of darden as the man who shot her husband
ms. bass, a lakeland secretary, said darden's car had broke down near her home, and he waited for a tow truck from 4 p.m. to 5:35 p.m. on sept. 8, 1973. her house was eight miles from the furniture store. prosecutors say the crime occurred about 6 p.m
as ms. bass and sparks made their claims, a sixth warrant against darden was stayed and the u.s. supreme court agreed to consider his appeal for the fourth time
on monday, the u.s. supreme court ruled 6-3 that darden had received a fair trial and had been properly sentenced
the governor siged a seventh death warrant tuesday, which gave the inmate's attorneys less than a week to prepare his case. usually, at least 30 days are allowed
amnesty international officials said martinez was rushing to execute darden for political reasons
i think what the governor is looking for some kind of ritualistic sacrifice that he can go through to prove he's tough on crime,'' said magdaleno rose-avila, national director of amnesty international's campaign to abolish the death penalty
she said the governor's popularity waned after the controversy last year over a state sales tax on services. the governor originally backed the tax but later repudiated it
peck, the governor's spokesman, said politics had no bearing on the new death warrant
peck said martinez had instituted a new policy recently to schedule executions on subsequent warrants within 20 days, rather than 30 days, which he said would have put the execution near the good friday and easter holidays
it seemed like kind of an inappropriate time,'' peck said
darden attorney mark olive said he wasn't sure when he would file an execution appeal
when martinez signed the sixth death warrant in darden's case earlier this year, soviet dissident andrei sakharov, american actress margot kidder and british rock star peter gabriel urged clemency for darden
darden, 54, has been on death row since jan. 29, 1974. a prolific writer, he is nicknamed the ``poet of death row.''
italy's big league stylists said friday that five days of presentations of deluxe ready-to-wear clothes for next fall and winter went better than expected
strong trends such as the new, smaller silhouette and a revival of pants caught the interest of the fashion traders in milan. revitalized classics coupled with the high quality italian fabrics and workmanship contributed to the success
fear of the low buying power of the dollar had caused the italians to step carefully. the result was a simplified silhouette with plenty of commercially valid, wearable clothes
rigid cost control and the use of less opulent materials by some fashion companies kept price tags within reasonable limits. fashion houses reported price increases of never more than 10 percent above last year's prices
jitters regarding competition from avant-garde foreign designers _ the french in particular _ also showed signs of subsiding as orders rolled in
the general good health of italian fashion houses is demonstrated by their continuous expansion into profitable market sectors outside their ready-to-wear lines. perfumes, furs, eyeglasses, footwear, pens and watches are just some of the sidelines that stylists sign to promote their name and make money
perhaps the most successful part of the milan shows was the renewed interest in pants
pants are what it's all about,'' said kal ruttenstein, senior vice president-fashion director at bloomingdales
sal ruggiero, fashion director at marshall field and company of chicago, called them ``a great option'' until skirt lengths settle down
armani, mario valentino and krizia showed them in easy-fitting versions. ferre, versace and genny preferred a tighter look
pants frequently were cut high to emphasize the waist
the new tiny jacket, cropped at the waist and with tight-fitting sleeves, is a keynote of the well-bred trend. equally important is the tailored city coat modeled on riding jacket lines, flaring out from a fitted top
armani showed a winner in glen plaid and then repeated it in velvet for a formal evening. chalk-stripe gray flannel was the fabric choice used by other designers for this shape
on the same refined wavelength are the dickensian-style frock coats shown by romeo gigli, one of italy's youngest designers in the top slot. he continues to use his favorite knit fabrics for styles that fit as tight as a second skin, a habit copied by many of his colleagues
lots of boots, clinging tight as stockings, came in flat- or high-heeled versions and heralded a return of the footwear after several seasons
fake furs enjoyed another revival. fendi, byblos and armani for emporio produced some of the most beautiful
many of the biggest names in italian fashion will participate in ``moda italia,'' in new york. the show promoted by the italian trade commission will run from march 31 to april 17 in new york and then move to other cities. airfield. no pickup</note>
prince charles today said he and others in his party knew the risks of skiing off marked trails before an avalanche killed a companion and injured another in a ``whirling maelstrom.''
in a statement read to reporters shortly before the royal party flew from zurich airport to london, prince charles said:
i would like to emphazise that all members of my party, including myself, were skiing off the piste (trail) at our own risk and we all accepted ... that the mountains have to be treated with the greatest respect and not treated lightly.''
the handwritten statement, read by a press spokesman, also described thursday's tragedy in the mountains near the alpine resort of klosters
the snow slide missed the prince but killed a close friend, army maj. hugh lindsay, 34. another friend, patricia palmer-tomkinson, was knocked unconscious and suffered fractures of both legs
when the avalanche started, with a trememdous roaring, bruno sprechter (a guide), charles palmer-tomkinson, the swiss policeman and myself all managed by a great good fortune to ski to one side
to my horror, maj. hugh lindsay and mrs. palmer-tomkinson just failed to ski clear and were swept away in a whirling maelstrom as the whole mountainside seemed to hurtle past us to the valley below,'' the prince said
it was all over in a terrifying matter of seconds,'' the prince said
charles, his wife, diana, and sister-in-law, the duchess of york, landed at northolt, a royal air force base 11 miles west of london, this afternoon aboard a queen's flight aircraft after a 1{-hour from zurich. the plane carried lindsay's coffin
lindsay's pregnant widow, sarah, was at northolt when the royal party, wearing black, arrived. the 34-year-old press officer at buckingham palace watched from a vip lounge as eight officers from her husband's royal lancers regiment carried the coffin from the aircraft
she is expecting her first baby in may
earlier today, a doctor said charles' quick rescue efforts helped save the life of mrs. palmer-tomkinson, who was buried under the snowslide with lindsay
elsa rauch, a doctor who was flown to the scene, said charles and others dug out mrs. palmer-tomkinson
they were so fast that they dug her out in a few minutes and i would say they saved her life,'' she told the bbc. ``he (charles) helped to dig her out with his own hands. he was very controlled. he talked to the lady.''
witnesses said charles was distraught, in tears and trembling when a helicopter came to take him away from the scene
british newspapers clamored today for charles and other royals to abandon dangerous pursuits
charles is the next king. ... that means he must be ... safeguarded, if need be from himself,'' the daily mirror admonished in an editorial
the loose snow cascaded down as charles, 39, and five companions were skiing at about 5,800 feet in an area that was off the main skiing trails. authorities earlier in the day had warned it was prone to avalanches
diana and the duchess, the former sarah ferguson, were safe in a chalet when the avalanche struck. sarah is married to charles' younger brother, prince andrew, and is expecting the couple's first child in august
mrs. palmer-tomkinson regained consciousness after mouth-to-mouth resuscitation on the scene. a helicopter took her to davos, where she underwent surgery for multiple fractures of both legs and was reported in satisfactory condition this morning in a hospital intensive care unit
it was the royal family's worst accident since prince william of gloucester, a cousin of the queen, died when his sports plane crashed during an air race in 1972
lindsay, a former aide of the queen, was a close friend of charles and diana, who attended his high-society wedding last july. he frequently accompanied the royal couple on the annual ski holiday
the palmer-tomkinsons also vacation with charles and diana annually at klosters
vietnam's premier pham hung, who joined the communist movement when he was 16 and played a key role in defeating the united states in the vietnam war, has died of a heart attack. he was 75
the domestic vietnamese radio, quoting official communiques, said hung died early thursday afternoon ``while working in ho chi minh city (formerly saigon) and other southern provinces.''
it said the council of ministers named a vice premier, vo van kiet, as acting premier until the national assembly chooses a permanent successor
kiet, in his late 70s, is chairman of the state planning commission and is regarded by western analysts as the leading proponent of western-style reforms aimed at resolving the country's economic crisis
hung was a member of the ``old guard,'' a small group of revolutionaries who took up radical politics in their teens, joined the communist party in the 1930s and over the next half-century guided it to victory over the french, japanese and americans
some western diplomats say that in recent years, hung had been in bad health and did not have a central role in important policy decisions
his death was the latest in a series of recent major upheavals in the vietnamese leadership
party chief le duan died in mid-1986. his successor, truong chinh, and two other top party officials resigned in december 1986, when the sixth national party congress elevated more pragmatic party officials to positions of power
in june 1987, hung replaced pham van dong, who had been premier since 1955
the radio said that ``in the last minute of his life, comrade pham hung ... has closed his eyes like a combatant who has fallen in the battlefield.''
the broadcast announced three days of national mourning, from sunday to tuesday, when the funeral will be held
hung was born on june 11, 1912 in vinh long province, now called cuu long province, in the mekong river delta of southern vietnam
at the age of 16, he declared himself a radical, his activities eventually leading to his expulsion from secondary school
he joined the indochinese communist party in 1930, the year it was founded by ho chi minh. the following year, hung was arrested by french authorities and sentenced to death
after the penalty was commuted, hung spent the next decade and a half in hard labor at the notorious prison island of poulo condore
hung was released when communist forces came to power in north vietnam in 1945 and spent the next nine years of the war against the french in key party positions in south vietnam
after the french defeat at dien bien phu, hung rose rapidly in party and government ranks and returned to north vietnam. he entered the politburo in 1956 and two years later became vice premier of north vietnam
hung played key roles in the 1960-75 war against the u.s.-backed government of south vietnam. he was sent south in 1967 as secretary of the south vietnam commission of the party's central committee and as political commissar of the south vietnam liberation armed forces, commonly known as the viet cong
in 1975, he served as the political commissar of the ho chi minh campaign, the final north vietnamese offensive which climaxed with the capture of saigon on april 30
he became a vice premier in 1976, and in 1980 was named interior minister, a powerful post that deals with internal security. at the december 1986 party congress, he moved up to the no. 2 slot in the party politburo, behind the newly-chosen party general secretary, nguyen van linh
in 1987, he was replaced as interior minister in a major government reshuffle. that june, the national assembly named hung to replace dong, a veteran diplomat who was the only premier communist vietnam had ever had
given his age and conservative reputation, western diplomats said hung probably was elevated as a ``transitional'' figure who would pave the way for younger technocrats to preside over economic reforms
the national assembly on friday extended a state of emergency invoked feb. 26 during post-election riots in the capital of this western african nation
the violence broke out after the announcement that senegalese president abdou diouf, of the socialist party, had won re-election to a second five-year term. police waged running battles with stone-throwing protesters, and city businesses and homes of governing party officials were damaged
diouf's chief opponent, abdoulaye wade, of the senegalese democratic party, was charged by the government wednesday with 12 other opposition leaders in connection with the violence
diouf's party holds 103 of 120 seats in the assembly. under senegalese law, the president is required to gain its approval to extend the state of emergency
senegal has a democratic tradition with 17 political parties and a press that often criticizes the government
women who enter a public restroom have a legal right to expect the same privacy they have in their homes or offices, the state superior court ruled
the court rejected claims by a man convicted on felony trespass charges after he entered the ladies' room of the society hill club. his attorney contended that anthony white should have been found guilty only of ``defiant trespass,'' a misdemeanor, because the club was open to public access and, therefore, so were all restrooms
we deem the ladies' room to be a separately secured or occupied portion of the structure housing the society hill club,'' the said wednesday in upholding the felony trespass finding of a lower court
the trial court stated that the criminal trespass statute gives legal protection to the expectation of privacy that the occupants of the smaller units (within a structure or building) would realistically assume. the court concluded that the legislature intended to afford occupants of a restroom the same protection afforded occupants of an office.''
in other words, ``all women in the restroom may exclude all men, even those legitimately in the club,'' the court added
an aerobics instructor was alone in the restroom when white entered it, according to the court. white rifled through the contents of the woman's gym bag, made indecent propositions to her and used obscene language and gestures, the court said
white was sentenced to 1{ to three years in prison after being convicted of felony trespass and attempted robbery in philadelphia common pleas court in 1987
nearly 6,000 political activists have been imprisoned since the opposition launched its anti-government campaign last october, it was reported friday
holiday, an independent english-language weekly, said that about 6,000 people were ``languishing'' in jails
home secretary kamaluddin choudhury denied the report and said the figure was too high
most of the political prisoners arrested in recent months have been freed,'' he said
choudhury, however, declined to say how many activists were in jail
