pop singer andy gibb died of an inflamed heart caused most likely by a virus, not drug or alcohol abuse, doctors said today
the oxford coroner's office said an autopsy showed that gibb, 30, died naturally of a heart condition
the statements came after bee gees singer robin gibb angrily denied reports that his brother's death was related to drug abuse
constable michael harvey of the oxford coroner's office said that since the cause of death was natural, an inquest would not be conducted
mr. gibb died from inflammation of the heart of the sort commonly caused by a virus. there is no evidence that his death was related to drink or drugs,'' said a statement from the john radcliffe hospital in oxford where the singer died thursday
gibb had followed his brothers, who formed the bee gees rock group, to stardom in the late 1970s
there was no question of andy using drugs. i don't know where that story came from, but there is absolutely no truth in it. he was not using cocaine again,'' robin gibb told reporters at heathrow airport. british tabloids had said drug abuse may have caused the death
it was so unexpected,'' he said. ``andy had been ill with stomach pains for about four days.''
robin gibb, 39, was at the airport to meet his 72-year-old father, hughie, who was arriving from los angeles
press association, the domestic british news agency, said gibb was admitted to john radcliffe hospital on monday, discharged, and readmitted wednesday night after complaining of stomach pains
a hospital spokesman said the two-time grammy award nominee died at 8:45 a.m. thursday in the hospital, 50 miles northwest of london
in 1982, gibb acknowledged he became heavily involved in drugs and dropped his career after the break-up of his highly publicized relationship with television star victoria principal
three years later, he entered the betty ford rehabilitation center in rancho mirage, calif., for treatment of a cocaine habit
a spokesman for island records ltd., who spoke on condition of anonymity, said gibb signed a contract two months ago and would have started working on a new album this spring
gibb, who at times sang in a falsetto voice, had a string of hits in the late 1970s and early 1980s. his chart-toppers included ``i just want to be your everything,'' ``love is thicker than water,'' ``shadow dancing,'' ``everlasting love,'' and ``our love (don't throw it all away).''
despite his successful solo career, gibb never fully emerged from the shadow of his older superstar brothers, maurice, robin and barry, who formed the bee gees. last year, gibb went into bankruptcy proceedings in miami, where he had been living
but his miami lawyer, john kozyak, said gibb's bankruptcy was discharged in january, his debts were settled, and he ``was back on his feet and in good spirits and trying to put together a record contract.''
gibb was divorced from his wife, kim, in 1978. the couple had one child, a daughter, peta, 12
in addition to his singing career, gibb had a stint as a co-host on tv's ``solid gold,'' the syndicated musical variety show, but he was fired in 1982 for missing too many tapings
chronic absenteeism also cost gibb the title role of the broadway musical ``joseph and the amazing technicolor dreamcoat.'' after opening dec. 1, 1982 to generally favorable notices, gibb was fired the following month for missing 12 performances
president oscar arias, winner of the 1987 nobel peace prize for his central american peace plan, said the united states and soviet union should give the region a chance to work out its problems on its own
in an interview with the associated press, arias said he also has urged president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev to include central america as a topic in their next summit
stressing that the purpose of his peace plan was to ``build bridges,'' arias said he had received indications from both united states and soviet union that the superpowers will discuss the issue
i went to the u.s. congress to ask congressmen to give us central americans an opportunity to work out our problems,'' arias said in the interview, conducted thursday. ``but i cannot do the same thing in the soviet union because of the nature of its regime, radically different from the pluralistic democracy system of the west.''
arias said he was pleased that nicaragua's contra rebels had agreed to meet with nicaraguan government representatives inside that country and without a mediator for cease-fire talks. previous peace talks have been held outside the country and were mediated by nicaragua's roman catholic bishop
arias described a nicaraguan cease-fire as the ``key ... that would then open other possibilities'' for peace
but he expressed regrets that the soviet union continued to provide aid to leftist guerrilla movements in central america
i cannot use the soviet union's media and ask its government to give us the same chance i requested from the u.s. congress. i see where the soviet union continues to help guerrilla movements in central america and, in the last few months, as never before, is helping the sandinista governemnt militarily,'' he added
the war in nicaragua is one of the central american conflicts that arias hopes will be resolved as a result of his peace plan, which also seeks to end guerrilla wars in el salvador and honduras, bring democracy to the entire region, and end foreign aid to insurgents
the presidents of nicaragua, el salvador, honduras, and guatemala joined arias in signing the plan last august
arias said that if the united states and soviet union include central america's armed conflicts in their summit agenda, ``it would be very important for us to show between now and then that some progress has been made toward reaching a regional political solution.''
we have an opportunity, as never before, to find peace in central america,'' arias said. ``if we do not, those who come after us will feel less of a commitment to search for it.''
arias said a problem with making the peace plan work has been a lack of consistency between what is being said and done
there can be no peace without democracy in our region. they must go hand in hand,'' he said. ritalin</head>
a group formed by the church of scientology has filed five medical malpractice lawsuits in massachusetts against physicians who prescribed the drug ritalin to children to control supposed hyperactivity
the citizens commission for human rights claims ritalin is dangerous and over-prescribed
the maker of the drug, not named in any of the suits, denied all the group's claims friday
dennis clarke, president of the commission that was formed in 1969, read aloud from medical and psychiatric journals to back up the group's claims when the group announced the suits thursday with attorneys and two mothers who are plaintiffs. the suits do not request specific damages
too often, clarke said, teachers and school officials complain that a child is too active and suggest to parents that the child be taken to a pediatrician who recommends ritalin without careful examination
clarke said ritalin use requires increased dosage over time. withdrawal results in depression and can sometimes result in suicidal behavior, he claimed. he also cited medical journals in his claim that ritalin has been shown to cause psychotic episodes in children
such claims were all denied friday by ciba-geigy corp. spokeswoman gloria martini in summit, n.j., who said she has never seen in medical journals any of the claims clarke cited
ritalin has been out there for over 30 years and it has a long history of experience for physicians who use it,'' mrs. martini said. ``there is no evidence that it is addictive when used as directed.''
she said it has a potential for abuse, however
ciba-geigy introduced ritalin to the u.s. market in 1955. in 1987 it was used by an estimated 600,000 to 700,000 patients, mrs. martini said
clarke said he spoke briefly to attorneys representing rod matthews, the 15-year-old canton boy convicted of second-degree murder in the bludgeoning a classmate with a baseball bat. matthews' attorneys claimed the teen-ager had been taking ritalin and that it may have triggered the violent episode
susan marshall of hingham, mother of a child placed on ritalin and a plaintiff in one of the suits, said ritalin was prescribed for her ``normal, happy, well-adjusted'' son when he began to have slight handwriting problems in the first grade
i was not given any diagnosis, i was never told about any side effects,'' said mrs. marshall
her son took the drug for six months and became angry, hostile, moody and stopped eating most meals, she said. a neurologist later discovered his problem stemmed from slight brain damage
rita lassiter of new bedford said her son, matthew, was first described as ``too active'' by his kindergarten teachers and was given ritalin after a 10-minute examination by a pediatrician
bernard portnoy, who prescribed the drug for matthew lassiter, said he was unaware of the lawsuit against him
of ritalin, he said, ``i think it can be of help when it's used properly. it can be helpful in many cases.''
