a former top aide to gov. evan mecham testified today that he believed the governor was loyal to a state official accused of making a death threat because the man had been an effective campaign fund-raiser
former special assistant sam steiger, who faces a criminal extortion charge unrelated to mecham's case, testified at the governor's impeachment trial that mecham has a ``dangerous tendency of extreme loyalty'' to people who have helped him
mecham felt such loyalty toward lee watkins, who is accused of making a death threat against former mecham aide donna carlson, steiger said. ms. carlson was about to testify before a grand jury investigating the governor's campaign finances
mecham is accused of trying to thwart an investigation of the alleged threat
during thursday's testimony, mecham's defense lawyer angered senators by accusing the senate majority leader of showing ``overwhelming'' bias against the governor during his impeachment trial
jerris leonard lashed out at majority leader bob usdane when the republican lawmaker questioned whether the impeached governor's new lawyers erred when they said weeks ago they were ready to defend mecham
usdane ``ought to show a little more impartiality,'' said leonard. ``his bias and prejudice are overwhelming,'' and under normal trial circumstances he should be disqualified, the attorney said
for months, usdane has been accused by some lawmakers of being too accommodating toward mecham's gop administration
leonard's attack came during testimony on an accusation that mecham tried to block an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official. testimony on that charge was expected to continue today
usdane called the lawyer's blast ``ill-conceived.''
i don't think i'm biased,'' the majority leader added. ``i swore an oath to go (make a decision) based on the evidence and that's what i'll go on.''
minority leader alan stephens also took issue with leonard's statement
maybe they figured they've lost their case, and are going to go one by one trying to create controversy,'' stephens said. ``if that's so, we're all in for a very unpleasant time.''
the controversy arose when usdane challenged leonard's contention that he should be allowed to question a witness on matters not specified earlier because there had not been enough time to prepare for trial
the senator asked whether that countered an affidavit by mecham's new lawyers certifiying they were ready shortly before the trial began feb. 29
leonard joined mecham's defense team a week before the trial opened, and the governor's original defense lawyer resigned three days later
mecham, 63, is also accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 from a state protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership. he faces an april 21 criminal trial on charges of hiding the $350,000 loan, and a may 17 recall election
the governor is accused of ordering department of public safety director ralph milstead not to cooperate with a probe of the alleged threat last november against ms. carlson, a former mecham aide about to testify before a grand jury about the $350,000 loan
peggy griffith, head of the governor's office of women's services, testified last week that watkins, then the state prison construction chief, threatened ms. carlson's life during the second of two conversations nov. 12
the defense sought thursday to discredit mrs. griffith with testimony from her secretary, terri fields, who said her boss ``tends to exaggerate things a little'' and was not thorough in her work
when asked for an example of an exaggeration by mrs. griffith, ms. fields said she could not think of one. ms. fields testified she did not believe the second conversation between mrs. griffith and watkins ever happened
maybe she did have the conversation with lee watkins, but i don't believe that a threat came out of it,'' ms. fields said
ray russell, the only one of mecham's original special assistants still on his staff a year after the governor took office, testified that administration officials felt that ``every time you turned around it looked like somebody was investigating us for breaking the law.''
i know what's in his (mecham's) heart,'' russell said. ``i find him to be an honest, sincere man.''
mecham is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades and the first ever in arizona. a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required for a conviction that could bar him from ever holding public office again. bgng ``there's more...</note>
favorite son jesse jackson, looking for a warm homecoming in south carolina in saturday's democratic caucuses, said today ``it's get out the vote time'' in the state that gave him one of his few 1984 wins
jackson told about 250 supporters at the university of south carolina that the new challenge for the south is to ``find common ground where the people can come together.''
most political experts and campaign officials in the state agreed that jackson was the clear front-runner in the caucuses
there's more suspense over how close tennessee sen. albert gore jr. can come to jackson and the division of delegates, 44 of which are at stake saturday
south carolina's democratic leaders decided against following the crowd on super tuesday, when all of the other southern states held primaries
the candidates are relying on grass-roots organizing, telephone banks and direct mail to lure democrats to the caucus; gore is also buying television advertisements
gore, who was campaigning in greenville, columbia and charleston today, has the largest organization in the state and the most endorsements from elected officials, who wield strong influence at the caucuses
missouri rep. richard gephardt, who traveled across the state wednesday and thursday, has a skeletal organization. but his few endorsements from elected officials are the biggest _ former govs. dick riley and robert mcnair and all of the south carolina democratic congressmen who have chosen sides
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis has an even smaller local organization and virtually no endorsements from elected officials
but dukakis' strong super tuesday showing will help earn him a chunk of votes saturday, barry weiner, dukakis' national campaign co-chairman, said thursday in columbia
all of the competing state campaigns except gore's have conceded that jackson will win the lion's share of the 44 delegates at stake
i don't think there is any doubt that jesse jackson will win,'' said bill prince, gephardt's state coordinator
house speaker robert sheheen, gore's state chairman, said ``there's really no way of knowing'' whether the tennessee senator can upset jackson. ``we're not conceding anything to anybody.''
gore is promoting his strong ties to the south and a strong defense, which plays well in the palmetto state
gephardt is hoping to use his trade policy to gain votes in the state, which has seen its largest industry _ textiles _ severely weakened by cheap foreign imports. his first stop wednesday was a textile plant in aiken county that is scheduled to close next month and put 420 people out of work
between a quarter and a half of south carolina democrats traditionally remain uncommitted at the caucus meetings to give themselves more maneuvering room through the nominating process. they usually choose a candidate at the county or state convention
that leaves relatively few delegates for the candidates to divide up saturday. but in a tight national race in which no candidate has been able to take a decisive lead, every one helps
this certainly increases the importance of south carolina because the delegate count is so close,'' said kevin gray, state coordinator for jackson
thailand's envoy urged the united states on friday not to cut quotas for indochinese refugees to make room for armenians fleeing the soviet union
if more armenians are permitted into the united states the quotas for eastern europe should be raised and the quotas for indochina should be left alone, ambassador arsa sarasin told a news conference
the u.s. budget currently permits the annual entry of 68,500 refugees from around the world, including 23,000 from indochina. thailand, where 400,000 indochinese refugees reside, mostly in camps, is pressing continuously for higher quotas
the united states must not cut the quota and give it to eastern europe,' sarasin said
the reagan administration is in the process of deciding what to do about a massive increase in applications for entry from residents of soviet armenia
according to state department records, armenians are applying for asylum at a rate of 1,500 a month, compared with 200 applicants in all of 1985 and 200 to 300 a month as recently as 1987. up to 12,000 armenians are reportedly waiting to come to the united states
a current wave of ethnic protests in armenia has highlighted some of the dissatisfaction there toward soviet government policies in the region
sarasin said he felt better about the situation after jonathan moore, director of the state department's division of refugee affairs, told a congressional hearing feb. 24 that no decision to alter quotas had been made
a u.s. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said however that changes were possible under some of the options being considered by an interagency group
the group may decide to reallocate quotas, grant emergency quotas for the armenians, or slow down processing of refugees to pay for the influx from armenia
relations between the united states and thailand have been in a somewhat sour state lately, mostly because of the refugee problem. after years of providing asylum to people fleeing cambodia, vietnam and laos, resistance is growing in thailand to the continuing influx
leaders there have accused the united states, australia, canada and other resettlement countries of failing to live up to commitments to find new homes for the refugees
thailand cannot bear the burden indefinitely,'' sarasin said. ``there is a limit to our capacity.''
moore and other u.s. officials have been sympathetic to thailand's concerns and have sought higher refugee quotas. at the same time, they have criticized inhumane treatment of refugees in thailand
such treatment has included the closing of some camps, the pushing of boats laden with refugees out to sea and the forced repatriation of lao tribesmen seeking a haven in thailand. up 6th graf pvs, `bruecher had ....'</note>
the captain of a continental airlines flight that crashed last november, killing 28 people and injuring 54, generally performed well when he was tested on a dc-9, a flight trainer testified today at a federal hearing
however, the co-pilot, first officer lee bruecher, 26, was at the controls of continental flight 1713 when it crashed at denver's stapleton international airport on nov. 15. both the pilot and co-pilot were killed
on thursday, a different flight trainer testified that bruecher had trouble with takeoffs and landings during his simulator training on the dc-9
in testimony today before national transportation safety board officials investigating the accident, continental capt. james edward madsen said capt. frank zvonek did a good job on a test ride from denver to albuquerque, n.m., but he did not give himself as long a final approach as madsen would have liked and did not allow enough visual clearance behind a small aircraft
i would have given myself another mile or two of spacing,'' said madsen, but added, ``it was not a down or unsatisfactory flight at all.''
continental pilot trainer j.e. summerville's testimony thursday about bruecher's performance highlighted the third day of the four-day ntsb hearing. the board is trying to identify factors that caused the dc-9 to crash moments after takeoff
bruecher was a good student but had problems with takeoffs and landings, and summerville once had to ``freeze'' the training simulator to avoid a crash during a practice landing, he said thursday
bruecher ``had trouble controlling altitude and airspeed within reasonable limits,'' summerville wrote, and repeated one course of the seven-part flight simulator training
however, at the conclusion of the training, summerville said, he recommended bruecher for the federal aviation administration proficiency test needed to fly a specific kind of airplane
bruecher finished a proficiency check on sept. 14, 1987, with another instructor who graded his performance ``average'' and began his initial operating experience as a line pilot with continental on oct. 2. at the time of the crash, he had only 36 hours piloting dc-9s, ntsb investigators have said
zvonek had 198 hours on a dc-9 with only the previous 33 hours as captain
ntsb officials on thursday also questioned capt. dave dickerson, manager of continental's dc-9 program at houston, about training procedures. dickerson said he saw no correlation between bruecher's level of experience and the problems he experienced
de-icing was another subject of testimony
summerville said he instructs pilots during training to re-evaluate the condition of their aircraft if 20 minutes or more elapse between the time the plane is de-iced and takeoff
i tell them to look at the parts you can see from the cockpit, including the nose, the windshield wipers, unheated windows and any aircraft around you.''
depending on the weather conditions, summerville said, he sometimes would advise pilots to go into the cabin and look out at the wings. ``but we all know that's not the best way to look to see if you've got ice on the wings.'' a mechanic's inspection at the gate would be better, he said
earlier testimony showed that a mixup by air traffic officials delayed flight 1713's takeoff by minutes, but no conclusions were drawn on whether that had any role in the crash
also under investigation is the possibility that a wing vortex, or swirling wind triggered by another plane's wing moving through the air, could have contributed to the crash
authorities say it's just too bad: michael jackson cannot bring his pet chimpanzee bubbles along when he performs here this summer
the aftonbladet newspaper reported friday that the national board of agriculture has said ``definitely not'' to bubbles, a 3-year-old former laboratory chimp used for cancer research. sweden's stringent regulations impose quarantines of up to six months on most animals entering the country
