a truck driver surrendered to police this morning after he stormed into his estranged wife's home and fired six blasts from a shotgun, then jackknifed his rig on a busy freeway, authorities said
one shot was fired a short time before the incident ended about 7:25 a.m., but police said it was not aimed at them and nobody was injured
ronald stone, 34, was taken to solano county jail to be booked for investigation of attempted murder, according to police lt. gary mallory
it was a replay of a similar incident from a decade ago, according to police chief gary tatum, who said stone then held off police with a gun in a domestic dispute and spent some time in jail as a result
the truck driver had threatened to shoot anyone who approached, police said. officers from three agencies surrounded the section of interstate 80 where stone sat in the vehicle with ``lots of ammunition,'' said mallory
a special weapons and tactics unit from the police department, california highway patrol officers and solano county sheriff's deputies rushed to the area
he has a 12-gauge shotgun and he fired six rounds while at his wife's home, four inside and two outside,'' mallory said
tatum said jackie stone first called police at 12:46 a.m. to report her husband was at the door and appeared to be drunk. by the time officers arrived, he was gone
tatum said they received a second call about half an hour later saying stone had returned
stone, who separated from his wife about a month ago, kicked in the front door of the house
after telling the couple's three children it was time for their mother ``and him to die,'' stone began beating his wife, mallory said
his mother-in-law and the children fled from the house, and stone's wife managed to escape soon after, police said
when officers arrived, stone threatened to kill himself, holding the shotgun beneath his chin with a finger poised on the trigger, mallory said
finally, he leaped into his unmarked tractor-trailer rig and, with police pursuing, headed for the freeway, the officer said. there, stone jackknifed the truck, leaving the cab stuck in the median and the trailer jutting into traffic
police talked with stone, first by cb radio and then, after he stopped, via a field telephone tossed into the cab
after firing a final blast out the window of the truck, stone gave up. he suffered minor powder burns from the shotgun, but was otherwise unhurt
the highway patrol closed the freeway in both directions, jamming one of the main arteries leading to the san francisco bay area and the state capital in sacramento. graf pvs bgng ``the precinct delegates...</note>
jesse jackson finished first in alaska's democratic precinct caucuses, posting a narrow victory over massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in a nonbinding preference poll announced today
with about 90 percent of alaska's 442 precincts reporting, jackson claimed 872 delegates, or 35 percent of the total, to dukakis' 769 delegates, or 31 percent
a close third, however, were 768 delegates, or 31 percent, who were uncommitted
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. finished a distant fourth, with 47 delegates or 2 percent, followed by illinois sen. paul simon with 18 delegates, less than 1 percent, and missouri rep. richard gephardt, 16 delegates for less than 1 percent
henry lancaster, statewide coordinator for the jackson campaign, said that with blacks comprising just 3 percent of alaska's population, his candidate's appeal came from the anti-drug and economic issues he's been voicing around the nation
this state has a lot of working-class people who've come from the south, the midwest and the northwest,'' lancaster said. ``in down times, people are looking for solutions. and this is a down time.''
that reference was to the collapse of alaska's oil-fired economy. about 85 percent of the state's budget is supported by oil revenues, and world oil prices are less than half what they were three years ago
the democrats chose 2,496 delegates in caucuses around the state thursday night. the caucuses were open to any registered democrat and anyone who wished to register at the door
the precinct delegates selected thursday will meet at 27 district caucuses on april 9-10. they will select 390 delegates to attend the state convention in fairbanks on may 13-15
none of the delegates chosen before the state convention is bound to a particular candidate
the 12 delegates emerging from the state convention will attend the national convention in atlanta in july. those delegates will be bound to a specific candidate for at least the first ballot. graf, on the</note>
democrat gary hart dropped out of the presidential campaign today, saying ``i got a fair hearing and the people have decided,'' as republicans bob dole and pat robertson vowed to stay in the race
hart left the campaign last may after disclosure of his relationship with model donna rice but then rejoined it in december, declaring, ``let the people decide.''
today in denver, as he withdrew again, he said the people had had their say: ``clearly i should not go forward.''
hart failed to win any delegates in the primaries and caucuses, polled no more than 5 percent of the vote in any of the super tuesday primaries and lost his eligibility for further federal matching funds
my friends and supporters have given the word `loyalty' new meaning,'' he said. ``they've toiled tirelessly in an uphill fight.''
dole said today in remarks to illinois farm bureau leaders, ``i want to make certain you understand i am in this race.'' press reports had noted he had taken his television ads off the air in illinois and had drastically cut his campaign staff after being beaten by vice president george bush in 16 super tuesday contests
noting those reports, he said today, ``it's hard to focus on the issues sometimes because the press won't let us do that. they would rather write about how many staff you reduced your numbers by. i never thought that a campaign was a jobs program.''
in peoria, robertson said, ``i'm in it until new orleans (site of the republican national convention). it looks overwhelming for one of the republican candidates, but goliath was pretty overwhelming as well. we're going to win.''
five days before the illinois primary, democratic candidates participated in a televised forum thursday night, but in contrast to many of their joint appearances, not a cross word was exchanged
it was ``all sweetness and light,'' said illinois sen. paul simon after the forum sponsored by wls-tv and the roosevelt center for american policy studies
simon greeted people eating breakfast today at the golden nugget pancake house on the north side of chicago and predicted the democratic convention would need at least two ballots to choose its presidential nominee
i think i have as good a chance as anyone,'' he said
then simon stopped by the polish national alliance where he received the endorsement of the polish daily zgoda, a polish language newspaper
a washington post-abc news poll published today but conducted wednesday, the day after the super tuesday primaries and six days before illinois votes, said vice president george bush had the support of 58 percent of republicans
on the democratic side, simon was backed by 38 percent of the likely voters surveyed and chicago-based jesse jackson had support of 33 percent. the figures for simon and jackson were well within the 8 percentage point margin of error
in alaska, democratic officials said today that jackson finished first in the state's precinct caucuses, posting a narrow victory over massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in a nonbinding preference poll, 34.9 percent to 31 percent
uncommitted caucus delegates ran a close third, with the other candidates far behind
rep. jack kemp of new york ended his presidential bid on thursday and said the idea of being the republican candidate for vice president was ``a very flattering and awesome thought.''
kemp declined to endorse any of the surviving candidates _ bush, dole and pat robertson _ describing them all as ``reagan conservatives.''
dole scotched rumors that he was about to join kemp on the campaign sidelines
bob dole's no dropout,'' he said in a statement issued in washington and illinois. ``i'm in this one to win.''
bush beat dole in all 16 super tuesday primaries and now has 705 national convention delegates compared to 165 for the kansas senator
dole did not say whether he would remain in the race if he loses to bush in illinois but an aide said, ``i think it's clear to dole that it's do or die.''
dole canceled all television commercials in illinois and ordered deep layoffs in his staff. an aide said the campaign was considering airing a 30-minute paid broadcast in the closing hours of the campaign
one bright spot for the kansas senator was the endorsement of the chicago tribune which said that bush's identification with president reagan, while a big help in republican primary contests, might be a handicap in the general election
nowhere have the republican candidates asked or answered the kind of harsh questions the democrats surely will raise in november about the reagan administration, whose colors mr. bush has been able to wave more furiously than anyone else,'' the newspaper said in an editorial headlined, ``why illinois should pick dole.''
robertson, who also had a disappointing day on super tuesday, also ordered deep staff cuts
we want to stay lean and mean,'' he said, declining to give the number of employees laid off
the vice president also was campaigning in the state in advance of tuesday's primary. illinois voters will elect delegates and also express their preferences in a beauty contest on the ballot
bush told a governors club luncheon in chicago that he was ``tired of being embarrassed'' by scandals involving government officials and he called for establishment of a white house ethics panel
bush has refused, however, to criticize any administration officials, including attorney general edwin meese iii, who have come under investigation by grand juries
a snowstorm caused south dakota democrats to postpone a statewide caucus called for saturday, when the party was to decide how to apportion 15 of the state's national convention delegates
it's a quality snowstorm,'' said rick hauffe, acting director of the south dakota democratic party. ``it really dumped.''
the friday storm was expected to leave from 4 to 18 inches of snow across the state
hauffe said the caucus has been rescheduled for march 19
missouri rep. richard gephardt won the state's democratic primary on feb. 23, but national party rules would not permit the election to have any directly binding effect on the national convention delegates
the dispute with the national party centered on the timing of the primary, which came two weeks earlier than allowed by national party rules
the statewide caucus, meeting within the time allowed by the national rules, was to decide whether to allocate the delegates among the presidential candidates in proportion to the primary results. under the rules, the caucus is free to use the primary results or reject them entirely, basing the allocation instead on the presidential preferences of the people attending the caucus
if the caucus decides to use the primary results, only gephardt and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis would qualify for any delegates
based on the primary results, gephardt would receive nine pedged delegates to the democratic national convention and dukakis would get six, party officials have said
a close aide to president suharto was sworn in as vice president friday despite opposition from the parliament's moslem faction and some members of the military
state secretary sudharmono was elected to the post earlier in the day, hours after suharto was sworn in for a fifth five-year term. the five factions of the people's consultative assembly reached a consensus to elect sudharmono after the moslem united development party dropped its candidate, party chairman jailani naro
the decision to withdraw naro's candidacy came after suharto named the 61-year-old sudharmono as his choice for vice president in a meeting with the assembly leadership
sudharmono was formally nominated by the governing golkar party, an acronym for the indonesian words ``golongan karya'' or functional group. he was also supported by the assembly's government-nominated military faction, the government-nominated provincial faction and the nationalist christian indonesian democratic party faction
suharto, 66, reportedly told golkar members last month that the next vice president should be able to lead the nation should the president become incapacitated
military sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said some members of the army had opposed his nomination. they supported instead the newly appointed armed forces commander, gen. try sutrisno, 52, a popular figure and a former suharto aide
an army general took to the podium following suharto's re-election thursday to protest nominating procedures for the vice president
we indonesian soldiers who believe in god and defend honesty and justice have heard rumors that the nomination of the vice president is not being fairly and correctly carried out,'' said brig. gen. ibrahim saleh, an assembly member from the government-nominated military faction
there are certain things that we feel are against our consience,'' said saleh, who was escorted out by assembly officials before he could finish his statement
sudharmono, a retired army lieutenant general, is a military lawyer by training. he became one of the country's leading bureaucrats after years of government apprenticeship, first under the late president sukarno and then as a founding member of the suharto administration
addressing the parliament after he was sworn in, sudharmono said an ability to work closely with the president was of extreme importance
i extend my deepest gratitude to president suharto for giving me this honor and trust to work with him in the coming five years,'' he said
authorities broadcast warnings friday to tibetan rebels to turn themselves in by march 20 or face punishment, according to a western source in the tibetan capital of lhasa
the source, a tibetan-speaking traveler, said vans with loudspeakers were driving through the city every hour repeating the same message
police with machine guns, meanwhile, remained posted in front of the city's holiest temple, the sprawling, white-washed jokhang temple, and on the roofs of nearby buildings, western tourists said. it was at the jokhang that last weekend's riots began
they're warning people to do their duty, report troublemakers. they'll be rewarded if they give information,'' the tibetan-speaking traveler said in a telephone interview from beijing
she said one announcement called ``for people to surrender _ people who were involved in the disturbances _ before the 20th, otherwise they would be punished.''
thousands of tibetans demanding independence from china stoned police and set bonfires throughout lhasa last saturday in a day of violence triggered when one buddhist monk stood up at a prayer festival and began shouting anti-chinese slogans
official reports said one chinese police officer and one tibetan were killed. however, an american traveler in lhasa who saw some of the violence said tibetans estimate 21 tibetans and three police were killed
the official xinhua news agency said a hero's funeral was held friday in lhasa for the dead policeman, 21-year-old yuan shisheng, who was stabbed and thrown out of a second-story window. it said more than 2,500 mourners attended
the hong kong branch of the china news service, also an official mainland agency, reported that a local tibetan civil and religious official and two 18-year-old tibetans were arrested wednesday. the brief report said they were accused of taking part in violent anti-chinese protests in october
at least 14 people were killed in the largest of those protests, when thousands of tibetans stoned and burned a police station on oct. 1
the china news service report did not say why the three were arrested only now. it was the first official report of any arrests since the march 5 uprising
unofficial reports of wide-scale arrests continued to filter out of lhasa. estimates ranged up to 1,000, but none of the figures could be confirmed. authorities have refused to allow foreign reporters to visit lhasa this week and have halted sales of plane tickets to lhasa to all foreigners
the approximately one dozen foreign travelers in lhasa have been virtually the only source of information on events in the remote mile-high city surrounded by mountains
an ethnic tibetan from nepal who left lhasa on friday said police came to his uncle's house several times in recent days, making house-to-house checks for suspects
the western woman reported 10 arrests among the families of her tibetan acquaintances. she said the tibetans reported police dragged suspects from their homes in the middle of the night, beating them
she said she had stopped visiting tibetan friends for fear of drawing police attention to them
she said it was ``almost impossible'' to telephone outside of lhasa, and interrupted the interview several times to say, ``people here (running the hotel) are getting very nervous'' about her conversation
trucks carrying armed police also drove through the city friday, but in smaller convoys than earlier in the week, the foreigners reported
on wednesday and thursday, one american said he counted more than 100 trucks, each carrying 20 to 30 police, driving in a parade through the city in a show of force
even under normal circumstances, tibet is a heavily militarized region because of its long border with india, with which china has clashed several times. large police and military installations rim the capital city of about 150,000 people, and some western experts estimate there is one chinese soldier for every 10 tibetans
china claims tibet has been part of its empire since the 13th century. however, the remote region was effectively ruled for much of that time by the buddhist monasteries and the dalai lama, whom tibetans regard as a reincarnation of their protector god
the current dalai lama, regarded as the 14th in a line of reincarnations, fled to india in 1959, nine years after chinese communist troops entered tibet. his flight was triggered by a massive anti-chinese uprising in which thousands of tibetans were killed
athens has linked its improving relations with turkey to its talks with the united states on military bases in greece, a government spokesman said friday
greece and the united states ended their fourth round of negotiations on a new agreement to replace one expiring in december
the talks were also dedicated this time to the exchange of views between the two sides on issues of principle that have been put forward by the greek government,'' said spokesman sotiris kostopoulos
kostopoulos apparently was referring to greek demands linking a new accord to progress on greek-turkish problems
relations between the two neighboring allies have been steadily improving since premier andreas papandreou's recent meetings with turkish prime minister turgut ozal. greece and turkey have quarreled over aegean airspace and seabed rights
the united states has said it wants to avoid regional politics in the bilateral base negotiations
there are four u.s. bases in greece: two near athens and two on the southern island of crete. greece receives more than $300 million a year in military credits as payment
more negotiations are scheduled in athens next month and in washington in may. ast, picking up 7th graf pvs, ``no use ....'</note>
strong winds and unseasonably warm temperatures whittled a 70-year-old musher's lead in the 1,150-mile iditarod trail sled dog race to a matter of minutes, according to standings this morning
at last report, joe redington, known as the ``father of the iditarod'' because he helped organize the first race 16 years ago, still was on the trail between cripple and sulatna crossing today, the seventh day of the race
it's only 47 miles between the two checkpoints, and the length of time it was taking redington to cover the distance was a reflection of the weather. normally, iditarod teams average 8-10 mph
all 50 dog teams in the race from anchorage to nome were slowed thursday by temperatures that climbed into the 40s, turning the trail soggy and overheating the cold-loving huskies who pull the sleds
redington waited 11 hours after reaching cripple for more favorable weather, and by the time he decided to move, second-place herbie nayokpuk decided his team was rested enough to push on
nayokpuk, known as the shishmaref cannonball, had arrived in cripple more than six hours behind redington, but he left at 3:20 p.m., only five minutes after the leader
in third place was martin buser of big lake, who pulled into cripple at 2:50 p.m. he was followed by four-time iditarod champion rick swenson of two rivers at 3:20 p.m.; joe garnie of teller at 3:22 p.m.; and defending champion susan butcher of manley at 4:35 p.m
redington, who arrived in cripple, 525 miles from the start, at 4:50 a.m., tried leaving at 9 a.m. thursday, but the sun-softened snow turned him around
no use to fight that. let it harden up a little bit,'' he said just before leaving thursday afternoon. ``the dogs were right up to their bellies, going along about 4 to 5 miles an hour. i went out about three miles and came back. thought i'd wait a while.''
the delay gave an advantage to teams that have been hounding redington since he took the lead 260 miles back in rohn, but he said there was little choice, given the soft trail
it doesn't hurt to give the dogs a little more rest,'' he said
from cripple, the trail heads to ruby, on the yukon river, then follows the frozen river to kaltag and cuts over to unalakleet on the bering sea coast
the first musher to reach nome will win $30,000. the next 19 finishers will split the rest of a $150,000 purse
two teams have dropped out of the race, and two of the more than 800 dogs running have died, race officials said. both deaths were ruled accidental
having friends in high places brought in a load of booty last year for top u.s. government officials, who collected $232,404 in presents that ranged from the edible to the incredible
when soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev came to washington to sign an arms treaty in december, he brought 35 ounces of russian black caviar for president reagan, worth $875
from west german chancellor helmut kohl, reagan received a $300 case of german wine; from canadian governor general jeanne suave, a $10 bottle of maple syrup; and from king hassan of morocco, ``a large basket of delicacies and foodstuffs'' with a price tag of $100
first lady nancy reagan was given two enlarged photogrphs, taken by a french satellite, of the reagans' ranch in california's santa ynez mountains. that and other gifts came from french prime minister jacques chirac. value: $1,500
among other gifts from foreign officials, which were listed by the state department in friday's federal register, was an ak-47 automatic rifle, ``with separate box of ammunition,'' given to former defense secretary caspar weinberger by chinese gen. yang shangkun
secretary of state george shultz's wife, helena, was given a $20 ``horse tail fly whisk'' by women from the cameroon people's democratic movement
and gen. manuel antonio noriega, who is being pressured by the united states to step down as panama's military ruler, sent a dozen bottles of champagne worth $285 to the u.s. army southern command at fort clayton, panama, last july 4
edible gifts, like the syrup and the caviar, can be consumed by the recipients. less expensive items also can be kept, but federal law requires that anything worth more than $180 be turned over to the government to go into a museum or to be auctioned off. in many cases, the gifts can be retained ``for official use'' in the offices of the recipient
in each case, the gifts were accepted because ``refusal would have caused embarrassment to donor and u.s. government,'' the state department said
the reagans received a total of $81,178 in presents, the most expensive of which was a $12,600 crystal bowl and platter from swedish prime minister ingvar carlsson
knowing of mrs. reagan's fondness for smart clothes, semra ozal, wife of the turkish prime miniser, gave the first lady a brown leather dress with black velvet and gold bead decorations, a matching fur-trimmed leather jacket and a black leather evening suit, also trimmed with fur. the outfits were valued at $700
the prime minister, turgut ozal, gave the president a pair of carved-wood walking sticks decorated with silver-colored metal and bearing pictures of the reagans. they were valued at $120
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir gave the reagans a calligraphic sculpture forming the hebrew letters resh and nun, which spell the word ``ron'' phonetically and also stand for the hebrew characters for ``ronald'' and ``nancy.'' it was worth an estimated $750
many of the gifts were in some way identified with the donor nation. african countries tended to give handmade craft items, middle eastern countries often gave rugs, and some foreign leaders gave pictures of themselves
at least one gift couldn't be appraised. reagan was given a stone launched by the romans in the first-century seige of masada, in southern israel, which israeli president chaim herzog had encased in lucite and mounted on black marble
vice president george bush reported receiving a pair of $4,475 ``gyro-stabilized binoculars'' from jordan's gen. zeid bin shaker and a $5,700 set of olympic commemorative coins from former south korean president chun doo-hwan. bush got his own caviar from gorbachev as well, 35 ounces also valued at $875
senate republican leader bob dole of kansas received from gorbachev a black lacquer box, worth $300 to $500, that was decorated with a picture of moscow. sen. robert kasten, r-wis., was given a pair of unappraised elephant tusks by president hissene habre of chad. and sen. edward kennedy, d-mass., and two aides received watches and cuff links worth a total of $8,500 from the amir of bahrain
cia director william webster got a long list of items, ranging from a $350 indo-persian silk wall hanging to a gold egyptian ceremonial sword worth $1,000. the identity of the donors was deemed too sensitive to be disclosed
the marine corps, already renowned for its rigorous physical conditioning, is about to make things tougher for those who have already made it through basic training
a new training policy order, signed last week and now being prepared for distribution to the field, will require all commands to refocus their physical conditioning program so that it goes beyond just staying in shape to pass the standard physical fitness test
among other things, all marines are going to be expected to start lifting weights or to engage in some equivalent type of ``progressive resistance training'' such as ``isometric exercises or partner resistance exercises.''
the new directive was signed by brig. gen. f.e. sisley, the corps' deputy chief of staff for training, but was really prompted by gen. alfred m. gray jr., the man who took over as the corps' commandant last july
gray, a stocky, tobacco-chewing general who rose through the ranks by staying away from the pentagon, complained shortly after arriving in washington he was sick and tired of seeing his marines jogging for exercise ``in cute little sneaks.''
marine headquarters ``looks like a morgue'' every afternoon because everyone is out jogging to ``look nice,'' gray added
i think if we would run a little more each day we'd be the best looking outfit ever to get run off a hill.''
reflecting that philosophy, the new directive states: ``historically, the purpose of many physical conditioning programs has been to prepare marines for fitness testing, rather than training them for the physical rigors of combat
the focus, therefore, of our programs must change. each commander must emphasize unit and combat fitness training, (instead of) physical fitness testing, and reflect this distinction in training plans and schedules.''
the directive makes it clear the corps is not changing its standard physical fitness test, which all marines must pass at least once every six months. that test requires marines to meet standards for a 3-mile run and performing sit-ups and pullups
rather, the directive says commanders must ensure their marines face ``a minimum program of three hours per week'' of exercises that can be divided between anaerobic conditioning, progressive resistance training and aerobic conditioning
anaerobic conditioning would include calisthenics and other exercises ``to increase speed, flexibility and agility,'' while aerobic includes running and any exercise that ``enhances cardiovascular endurance.''
weight-lifting will fulfill the requirement for progressive resistance training and is needed because of the ``correlation of muscular strength and endurance to success in combat operations,'' the directive states
moreover, when a marine is finished with his regular physical conditioning, his commander should make sure he gets some ``occupational conditioning,'' the directive continues
a marine who is schooled as an infantryman, for example, should face some ``progressive load-bearing marches, dry net training, swimming, obstacle courses, confidence courses, etc.,'' the directive says
and once the marine is done with his occupational training, his commander should include some ``competitive conditioning activities ... to foster competitive attitudes.''
however, the directive does warn the commander to keep in mind ``the stark truth of the saying, `no enemy has ever been killed by a basketball.'''
the overall objective, the directive concludes, ``is to develop in marines a reserve level of physical fitness that will enhance their chances of winning in a combat situation.''
a private college group urged president reagan on friday to sign the civil rights restoration act, even though the act fails to include a broad exemption for religious schools
richard f. rosser, president of the national association of independent colleges and universities, said his organization was the main proponent of efforts that failed in the house to add a so-called religious tenet amendment to the bill
but the association of 800 private institutions, including catholic and other religious-affiliated colleges, still wants reagan to sign the bill, which restores the scope of civil rights laws restricted by the supreme court in a 1984 case involving grove city (pa.) college
rosser, in a letter to reagan, said it was made clear during the house debate that the legislative intent of the new bill is ``to give deferential treatment to requests for religious exemption under title ix.''
as the lead organization seeking passage of a religious tenet amendment ... we hope that the religious liberty concerns we articulated can be addressed by the congress at a future time,'' rosser said
we want to reiterate our unqualified support for this legislation,'' he added
reagan has repeatedly threatened to veto the legislation, which was passed by margins of 75-14 in the senate and 315-98 in the house _ easily enough to override a veto
the senate approved the bill last month after adding an amendment that says nothing in the bill or existing law requires any institution to perform or pay for abortions
the house passed the bill march 2 despite a written warning from reagan that he would veto it ``if it is presented to me in its current form.''
he said then it ``dramatically expands the scope of federal jurisdiction over state and local governments and the private sector'' and ``poses a particular threat to religious liberty.''
the restoration act specifies that entire institutions and government agencies are covered by federal laws protecting the civil rights of women, minorities, the handicapped and the elderly if any program or activity within the institutions receives federal aid
the bill exempts farmers getting crop subsidies, people on food stamps and others receiving federal assistance
when sen. paul simon asked local supporters this week to cast nine votes for him in illinois' democratic primary, it wasn't an incitement to vote fraud
simon's plea reflected illinois' two-part presidential ballot: a non-binding ``beauty contest'' preference vote and dozens of local races for the democratic and republican delegate slots that are the real prize on tuesday
unlike many states in which delegates are apportioned on the basis of a statewide vote, illinois' delegates are elected directly by voters in congressional district races
it's a key feature of the political terrain for presidential candidates in illinois, offering advantages to simon, george bush and bob dole and posing daunting problems for others, political obervers say
the 82 republican and 113 democratic delegate slots to be filled tuesday are apportioned among the state's 22 congressional districts on the basis of relative strength in previous primaries
for example, in the heavily democratic 1st district on chicago's south side, democratic voters will select nine delegates and three alternates, while republicans will choose two delegates and two alternates
recruiting delegate-candidates is a key organizational hurdle for the presidential campaigns. without backers on the delegate ballot, a candidate can't translate illinois support into convention votes
the system is further complicted this year by the crowded presidential field, leaving voters in some areas to choose among as many as 70 delegate candidates
i am asking for nine votes,'' simon told backers at a springfield fund-raiser on wednesday. ``six for delegates, two for alternates and one for that beauty contest. all nine votes are important.''
simon's political roots in illinois gave him an edge in recruiting well-known delegate-candidates with a voter appeal of their own. his slates are studded with state legislators, labor leaders and party activists
basically, we looked for people that have well-known names or would bring in a supporting group: a labor-union leader, a person from nuclear freeze, an elected official or party leader,'' said mike kreloff, simon's illinois delegate coordinator
they'll help him hold off (michael) dukakis, but their impact is minimized by the fact that the presidential candidate's name appears on the ballot'' alongside the delegate-candidates, said steve copple, jesse jackson's national delegate coordinator. ``the bulk of the people are going to vote for their presidential candidates' supporters.''
illinois' delegate selection system is a handicap for jackson, whose stronghold is three predominantly black districts in chicago. those districts will elect 24 of the 113 democratic delegates, but his chances of success elsewhere are questionable
simon's other democratic foes had little success in recruiting big names, and only he and dukakis have full slates in every district. albert gore has no supporters on the ballot in three districts and richard gephardt is short of a full slate in five districts
even favorite son jackson has no delegate slate in the heavily republican 12th district, and is short of a full slate in three other districts
we were looking for people who had a fundamental commitment to al gore and his philosophy,'' said larry perlman, who runs the gore campaign in illinois. ``that meant we didn't get a lot of people who have been around party politics for a long time.''
on the gop side, bush and dole both assembled impressive slates with the help of their state chairmen, gov. james r. thompson and illinois house republican leader lee daniels. pat robertson also has a full slate in every district, but virtually all of his candidates are political unknowns
bush operatives acknowledge that well-known dole delegate-candidates such as former gov. richard ogilvie and former u.s. attorney dan k. webb might help dole revive his candidacy
i don't think name recognition alone is going to win for the delegates,'' said ed murnane, deputy director of bush's illinois campaign. ``but in the really close, tight races, that's where name recognition probably does have some impact.''
half the arab policemen in the west bank resigned by plo order friday and israeli soldiers closed the main gaza mosque on the moslem sabbath for the first time worshipers could remember
the al amari mosque in gaza city has been a rallying point for protest since riots began dec. 8 in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, with prayer leaders sometimes calling over its loudspeakers for resistance to the army
israeli troopers shot and wounded nine palestinians during street battles after friday prayers at other mosques in the occupied territories. the army demolished the homes of four arabs accused of attacking either israelis or palestinians accused of collaborating with them
two alleged collaborators have been killed by fellow arabs, one of them a policemen. israeli bullets or beatings have killed at least 87 palestinians in more than three months of violence, and hundreds have been wounded
army units turned journalists away from hebron and nablus but the press restriction was not as widespread as on march 4, when nearly all the west bank was put off-limits
prime minister yitzhak shamir made his first public criticism of new u.s. peace proposals secretary of state george p. shultz brought to the region, declaring: ``the only word i agree with in the u.s. plan is the name shultz.'' about half the 500 arab police officiers in the west bank resigned in response to a call from the palestine liberation organization and underground united national command of the uprising, sources reported. the order was given in a leaflet circulated thursday
mustafa adani, 44, said he resigned after 25 years on the force along with ``almost all the police in the bethlehem station, about 50 to 55. the only ones who didn't quit were those who didn't know about the orders.''
a senior military official said the resignations would have ``a negative impact on other palestinians who work with israel in the territories. it is not very encouraging.''
leaflet no. 10 also demanded the resignations of west bank residents who serve in jordan's parliament, apparently to reinforce the plo role as the sole representative of palestinians
israel captured the west bank from jordan, and the gaza strip from egypt, in the 1967 middle east war
soldiers wounded eight palestinians, two of them seriously, during riots friday at a mosque in beit ummar, 10 miles south of jerusalem, according to officials at beit jallah and mukassed hospitals
the confrontation began when troopers tried to disperse arabs protesting outside the mosque. they fired tear gas and one canister broke a window, falling inside the mosque, arab witnesses said
half a dozen soldiers entered the mosque during prayers to ask the imam, or religious leader, to urge protesters on the mosque loudspeaker to go home, the witnesses said
the soldiers entered the mosque while we were still kneeling barefoot on our prayer rugs. people started shouting allahu akhbar (god is great),'' youssef hassan khalil, 30, said at mukassed hospital. he lay on a cot with a wounded right ankle
witnesses said the presence of israeli soldiers in the mosque during prayers inflamed the arabs, who hurled rocks and bottles and received volleys of tear gas, rubber bullets and gunfire in return
in the gaza strip, soldiers wounded a palestinian in the leg while trying to disperse protesters at the jabaliya refugee camp, hospital officials said
an army cordon around al amari in gaza prevented a weekly prayer service that normally attracts 2,500 worshipers
jerusalem's mufti, the ranking moslem religious leader, issued a statement accusing israel of blocking some mosques, raiding others and confiscating loudspeakers used to call palestinian moslems to prayer
sheik said adin alami called on worshipers ``to defend the mosques by all possible means despite the attackers.''
the army said it demolished three arab homes overnight in biddya, 30 miles northwest of jerusalem, to punish palestinians accused of involvement in an attack march 5 on an arab suspected of cooperating with israel
soldiers also blew up the home in hebron of ahmed mahmoud abdullah kawasmeh, whose 22-year-old son is accused of knifing an israeli settler from nearby kiryat arba five months ago
israeli troops have destroyed 14 palestinian homes since dec. 8, the arab-run palestine press service said
the rhode island supreme court on friday refused to block efforts to get a deposition from a priest regarding talks he had with another pastor later convicted of sexually molesting young boys
the roman catholic diocese of providence is being sued for $12 million by a narragansett woman and her son who contend the diocese knew the rev. william c. o'connell was molesting boys but did nothing about it. as a result, the suit contends, the boy became one of o'connell's victims
the family's attorney, r. daniel prentiss, has been trying to take a deposition from the rev. richard c. bucci. but bishop louis e. gelineau and auxiliary bishop kenneth a. angell, named as defendants in the suit with o'connell, argued any conversations between bucci and o'connell are privileged
the diocese contended the discussions are protected by a state law that prohibits a priest from testifying about ``confidential communication entrusted to him in his professional capacity.''
prentiss contended the state law is intended to prevent a priest from divulging what he is told in confession
my interpretation was that a statutory privilege absolutely does not apply and cannot be used to silence a witness the way they were trying here,'' prentiss said friday
monday, a superior court judge denied the diocese's request to permanently block the deposition, but granted church attorneys a temporary stay pending a supreme court appeal
prentiss and diocese attorney william t. murphy met in chambers friday with supreme court associate justice florence k. murray
about an hour later or less, i got a telephone call from the court saying there was not going to be a stay of the deposition,'' prentiss said
there was no elaboration on the decision, prentiss said
he said bucci is scheduled to give his deposition monday
murphy indicated he would not appeal the high court's decision
o'connell was arrested in 1985 on charges of sexually assaulting three boys. he was accused of fondling them in the rectory of st. mary's church in bristol and in his south kingstown summer cottage between 1982 and 1984
he pleaded no contest to 26 separate counts in 1986 _ seven of them involving the plaintiff in the civil suit _ and was sentenced to one year in jail. he also agreed to spend two years in therapy at a church-run program for clergy members with alcohol and psychological problems
the woman and her son contend the diocese and the bishops failed to remove o'connell from his position as pastor of st. mary's after being informed of his sexual involvement with boys, some of them altar boys
buccci, an assistant pastor at st. mary's in 1984 and 1985, has not publicly admitted discussing o'connell's behavior with diocesan officials. but he did file statements with police about o'connell, and he provided information to the state department for children and their families
forty million children in 34 countries will be vaccinated in the next four years under a program to eradicate polio in latin america and the caribbean, a doctor said friday
dr. ciro a. de quadros, an adviser to the world health organization, said governments in the region have committed $350 million to the project, which is expected to cost $450 million
the rest is to be donated by other groups such as the u.s. agency for international development, unicef, who, and the private rotary international
quadros spoke at a three-day meeting of development experts, doctors and health ministers in this alpine town. the conference is sponsored by the task force for child survival, whose members include unicef, who, the u.n. development program, the world bank and the rockefeller foundation
quadros told the group that the polio campaign expects to reach 10 million of the 11 million children born in latin america each year between now and 1991. the goal is to reach 85 percent of the children in every country in latin america, either through established health care systems or special immunization days
the campaign is an intensified version of a project already under way
in paraguay and the dominican republic, health workers have gone door-to-door administering the oral polio vaccine. nine countries last year held special immunization days, including el salvador, where government troops and rebels called a one-day truce to allow children to be immunized
we are four years away from wiping out polio and we are very confident,'' quadros said, adding that the incidence of the disease is already low when compared to other childhood diseases
fourteen latin american countries last year reported about 900 cases of polio, he said, three times more than in europe
the united states has been virtually free of the paralyzing virus for a decade
so, the long-term goal of the polio project not just to wipe out polio,'' quadros said in an interview. ``it is to establish an infrastucture, a health care system in developing countries that can be used for other types of immunization and for delivering other care.''
in addition, success in fighting polio is expected to boost the morale of health care workers and communities struggling against the enormous medical problems that confront the impoverished third world
dr. william h. foege, executive director of the task force and former head of the centers for disease control in atlanta, said lessons learned in south america will be used to set a date for eradicating the disease in asia, africa and elsewhere
among those attending the meeting at a 16th century stone monastery in the french alps are world bank president barber conable, unicef executive director james p. grant, who director general halfdan mahler, leaders of more than a dozen other international aid agencies and health ministers from 11 countries
since the early 1980s, task force organizations have been cooperating to vaccinate children against diptheria, whooping cough, tuberculosis and neonatal tetanus, in addition to polio. the project, aimed at developing countries, has raised immunization from 5 percent to 50 percent of the world's children in less than a decade
a senior state department official on friday defended an agreement giving japan access to u.s. nuclear wastes and disputed reports that negotiations with congress to avert a move to kill it had broken down
we're more than prepared to continue the discussions with the congress to see if there is a basis for moving forward on the agreement,'' fred mcgoldrick, director of the office of non-proliferation and export policy, said
mcgoldrick said the agreement concluded last november with japan and facing a disapproval vote next week in the senate has adequate safeguards against proliferation and terrorism
we think the agreement is very much in our interest,'` mcgoldrick said. ``if we do not have this kind of agreement, the japanese will simply go elsewhere to buy their enriched uranium. that not only has commercial implications _ we would lose export revenues _ it means we do not have nonproliferation controls and influence that we have in this agreement.''
two former pentagon officials and the congressional general accounting office have been sharply critical of the pact, which allows japan to retrieve plutonium, the primary ingredient of nuclear weapons, from u.s. nuclear fuel once the fuel has been used
critics of the nuclear cooperation agreement said thursday they may move to kill the accord next week in congress
the former pentagon officials, richard n. perle and frank j. gaffney jr., said the defense department was not given a significant role in negotiations and considers the agreement ``seriously flawed.''
the strong position that the department has taken against nuclear proliferation would have helped to shape the accord differently,'' they said in a letter written to sen. john glenn, d-ohio, and obtained by the associated press. ``that, we are quite sure, is why the department of state went to such lengths to work around us.''
perle and gaffney cited two provisions of the agreement as ``especially troublesome.'' first, they said, the pact gives japan advance u.s. consent for 30 years to reprocess and use american plutonium in any japanese facility without restriction on the amount or the purpose
second, they said, the pact ``imposes extraordinary and unprecedented restrictions on the right of the united states to suspend that prior consent.''
perle and gaffney said they were the pentagon officials responsible for non-proliferation issues while the agreement was negotiated
a gao report, meanwhile, said the agreement would leave the united states without ``effective control'' over reprocessing of the hazardous material
the feb. 29 report also found fault with the agreement's provisions to guard against proliferation and said it deprived congress of its oversight function
congressional opponents want the united states to have the right to review japanese use of plutonium on a case-by-case basis, and to be able to suspend the agreement to counter terrorism threats or address other national security concerns
the congressional foes also want the agreement to be reviewed every five years
these changes would require renegotiating the terms with japan, which the state department declines to do, said a congressional source, speaking on condition of anonymity
mcgoldrick said the united states has ``an unfettered right to suspend our approval to use plutonium that would result in a significant increase in the risk of proliferation or a threat to the national security.''
and, he said, the pact includes ``defined safeguards'' against misuse of the plutonium
mcgoldrick said canada and australia, which have strong non-proliferation policies, have entered into similar agreements with japan and west european countries without case-by-case restrictions
the gao report said the agreement did not meet various requirements of the atomic energy act. it said giving blanket approval to japan for reprocessing plutonium ``would leave the united states with no effective control over the life of the proposed agreement.''
in december, the senate foreign relations committee voted 15-3 to return the pact to president reagan and asked that it be renegotiated. opponents argued that it sets a precedent to encourage potentially hazardous trade in plutonium, which is a potent cancer-causing agent
under the agreement, japan would ship the spent nuclear fuel from the united states to reprocessing plants in britain or france, which would separate plutonium from the waste. the plutonium then would be shipped to japan by air. say</head>
dogs that helped seize $135 million worth of drugs in less than a year have enraged drug traffickers who are offering $30,000 to anyone who kills the animals, federal authorities say
the threats are aimed mostly at one dog, nicknamed rocky, who has become a sort of mascot in the fight against drugs and is used in many drug awareness programs for children, according to terry mcintosh, deputy regional chief of the u.s. border patrol in dallas
however, mcintosh said wednesday, the threats made by telephone a few months ago to the mcallen office cover all 14 dogs used by the border patrol
the callers said they have put out the word they will pay to have the dogs killed,'' mcintosh said
the dogs are stationed in mcallen and laredo as well as in marfa, el paso and del rio
mcintosh said the dogs have been guarded round the clock since the threats
informal meetings were held friday in the afghanistan peace talks after what u.n. mediator diego cordovez said was a week spent tackling ``enormous difficulties'' in the proposed settlement to end nine years of fighting
he told reporters that he asked the afghan and pakistani representatives to seek ``strengthened instructions'' for the next session scheduled monday in the indirect talks between the two sides
this would be just one day before a march 15 target date set for the negotiations by soviet leader mikhail gorbachev last month. he said moscow would bring home its troops beginning may 15 if the settlement was signed by march 15
however, sources close to the talks have said the date was not meant as a deadline after which the soviet pullout might be in doubt
in peshawar, pakistan, meanwhile, a moderate faction that split from the alliance of moslem afghan guerrillas last week rejoined the alliance friday
sibghatullah mojaddedi told members of his afghan national liberation front that assurances from other leaders and from pakistani officials persuaded him to rejoin the guerrillas' effort to hammer out an interim government to oversee the withdrawal of soviet troops from afghanistan
mojaddedi split with the alliance because he was worried that moslem extremists would dominate the interim government
in geneva, cordovez reiterated that agreement existed ``on the substance of things.''
the problem now concerns the sequence of actions in afghanistan, leading up to and including the withdrawal of the 115,000 soviet troops
it also hinges on pakistan's insistence that an interim government be ready to take control in kabul before the soviets begin their withdrawal
emerging with him from a closed-door meeting was the chief pakistani delegate, acting foreign minister zain noorani, who said the negotiations were ``inching slowly.''
pakistan's position about the interim government came under new fire from the soviet union thursday with moscow's special envoy, nikolay kozyrev, saying the talks had ``bogged down'' because of it
kozyrev warned that islamabad would bear the responsibility if there was no final agreement despite completion of all the main elements of the settlement
he also said that moscow felt free to continue military assistance to afghanistan even after the troop withdrawal. he rejected a u.s. demand that military aid should be cut off simultaneously to both the kabul government and the anti-communist guerrillas. kozyrev said assistance to the government was not covered in the draft agreements
sources close to the pakistani delegation said the cut-off issue was among items discussed with cordovez at the informal meeting friday but they did not dsclose details
washington _ president reagan, stepping up u.s. economic pressure on panama, today ordered that a $6.5 million payment due that country on tuesday be put into escrow
the move was part of a series of sanctions designed to weaken panama's military-dominated government, which reagan called ``illegitimate,'' and orce strongman manuel antonio noriega from power
reagan called on noriega to resign as commander of the panamanian defense forces and said in a statement that the united states can no longer conduct business as usual with noriega's government
reagan ordered that u.s. government payments due to panama be held in escrow until constitutional rule is restored in panama. the payment due tuesday relates to operations of the panama canal
reagan also ordered that the trade benefits panama receives under a special system set up for third world countries be withdrawn. similarly, he suspended panamanian participation in the caribbean basin initiaitve, under which some panamanian products receive duty-free access to u.s. markets
in addition, reagan said he has ordered that panama be subject to intensified scrutiny by u.s. immigration and customs officials
the purpose of that move, he said, is to ``apprehend drug traffickers and money launderers.''
secretary of state george p. shultz said there was no need to impose an additional sanction relating to the fees panama receives from alaskan oil shipments transferred to u.s. east coast ports through a panamanian pipeline
shultz told a news conference those fees already have been frozen based on earlier court action
shultz noted that the president's statement referred to the panamanian government as ``illegitimate.''
that's a very strong word,'' shultz said, underscoring the seriousness with which the united states views the situation there
he accused noriega of trying to impose a military coup in panama by deposing president eric arturo delvalle, whom the united states regards as the legitimate constitutional authority
under the caribbean basin initiative, panama and about 20 other countries are eligible to sell most products duty-free to u.s. markets
but this measure will have mostly symbolic impact because the bulk of panama's exports to the united states are not subject to duties in the first place. panama exported between $342 million and $388 million worth of products to the united states last year, according to figures provided by u.s. government agencies
on thursday, the house voted 367-2 in support of a non-binding resolution demanding noriega's ouster
the resolution, which took note of allegations of drug trafficking, murder, money laundering and racketeering against panama's defense forces, was approved shortly before the white house meeting was convened
it called on reagan to ``consider seriously'' additional economic and political sanctions
members on both sides of the political spectrum lashed out at noriega and gave the administration virtually carte blanche to impose additional sanctions. rep. mel levine, d-calif., said ``the government of panama is in the hands of a thug, a common criminal.''
the government said friday that retail sales edged up 0.6 percent in february, bolstered by strong demand for autos, but economists expressed worries that sales in january were much weaker than previously believed
in good news on the inflation front, wholesale prices fell 0.2 percent in february, pushed down by drops in both food and energy costs
for the first two months of the year, the labor department said prices have been rising at an annual rate of 1.1 percent, half the modest 2.2 percent increase in 1987. analysts said inflation should remain moderate for the rest of the year
the commerce department report on retail sales said that consumers purchased $128 billion worth of goods last month, up $714 million from january after adjusting for seasonal variations. while the february increase was in line with expectations, many economists focused on a sharp downward revision to the january data
instead of a 0.5 percent rise in sales, the government said sales actually fell 0.2 percent during january, showing that the consumer sector is weaker than previously believed
ever since the record collapse of stock prices in october, analysts have been worried that consumers would become more cautious and cut back on spending. since consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of overall economic activity, any significant slowdown in this area could topple the country into a recession
the large downward revision in january shows that the consumer sector is quite weak,'' said bruce steinberg, an economist with merrill lynch. ``car sales are doing o.k. with the incentives but other than that, nothing seems to be doing very well.''
david wyss, an economist with data resouces inc., a private forecasting firm, said that since october, americans have been building up savings, reflecting worries about the future caused by the stock market decline
but he said that strength in other sectors, reflected by the strong employment gains in february, should provide enough momentum to keep the country out of a recession. wyss predicted that overall economic growth, as measured by the gross national product, would be an anemic 1.5 percent this year, less than half the 3.9 percent gnp growth turned in during 1987
auto sales in february increased 1.6 percent following an even stronger 2 percent advance in january. february sales accounted for almost one-fourth of total retail spending during the month
without the strength in auto sales, which has been bolstered by new incentive programs, total retail sales would have risen a smaller 0.3 percent last month
the general merchandise category, which includes department store sales, suffered a 1.6 percent decline in sales in february following a 0.1 percent decline in january. january department store sales had originally been reported as an increase and the back-to-back declines in this key sector were particularly disappointing to economists
consumer spending is weaker than we had anticipated, but we weren't looking for much strength in this sector this year anyway,'' said sandra shaber, an economist with the futures group, a washington consulting firm
sales of all durable goods, items expected to last three or more years, were up 1.6 percent in february, boosted by the increase in car sales, while sales of non-durable goods edged down 0.1 percent
wyss said the car data indicated to him that dealers were having trouble selling used cars and consumers should be able to find some good deals in this area in the months ahead
sales at building materials and hardware stores jumped a sharp 2.3 percent in february while sales at furniture and appliance stores were up a more modest 0.3 percent
sales at specialty clothing stores climbed 0.6 percent in february, only a partial rebound following a giant 3.3 percent january decline
sales at gasoline stations fell 1.6 percent in february while sales at restaurants edged up 0.1 percent and sales at drug stores posted a 0.6 percent increase
sales at grocery stores enjoyed a 0.7 percent rise in sales in february, reversing a 0.6 percent january decline
the labor department report on wholesale prices said that food prices declined 1.1 percent in february while energy prices dropped 0.8 percent. the cost of lettuce, which had skyrocketed through the late fall and early winter, fell a dramatic 70 percent
ford motor co. is recalling 214,900 cars of various designs from the 1982 and 1983 model years to fix pollution-control equipment, the environmental protection agency said friday
the company has begun notifying owners of 185,000 cars from 1983 equipped with the 1.6-liter four-cylinder engine to bring them in for adjustment of the exhaust air-injection systems. these cars were sold as the ford escort, escort exp and escort wagon and the mercury lynx, lynx ln-7 and lynx wagon. about 4,000 cars originally were sold in california, which has stricter standards than those applying in other states
cars with this engine equipped with fuel injection, or designated ``high output,'' are not affected
these cars have been exceeding the federal emission standards for carbon monoxide and unburned fuel, epa said
the agency said ford also will recall 29,900 cars from the 1982 model year to fix an exhaust gas recirculation system which can cause excessive emissions of nitrogen oxides
the cars affected all have 2.3-liter four-cylinder engines and automatic transmissions. they were sold as the ford mustang, granada and fairmont and the mercury capri and zephyr. cars originally sold in california are not affected
dealers will check the carburetor spacer plates, which allows some exhaust to enter the intake manifold, and clean them of deposits if necessary
alpine skiers who seek out daring runs on unmarked trails accounted for half of all swiss avalanche deaths last winter and also pose problems for the environment, officials said friday
maj. hugh lindsay, a close friend of britain's prince charles, was killed thursday by a snowslide while skiing outside the normal slopes above klosters, switzerland, the traditional royal winter resort
the heir to the british throne escaped unhurt
the swiss federal avalanche research institute had warned thursday of considerable avalanche danger above 5,250 feet in the region. the party was skiing at about 5,900 feet
one obviously doesn't like seeing anyone getting killed. but when you ski off the path, that is your own responsibility,'' said david bramwell, a british skier vacationing in this remote village 90 miles southeast of zurich
in a statement before leaving switzerland, charles said everyone in his group understood the dangers before they embarked into the avalanche-prone area
i would like to emphazise that all members of my party, including myself, were skiing off the piste (trail) at our own risk and we all accepted ... that the mountains have to be treated with the greatest respect,'' charles said
but many vacationing skiers and residents in klosters indicated they thought charles should have not been so willing to lead his companions down the dangerous slope
last winter, eight of the 16 people killed by snowslides in switzerland were off-trail skiers, said claude francois jaccard, director of the avalanche research institute atop mount weissfluhjoch
over the long-term, they make up about 30 percent of all avalanche deaths. the toll is highest among ski hikers who tour across mountains on skis often for days, jaccard said
about 1 million skiers, including many foreigners, cut loose on unmarked runs every year, the swiss national association for sports says
christian tischauser, chief ski warden at corvatsch, about 30 miles south of klosters, recently called on the swiss government to consider legislating curbs on off-trail skiing
neighboring austria has banned the practice as of this year, with violators facing fines
switzerland has not followed suit. but one recent outing became expensive for three swiss who set off an avalanche as they skied off marked trails near zermatt
a court last month made them pay the cost of sending out search teams
swiss authorities, tourism offices and sports associations have taken the tack of appealing to skiers' responsibility when venturing off regular runs
some resorts in the grisons region, where klosters is located, already have limited such skiing
a nationwide information campaign was launched late last year to make off-trail skiers aware of safe areas to practice the sport
the basic capital for tourism is unblemished nature,'' said peter anrig of the swiss tourism association
inexperienced skiers are known to rip through saplings, ultimately killing off a future tree in a country concerned about widespread forest damage from pollution, he said. snow tourists also tend to litter in the otherwise virgin areas
alpine animals are jolted by off-trailers, experts say, citing the example of the snow grouse. skiers often scare the birds out of snow caves in which they hibernate, leaving them to die of cold and consumption in glacial temperatures
swiss avalanches have killed an average of 27 people each year over the past 50 years, according to the federal institute. six out of 10 victims are skiers
lindsay's death brought this winter's toll to 12
seventy members of the israeli parliament on friday presented a petition calling on president reagan to pardon jonathan j. pollard, the navy analyst who was convicted of passing secrets to israel
the petition, presented to u.s. ambassador thomas pickering, was signed by most of the right-wing likud bloc in the knesset, or parliament, and by the left-wing mapam faction. it was a rare display of unity among israel's divided legislators
the committee for justice for the pollards released news of the petition in the united states
it called on reagan to pardon pollard, a civilian navy intelligence analyst convicted last year of selling secrets to israel and sentenced to life in prison. the petitioners also asked reagan to pardon pollard's wife, anne henderson-pollard, who was sentenced to five years in jail for being an accessory
it is very rare for an issue to so cut across party lines as does the plight of the pollards,'' according to the petitioners. ``all israel is praying for their release.''
the israeli government was severely embarrassed by pollard's arrest outside its washington embassy in 1985, saying it had not authorized the spying operation. public pressure, however, forced the government to foot the bill for some of pollard's legal fees
the pollard committee noted that the pollards' punishment was particularly harsh in view of the fact that he spied for a u.s. ally
in general, ``spies for allies are treated more leniently, if they are prosecuted at all,'' the committee said
thousands of workers across norway left their jobs for several hours friday to protest a government proposal to limit wage increases
the labor government introduced the wage limitations in parliament friday, and prime minister gro harlem brundtland condemned the protests as illegal
the bill would limit the average worker's increase on a weekly paycheck to 3.5 percent. the government argued the move is needed to make norwegian products more competitive and curb last year's 8.7 percent inflation rate, more than twice the european average
the bill represents the most severe economic package since a 15-month wage-price freeze was approved 10 years ago. it would limit pay raises to 15 cents an hour in the next two years
bus drivers, municipal employees, nurses and thousands more workers in oslo and 10 other cities left their jobs. norwegian radio went off the air for two hours
about 1,000 people demonstrated against the bill outside parliament in oslo. ``we do not accept being robbed of our right to negotiate,'' said jan andersen-gott, spokesman for a white-collar trade union federation
six trade federations representing about 400,000 workers were involved in the protests, the norwegian news agency ntb reported
the proposed law followed the lines of an agreement reached two weeks ago between employers and norway's largest trade union federation, which represents about 350,000 members
the legislation would take immediate effect upon passage, which could be within a week. withdraw slogan. no pickup.</note>
the archbishop of canterbury's office on friday attacked the ``jesus is alive!'' postmark that is being stamped on millions of letters mailed in britain, but the post office said it would not withdraw the slogan
bishop ronald gordon, archbishop robert runcie's chief of staff, said the post office's decision to frank letters with the easter message was inappropriate and an imposition
the belief that jesus is alive is at the heart of the christian faith and christians must be expected to wish to affirm it on appropriate occasions,'' gordon wrote in reply to a letter of protest from the british humanist association
but the imposition of a postmark by a public monopoly is hardly an affirmation of faith since the sender can exercise no choice in the matter. in this respect the imposition may be regarded as insensitive,'' he added
the post office said it was surprised by the criticism and said many religious groups had used the postal service in the past to spread religious messages
there has been a large measure of popular support for this particular postmark,'' said a post office spokesman, speaking on condition he not be identified
the postmark, which also has drawn protestfrom jews, is being stamped on nearly all letters mailed in britain. it says ``jesus is alive!'' next to a cross
paul slennett, an evangelist bookseller, paid the post office the equivalent of $92,000 to use the postmark for six weeks starting march 1. he says it is an easter message and that god told him to do it
underworld assassins ambushed and shot to death two local officials in southern italy, police reported friday
the town councilmen from afragola, near naples, were attacked thursday as they drove home from a council meeting, police said. an undetermined number of assassins riddled their volvo with gunfire and fled in their own car
the victims were identified as paolo sibilio, 39; and francesco salzano, 40. both were christian democrats
investigators said the killings appeared linked to attempts by organized crime to gain contracts for reconstruction of buildings damaged in an earthquake in the area in 1980. sibilio was in charge of awarding such contracts
a local official in southwestern china was expelled from the communist party after his use of influence to buy up scarce fertilizer led to a protest by 400 farmers, a newspaper reported friday
the party expelled liu xingdong, deputy secretary of tiefeng township in sichuan province, according to the official china daily. it said liu was under investigation for using the ``back door'' to buy up chemical fertilizer
such fertilizers are in chronic short supply in china, and there are reports in the official media of widespread corruption in their sale and distribution
the report said liu last october asked the local supply cooperative to sell him 990 pounds of fertilizer for family members. the report said cooperative workers and truck drivers took that cue to use their own connections to obtain fertilizer before it was distributed to local farmers
when distribution began in december, farmers reportedly broke into the cooperative to get fertilizer and remained there for three days until county officials persuaded them to hand it all back, the daily said
the report said four farmers who led the protest will face trial
a group of u.s. senators told mikhail s. gorbachev on friday that soviet superiority in tanks and artillery scared the west into a nuclear defense, so cutbacks in those arms should precede strategic missile reductions
the senators said they sensed the soviet leader is less worried about president reagan's strategic defense initiative, but they said they doubted that signaled greater tolerance of it
i think there has been a lessening of soviet apprehension about sdi,'' said sen. sam nunn, chairman of the senate armed services committee. ``i think they recognize that it is a long-term project.''
the senators met with reporters after a weeklong exchange with high-level soviet military and political officials
the kremlin wants to link a superpower agreement on reduction of strategic weapons to compliance with the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty. the treaty outlaws space-based defense systems like that seen under sdi, popularly known as the ``star wars'' program
nunn said the americans pressed for ``delinkage'' of the two issues, but they ``did not get any encouragement at all along that line.''
the official news agency tass, in its account of the meeting, said gorbachev reiterated the kremlin's ``allegiance to its position on a direct linkage'' of missiles cuts with abm compliance
violating it destroys the entire machinery of the agreement,'' tass quoted gorbachev as saying. ``we shall never be able to bridle the rabid charger of the arms race if it is let loose in outer space.''
gorbachev and reagan signed an agreement eliminating all medium-range nuclear weapons at their washington summit in december
sen. alan cranston, d-calif., said he assured gorbachev that the treaty was likely to be ratified this spring ``with no crippling amendments'' and that the concern of the congress and administration had turned to the issue of how to cut strategic, or long-range nuclear arms
u.s. and soviet negotiators are at work in geneva on a proposed treaty to eliminate 50 percent of the superpowers' long-range, or intercontintal nuclear missiles
both sides have said they would like the treaty ready for signing in late may or early june when reagan visits moscow, but the senators expressed doubt it would be ready in time
nunn said the kremlin should first cut its overwhelming superiority in conventional weaponry such as tanks and artillery
there is a great correlation between our first-use reliance on nuclear weapons and their massive conventional forces,'' nunn said
he said he explained to gorbachev during the group's meeting, which lasted more than three hours, that a soviet rollback of tanks and artillery from eastern europe would go far in reducing the fears of america's european allies about a soviet military threat
the north atlantic treaty organization nations, which will lose their medium-range missiles under the agreement signed in december, have balked at further nuclear cuts without prior reductions in soviet conventional arms
we would like to see the soviet union save some money so it can devote it to their economic development,'' nunn said he told gorbachev
the senate group, which also included sens. william cohen, r-maine, alan simpson, r-wyo., and carl levin, d-mich., also met in the past week with soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze, communist party foreign affairs secretary anatoly f. dobrynin and army chief of staff sergei f. akhromeyev
zbigniew nowakowski jumped ship in the dead of winter with little more than the clothes on his back and hope. less than two months later, he and fellow defectors from polish vessels are working to build their personal american dream
nowakowski and 16 other polish seamen walked off four ships docked in or near boston in late january, saying they wanted to flee oppressive political and economic conditions at home
most left wives and children. none spoke english. they have had their share of struggle. but they say they have no regrets
i knew it would be difficult at first, and i expected hardships,'' said nowakowski, 36. ``i have no intention of ever leaving.''
defector artur misiaczuk shook his head vehemently when asked if he ever considered returning to poland during the darker moments of his adventure
return? no, this is my home now,'' he said
the two men, both of whom say they were members of the outlawed solidarity free trade union, spoke friday through an interpreter
the immigration and naturalization service is processing asylum requests from the 17. while declining specific comments about the applications, ins district director charles cob said requests from soviet bloc countries ``have a higher percentage of approval than those from other countries do.''
sitting in a booth of the polish-american citizens club in dorchester, a tough, working-class section of boston, nowakowski and misiaczuk chainsmoked american cigarettes, a luxury in their homeland
our initial dream has come true, and that is to have the freedom of mobility,'' said misiaczuk, 25, who left his wife and 11-month-old daughter in the seaport of szeczin
we want to fullfil our personal american dream, which is the american dream of all immigrants who come here, to eventually bring our families here and to continue living and working and geting acclimated to american society,'' he said
nowakowski, a fellow szecziner, who left behind his wife, a 2-year-old son and a daughter, 12, looked even further ahead
i intend to work very hard in the next 20 years,'' he said. ``to me, the most important thing is that i am free now and i will be free in 20 years
our overall goal is to be with our families, and yes, to have our own homes eventually, a nice place to live and for our families to live with us.''
the two now share a two-bedroom apartment in south boston with two fellow polish defectors. nowakowski works nights in a food processing plant, while misiaczuk is a general laborer for a construction contractor
neither the cramped quarters nor the hard work draw complaints. nowakowski, a trained refrigeration technician who attends english classes by day, spoke with relish about working his way up
eventuallly, through school and my own personal ambition, i'd like to have my own business,'' he said
several of the poles spent their first night in america in the office of mayor raymond s. flynn, and nowakowski and misiaczuk spoke enthusiastically of the financial and moral support given them since, both by the city and boston's sizeable polish community
but all the help cannot bridge the occasional loneliness. misiaczuk's voice trembled when he described his first telephone call with his wife
we cried as soon as we heard each others' voice, because we knew in our hearts that we would not be seeing each other in the near future, and she told me that they laid her off from work because of my defection,'' he said. ``i miss them tremendously
but they are heartened by my stay here and ... about the fact that things are working out better here than initially expected.''
he brightened when asked about his favorite things in america
pizza,'' he laughed. ``and madonna.''
a soviet dissident said friday he saw scores of tanks and soldiers, police and militia keeping order in a frightened southern city where ethnic rioting killed at least 32 people
andrei shelkov, who works on the independent political publication glasnost, said residents of sumgait were still ``hysterical'' about the rioting that broke out there two weeks ago
shelkov told a news conference in moscow that he was in sumgait, in the republic of azerbaijan, for about five hours on wednesday. he returned to moscow the following day
shelkov said that on one street, ``there was a solid line of light tanks. i counted 47 of them.''nearby were about 40 civilian buses full of soldiers, he said
streets were full of soldiers, police and civilian militia. a curfew was in effect, but businesses and schools were operating, shelkov said. he said he talked to azeris, as the natives of azerbaijan are called, and russians in sumgait but did not meet any of the estimated 18,000 armenians who lived in the industrial city of 160,000 people
tensions between armenians and azeris, whose republics are next to each other, erupted in violence in sumgait on feb. 28. the rioting was believed sparked by armenians demands that nagorno-karabakh, an armenian-dominated region of azerbaijan, be annexed to armenia
an hour-long general strike had been proposed in armenia on friday, but a communist party official in the armenian city of kafan told the associated press it was canceled to avoid stirring up unrest
gamlet kocharyan, a member of armenia's party central committee and of kafan's governing body, said by telephone that tanks and troops remained in regions where ethnic tensions had erupted, but that ``the situation is quieting down a little.''
we are waiting for the 26th,'' when a party and government meeting on the fate of nagorno-karabakh is to be held, he said
kocharyan said armenians are convinced the moscow leadership will make ``the only just decision'' and return nagorno-karabakh region to armenia
former political prisoner sergei grigoryants, the editor of glasnost, said he traveled to the armenian capital, yerevan, to witness a march tuesday by hundreds of thousands of fellow armenians in memory of those killed in the sumgait rioting
he showed journalists photographs of streets packed with people and said they were taken at the march
some armenians claim the death toll in sumgait was 350 to 400, but the government has put the official death toll at 32
shelkov said he could not reach the cemeteries in sumgait because they are outside the city, and roads were blocked off
western reporters have not been allowed to travel to the region
shelkov said he was told by a nurse who worked in a maternity hospital that azeris broke in during the riots and threw babies out the window, and that one woman had been disemboweled
a man who addressed a gathering of armenians in moscow on tuesday also said he had seen the body of a slain pregnant woman and her mutilated unborn baby
neither report was confirmed
the army arrived on march 2 to restore order to sumgait, shelkov said
it was simply a hysterical scene,'' he said of his conversations with residents of the city
the russians and azeris claimed that the violence was the work of azeris who came to sumgait from throughout azerbaijan
grigoryants said armenians at tuesday's memorial march did not blame average azeris for the killings
almost every armenian family will recall how azerbaijanis hid them or tried to hide them,'' he said
but he said armenians were angry with the moscow media for portraying as extremists those who demonstrated in favor of annexation of nagorno-karabakh
azeris are predominantly shiite moslems and most armenians are christians
seven knife-wielding men robbed a watch company friday and stole about $2.3 million in spare parts in the biggest recorded robbery in hong kong's history, police said
police said the robbers entered the watch company on the 12th floor of a factory building and tied up five employees before escaping with 13 cartons of watch movements
no one was injured in the heist which occurred in the kwai chung industrial area in the new territories. there were no arrests reported
friday's robbery broke a record set last month when a gang of masked men snatched $1.65 million in gold and cash from a trading company's van on its way to the airport
a clergyman who is a leading anti-apartheid activist said friday he received two death threats in the past week and that his house and office were stoned
the rev. allan boesak, president of the world alliance of reformed churches, said he received a call friday on his private telephone line from a man who said: ``we are going to kill you.''
a similar call was received monday, boesak said
boesak said a stone was thrown through a window of his office near cape town while he was at a meeting there thursday night. his children called 15 minutes later from the family home nearby to say a brick had been thrown through a front window, boesak said
boesak, anglican archbishop desmond tutu and other church leaders have pledged to lead opposition to the white-led government's recent crackdown on black anti-apartheid organizations and activists
in a series of tough moves starting last month, the government banned political activity by 18 groups, imposed restrictions on individual activists and introduced legislation to prohibit foreign funding of political activity
the clergymen plan a series of protest rallies sunday and have indicated they may defy any attempt by authorities to stop them
pro-government newspapers have assailed the church leaders' stance and suggested that authorities should not tolerate civil disobedience
boesak, 42, is of mixed-race and is one of the co-founders of the united democratic front, the nation's largest anti-apartheid coalition. the udf was one of the 18 organizations banned from political activity
the ban was challenged in court papers filed thursday by three of the groups _ the congress of south african trade unions, the detainees parents support committee and the release mandela committee
peter harris, a lawyer involved in the challenge, said the groups contend that the new restrictions ``comprise so fundamental an inroad into the ordinary rights of citizens that they could never have been contemplated by parliament.''
a supreme court hearing on the challenge is expected in late april or early may
the country's roman catholic bishops held a news conference in johannesburg to express ``profound dismay'' at the crackdown
the drive-in church can move, but when the spririt moves its members, they'll have to keep their hands off the horn
the city's planning commission on thursday approved the new location for the drive-in church on the condition that its mobile worshipers abandon a tradition of honking their horns when they are compelled to make a joyful noise
for 18 years, sunday services have been held at the woodland drive-in theater. but the drive-in is being torn down, causing the fifth reformed church to hunt for a new locale
city officials said the threat of increased sunday traffic and the possibility of a particularly moving sermon causing a racket at the new site prompted some opposition to the plan
so church officials said they'd tell the faithful to flash their lights when they felt particularly illuminated during services. commissioners thought that idea was ok, but wrote a no-horn-honking provision into the resolution supporting the proposal
the wheels of bureaucracy sometimes grind slowly, but the passage of a 199-year-old resolution that has ``more mold on it than 6-month-old bread'' may be setting a record
the west virginia legislature has approved the legislation, 197 years after the mother state endorsed it. the 1789 federal constitutional amendment allows congress to approve a pay raise for itself, but the raise would not be effective until the following congressional session
the amendment was approved by eight states before it dropped by the wayside in the 1790s, said the sponsor, del. david mckinley. virginia, which divided to form west virginia in 1863, approved it 197 years ago
but congress neglected to put an expiration date into the proposal and it has hung around ever since, mckinley said
the house of delegates approved it last month and the senate followed suit on thursday, endorsing it on a 34-0 vote
del. jim humphreys balked at the proposal. ``it's got more mold on it than 6-month-old bread,'' he said. ``i just don't think it's serious. it's a waste of our time is what it is.''
but mckinley defended the resolution. ``it's a classy little piece,'' he said. he added of the nearly 200-year-old proposal, ``it's a sleeper.''
the news around newport news isn't good for those who are tired of having their hometown mistaken for a newspaper
lawmakers in the southeastern virginia city have rejected a proposal that would drop the cryptic ``news,'' making the city's name simply newport
based on historical facts and information, it would serve no good purpose to change the name of newport news to newport,'' the city's historical commission said thursday
the suggestion for the name change came from councilman joseph c. ritchie, who said he was tired of going on business trips and saying he was from newport news, which invariably brought the response, ``how do you like working for a newspaper?''
the committee discovered that around the turn of the century, the city tried to persuade officials of newport, va., near blacksburg, to change their hamlet's name. then newport news could become the newport
but the original newportians resisted, taking their case to court, where, as the current names suggest, they won
in its research, the commission also established that the ``newport'' in the city's name came from explorer capt. christopher newport, but where the ``news'' came from is anybody's guess. premier and adds details. adds byline. no pickup.</note>
premier giovanni goria resigned friday as the leader of italy's 47th postwar government, saying there was no reason to delay the fall of the shaky coalition for talks to smooth the transition of power
it was the third time the christian democrat quit since taking office in august, but president francesco cossiga rejected his earlier resignations and persuaded him to stay on
goria handed in his latest resignation to cossiga on friday night. cossiga asked him to stay on as a caretaker premier until a new government can be formed
goria, who at 44 was italy's youngest premier, resigned for the first time in november in a dispute with the tiny liberal party
he quit again feb. 10 after defectors in his own party caused him to lose a series of secret votes on the budget. however, cossiga talked him into returning to office to help pass the national budget before the april 30 deadline
the lower house of parliament gave final approval thursday night to a budget that includes a deficit of 122 trillion lire, or $98.8 billion. the spending plan was very different from the original proposed by the coalition, which forecast a deficit of $83.3 billion
with the budget passed, goria's days were numbered as the head of the coalition of christian democrats, socialists, republicans, social democrats and liberals
throughout goria's seven months in office, political infighting and defections in secret votes made it difficult for him to govern
goria was expected to resign next week with the start of consultations among leaders of the various political parties about his successor
but goria said he decided to step down immediately because it was clear that the ``intentions of some parties was not to reach an understanding that had the interest of the country'' at heart
he did not specify any political party, but cabinet ministers from various parties said goria quit because of socialist party opposition to the government's plan to resume construction at a nuclear power plant
the government announced a moratorium on the construction of the plant after voters in a referendum expressed their opposition to nuclear power
the government's decision wednesday to go ahead with the project angered the socialist party leaders
at the time of his resignation in february, analysts suggested some christian democrats wanted to undermine goria and make party secretary ciriaco de mita the premier
why do americans have different beers for different times of the day, asked a visiting soviet public relations executive who was confused by some u.s. advertizing techniques and wound up confusing his hosts
valentin v. kozitsyn, who is traveling with a soviet cultural exhibit now at cincinnati's union terminal center, had some questions for members of the cincinnati public relations company he visited thursday
employees at smith kaufman public relations were confused by his beer question
they understood when kozitsyn explained that he had seen a television commercial saying ``the night belongs to michelob.''
and another thing: ``why is k mart america's favorite store?'' he asked
any advertising or public relations effort in the soviet union is ``done very slowly, with much care and deliberation,'' kozitsyn said. he described the american media as fast, colorful and timely
there is much to learn about the methods here,'' he said
much of thursday's informal discussion was spent explaining to kozitsyn the distinctions between u.s. advertising, public relations and journalism
in our country, it isn't so important to explain everything,'' he said
kozitsyn said interest in public relations methodology is increasing in the soviet union because the country, under communist party leader mikhail gorbachev, is taking a hard look at its traditions
we have not only successes _ we have mistakes,'' kozitsyn said. ``there is a need for us to explain our mistakes in history and modern life. ... there is the need to understand truths.''
there is much we need to teach our own people, and much to learn about accomplishing that,'' kozitsyn said
lora l. doerr, an account supervisor with smith kaufman, said the cincinnati firm first came in contact with kozitsyn while arranging publicity for the exhibit. from mcfarlane, walsh and reagan; subs pvs 12th graf bgng, robinson filed, to make 2nd reference to walsh.</note>
former national security adviser robert c. mcfarlane pleaded guilty today to four misdemeanor charges of withholding information from congress about reagan administration efforts to help nicaraguan contra rebels during a statutory ban on military aid
mcfarlane, standing before u.s. district judge aubrey e. robinson jr., admitted that he withheld information about the activities of lt. col. oliver l. north and other members of the national security council staff in three 1985 letters to house committees
he also admitted withholding information from the house foreign affairs committee when he told the panel on dec. 8, 1986, that he was unaware of any efforts to solicit donations for the contras from a third country
each of the four charges carries a maximum penalty of one year in prison and a $1,000 fine
after entering his plea, mcfarlane told reporters that he did withhold information from congress on the occasions cited in the charges, but added:
my actions were motivated by what i believed to be in the foreign policy interest of the united states.''
mcfarlane said that since the iran-contra affair became public in late 1986, he had spent more than 200 hours testifying privately and publicly without immunity from prosecution. he promised to continue cooperating ``until this matter is finally resolved.''
independent counsel lawrence e. walsh said he could have sought more serious perjury charges against mcfarlane, but settled for the misdemeanor charges because the former white house aide had shown remorse and had tried to correct his original testimony
president reagan, boarding a helicopter for a weekend at camp david, md., refused to comment when asked about mcfarlane. ``it's in the court,'' reagan shouted to reporters
each charge carries a minimum sentence of one month in prison, but robinson reminded mcfarlane he could receive a maximum four-year sentence
you understand that imprisonment could be consecutive?'' the judge asked
i understand that,'' said mcfarlane, who spoke in a very soft, subdued voice
q. ``this is the action you knowingly took with respect to writing the letters?''
a. ``it is, your honor.''
referring to testimony mcfarlane gave the house foreign affairs committee, the judge asked, ``that was a knowing response?''
it was, your honor,'' mcfarlane replied
robinson filed under seal a letter of cooperation that mcfarlane and his attorney, leonard garment, had signed as part of plea bargain struck with walsh, who is investigating the iran-contra affair
robinson did not set a date for sentencing, indicating that he will assess mcfarlane's degree of cooperation with the prosecutor before making a decision
mcfarlane was released on his personal recognizance
the charges of withholding information from congress were detailed in a criminal information, which is filed when a defendant hs agreed to enter a guilty plea to charges
secretary of state george shultz, asked at the white house about mcfarlane's guilty plea, told reporters that ``if he has made some mistakes, i don't know about that. ... bud mcfarlane continues to have my strong friendship.''
the document filed today alleges that mcfarlane made false statements in letters sent in 1985 to the house intelligence and foreign affairs committees and a foreign affairs subcommittee
the charges involve assurances to congress that members of mcfarlane's national security council staff, specifically lt. col. oliver l. north, were not involved in private efforts to help the contras
in an oct. 7, 1985, letter to the house intelligence committee, mcfarlane wrote that ``lieutenant colonel north did not use his influence to facilitate the movement of supplies to the resistance,'' the information said
in addition, it said, mcfarlane assured the committee there was ``no official or unofficial relationship with any member of the nsc staff regarding fund raising for the nicaraguan democratic opposition.''
another charge states that on sept. 5, 1985, mcfarlane withheld information from the house intelligence committee when he wrote: ``i can state with deep personal conviction that at no time did i or any member of the national security council violate the letter of spirit'' of the boland amendment, which banned u.s. military aid to the contras
the sept. 5 letter also stated that ``we did not solicit funds or other support for military or paramilitary activities either from americans or third parties.''
the charge notes that the letter ``unlawfully withheld material information'' from the panel because mcfarlane ``then and there knew and believed that a member of the nsc staff had violated the letter or spirit of the boland amendment by, among other things, soliciting support for military and paramilitary activities of the contras and offering certain advice for the conduct of the contra's military activities and organization.''
the letter was written in response to an aug. 20, 1985, letter from the panel's chairman, rep. lee hamilton, d-ind., requesting information about news reports that the nsc staff was helping the contras
another charge relates to dec. 8, 1986, testimony in which mcfarlane told the house foreign affairs committee that he was not aware of any third country or citizens of a foreign nation helping the contras
the concrete character of that is beyond my ken,'' mcfarlane told the committee
the court documents said mcfarlane was withholding his knowledge that ``since 1984 the nationals of the third country referred to had expressed willingness to contribute millions of dollars to the contras,'' and that mcfarlane gave a ``representative of that third country with the number of a contra-controlled bank account into which the funds could be deposited.''
the plea bargain was negotiated by mcfarlane's attorney, leonard garment, and walsh, who is expected to seek a round of indictments in coming weeks from a federal grand jury that has been investigating the arms sales to iran and diversion of profits to the contras
mcfarlane has testified extensively before the grand jury impaneled by walsh. last year, mcfarlane tried to kill himself with an overdose of the tranquilizer valium the day before his scheduled testimony before a presidential commission that investigated the iran-contra affair
two other iran-contra figures have entered guilty pleas in walsh's investigation and are cooperating with the independent counsel
two conservative fund-raisers, carl r. ``spitz'' channell and richard miller admitted last year that they participated with north in an illegal scheme to use a tax-exempt foundation to raise money for the contras
mcfarlane, who resigned as white house national security adviser on dec. 4, 1985, traveled with north to tehran in may 1986 aboard a plane that delivered spare parts for hawk missiles that had previously been shipped to iran by the israelis
mcfarlane carried a cake and a bible to give to the iranians during negotiations over the release of american hostages being held in lebanon
during testimony before congressional investigators last summer, mcfarlane said he ordered his nsc staff not to solicit private funds for the contras
north, however, testified that ``i never heard those instructions.'' he said mcfarlane had asked him to help keep contra forces operating after congress imposed a ban on direct u.s. military aid
mcfarlane said he was not aware that arms sale proceeds were being diverted to the contras until north told him about it during their return trip from iran
north testified that mcfarlane told him to include false information in a chronology of the arms deal which was prepared in the fall of 1986, while the iran-contra affair was uraveling
mcfarlane denied he knowingly falsified the chronology, and said incorrect information was given to him during a meeting led by north
the state board of regents began an investigation friday of a board member and a state education department employee who wrote a guidebook designed to help students pass a new regents-required examination
a statement issued by board vice chancellor r. carlos carballada said a four-member regents committee would investigate circumstances surrounding publication of the book and any possibility of a conflict of interest
the guidebook, designed to improve student performance on the new social studies evaluation test required of all sixth-graders, was written by regent louise matteoni and renee levitt, an education department employee
state education commissioner thomas sobol said he was investigating levitt's role in the development of the book, which is published by scribner laidlaw
a brochure from the publisher promoting the book says it ``offers test-taking practice in multiple-choice formats, identical to those on the new york state program evaluation test.'' the test was first given last may
the promotional literature does not identify matteoni as a member of the board of regents
the 16-member board of regents sets education policy for the state. the board members, elected by the state legislature, serve without salary
in an interview with the albany times-union, matteoni said she didn't perceive any conflict of interest in what she had done
i thought i was doing something for the children of the state and teachers of the state,'' said matteoni, a brooklyn college education professor
levitt, reached at her new york city office, refused to talk about the book, which is sold to schools in packages of 30 for $140
levitt is a $49,094-a-year associate in reading education and has worked for the education department for almost 15 years, said department spokesman chris carpenter
carballada's appointment of the panel to investigate production of the book came after complaints by the chairmen of the legislature's education committees. graf, `malta's state ...' adds 2 grafs to update with message from malta prime minister to gadhafi.</note>
panicked soccer fans fled knife-wielding ruffians and triggered the collapse of a sports stadium in libya, killing at least 20 people, according to news reports friday
malta's state radio said two libyans were arrested in tripoli after the collapse
newspapers in belgrade, quoting a report from the yugoslav state news agency tanjug from tripoli, said at least 20 people were killed and hundreds injured when a stadium dividing wall fell thursday during a match between malta and libya
joe sacco, the general secretary of the maltese football association who was in tripoli with the maltese team, said friday there was speculation in the libyan capital that the death toll could be higher
the libyan news agency jana said a row of seats collapsed at the june 11 stadium and that a ``number of spectators were injured.'' the stadium reportedly has a capacity of 70,000, it was not immediately known how many people were at the game
the times of malta said panic occurred when someone in the stands brandished a weapon and the spectators rushed to get out
politika ekspres, a belgrade daily, said the incident began when several fans pulled out knives during a quarrel
some spectators returning to malta told reporters at the airport the same story while others quoted people in the stadium as saying a man was terrorizing the crowd with a snake
politika ekspres said spectators seeking safety toppled an iron fence. at the same time, a six-foot thick, 15-foot long wall dividing the second from the third level of the stadium also crashed down
it is hard to believe that anyone under it could have remained alive,'' politika ekspres said, quoting eyewitnesses
several hundred people reportedly were injured when the crowd from the third level surged down, creating panic that soon spread to other parts of the stadium
people rushed to all exits, and that caused more injuries, the paper said
finally, about 5,000 fans in the field started chasing the culprits. one of them was captured but police managed to drag him free from the hands of the crowd, politika ekspres said
malta's department of information said the foreign ministry was informed that no maltese nationals were involved in the accident
the libyans were leading 1-0 in the exhibition game between the two national teams. the game was stopped and did not resume
maltese prime minister edward fench adami sent a message friday to libyan leader col. moammar gadhafi extending ``our condolences and deepest sympathies to the familes of the bereaved and to all those hit by this tragedy.''
the people of malta join me in sharing your profound grief at this unhappy moment during the sports festival,'' fenech adami said in the message
arnold f. willat, who developed the first cold permanent wave for women, has died. he was 102
the detroit-born electrical engineer, who died monday, boasted in 1952 that he would pay $1,000 to the first woman whose hair he couldn't curl. a newspaper story at the time said no one collected
at age 95 he was named to the cosmetology hall of fame
willat manufactured and sold his own solutions and equipment for permanent waves for 50 years, and only last year his willat co. of san francisco discontinued manufacturing cold wave solutions. willat curl papers and dispensers are still found in beauty shops
one of the nation's early electrical engineers, with a degree from georgia tech in 1907, willat traveled the east coast after graduation, and came to san francisco with his wife in 1913
at a manufacturer's request, willat developed an electricity-and-heat permanent wave machine for beauty shops but eventually found a better way to curl hair
willat's son, forest of greenbrae, calif., said his father gave up rights to several patents in the 1960s after winning large settlements from major manufacturers. the younger willat said scores of companies soon were making and selling cold wave kits
willat is survived by two other sons, thoreau of new mexico and leon of mill valley, calif.; 11 grandchildren and six great-grandchildren
services will be private
iran and iraq stopped nearly two weeks of attacks on each other's cities friday, but the iraqis said they got in the last volley with 11 missiles fired before their afternoon truce deadline
hundreds of civilians have been killed or wounded since the exchange began feb. 29
eight rockets were aimed at tehran on friday and three at the iranian holy city of qom, the official iraqi news agency reported. it said the last missile left its launcher at 3:44 p.m., just 16 minutes before time iraq said it would stop shooting
an iraqi military communique said iranian leaders would ``be sparing the blood of their people'' if they also observed a cease-fire, but if they did not, ``by god, we will make them taste bitter defeat, and we will deal them unprecedented, violent blows.''
tehran's official islamic republic news agency said eight civilians were killed and 20 wounded friday, bringing the toll since the missile exchange began feb. 29 to 165 killed and 440 wounded. iraq has reported many deaths and injuries, but has not given figures
thousands of people have been killed in periodic rounds of the ``war of the cities'' since the persian gulf neighbors went to war in september 1980
iraq said its jets raided an iranian tanker in the gulf and seven cities in iran, but maritime officials said they could not confirm the ship attack. iran said civilians were killed in the air raids
in washington, u.s. military sources said iran had begun building launch pads for silkworm anti-ship missiles on abu musa, one of its gulf islands, potentially increasing its ability to menace shipping
there were no reports of iranian missile attacks after two were fired thursday night, but iran said its artillery pounded basra and other southern iraqi cities and its warplanes bombed iraqi troop concentrations. iraq said women and children were killed in the shelling
a military spokesman said on tehran radio later friday that iran had stopped its ``deterrent attacks'' on iraqi cities, but would respond if iraq attacked iranian residential areas
turkey was instrumental in arranging the truce, which it had intended to begin thursday. the turks have good relations with both sides and represent the interests of each on the other's territory
iran had said it would start its cease-fire thursday afternoon, but presumably continued its attacks when iraq did the same
manuser mottaki, iran's ambassador to turkey, said friday in ankara that the iranians would honor the truce if iraq did. both combatants had made similar statements while turkey was arranging the cease-fire
iraq reported firing 71 missiles in the 12 days, 59 of them into tehran, and iran said it launched 29, all but two at baghdad
tehran was safe from attack by surface-to-surface missiles until now because it is 290 miles from the border and iraq did not have rockets capable of reaching it. iran periodically fired missiles into baghdad, which is only 80 miles from the frontier
iraq said it developed its own long-range missile, but military analysts say it is using soviet-made scud-bs with strap-on boosters for added range. they say iran also uses scud-bs, which can fly 190 miles without boosters
the defense officials in washington, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said u.s. intelligence had not yet detected efforts by iran to move any of its chinese-built silkworms to abu musa
iran has batteries of silkworms, which have a range of about 50 miles, on its shore of the narrow strait of hormuz, southern gateway to the persian gulf
it also has fired missiles believed to be silkworms into kuwait's main anchorage from the faw peninsula, which it captured from iraq early in the war
in washington, the pentagon announced that the 16th convoy operation of 1988 had ended quietly friday with two reflagged kuwaiti tankers steaming out of the persian gulf into the gulf of oman
the sea isle city and chesapeake city, which began the southbound transit (from kuwait) through the persian gulf on tuesday, were escorted by the guided-missile frigate uss simpson,'' the pentagon said
a man convicted in the slaying of a drug dealer later fell in love with a police officer's daughter and lived with her family for several months before his secret was revealed
ross basurto, 24, was sentenced thursday to 10 years to life in prison for his role in the november 1985 killing of mark b. borgerson, 25. basurto admitted in january that he was present when borgerson was killed
officer jose r. lopez and his daughter, rachel, testified for leniency on behalf of basurto at sentencing, before multnomah county circuit judge richard l. unis
lopez, a 20-year police veteran, told the judge basurto, using the name jay adams, came to live with his family in july 1986. basurto, who met rachel after the killing, was her boyfriend before he moved in with the family
he told me that he had just moved up from california,'' lopez said. ``he lived with us four or five months.''
as a police technician, lopez had collected evidence at the scene of the borgerson killing. but lopez said he never suspected basurto of wrongdoing
basurto, he said, had a good record as an employee of a gas station and later a towing company
testimony indicated that rachel lopez, who is nine months pregnant with basurto's child, learned her boyfriend's real name and read police reports on the killing while working that summer at the police bureau's records department. she said she hopes to marry basurto
she never revealed what she had discovered to her father, who learned basurto's real identity only after his arrest last october. basurto was recognized by an individual who had read an item about the crime in a newspaper
between the time he moved in with the lopez family and his arrest, basurto also lived in yuma, ariz., and fort lauderdale, fla
basurto is the third and last defendant convicted in the killing
basurto admitted carrying a gun and being present when a co-defendant shot borgerson after the two had gone to the victim's apartment to steal drugs
defense lawyer gary carlson said basurto was a peaceful, industrious person ``who got swept away'' by an unfortunate friendship
but prosecutor john foote characterized basurto as a man of many sides who had shown his best side to his family and friends
two former bank executives were portrayed friday as greedy men hungry for wealth as prosecutors began presenting their case in a fraud trial linked to the near-demise of continental illinois bank and trust co
u.s. district court jurors, who may sit through six weeks of testimony, listened to detailed descriptions of alleged fraud that involved millions of dollars and stretched from the oil fields of oklahoma to continental's offices in chicago
the government has accused former continental vice president john lytle of buying high-risk loans from now-defunct penn square bank in oklahoma city in exchange for nearly $600,000 in kickbacks between 1980 and 1982
defendant william patterson, former head of energy lending at penn square, gave the kickbacks to lytle in the form of unsecured loans, the government contends
a third defendant, tulsa oil driller jere sturgis, is accused of making payments to lytle in hopes of getting future loans from continental
the three men have pleaded innocent
ladies and gentlemen, you're going to hear evidence that will prove that john lytle was not serving the interests of his employer,'' assistant u.s. attorney mark l. rotert said
he contended lytle ``was completely financially dependent on bill patterson.''
lytle's lifestyle, rotert said, involved the kind of ``consumption of goods that is associated in this country with the wealthy, the well-off.''
he was adding rooms to his home in northbrook. he took vacations _ not one-week vacations, not two-week vacations, but month-long vacations,'' rotert said
lytle, who worked at continental from 1959 until his dismissal in 1982, bought furs and rare automobiles, took trips to the french west indies and stayed in a luxurious condominium in vail, colo., where he liked to ski, the prosecutor said
he had a hot tub there with a retractable roof. he could sit back and see the craggy peaks of the rocky mountains,'' rotert said
patterson, meanwhile, was the third-largest shareholder in the first penn corp., parent company of penn square bank, the prosecutor said
the success of penn square bank was his future, his career, his livelihood,'' rotert said
patterson is accused of paying lytle to ensure continental's involvement in loans with penn square
continental would be the principle lender in most cases, but penn square benefited from finder's fees worth thousands of dollars, rotert said
continental and penn square became lending partners on millions of dollars in loans, largely because of the relationship between lytle and patterson, the prosecutor said
lytle's job as the head of continental's gas and oil lending operation in oklahoma did not involve routine loan approvals, but he constantly overruled loan officers who opposed risky deals with penn square
mr. lytle did what mr. patterson wanted him to do,'' rotert said
lytle, 52, and patterson, 37, are charged with misapplication of bank funds and wire fraud
sturgis, 40, charged with wire fraud, is acccused of joining the alleged scheme by helping lytle cover the unsecured loans from patterson after continental discovered lytle's personal dealings
penn square collapsed in july 1982 under the weight of energy loans it could not collect. in 1984, continental survived the largest run on deposits in banking history, with the help of a $4.5 billion government bailout
sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., chairman of the senate labor and resources committee, expressed his support friday for increasing the minimum wage to $5.05 per hour over four years but said he still remains committed to raises tied to inflation
i continue to support indexing,'' said kennedy, in a statement released by his washington office. ``it's the best way to make the minimum wage a living wage.''
kennedy said his committee has scheduled action on the minimum wage bill during the week of april 11
the house education and labor committee voted thursday to raise the federal minimum wage to $5.05 an hour in several steps over the next four years
the vote to increase the minimum wage to $5.05, instead of the $4.65 voted last week by the house labor standards subcommittee, was seen as an attempt by supporters of an increase to gain a bargaining chip that will assure the minimum wage will be at least $4.65 when the measure leaves the house
last week, the subcommittee approved a bill to raise the $3.35-an-hour minimum wage to $3.85 in 1989, $4.25 in 1990 and $4.65 in 1991. at the same time, the subcommittee voted to strip the bill of a controversial proposal that would have indexed or tied future increases to the rate of inflation
a fourth year increase is less satisfactory, but it could make a stronger package, given the president's veto threats,'' said kennedy. ``the last time congress raised the minimum wage in 1977, we enacted a four-step increase, too.''
a 25-year-old albanian oil company employee seeking political asylum in greece crawled under an electric wire fence and gave himself up to authorities, police in this northern town said friday
the man, identified as spetim kenai, from the southern albanian town of fier, crossed the border in daylight wednesday before presenting himself at the local police station in the border village of pogoniani, a police spokesman said
he has now been moved to the united nations refugee center outside athens and plans to ask for political asylum,'' said the spokesman, who requested anonymity in accordance with greek practice
according to a report in the conservative athens daily, free press, the man said 17 soldiers and an army officer also recently fled the self-isolated balkan state by crossing the border into yugoslavia
