perzell dinkins, 22, was taken into custody thursday on a fugitive from justice charge, said campus security capt. gene crawford. dinkins was being held friday pending $500 bond, officials said
dinkins faces felony charges in lawrence county, ohio, for allegedly receiving stolen property, crawford said. he also has outstanding arrest warrants in ashland, ky., and jackson, miss., but the charges in those cities were not immediately known, he added
campus security searched the attic of hodges hall after residents reported a man living there, marshall's student newspaper, the parthenon, reported friday
he had some clothing there _ he left it there and would come in frequently to take a shower and change clothes,'' crawford said
the parthenon reported that dinkins told residents of hodges hall he was the new quarterback for the football team. the mens' dormitory houses most of the school's male athletes and residents had seen dinkins there for several days, the paper said
crawford said dinkins didn't tell police he was on the football team, ``but he did say he was trying to get a football scholarship.''
dinkins said he had been living in the huntington area since january but denied living in the dormitory, police said
a baptist minister and a secretary insisted friday that a convicted killer who has escaped florida's electric chair six times is innocent and should not be executed next week
the rev. sam sparks and christine bass also said they were disappointed that gov. bob martinez refused to meet with them friday to hear evidence they hoped would clear willie jasper darden
i think a lot of people in florida are wondering why he won't sit down for even 15 minutes with ms. bass and me. that seems reasonable,'' said sparks
meanwhile, darden's attorneys filed a last-ditch appeal on his behalf friday in the florida supreme court. no immediate ruling was issued
the governor said he was satisfied the courts had reviewed darden's case thoroughly
there is nothing that would change my mind. ... the evidence was clear, the rulings were proper by the courts,'' martinez said
sparks and ms. bass appeared at a news conference called by amnesty international, which has tried to focus international pressure on the governor, who signed a seventh death for darden this week, one day after the u.s. supreme court turned down an appeal
soviet dissident andrei sakharov, american actress margot kidder and british rock star peter gabriel are among those opposing his electrocution
amnesty international delivered to the governor's office petitions bearing the signatures of 10,000 people in the netherlands who opposed florida's system of capital punishment. the group also urged its supporters to call or cable the governor's office friday
it is a violation of human rights,'' said magdaleno rose-avila, head of the group's campaign to abolish the death penalty
darden, 54, has survived more death warrants and has been on florida's death row longer than any other inmate except one. his case has become a focal point for capital punishment opponents who say his trial was tainted by racial prejudice. darden is black, and the man he was convicted of killing was white
sparks and ms. bass have issued affidavits about the events of sept. 8, 1973, that conflict with the versions of the killing related by the victim's wife and prosecutors
darden was convicted of killing lakeland furniture store owner james turman during a robbery that netted $15. a store employee also was shot three times and crippled, and turman's wife had to fend off a sexual attack
sparks said turman's wife had told him all blacks looked alike to her and that her identification of darden was unimportant because the lawyers had told her that darden committed the crime
helen baum, formerly helen turman, recently denied having made that statement to sparks and reaffirmed her identification of darden as the one who shot her husband. mrs. baum said it was her sister who made the statement sparks quoted, but sparks insisted that it was mrs. baum
ms. bass, a lakeland secretary, said darden had an accident near her house and that he waited for a tow truck until 5:35 p.m. her house was eight miles from turman's store and prosecutor say the crime occurred at about 6 p.m
willie darden is innocent, and i know it,'' ms. bass said
ms. bass said she tried to meet with darden's attorney to tell him what she knew, but was rebuffed
sparks said he did not come forward sooner because he had been told by mrs. baum about a month after her husband's death that darden confessed to the crime. sparks said he didn't know otherwise until he started talking to ms. bass and they compared notes on the crime
a doctor who taped a suicide note to the wheel of his van at niagara falls and disappeared after he was charged with attempted murder of his estranged wife has telephoned his father
he has contacted me and i told the fbi and the court and so forth,'' howard johe, a charleston architect, said friday of his son, dr. david johe. ``i don't know what will happen now. i think the less said, the better.''
johe said his son got in touch with him in the past few weeks
until that call, the family had believed that david johe, 35, had committed suicide in july
in june, authorities arrested johe and accused him of breaking into the bradford, pa., home of his estranged wife, blair plott johe, and trying to strangle her
several days after his release on bond, police in niagara falls found johe's van parked in a motel parking lot. a note taped to the steering wheel read: ``goodbye. i hope the water's not too cold. i guess i'll never know. david.''
both the elder johe and his daughter, sara johe, said a note left in david johe's home and articles sent to the family convinced them he had planned to kill himself
a body was never recovered
bradford township, pa., police chief david doyle has maintained that he didn't believe the doctor was dead
johe, an orthopedic physician, specialized in reattaching severed limbs, fingers and toes
about 50 conservationists and residents of this scenic philadelphia suburb gathered friday to protest a planned power line through a farm made famous by artist andrew wyeth
wyeth, who is from chadds ford, used the kuerner farm for more than 1,000 studies and at least five paintings over 45 years
he spent as much time here as i did farming. he painted while we worked,'' said karl kuerner jr., 61, who raises cattle and grows hay on the 35-acre farm
philadelphia electric co. plans to place wooden utility poles on a 250-foot stretch of the farm as part of a 11-mile power line between a concord substation and kennett square, said bill jones, a spokesman for the company
growth in the area southwest of philadelphia near the delaware state line makes the new line necessary before peak demand in the summer, he said
the existing lines in the area were overloaded almost daily when the temperature got over 90 last summer,'' jones said, adding that there were several brief blackouts because of the demand
philadelphia electric serves 1.4 electric customers in southeastern pennsylvania and northern maryland
a power line already traverses the kuerner farm, with three 100-foot metal towers standing on a meadow near a shingled barn. the new line would come within 35 feet of the barn, kuerner said
demonstrators holding signs outside the entrance to the kuerner farm said an alternate route along a nearby highway would have less of an impact on the environment
route 1 has already got poles and everything. it's not going to affect the aesthetics,'' said harry g. haskell jr., a former mayor of wilmington who grew up with wyeth in chadds ford
wyeth was ill with the flu and could not attend the demonstration, said john sheppard, a spokesman for the brandywine river museum, where many of wyeth's paintings are displayed
j.l. peters, a division manager for philadelphia electric, said the route over the kuerner's farm had the least impact
we are cognizant of the natural beauty of the chadds ford area and we have spent considerable time and effort looking at all the possible routes through the area so as to minimize the impact on the aesthetics,'' peters said
we are convinced the route we have selected achieves that,'' he said
wyeth's paintings using kuerner's farm include ``snow flurries,'' which is on display at the national gallery in washington; ``evening at kuerners''; ``trodden weed''; ``pine baron''; and ``young bull.''
he has a special feeling for the land,'' haskell said
kuerner said wyeth still paints at the farm
he comes quite often, mostly snow scenes,'' he said
outgoing president antonio ortiz mena of the inter-american development bank predicted on friday that its loans to latin america will increase from last year's $2.361 billion to between $2.5 billion and $3 billion in 1988
we can continue on this level until the end of the century,'' ortiz mena told a news conference
the bank, owned by 44 governments, is a major source of loans to raise the living standards of latin american countries, most of which have seen declines in recent years from their already low levels
after 17 years with the bank, ortiz mena is returning to his native mexico. he will be succeeded by enrique iglesias of uruguay
ortiz mena blamed the drop in the bank's lending in part on the drop in the value of the u.s. dollar, which he said cost the bank $1.2 billion last year and will cost it another $2 billion in 1988
the bank is deep in a dispute with the u.s. government, its biggest shareholder, which is seeking more control over its lending
ortiz mena denied that he had blocked a u.s. effort to place a new man as the bank's executive vice president _ james w. conrow, deputy assistant secretary of the treasury for developing nations. he said the report was a ``fabrication.''
ortiz mena will not be going to a meeting of the bank's board of governors to be held in caracas, venezuela, on march 21. he said there would be discussion there of additional resources for the bank from japan. he would not give a figure
he added that there would also be discussion of increasing japan's voting strength in the fund, now 1.08 percent of the total. the united states, the largest contributor, controls 34.5 percent of the votes
ortiz mena said the major challenge for the inter-american bank is to help reverse the present situation in which capital is flowing out of latin america instead of into it. the outflow, much of it interest on old debts, is estimated at $15.7 billion for 1987
latin american countries can not fulfill theur debt commitments unless there is economic growth,'' ortiz mena said. ``to achieve growth, it needs investment. there can be no investment if it is exporting capital. it needs to import capital.'' mounts</head>
lyndon larouche's attorneys demanded access friday to information a prosecutor relied on when he said a top fbi official conferred with a key figure in the iran-contra scandal about an effort to collect information against larouche
the attorneys said the information might help them prove their contention that former white house aide oliver north asked the fbi and cia to infiltrate larouche groups because they were interfering with north's private contra-resupply effort
also friday, the trial judge again delayed the resumption of testimony in the fraud and conspiracy case against larouche, six aides and five organizations because of pending searches of government records, including those of the white house and vice president george bush, for any evidence suggesting infiltration of larouche groups
a prosecutor said the records searches ordered by u.s. district judge robert e. keeton would take up to three weeks
assistant u.s. attorney john markham urged the judge to allow testimony to continue in the interim, but defense lawyers said they would be unable to competently question witnesses without first having all evidence of possible government infiltration of larouche groups
keeton said the earliest the jury would be called back to court was tuesday. he also said he would decide monday if a longer delay was necessary
also friday, the larouche attorneys unleashed several new allegations of prosecutorial and government misconduct. they charged the government withheld documents favorable to defense claims that evidence against larouche and followers was fabricated by government agents working undercover in the political extremist's organizations
in a memo sent to north by retired air force maj. gen. richard secord, one of north's principal operatives in the contra-resupply network, secord said that ``our man'' told him retired army sgt. maj. fred lewis had gathered ``info against larouche.''
lewis is the executive vice president of rhyolite management systems, a texas company the larouche lawyers contend was one of several private companies run by former military officers used by the cia to carry out covert activities
assistant u.s. attorney john markham had told larouche defense lawyers that ``our man'' referred to oliver ``buck'' revell, a top fbi official involved in counterintelligence operations. markham since has said he was mistaken and that the reference was to john cupp, a secord associate who worked in the resupply effort
secord and cupp, in interviews this week, also have said the reference was to cupp. both denied any role in or knowledge of a government effort to spy on larouche
if `our man here' is in fact oliver revell, it would create a motive for high-level forces in the fbi and national security council to conceal that in order to protect mr. revell,'' the defense motion said
markham did not immediately respond to the request for information concerning revell. an fbi spokesman earlier this week refused to relay questions from the associated press to revell, saying the agency would not comment on matters that were at issue in a current trial
an fbi document declassified this week quotes lewis and two other men as saying top fbi and cia officials asked them to infiltrate larouche groups. larouche lawyers said they had evidence the three asked larouche aides to assist them in illegal activities
markham contended in a document filed friday that lewis and the two other men were lying when they said they had been asked to infiltrate larouche groups
larouche attorney odin anderson also said friday that he had evidence showing revell intervened to block a planned meeting between larouche and william clark, who at the time of the alleged incident was president reagan's national security adviser
the united states and vietnam have scheduled another meeting this weekend to discuss the search for american servicemen missing from the vietnam war, the pentagon said friday
the so-called technical meeting of mia specialists from the two countries will begin in hanoi on saturday and extend through tuesday, the pentagon said in a statement. the last such meeting was held in january
the u.s. team will be led by lt. col. joe harvey, commander of the joint casualty resolution center in hawaii, the pentagon said
rosa l. parks, who sparked the 1955 alabama bus boycott, was discharged friday from johns hopkins hospital, a spokesman said
ms. parks, 75, received a pacemaker tuesday, said hospital spokesman phil kibak
ms. parks, of detroit, was in baltimore for medical tests and to help plan a national birthday celebration scheduled for her in june, said spokesman ghita levine. she chose to undergo tests at johns hopkins at the request of dr. levi watkins jr., whom ms. parks met at a speaking engagement here in january, levine said
nearly 33 years ago, ms. parks refused to give up her seat to a white man on a segregated bus in montgomery, ala. she was arrested, and the black community retaliated by boycotting the buses
a woman was being held friday on charges she tried to smuggle a gun, hidden in a lemon pie, into the county jail, authorities said
sherry spencer, also known as lea spencer, 24, of elkview is charged with two felony counts of aiding an escape attempt and one misdemeanor count of carrying a dangerous weapon, sheriff robey knight said. he would not identify the prisoner to whom spencer allegedly was trying to smuggle the weapon
sheriff's department sgt. russell goodwin said spencer was arrested after she showed up at the roane county jail on sunday and dropped off a lemon pie for a prisoner
the pie was in an aluminum dish, and because prisoners are prohibited from receiving metal objects, a guard transferred the pie to a paper plate. as he did, russell said, a .22-caliber pistol and 13 rounds of ammunition dropped out
the gun and ammunition were wrapped in plastic, russell said
spencer was being held in the wirt county jail pending $12,500 bond, knight said. a preliminary hearing is scheduled wednesday
here is a chronology of gary hart's 1988 campaign for the presidency:
april 13 _ hart declares candidacy, promising voters ``a presidency you can be proud of.''
april 24 _ hart aides confirm federal election commission is questioning legal status of $421,000 debt still owed at end of 1986 from hart's 1984 campaign
may 3 _ miami herald reports young woman, later identified as part-time model donna rice, spent much of weekend with hart. hart denies she stayed at his washington apartment. des moines register says poll of democrats in iowa shows hart with 65 percent support
may 6 _ hart's wife, lee, says she believes her husband when he says nothing happened between him and rice. poll of new hampshire democrats shows massachusetts gov. michael dukakis leading hart, 27 to 17 percent. a week earlier, same poll showed pair tied at 32 percent
may 8 _ hart withdraws from presidential race
sept. 8 _ he says in television interview, ``i am not running for president. i'm out.''
dec. 15 _ he re-enters democratic race, filing for new hampshire primary. ``let the people decide,'' he says. he immediately jumps to top of democratic field in national and iowa polls
january _ hart's campaign suffers another blow when reports surface that hollywood producer stuart karl improperly bankrolled campaign. hart later acknowledges several contributions were illegal and returns money
feb. 8 _ he wins only 1 percent of vote in iowa caucuses
feb. 16 _ he wins 4 percent of vote in new hampshire primary
march 8 _ he finishes with 3 percent of vote overall on super tuesday
march 9 _ federal election commission announces hart has not received enough support to be eligible for matching federal campaign funds
march 11 _ hart withdraws from race for second time
nine wheaton college graduates go to court monday in an attempt to prevent the school from using funds raised by alumnae for new coeducational purposes
the group claims to represent hundreds of alumnae around the country upset by the school's plan to admit men this fall for the first time in its 154-year history
at issue is $10.7 million raised by alumnae from 1983 to 1985 in a telephone fund drive marking wheaton's 150th anniversary, says alumna mary anne marsh
the theme of the drive was preparing women for the 21st century,'' said marsh. ``we had been given no idea they planned to make the school coed.''
alumnae first received letters informing them of the plan to go coeducational in january 1987, marsh said. but she added, ``it's very clear that this plan was conceived before the first phone was picked up.''
the trustees of this college of 1,200 students 30 miles south of boston endorsed the move last may. at that time, president alice emerson said the change was not being made for financial reasons but because of a nationwide decline in high school graduates and studies showing a waning interest in single-sex colleges
nancy mccann, another of the nine alumnae, expressed anger about the plan
it's important to keep women's colleges alive,'' she said. ``there should be options. women's colleges afford women the chance to take a real leadership role while they are trying out their wings before they go into the real world.''
wheaton spokeswoman lisa byrnes said the school would ``seek judicial approval to use these funds for coeducational purposes'' at monday's hearing in bristol county probate court
u.s. rep. mario biaggi and six co-defendants were greedy thieves who plundered a now-defunct bronx defense contractor for millions of dollars, the government charged friday as the wedtech corp. racketeering trial unfolded
this is a case about corruption and greed and the purchase and sale of public offices. it is a case about public officials who want to get paid twice, once by the people who elected them to do their job, again by someone else,'' assistant u.s. attorney howard wilson told the jury in u.s. district court in manhattan
this case involves the story of the rise of a little company in the bronx'' that began in 1965 as a machine shop and grew by 1978 to $1.5 million in sales by taking advantage of laws that promoted the growth of minority-owned enterprises, wilson said
seven years later, this company had grown like topsy'' to a defense contractor with 1,000 employees and $117 million in revenues, becoming ``the biggest single employer in the bronx,'' he said
the success was achieved through corruption and lies.''
this case is part of a scandal that also led to the indictment of former white house aide lyn nofziger and two former associates of attorney general edwin meese iii
nofziger was convicted last month of lobbying former white house associates within one year after he left the government on matters including a federal contract for wedtech
defendants in the manhattan trial are biaggi, 70: former bronx borough president stanley simon, 57; bernard g. ehrlich, 59, of bedford, biaggi's former law partner and a former major general in the new york national guard; biaggi's son richard, 38, of fort lee, n.j.; peter neglia, 39, of armonk, the former regional administrator of the small business administration; john mariotta, 57, scarsdale, former wedtech chairman; and ronald betso, 39, of brooklyn, a former cop and friend of neglia's
they all treated this company like a gold mine,'' said wilson. ``some took a lot. some took a little. but they all took.''
they engaged in the scheme by saying that mariotta, who is hispanic, was the majority owner of wedtech, and thus the company was entitled to a federal program that allowed companies to get government business without bidding, the government says
the minority member of the company must own more than 51 percent of the firm. but in fact, wilson charged, mariotta owned less than half
biaggi at one point demanded 5 percent of wedtech's revenues, but that was too much for wedtech officials, wilson said, who then gave him 5 percent of wedtech stock that was put in his son's name
at another point, biaggi asked for $50,000 for expediting a lease before the city's board of estimate, the prosecutor said, and the law firm his son worked for received the money the day after the lease was signed
in addition, the law firm earned $1 million in retainers' fees from wedtech from 1978 to 1985, wilson said
simon, who was borough president from 1979 to 1987, demanded and received over $50,000 that came in cash in envelopes, meals, chips for gambling in atlantic city casinos, pink marble in his home, a trip to rome and contributions in his name to charities, wilson said
he also got a job for his brother-in-law at wedtech and took half his raises over the years, wilson said
neglia as regional sba head and then as acting chief of staff in washington was wedtech's ``paid-for friend,'' wilson said
among other things, wilson contended, neglia warned the company about a congressional inquiry, provided navy specifications for bidding on a pontoon contract wedtech wanted and helped wedtech obtain contracts of increasing value
neglia was paid with stock options, frequent meals, contributions to the republican party in his name and the promise of a job once he left office, wilson said. less than a month after leaving the government in early 1986, he went to work for the law firm biaggi and ehrlich
mariotta embezzled about $1 million and sold wedtech stock worth between $6 million and $8 million, wilson charges. ehrlich was ``mario biaggi's partner in the plunder of wedtech. when he got it, he split it,'' wilson charged
richard biaggi became a lawyer in 1982 and ``became the front man in this case,'' wilson said, sometimes taking money or stock in his father's name. betso was a smaller player who took stock options in his name for his friend neglia, wilson alleged
wilson said he would present testimony from wedtech accountants, supervisors, workers, sen. alfonse d'amato, and four former officials who have pleaded guilty to crimes involving wedtech
defense attorneys begin presenting their arguments monday
in life, bill britt's refusal to budge from his makeshift hut in the woods earned him the image of cantankerous eccentric. but friends and family on friday mourned the 52-year-old hermit as a free spirit who loved nature
my father never really was a hermit,'' said his tearful daughter, ingrid boughner, 28. ``he was a naturalist. ... he was the most colorful and articulate human being. he loved me for being me and he gave me the courage to be myself.''
bill britt was a truly rare human being. there are not enough accolades to describe him. he had a zest for life, a passion for freedom, independence and the beauty of the woods,'' said bill baird, the abortion activist who befriended britt 20 years ago
britt's daughter and son, britton steven boughner, 30, as well as his mother, marion, 86, two brothers and many other relatives gathered with his friends for the memorial service at a funeral home
the oak casket at the front of the room was bedecked with flowers. someone had also placed on it a photograph of the hermit hugging one of his beloved trees. there was also a stuffed toy raccoon, a memory of the man's love for wild animals, and a hand-made card written by his son and daughter
the family planned to cremate the body. baird said he would scatter the ashes saturday at britt's favorite tree despite objections that a license is needed
britt was once a married man with a house, three children and a job in an office. it all crumbled when he divorced in 1969
britt cast off his three-piece suits and his three-piece name, britton william boughner. he began to spend time in the woods at the state-owned chestnut hill reservoir, near the affluent suburb of the same name where he was born and raised. they called him the ``hermit of chestnut hill.''
but he was hardly a recluse
britt was shrewd and stubborn, given to tears when he didn't get his way. he resembled a tall child as he rode the trolleys and hunted for pay phones to call reporters, clad in cast-off clothing and dragging a clattering armful of plastic buckets that served as his portable office
bear-shaped and nearly toothless, britt had blind eyes swollen with infection. he refused welfare and lived on the nickels he got for empty bottles and cans
two years ago, britt became the subject of legal efforts to pry him from the patch of state land
britt fought back by cultivating the image of misunderstood hermit who wanted only to be left alone among the trees. it landed him a spot on ``late night with david letterman.'' actor mickey rooney suggested making a tv movie about britt's life
a sympathetic judge respected britt's wish for a suburban eden and ordered the state to find a suitable alternative site
britt refused them all
last july, he was finally forced from state land and moved to the adjacent boston cemetry
officials said britt froze to death about two weeks before his body was found monday at the chestnut hill cemetery. his remains were found by his daughter and son, inside the lean-to where he lived
an american peace activist held by contra rebels for nine days said friday the experience was ``the most terrifying'' of his life and his captors threatened to kill him if he tried to escape
richard boren, a 30-year-old witness for peace volunteer from elkin, n.c., said he was forced at gunpoint to go with the contras after they captured him during an attack march 1 on a northern farm cooperative
they freed him wednesday night, suffering from a cold but unharmed
witness for peace, based in durham, n.c., opposes u.s. policy on nicaragua and support for the rebels, and seeks to document contra human rights abuses
the explosions sounded like they were all around, literally, i thought we'd end up getting killed,'' boren said of the rebel attack on the cooperative
i heard a shot right at the door to the house i was staying in,'' he said. ``i looked up and saw isabel ramos, the 13-year-old girl, was wounded.''
he said he left the house with his arms raised and was taken, along with 12 nicaraguans, by the contras. ``i asked them if they were going to kill me and their response was `yes' if i ran'' away, he added
boren said his release wednesday night near quilali, a village 170 miles north of managua, surprised him. he said he plans to go back to the united states for a while to see his family and friends
i have now personally experienced the terror the nicaraguan people are subjected to at the hands of the contras,'' he said. ``it has been the most terrifying experience of my life and i doubt the emotional scars from the experience will ever completely heal.''
he was the second american member of witness for peace captured by the contras. last october, the rebels held robert fisher for two weeks in central chontales province
the american-arab anti-discrimination committee said friday it has asked attorney general edwin meese iii to place israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir on its border ``watch list'' and order that he not be allowed to enter the united states as a private citizen
the committee also filed suit in federal court demanding u.s. government documents relating to shamir's activities as a member of the militant stern gang which waged guerrilla warfare in the struggle for an independent state in what now is israel
we believe in the adc there should be one stand for terrorists, one for friend and foe alike,'' said abdeen jabara, president of the committee. ``we believe the u.s. government should have one yardstick.''
shamir is to visit the united states next week, meeting with president reagan on wednesday. even if he were on the watch list, shamir would not be turned away since he is coming in an official capacity
the united states last year placed austrian president kurt waldheim on its watch list because of his suspected participation in nazi war crimes during world war ii. the watch list is so called because u.s. consular officials around the world check the list before issuing visas for visits to the united states
the basis for this request rests on the long history and involvement of mr. shamir as a leader of the infamous stern gang which was responsible for numerous acts of terrorism,'' said the adc's letter to meese, dated thursday. the department of justice had no comment on the letter
the court petition, also filed thursday, asked for documents in the possession of the departments of justice, defense and state, the cia and the immigration and naturalization service
shamir's violent opposition to the british forces in palestine led to his imprisonment on at least two occasions,'' the court complaint said. ``shamir was in charge of organization and operations of lehi (the formal name of the stern group) which had adopted a policy of individual acts of terror.''
jabara said his group wants the documents to back its efforts to have shamir declared persona non grata
shamir has never renoucned his participation with the above mentioned groups nor has he ever denounced their use of terrorism,'' the adc complaint said. ``shamir is legally excludable from entering the united states.''
the state department on friday questioned the right of the soviet union to provide arms to the government in afghanistan, denouncing the regime in kabul as ``a faction in the afghan civil strife.''
in a strong statement, department spokesman charles e. redman said u.s. aid to the afghan rebels who have waged a civil war for more than eight years would not be halted until the soviets stopped their assistance to the kabul government
there will be no cutoff of support for the resistance under any other circumstances,'' redman said
on thursday, nikolai kozyrev, the soviet foreign ministry's adviser on afghan affairs, declared that moscow would not stop arming the kabul government as part of an agreement for an afghan cease-fire
the official accused pakistan and the united states of holding up a peace agreement that would end the war and allow the soviets to withdraw an estimated 120,000 troops from the country
it was not immediately clear what impact the u.s. and soviet disagreement on aiding the rival groups would have on negotiations the united nations is holding in geneva between pakistan and afghanistan
soviet general secretary mikhail s. gorbachev had offered to begin a troop withdrawal on may 15 if an agreement was concluded by next tuesday
the geneva draft agreement calls for ``noninterference'' in afghanistan
redman said it was ``only logical'' that the provision apply to the soviet union as well as the united states
the soviets cannot claim a right to aid a faction in the afghan civil strife just because that particular faction tries to call itself the government of afghanistan,'' the spokesman said
the war in afghanistan, in fact, is on this central issue, concerning the very legitimacy of the kabul regime,'' he said
even with soviet support, redman said, ``the present kabul regime has been barely able to secure the capital and a few other cities.''
the u.s. official did not mention the u.s. weapons, including stinger anti-aircraft missiles, that washington has sent the rebels through pakistan
the stingers have downed soviet and afghan aircraft and helicopters and forced pilots to fly higher, reducing the effectiveness of air power against the guerrillas
tass charged friday that u.s. economic sanctions against panama are an attempt to subjugate that central american nation and reclaim the panama canal
the official soviet news agency said in its commentary, ``reports on developments around panama leave no doubt that the washington administration intends to crush the independence of that country and perpetuate u.s. domination over its territory, first of all the panama canal zone.''
it described drug-trafficking accusations against panama's military strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega, as ``a convenient pretext'' for interfering in internal panamanian affairs
it is only a short time ago that gen. noriega was regarded in washington as `one of ours,''' tass stated
president reagan stepped up economic pressure on panama friday, ordering that a $6.5 million payment due panama next week be put into escrow
trade benefits were suspended earlier and reagan ordered intensified scrutiny of panama by u.s. immigration and customs service officials
on thursday, the u.s. house of representatives passed a non-binding resolution demanding noriega's ouster. reagan has refered to the panamanian government as ``illegitimate.''
tass said the united states is trying to pressure panama into renegotiating agreements requiring u.s. soldiers to leave by the year 2000
what washington would really like is to do away with panama's independence, make it back into the obedient u.s. puppet it used to be, and seal the u.s. right forever to own part of panamanian territory and keep u.s. military bases there,'' tass said
noriega was indicted by u.s. grand juries in florida in february on drug-trafficking and money-laundering charges. he has denied the charges
the tass commentary lectured washington it should ``look first at what is happening under its very nose,'' and accused lt. col. oliver north and former national security advisers robert mcfarlane and john poindexter of ``direct involvement in drug-related crimes'' as part of the iran-contra scandal
here, at a glance, are developments in the economic picture friday:
retail sales edged up 0.6 percent in february, but sales in january were much weaker than previously believed
instead of a 0.5 percent rise, sales actually fell 0.2 percent during january, showing the consumer sector is weaker than previously believed
auto sales in february increased 1.6 percent following a 2 percent advance in january. february sales accounted for almost one-fourth of total retail spending during the month
without the strength in auto sales bolstered by new incentive programs, total retail sales would have risen a smaller 0.3 percent
wholesale prices fell 0.2 percent in february, pushed down by drops in both food and energy costs
for the first two months of the year, the labor department said prices have been rising at an annual rate of 1.1 percent, half the 2.2 percent increase in 1987. analysts expect inflation to remain moderate for the rest of the year
food prices declined 1.1 percent in february while energy prices dropped 0.8 percent. the cost of lettuce, which had skyrocketed through the late fall and early winter, fell a dramatic 70 percent
the dow jones average, down more than 20 points at midafternoon, closed with a gain of 8.95 at 2,034.98. for the week the average lost 22.88 points
the u.s. dollar fell against other major currencies in quiet european trading. in tokyo, the dollar closed at 127.80 japanese yen, down from thursday's close of 128.20 yen. later in london, it fell to 127.80 yen
the british pound continued to climb against the dollar, trading at $1.8535 up from $1.8435 late thursday. the pound has leaped by 4 percent in value against the dollar this week
dealers said trading was light and without direction both in typical pre-weekend fashion and because traders were waiting for the january u.s. trade report to be issued next thursday
federal aviation officials on friday unveiled a regional air traffic control center's new computer system, part of a $197 million nationwide system they say will improve air safety even though it will be replaced within 12 years
published suggestions that the new computers already are outdated are ``very, very misleading'' because the agency wanted computers with proven reliability, not the newest models available, said ed harris, an associate administrator of the federal aviation administration
we would have been crazy to gamble on a system that was unproven,'' harris said before the dedication of the new computers at the los angeles air route traffic control center
the center, in palmdale about 50 miles north of downtown los angeles, controls instrument flight operations in 177,000 square miles of airspace over southern and central california, southern nevada, southwestern utah, northwestern arizona and the pacific ocean out to 250 miles off california's coast
attention has been focused on the region's heavy mix of commercial and general aviation aircraft since a small plane flew into restricted airspace over suburban cerritos and collided with an aeromexico jet on aug. 31, 1986, killing 82 people. cerritos is 20 miles southeast of the airport
since the crash, several reviews of faa records indicated its radar and tracking network was a jumble of different computers and outdated electronics, many of which were inoperable or down for repairs a considerable amount of time
the los angeles center is the 13th of 20 faa traffic control centers nationally to activate the new computer system, made by international business machines corp
but the faa will start replacing the new computers _ as well as display screens and other equipment used by controllers _ with a highly advanced, $2 billion to $4 billion nationwide system by 1995, and intends to complete installation by the end of 1999, said william carson jr. of ibm
thousands of ibm 3083s like the ones unveiled friday were sold to banks and businesses until ibm stopped making them last year, carson said
computer technology ``is advancing so quickly that if you waited for state-of-the-art, you'd never buy anything,'' said nobby owens, an faa deputy associate administrator. ``the old (ibm 9020) system was at capacity. the reliability of this (ibm 3083) equipment offers use exactly what we want.''
faa spokeswoman elly brekke said ibm 3083 computers already have been activated at traffic control centers in oakland, calif., which covers the san francisco bay area; seattle; houston; denver; boston; washington; chicago; albuquerque, n.m.; memphis, tenn.; cleveland; atlanta; and miami
scheduled to get the computers by mid-year are centers in new york city; minneapolis; kansas city, mo.; indianapolis; jacksonville, fla.; fort worth, texas, including the dallas area; and salt lake city, she said
the new ibm mainframe computers are up to 10 times faster and have four to five times the storage capacity of the equipment they will replace,'' faa administrator t. allan mcartor said in a prepared statement
this will allow the air traffic control system to keep pace with projected traffic growth over the next decade and accomodate the introduction of new automation functions that will both enhance safety and increase controller productivity,'' he added
the los angeles center's system was activated march 1, but was formally dedicated friday by h.c. ``mac'' mcclure, faa regional director
the ibm 3083s will be equipped with conflict-alert programs to give controllers flashing warnings if two planes start to get too close, even if one of the planes isn't under a controller's jurisdiction, owens said, adding other software will help improve traffic flow
the 600-employee center in palmdale handled about 1.9 million flights last year and is the fifth busiest in the nation
the faa said the new computers are only one aspect of its $12 billion, 20-year modernization plan, which also will include new landing systems, better radars and a major upgrading of weather reports for pilots. fourteen percent of the modernization project has been completed nationwide, with 70 percent of the work under contract
robert c. mcfarlane left congressional iran-contra investigators in little doubt last spring that he had deliberately misled congress about efforts inside the reagan administration to sidestep a ban on aid to nicaragua's contra rebels
some committee members said at the time they felt the former national security adviser's under-oath testimony must have been true because it was so self-damaging
mcfarlane put the seal on that judgment friday when he pleaded guilty to four misdemeanor charges accusing him of withholding from congress the fact that the administration had helped the contra movement stay alive, in part through soliciting secret multi-million dollar contributions from third countries
by pleading guilty, mcfarlane in effect admitted he made false statements in letters sent in 1985 to the house intelligence and foreign affairs committees and in testimony in december 1986 before the foreign affairs panel
in that testimony mcfarlane made this statement: ``i did not solicit any country at any time to make contributions to the contras. i have seen reports that various countries have.''
that was challenged by john nields, chief counsel of the house iran-contra panel, who referred to the country involved as ``country 2'' although it had been independently identified as saudi arabia
now in fact, you did have a pretty good idea of country 2's funding of the contras, didn't you?'' nields asked
yes,'' mcfarlane replied
nields: ``in fact, as you've testified yesterday and today, you had a hand in obtaining contributions totaling approximately $32 million from country two?''
mcfarlane: ``yes.''
nields: ``but you did not tell that to the foreign affairs committee at that time?''
mcfarlane: ``no, i was trying to use some tortured language, inappropriately i think. ... it wasn't a full account. ... this isn't as full an account as i could have given.''
later, he said that testimony and his statements in the 1985 letters were ``clearly too categorical on my part.''
in other portions of his iran-contra testimony, mcfarlane said he had helped alter documents, failed to shut down an out-of-control covert operation and did nothing when marine lt. col. oliver l. north told him he planned to hold a ``shredding party.''
mcfarlane said repeatedly that if anyone was at fault in all of this, it was he
summing up, rep. lee hamilton, d-ind., chairman of the house committee, rejected mcfarlane's attempt to take all of the blame
as the national security adviser you are the spokesman for the president of the united states,'' hamilton told the witness
and when we write to you, we do not write to mr. mcfarlane, we write to you as the representative of the president
and when you spoke to the congress and when you wrote to the congress, we accepted your words and your assurances as those of the president
you spoke for the president,'' hamilton said. ``and the responsibility must rest with him, as well as with you. you cannot, it seems to me, accept responsibility for mistakes, as admirable as that may be, and thereby absolve the president of any responsibility.''
there is no rebuttal,'' mcfarlane replied
mcfarlane, who has testified at length before the grand jury empaneled by independent counsel lawrence e. walsh, attempted suicide last year by swallowing 30 to 40 valium tablets one day before his scheduled testimony before a presidential commission that also investigated the iran-contra affair
walsh was not permitted to use mcfarlane's testimony before the iran-contra panel as evidence in his case, since mcfarlane testified before the congressional committee under a grant of limited immunity
after resigning as national security adviser on dec. 4, 1985, mcfarlane was asked the following may to lead a secret mission to tehran to open contact with so-called moderate iranians thought to have influence with lebanese radicals holding several kidnapped americans
with north as a member of the party, the group traveled aboard an aircraft carrying spare parts for hawk missiles previously shipped to iran by israel
the cake and the bible signed by president reagan, which mcfarlane also carried as gifts, were to become celebrated symbols of the affair
koko, the cover girl gorilla who communicates through sign language, may be bred with colossus, reputed to be the largest lowland gorilla in captivity, a zoo official said friday
koko, whose ability to use sign language and doting upon a pet kitten landed her on the cover of national geographic magazine, has signed to her keepers that she wants to have a baby, said penny patterson, director of the gorilla foundation at woodside, calif., where the ape lives
she may get that chance with the aptly named 600-pound colossus, who is moving sunday from new hampshire to florida, said pat quinn, president and director of the zoo near this panhandle city
an initial attempt at breeding may be through artificial insemination, but quinn said he hoped colossus eventually would be able to mate naturally with koko and other females
semen will be obtained from colossus just before he is flown in a chartered dc-3 from benson's animal park in hudson, n.h., to nearby pensacola and then trucked to the zoo, quinn said
we are hoping to obtain some of that for use with koko because she is very anxious to become a mother,'' said ms. patterson
koko's original pet kitten, which she named all ball because the manx cat had no tail, was hit by a truck and killed after the national geographic story. but koko was given a replacement she named smokey, now full-grown
koko, 16, and a male gorilla, michael, communicate with sign language to express their feelings, ask for food and certain teachers and inquire about other animals
colossus' sperm may be used because captive gorillas sometimes develop incest taboos against cage mates so michael would be unsuitable, ms. patterson said. also, colossus was captured in the wild as an infant 20 years ago and isn't inbred with zoo gorillas
we hope to socialize him so he will breed naturally with females,'' quinn said
colossus has never seen another gorilla outside his original family. the socialization process would start by letting colossus see, smell and touch a male chipanzee, said quinn. then he would be introduced to another bachelor male gorilla or a non-productive female before trying to mate him
quinn said he is working closely with lester fisher, director of chicago's lincoln park zoo and chairman of the gorilla species survival plan for the american association of zoos and aquariums
fisher, a veterinarian, said nothing definite has been decided on breeding yet, but that he was happy to see colossus remain within the zoological community because he is the first gorilla in a long time to go on the auction block. he would provide a new gene pool because he was born in the wild
the plan is designed to develop a self-sustaining captive breeding program in north america because the number of animals in the wild are dwindling and threatened by encroaching civilization
after his arrival sunday night, colossus will be kept isolated for several days, with a coming-out news conference scheduled for friday, quinn said. daughter</head>
the father of a teen-age nude dancer who killed herself said he signed away his rights to the story ``to clear my conscience for being a failure,'' a newspaper reported friday
robert mancini said he signed the waiver for south florida promoter ron sachs, who is negotiating with warner brothers on a made-for-television movie about tina mancini. the 17-year-old killed herself two years ago
last october, theresa jackson, tina's mother, was convicted on three felony child abuse charges by jurors who agreed she had coerced her daughter into working in nude-dance bars
mrs. jackson is free on bail while she appeals the convictions and one-year jail sentence. she has been prevented from profiting from her daughter's suicide under the state's so-called ``son of sam'' law, in which a felon can be denied some or all of the money or ``any other thing of value accruing ... for an accounting of that convicted felon's crime.''
mancini, 47, who said he and mrs. jackson divorced while she was pregnant with tina, their second child, said he waived his rights ``to clear my conscience for being a failure ... for failing to reach tina.''
he said in an interview from his home near los angeles that he didn't see his daughter until she was 14 when she visited him for a few months
i tried to give her a normal life for a while _ disneyland and hiking in the mountains,'' mancini said. ``i always wish i'd have been smart enough to keep her here. it would be nice if we could save some other kids.''
sachs told the fort lauderdale news and sun-sentinel that warner brothers made an offer to make a television movie based on a proposal he presented and would co-produce. he can now depict mancini in the movie about tina
mancini said he will receive no money for the waiver
we're pretty much in accord on the story,'' said sachs, who owns the story rights of tina's grandfather, charles gouveia. ``i am almost certainly going to make a deal with warner brothers.''
sixty-three percent of social security managers said in an internal survey that they were uncomfortable with deep staff cuts and most said staff morale was poor, a union reported friday
kenneth t. blaylock, president of the american federation of government employees, released what he called a bootleg copy of the survey and said, ``dorcas hardy got more than she bargained for in this survey.''
he said it backs up union complaints to congress about the reagan administration's cuts in social security's staff. the agency, which had nearly 80,000 workers in 1984, is now down to 69,345, with 6,000 more jobs slated for elimination by 1990
phil gambino, a spokesman for the social security administration, confirmed that commissioner dorcas hardy ordered the survey of her managers last august ``and it showed there is quite a bit of concern and anxiety.''
we're aware there are a lot of anxieties and we're going to act on that,'' said gambino. hardy plans to start meeting in april with managers in each of social security's 10 regions to discuss their concerns
at the same time, gambino said, ``the performance of our employees is excellent and client satisfaction has never been higher.'' a recent check by the general accounting office indicated that most people are pleased with the service they get from social security
according to afge, the survey was distributed to all 9,000 social security supervisors grades 14 or below, and more than 4,700 responded
asked if they were comfortable with the way the agency was managing staff cuts, 67.2 percent said they were not, 14.2 percent said they were comfortable and 18.5 percent were undecided
asked to judge employee morale, 53.5 percent said it was poor or extremely poor. fifty-five percent said they would not recommend social security to friends as a good place to work
the union said some of the responses to the survey corroborated afge's charges that social security encourages ``cheating'' to meet productivity deadlines
it quoted one anonymous supervisor as writing on the questionnaire: ``everything looks great on paper, but the reality is ssa is going to pot.''
afge represents 60,000 social security workers
blaylock said the survey was ``a strong testimonial for an independent social security administration run by competent career federal employees instead of political appointees who know little or nothing of what ssa is all about.''
andy gibb, the british-born pop singer and former teen idol, died of heart inflammation and there was no evidence that drugs or alcohol were involved, doctors said friday
constable michael harvey of the oxford coroner's office said no inquest would be held because gibb died of natural causes
gibb died thursday at john radcliffe hospital, oxford, after complaining of stomach pains. he was about to resume singing and start recording for island records after years of personal and drug problems
brothers robin, barry and maurice of the bee gees singing group said the body ``will be flown back to his home in los angeles as soon as possible and a memorial service will be held there.''
all friends and family mourn the passing of this exceptionally talented and well-loved artist,'' they said in a statement issued through robin gibb's personal assistant, ken graydon
a hospital statement friday said: ``mr. gibb died from inflammation of the heart of the sort commonly caused by a virus. there is no evidence that his death was related to drink or drugs.''
the bee gees statement said: ``the family and friends of the gibbs are shocked by the untimely death of andy gibb. his passing was completely unexpected
he died of myocarditis, a rare viral infection of the heart muscle. this tends to occur without any warning and there is no effective treatment. the pathologist found no evidence that alcohol or other substances were implicated in any way.''
rob partridge, publicist for island records ltd., said gibb became ill last weekend and was admitted to the hospital ``essentially for observation.''
prior to him falling ill, i'm unaware of any heart condition at all,'' partridge said
asked whether the record company was disturbed by speculation about a drug-related death, he replied: ``of course we are. we wouldn't have signed anyone if there was the slightest suspicion of any kind of drug use
the andy gibb we knew was bright and optimistic and very ambitious for his new recording deal. he had just gained a pilot's license. ... those are not the kind of things drug addicts do.''
robin gibb, 39, spoke to reporters friday at london's heathrow airport. he was meeting his 72-year-old father, hughie gibb, arriving from los angeles
there was no question of andy using drugs,'' he said. ``i don't know where that story came from, but there is absolutely no truth in it. he was not using cocaine again.''
the oxford hospital said the two-time grammy award nominee died at 8:45 a.m. thursday
it was so unexpected,'' robin gibb said. ``andy had been ill with stomach pains for about four days.''
in 1982, andy gibb said he became heavily involved in drugs and dropped his career after the breakup of his highly publicized relationship with television star victoria principal
three years later, he entered the betty ford rehabilitation center in rancho mirage, calif., for treatment of a cocaine habit
an obituary friday in the times of london said gibb's ``immense success could hardly have been founded on vocal qualities alone.''
what sent the young fans wild was his pretty face, flowing blond locks, and his lithe figure, which radiated the healthy, tanned sex-appeal of a male farrah fawcett-majors,'' the daily said
jesse jackson campaigned across his native state on the eve of its democratic presidential caucus, stressing that his candidacy stands for blacks and whites
jackson emphasized issues he said blacks and whites alike believe in: raising the minimum wage, cleaning toxic waste dumps, reducing the flow of drugs into the country, subsidizing day care and saving the family farm
it's not so much black versus white as it is barracudas eating us small fish. they don't eat fish by color. they eat fish by size
what makes south carolina one today? we meet not in confrontation. we meet at the plant gate ... we meet at the toxic waste dump ... we meet on the corner where drugs are being distributed and killing the people.''
the candidate said a new challenge for the new south is to ``find common ground where the people can come together.''
the south carolina education association conference at a columbia motel was at a standstill as teachers waited in the halls and entrances for more than an hour to see jackson. the cooks and maids stopped working to join the greeting line when the greenville native arrived
when he arrived, they screamed, cried, reached out to shake his hand or just tried to touch him
i'm delighted to be home again,'' jackson said as he stood on a chair in an impromptu speech
you taught me,'' said the candidate who was educated through high school in greenville. ``you can have somebody in the white house that you taught. send me...''
jackson told crowds friday that half of the states have held primaries or caucuses and he has finished first or second in all but a few of them
south carolina and louisiana were the only states jackson won in 1984. most political experts and campaign officials concede that jackson should win the lion's share of 44 delegates at stake saturday
a survey of democratic chairmen and vice chairmen indicated jackson is the front-runner, with gore a distant second
twenty-five said jackson was likely to win their counties, five indicated they thought gore would win their counties, two said rep. richard gephardt might win and none predicted dukakis or sen. paul simon would win their counties
when he became president reagan's national security adviser in october 1983, robert c. mcfarlane epitomized the success that can come from a combination of luck, hard work, smarts and having the right mentors
as the son of a texas congressman, a u.s. naval academy graduate, career marine officer and protege of former secretaries of state henry kissinger and alexander haig, mcfarlane had reached the pinnacle of power
he mediated fights between the state and defense departments at home and between israel and its neighbors abroad, helped salvage the mx nuclear missile and put out fires for the administration on capitol hill
more than anyone else in this administration, bud mcfarlane is the guy who has the confidence of members of congress,'' rep. les aspin, d-wis., and chairman of the house armed service committee, said at the time
he had gotten the job despite opposition from conservative ideologues who wanted it to go to former u.n. ambassador jeane kirkpatrick. and no sooner did mcfarlane get the job than it began to unravel
within a week, 241 u.s. marines were killed in beirut, and mcfarlane lost his first major dispute as national security chief. reagan sided with defense secretary caspar w. weinberger to pull out the marines rather than retaliate militarily as mcfarlane and secretary of state george p. shultz urged
it only got worse. disputes between mcfarlane and new white house chief of staff donald t. regan erupted, eventually leading to mcfarlane's resignation in december 1985
while citing personal reasons and the desire to spend more time with his family as his reasons for resigning, mcfarlane later told interviewers that white house infighting made the job ``no longer fun and professional'' and he complained that reagan ``did not have a great interest in foreign affairs.''
then there was iran-contra _ a scheme through which the administration sold arms to iran and used the proceeds to finance nicaraguan rebels in violation of a congressional prohibition on aiding them militarily
although no one knew at the time, mcfarlane was a central player in those events both before and after he left the white house
on friday, mcfarlane, 51, agreed to plead guilty to four misdemeanor charges of withholding information from congress on the administration's secret help to the nicaraguan contras
his plea was an appropriate epilogue to two years of drama that included a secret flight to tehran in may 1986 with plane load of missile parts to be swapped for u.s. hostages, a suicide attempt and sorrowful confessions that he bore the brunt of the blame for the iran-contra affair
what really drove me to despair was a sense of having failed the country,'' mcfarlane told the new york times upon his release from the hospital after taking a overdose of the tranquilizer valium in february 1987
if i had stayed at the white house, i'm sure i could have stopped things from getting worse,'' he said
two months later in televised hearings, mcfarlane told inquiring congressmen and the nation how ``i regret and continue to regret the mistakes i have made.''
because of his suicide attempt just two months earlier, congressmen did not bore in on mcfarlane as much as they did some other witnesses. maintaining a stoic presence, mcfarlane complained of being treated like ``a fragile flower'' and told his questioners: ``shoot your best shot.''
while his testimony was viewed as being fuzzy on the details, he became a model for the psychotherapy community
psychologist joyce brothers praised him as a man ``who, though there was nothing left for him ... is very heroic on the stand.''
he's shown a great deal of ego strength ... after being through the worst that life has to offer, near death,'' ms. brothers said. ``people can see someone else who has been through the valley and come out safely on the other side.''
mcfarlane also has been a model, as an achiever, in his earlier secondary posts. after graduating from the naval academy in 1959, he began a 20-year marine corps career that included stints at strategy schools and war colleges here and abroad between tours of combat duty in vietnam
while still a marine, he was brought into the white house as a military and legislative aide to president nixon, switching to then national security adviser henry kissinger's staff and remaining there when brent scowcroft succeeded kissinger under president ford
after president carter's election, the marine corps sent mcfarlane to okinawa. unhappy with the assignment, he resigned in 1979 with the rank of lieutenant colonel and took a staff job with the senate armed services committee, working primarily for sen. john tower of texas, then the panel's ranking republican and later its chairman
with reagan's election in 1980, secretary of haig, as secretary of state, hired mcfarlane as his military counselor. when reagan in 1982 named undersecretary of state william p. clark as his national security adviser, mcfarlane moved back to the white house as clark's deputy assistant
twenty-one months later, clark decided he would rather be interior secretary and mcfarlane was elevated to the top national security job
president reagan on friday renewed his threat to veto trade legislation under consideration by a house-senate conference committee if it is ``anti-consumer, anti-jobs and anti-growth.''
speaking to representatives of a trade coalition gathered in the auditorium of the old executive office building, reagan said, ``i would note that on tuesday, those who had predicted that protectionism would be embraced in the south were proven wrong.''
reagan was referring to election returns on super tuesday in which rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., a proponent of tough trade sanctions against other nations, managed to win only one of 20 states, his homestate of missouri
too many backers of the trade bill talk about making america more competitive but support provisions that would bench some of the best competitors on our team,'' the president said. ``they talk about saving jobs, but they want provisions that have the potential to destroy thousands if not millions of american jobs.''
reagan said that any trade bill passed by congress should not violate accords the united states has signed in the general agreement on tariffs and trade
he also said the provisions of any such legislation should not ``provoke retaliation against our bombing export business,'' bringing a roar of laughter from the audience. reagan quickly corrected himself, saying, ``wait a minute _ our booming export business.''
alaska democrats gave jesse jackson a narrow victory over massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in a precinct caucus preference poll, announced friday
but it was the large bloc of uncommitted delegates that generated the most interest among the presidential campaigners
with about 90 percent of alaska's 442 precincts reporting, jackson claimed 872 delegates, or 34.9 percent of the total, to dukakis' 769 delegates, or 31 percent. a close third were the 768 delegates, or 30.8 percent, who remained uncommitted
the winners will attend 27 district caucuses on april 9-10, selecting 390 delegates to attend the state convention in fairbanks on may 13-15
the 12 delegates emerging from the state convention will attend the democratic national convention in atlanta in july and will be bound to a specific candidate at least for the first ballot. in atlanta the state also will have five ``super delegates,'' the governor and four members of the democratic national committee
commenting on the results of the preference poll, conducted among delegates selected at the precinct caucuses thursday night, bob speed, executive director of the alaska democratic party, said, ``that huge uncommitted figure represents a lot of people who want to support a democratic candidate but who haven't made up their minds.''
he added, ``the strong showing by the jackson and dukakis people shows the level of their campaigns. it was the lack of organization by the other candidates rather than apathy on the part of the delegates that made them go uncommitted.''
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. finished far back with 47 delegates or about 2 percent, followed by illinois sen. paul simon with 18 delegates, and missouri congressman dick gephardt, who had 16 delegates, less than 1 percent each
russ meekins, state chairman of the dukakis campaign, said organizers will be trying to sway the uncommitted delegates before next month's district caucuses
as of now, counting the gore, simon and gephardt supporters as uncommitted for purposes of selecting national delegates, the breakdown is five for jackson, three for dukakis and four uncommitted
henry lancaster, statewide coordinator for the jackson campaign, said with blacks comprising just 3 percent of alaska's population, his candidate's appeal was based on the anti-drug and economic issues he's been voicing around the nation
this state has a lot of working-class people who've come from the south, the midwest and the northwest,'' lancaster said. ``in down times, people are looking for solutions. and this is a down time.''
that reference was to the collapse of alaska's oil-fired economy. about 85 percent of the state's budget is supported by oil revenues, and world oil prices are less than half what they were three years ago
the democrats chose 2,496 delegates in caucuses around the state thursday night. the caucuses were open to any registered democrat and anyone who wished to register at the door
a former officer who was the principal witness in a series of miami police corruption trials was sentenced friday to 10 years in prison for his part in a cocaine ripoff ring
rodolfo arias, 32, had pleaded guilty to tax fraud and conspiracy to possess cocaine with intent to distribute
his testimony has opened many cans of worms,'' u.s. district judge kenneth ryskamp said of arias, who helped convict three officers of drug-related corruption in the so-called miami river cops trials in recent months
the case was named after the officers' most highly publicized theft, a 1985 raid on a smuggling boat on the miami river in which three drug guards drowned after jumping into the water. the officers stole millions of dollars in cocaine for resale
arias' cooperation was also instrumental in obtaining a dozen guilty pleas before the trials, as well as the suspension or investigation of nearly 100 miami officers whose names surfaced during the investigation
when this plea agreement was signed, we never realized what that cooperation will be. there will be more indictments yet to come,'' said special federal prosecutor russell killinger
arias could have received up to 20 years, but ryskamp honored the government's recommendation for a 10-year maximum
arias will receive credit for time spent in the federal witness protection program and could be free in five years, said his attorney, eugene sauls
this court has ambivalent feelings about this case,'' said the judge, acknowledging arias' cooperation but adding that the former officer's crimes ``cry out for retribution.''
another officer who cooperated with prosecutors received a 15-year sentence friday. carlos pedrera, 27, had pleaded guilty to the same counts
arias and pedrera were among a large group of officers the police department was forced to hire quickly after the mariel boatlift and liberty city riots in the early 1980s
many of the officers worked the midnight shift, and arias testified that his increasingly corrupt group turned miami's streets into its private crime kingdom
the officers routinely took small quantities of drugs and cash from suspects they detained, then expanded into stealing drugs directly from dealers
eastern airlines, embroiled in labor problems, has been forced to cancel numerous flights because of a shortage of pilots, and there is no sign the pilot drain is easing, an eastern executive testified friday
eastern's loss of pilots and details about the impact of that loss were disclosed during testimony in a federal court hearing on whether eastern should be allowed to go ahead with plans to lease 26 eastern jets to orion air, a north carolina cargo carrier
the air line pilots association is asking the u.s. court of appeals to stop the eastern-orion deal, claiming it is designed to circumvent the pilots' labor contract. eastern has said it wants orion to fly the planes with non-union pilots in case of a strike at eastern
in an attempt to show that eastern is planning to lease only spare aircraft to orion, the miami-based carrier produced internal documents showing a sharp increase in the number of pilots who have left the company
the departures and a high rate of sick leave by pilots at the airline are leaving aircraft sitting idle, testified william r. croucher, eastern's director of planning and administration
eastern submitted to the court internal documents showing that 500 pilots left the company for various reasons in 1987, a number that croucher said is nearly 10 times the historical average pilot attrition rate at the airline
he said so far this year, 259 eastern pilots have either left the company or have given notice to depart within 90 days. the airline anticipates losing a total of 600 pilots this year, according to croucher
the pilots union has said previously that the labor turmoil at eastern and a push by management to seek labor concessions has caused hundreds of pilots to seek early retirement or quit to join other airlines even though they are sacrificing their seniority
the figures provided by eastern in court friday, however, are the first details as to how serious the pilot drain has become at the airline, which has about 4,000 pilots. croucher said the airline is hiring about 30 pilots a week, but that because of long training periods, the number is inadequate to make up for the losses
croucher said the pilot shortage has forced eastern to cancel several thousand flying hours that had previously been scheduled for march and april and to cut back total planned flying hours for the rest of the year
during three days last month _ feb. 26 through feb. 28 _ eastern canceled a total of 135 single-point flights because no cockpit crews were available
judge barrington d. parker, who is hearing the orion-eastern case, continued the matter until next monday after granting a pilots union request for internal eastern documents on various eastern aircraft, including those that are to be leased to orion
eastern had refused to turn over the documents, claiming that they could be used by the pilots union to gain information about eastern's plans in event of a strike. parker directed that the documents be made available only to the union's three lawyers and two union members and that they not be copied
the simbrah association is being added to an agriculture department list of registered cattle breeds so owners can qualify for higher federal payments when animals are slaughtered under the department's brucellosis eradication program
brucellosis is a highly contagious disease, james w. glosser, acting administrator of the department's animal and plant health inspection service, said friday
our experience has shown that indemnities encourage owners to remove infected animals from their herds to prevent the spread of the disease,'' glosser said
brucellosis can be passed on to humans _ where it is known as undulant fever _ through raw milk from infected cows
simbrah cattle are a cross between simmental and brahman, the department said. approximately 2,200 u.s. producers own registered simbrah cattle
the indemnity rate for all dairy cattle, and registered beef cattle and bison is $250 per animal, while the payment for non-registered beef and bison is $50 per animal
officials said the new rule goes into effect on april 11. running, picking up in 9th graf pvs, throughout the</note>
republican sen. bob dole, scrambling to salvage his presidential campaign, challenged gop front-runner george bush on friday to show up for a live 30-minute television show dole has purchased for saturday night
earlier friday, as he campaigned around illinois, dole vowed to stay in the race at least through the state's primary on tuesday, though he said he would reassess his chances after that
dole, who pulled most of his tv ads off the air in illinois earlier this week, said he had bought television time on a chicago station and would broadcast live from a small college in galesburg, ill
he challenged vice president bush to join him there for a debate at knox college, which was the site of one of the famous lincoln-douglas debates
bush has declined dole's repeated challenges to a one-on-one debate. but dole said, ``in any event, i'll be there to discuss the issues. i dare george bush to have a debate with bob dole.''
bush is tentatively scheduled to be in galesburg saturday night to attend a gop dinner
earlier in the day, dole had joked with reporters that he might have a cardboard cutout of bush on the stage if the vice president wouldn't show up in person
we're hanging by our fingernails,'' dole said at an airport news conference in moline. ``we need to somehow capture the attention of the illinois voters.''
dole, campaigning across central and western illinois, denied reports that he and his aides had discussed the possibility of pulling out of the race. but he conceded there had been some discussion of another less drastic option
there was some talk about maybe just canceling a couple of days' events to heighten whatever we're going to do later,'' dole said at a stop in bloomington, where he spoke to illinois farm bureau leaders
dole said his deep staff cutbacks were ``just good management,'' made to save money and because most of the workers were no longer needed after super tuesday
campaign aides said dole also was buying television time to air ads on sunday
throughout the day, dole made it clear that his task in illinois, if he is to overtake bush, is to draw the vice president out on issues and to separate him from the good will that many republicans feel for president reagan
i'm sort of running against the ghost of ronald reagn,'' the senator said
in addition, dole said that bush's victories on tuesday had given him a big boost in polls
what we need to do is slow down this super tuesday momentum,'' dole said
one effort by dole is to continue to press bush to participate in one-on-one debates even though the vice president has declined
if we could just discuss the issues in one state ... i will win,'' dole said. ``it's pretty hard to slow down a freight train if you don't talk about the issues.''
one issue on which he has pressed bush is the vice president's involvement in the iran-contra affair, a subject that was back in the news friday as former national security adviser robert c. mcfarlane agreed to plead guilty to four misdemeanor charges that he withheld information from congress
it is going to revive that whole issue again and i've said from the start that it's not going to go away. that's why it should be addressed,'' dole said. bush ``is going to have all these things happening through the summer,'' he said
one uncertain element in dole's strategy is how illinois voters will react to the possibility that a bush victory in their state could effectively end the gop nominating race. dole maintains there are many voters who have yet to decide which candidate they will back
i know there are a lot of people, probably 20 percent, who are just now beginning to focus on who the candidates are,'' said dole. ``it's like last-minute christmas shoppers. some people don't even know what they're going to buy until the last 24 hours and then they buy whatever is left. we don't want that to happen.''
asked whether he would abandon the race if he loses next week, dole said, ``we will reassess after illinois. i am going to be very realistic about this.''
the government and bell helicopter textron signed agreements friday under which the fort worth, texas, company will pay $88 million to settle claims that it overcharged for military helicopter spare parts
the settlement, disclosed earlier in the week, is considered one of the largest ever in a defense contracting case
it resulted from inaccurate cost accounting information bell gave the government from october 1982 to october 1985, the justice department said in a statement
the justice department's civil division and the army each signed separate agreements with the company
during the course of the investigation, bell consistently maintained that there was no wrongdoing. and the u.s. attorney's office in fort worth said it notified bell on friday that the office has declined criminal prosecution in the case
that effectively closes our case,'' assistant u.s. attorney ron eddins said in fort worth. ``we did that because of all of the factors that were disclosed during the investigation. their coming forward and agreeing to work things out with the pentagon was a part of it too.''
eddins said the justice department's civil fraud division ``has also issued an agreement with them that accepts the payment and the administrative agreement to settle the civil issue. the case is closed there too.''
bell president l.m. horner said the settlement, which he described as ``encompassing issues well beyond those which were investigated, cleans the slate and will allow for the normalization of relations between bell and the army.''
under the settlement, bell will pay the government $69 million within the next 30 days. the government will also have its choice of about $11 million in spare parts inventory. additional provisions of the agreement make it worth somewhere in the neighborhood of $88 million, the pentagon's chief spokesman, dan howard, has said
bell will forgo claims to about $6 million worth of interest on contract progress payments withheld by the army and about $1.5 million in legal fees. offsetting that will be a $1.1 million payment by the army to bell to cover a separate contract that got sidelined in the dispute
maj. phil soucy, an army spokesman, has said most of the overcharges came as a result of an accounting system used in handling army contracts. bell switched to a computerized accounting and inventory system that had the effect, among other things, of accelerating the company's requests for army progress payments for work performed
bell agreed to implement a new accounting system that met the army's approval in october 1985
europe's ariane 3 rocket lifted off on schedule friday night for a mission to place french and u.s. communications satellites into orbit and reaffirm its role as the west's only active launcher
the rocket blasted off at 7:28 p.m. from this jungle space center on the northern coast of south america _ ariane's 21st launching and the first of eight planned for this year
andre payet, chief of mission, said no technical problems were reported and weather conditions were good for the launch of the rocket, owned by the european space agency
the launch was first scheduled for december but was delayed for extra tests after anomalies were detected in the oxygen and liquid hydrogen third-stage engine
we preferred to take the time to understand the problem,'' said frederic d'allest, president of arianespace, esa's commercial arm
third-stage engine failure was the cause of three of ariane's four failed launches _ in september 1982, september 1985 and may 1986. the last failure, the 18th launch, left the rocket grounded for more than a year
the other failed launch occurred in may 1980 because of a problem with the first-stage engine
ariane produced a perfect 20th launch nov. 21, 1987, but the west german television satellite it placed into orbit developed problems with its solar panels and is not fully operational
the 21st launch will thrust into orbit the american gte spacenet corp.'s fifth satellite, spacenet iii r-geostar r01. the satellite is aimed at increasing the company's wide-ranging telecommunications services in the united states and help set up a system of satellite communication with mobile units such as trucks, cars and trains
two transponders on spacenet iii purchased by the associated press are to provide the new york-based news cooperative with domestic satellite delivery services over the next 10 years. a satellite being used is nearing the end of its operational service
the french telecom ic, the third in a series of satellites owned by france telecom, the state-owned telecommunications system, is used for telephones, radio and television transmissions as well as military communications
the new satellite is to replace telecom 1-b, which broke down jan. 15
with the u.s. space shuttle grounded and titan 4 and delta rockets not yet competitive, ariane remains the only active launcher for commercial satellites in the west. however, arianespace is watching the return of the americans to the lucrative space market as well as competition from the soviet union, china and japan
including friday's payload, arianespace has 43 satellites on its order books worth $2.36 billion, according to the company
to keep up with the orders, the kourou space center has made two launch pads available
ariane's 21st launch is to be the first of eight this year, with nine launches each planned for 1989 and 1990, d'allest said earlier this week
the environmental protection agency said friday it had approved field tests in wisconsin for a genetically engineered bacterium designed to improve the ability of alfalfa to use nitrogen in the air as a fertilizer
the bacterium, rhizobium meliloti, grows naturally on alfalfa roots, and mutant forms have been used to enhance plant growth in the past
using the techniques of recombinant dna, biotechnica inc. of cambridge, mass. has re-inserted the genes responsible for nitrogen use _ nitrogen fixation _ back into the organism, giving it two copies of the genes
lab and greenhouse tests indicate this will enhance alfalfa yield, according to an epa announcement when the company applied for permission to test 13 months ago
epa has an active regulatory program for genetically engineered pesticides, but this bacterium is not a pesticide. it is the first genetic engineering case under epa's authority to regulate new chemicals, and the test will precede under approval of the company's ``premanufacture notice'' for a new chemical
the tests will be conducted in pepin county, wis., a county lying on the mississippi river about 20 miles southwest of eau claire
police chief jess ``doc'' hale was suspended friday after being charged with taking less than $200 from a drugstore cash register
hale, 47, was released on his own recognizance after pleading innocent to the misdemeanor charge. trial was set for may 24. he declined comment after the court appearance
pulaski county chief deputy prosecutor lloyd king said hale took money over the past several weeks from buice drug store, a popular coffee stop for police officers
the amount was not disclosed, but the misdemeanor charge means it was less than $200. buice drug store is owned by state rep. george wimberly
king said the prosecutor's office was tipped off by a resident of the county, but he would not elaborate. radio station karn, citing unidentified sources in the state police, said police secretly videotaped hale taking money
city manager tom dalton announced hale's suspension with pay
when i have sufficient information to determine whether the chief has violated the rules,'' dalton said, ``i will at that time make my decision as to whether or not to institute formal disciplinary action against the chief.''
hale earns $64,070 a year and also collects a pension of $18,766 from the police department, from which he retired as an assistant chief in 1982 after a 20-year career
he rejoined the force as chief 17 months ago after running the medicaid fraud division of the state attorney general's office
sen. paul simon, insisting he has ``as good a chance as anyone'' to become the democratic presidential nominee, campaigned friday for home-state support in next tuesday's illinois primary
simon sought the votes of educators and college students in his bid to beat illinois rival jesse jackson, his chief challenger in the state primary according to a new poll
we want to send a message to the nation from illinois,'' simon said in asking educators to help him win the primary. ``part of that message is that for people who need quality education, this administration has been out to lunch,'' he added
next, it was off to northwestern university in evanston where he drew applause from a crowd of about 1,000 students when he called for increasing grants and government loans to college students
saying again that he figures it will take more than one ballot for the party to settle on a white house nominee at the democratic national convention in atlanta in july, simon said at a north side pancake restaurant: ``i think i have as good a chance as anyone.''
a washington post-abc news poll published friday said simon and jackson were in a virtual dead heat in illinois at 38 percent and 33 percent, respectively, among 402 likely democratic voters, while massachusetts gov. michael dukakis was third at 16 percent. the difference between simon and jackson was within the poll's margin of error of plus or minus 8 percentage points
after being endorsed by the polish daily zgoda, a polish language newspaper, simon campaigned on friendly turf at the illinois education association's representative assembly meeting
simon, who serves on the senate labor and human resources committee's subcommittee on education, arts and humanities, noted that the educators' union had supported him in his successful 1984 bid to oust republican sen. charles percy against long odds
four years ago when i was running for the u.s. senate, there was not a single poll that showed paul simon winning. but the iea hung in there and didn't listen to the polls and, believe it or not, there was one final poll on a tuesday that showed paul simon winning,'' he said as the crowd applauded and cheered
he told the 750 union delegates and alternates what they wanted to hear. if elected president, he said, he would seek to raise teachers' salaries, improve preschool education programs and increase public school funding. he also called for a ``massive assault'' on illiteracy
i am the only candidate running for president who, either in state legislative service or in congressional service, has ever requested to be on the education committee,'' simon said
i mention that to show you i'm not just giving you another speech. i'm giving you a commitment to education that's been there for my whole lifetime,'' simon said
a powerful late-winter blizzard whitened the black hills of south dakota, with heavy snow and winds up to 65 mph barreling through parts of that state, colorado and nebraska on friday before moving east into minnesota
blizzard warnings extended from northeast colorado across the nebraska panhandle and northwest nebraska into much of south dakota. parts of interstate 80 in western nebraska were shut down
in south dakota, rapid city reported winds of up to 65 mph and heavy snow. nearby lead and deadwood had up to 3 feet of snow. sturgis had 20 inches, spearfish, 18, and custer and hill city 14
snow and strong winds also hammered the nebraska panhandle throughout the morning and afternoon. wind gusts of 40 to 50 mph reduced visibility to near zero. crawford received up to 16 inches of snow
the blizzard also blasted the northeast plains of colorado, where winds gusted to 50 mph at wellington, akron and fort morgan
wind-chill readings across much of north dakota, were from 10 below zero to 25 below. some interstates were closed
snow also continued to fall across much of wyoming, where rock springs received 15 inches, laramie, 11, and cheyenne, 7
the storm moved slowly northeastward into minnesota, where up to 3 inches of snow was measured north of bemidji. wind gusts of 49 mph were reported at duluth
elsewhere, cloudy skies prevailed across much of the great lakes, with some snow across upper michigan. the rest of the nation enjoying pleasant weather, with the southern plains and middle and lower mississippi valleys logging temperatures in the 60s and 70s. the atlantic coast states reported readings in the 50s and 60s
on the west coast, skies were mostly clear, except for fog along the pacific northwest coast. southern california had wind gusts to 40 mph
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 10 degrees at limestone, maine, to 88 at mcallen, texas
saturday's forecast called for the late-season storm system to bring widespread showers and thunderstorms from the lower ohio and western tennessee valleys into the lower mississippi valley and western georgia. blowing snow was likely from the middle missouri valley into parts of the great lakes. snow and sleet were forecast for central wisconsin, with rain across the lower great lakes and ohio valley and scattered snow in the northern plains and central rockies
high temperatures should be in the 20s, 30s or 40s across much of the nation, dipping into the teens across the northern plains into northern minnesota and reaching into the 50s and 60s from the pacific northwest through the southern rockies, northern texas, the middle mississippi, lower ohio and tennessee valleys into parts of the middle atlantic states. highs should hit the 70s in southern california and parts of texas across the lower mississippi valley and gulf coast region, the southern atlantic states and northern florida. southern texas and southern florida should see highs in the 80s. debate, subs 6th graf with 3 grafs, ``dole bought...</note>
republican bob dole tried to rescue a presidential candidacy that was ``hanging by our fingernails'' on friday and the democratic presidential race left behind gary hart, who acknowledged ``the people have decided'' against him
democrat jesse jackson continued to roll with a narrow victory over michael dukakis in alaska's precinct caucuses. he looked for further encouragement in saturday's caucuses in south carolina, his native state, and in tuesday's primary in illinois, his adopted state
the democratic sideshow in south carolina aside, the presidential campaign in both parties focused on illinois. its primary posed an opportunity for george bush to slam the door on dole's presidential hopes, and could present the democrats with a clearer race _ or a more muddled one
trailing bush badly in delegates and in polls in that state, dole pulled more than $200,000 in television ads off the air and dismissed more than half his campaign staff
we're hanging by our fingernails,'' he said in moline. ``we need to somehow capture the attention of the illinois voters.''
dole bought a half hour of live television time on a chicago station for saturday night and said, ``i dare george bush to have a debate.''
he pointed to the plea to iran-contra charges friday by former white house aide robert c. mcfarlane and said the iran-contra issue won't go away for bush
dole said his campaign had between $1 million and $2 million on hand. but he was reeling from his 17-state collapse on super tuesday, when bush won 16 of those states and took a giant step toward the nomination
what we need is to slow down this super tuesday momentum,'' dole said
we will reassess after illinois,'' he added. ``i am going to be very realistic about this.''
the only other republican left in the race, following jack kemp's withdrawal a day earlier, was pat robertson. he campaigned in peoria, ill., and vowed, ``i'm in it until new orleans,'' where the republicans hold their convention
bush campaigned with illinois gov. james r. thompson at his side, telling farm leaders he hoped to ``win as big in the land of lincoln as i did in the land of cotton.''
he said he would decline a one-on-one confrontation with dole, recalling he tried that with ronald reagan in 1980 _ a meeting that probably cost bush the nomination
i may be older, but i'm a lot smarter now, too,'' he said
hart ended his democratic campaign for a second time, flanked by family members at a denver announcement
i got a fair hearing and the people have decided and now i should not go forward,'' he declared
hart's exit contained only a trace of the defiance that marked his initial departure last may
once the prohibitive front-runner for his party's nomination, hart dropped out the first time amid disclosures of his relationship with miami model donna rice. he returned to the race in december, but he failed to win a single delegate and never reached double-digit percentages in the primaries
sen. albert gore jr. continued his attacks on dukakis, saying the massachusetts governor's lack of experience in foreign policy means he'd be ``a president who needs on-the-job training.''
his complete lack of experience in foreign policy is, i think, a major issue at a time when the next president must be prepared to seize the opportunities for a new relationship with the soviets,'' gore said
dukakis said he hopes to get a share of illinois' delegates and demonstrate ``i can appeal to people all over the country.''
dukakis began airing a new commercial that spoke to the possibility of a brokered convention being talked up by paul simon's campaign. ``some people would like to turn back the clock, to go back to the days when the voters didn't really pick their presidential nominee. they say you must turn over that power to them, to use at a brokered convention,'' the narrator intones
new york gov. mario cuomo also chimed in, saying democrats should get behind the candidate with the most delegates at the end of the primaries, even if he doesn't have a majority
if mike dukakis has 41 percent, get everybody together in a room and say, `jesse, gore, gephardt, you came close, but mike's the candidate,''' cuomo said. ``let's pick the guy who's ahead after california.''
democrat richard gephardt campaigned in chicago and complained about two rivals who hit him with a barrage of negative television ads in the south
i feel like dukakis and gore have mugged me in an alley,'' he said. ``they are borrowing my rhetoric, but they don't have any substance behind it.''
jackson claimed 35 percent of the vote in a nonbinding preference poll at thursday night's alaska caucuses. dukakis was next with 31 percent
campaigning in south carolina, jackson urged blacks and whites to unite around him
it's not so much black versus white as it is barracudas eating us small fish,'' jackson said. ``they don't eat fish by color. they eat fish by size.'' affair</head> to cbs; picks up 13th graf pvs, earlier, in; subs 18th graf pvs, mcfarlane told, to include additional quote</note>
former presidential aide robert c. mcfarlane pleaded guilty friday to misdemeanor charges that he misled congress by assuring lawmakers the reagan administration was not helping arm nicaraguan rebels during a ban on u.s. military aid
president reagan's former national security adviser pleaded guilty to four counts of withholding information from congress when questioned about news reports that members of his staff, particularly lt. col. oliver l. north, were helping to raise money and ship arms to the contra rebels
mcfarlane, who agreed to cooperate fully with independent counsel lawrence e. walsh's investigation, could be sentenced to up to four years imprisonment and fined as much as $400,000 for the guilty pleas he entered before u.s. district judge aubrey e. robinson jr
robinson released mcfarlane on his own recognizance and did not schedule a sentencing date. mcfarlane was subdued and spoke in a soft voice when responding to questions posed by the judge
you understand that imprisonment could be consecutive?'' robinson said, referring to the option of making the four one-year terms concurrent or consecutive
i understand that,'' mcfarlane said without showing any emotion
the judge later asked, ``do you know any reason i should not accept the plea?''
no,'' mcfarlane said
mcfarlane played a major role in the iran-contra affair, even after he resigned as national security adviser in december 1985. the following may, he led a secret mission to tehran to open contact with so-called moderate iranians who were thought to hold influence with kidnappers of american hostages. he brought with him a cake and a bible signed by president reagan
mcfarlane attempted suicide in february 1987 by taking an overdose of a tranquilizer the day before he was scheduled to testify before a presidential commission investigating the affair
president reagan, leaving the white house friday afternoon for a helicopter trip to camp david, md., refused to comment on mcfarlane's plea
it's in the court,'' he shouted to reporters
north, who is expected to be indicted for his role in the iran-contra affair, was asked by cbs news about mcfarlane. ``i wouldn't comment about mr. mcfarlane,'' north said. ``but as i think i told you once before, this marine is never going to plead guilty to any charge and i'll fight this or any other allegations of misconduct forever.''
earlier, in an impromptu news conference following the hearing, walsh acknowledged that mcfarlane could have been charged with perjury, a felony that carries a five-year sentence for each charge
but walsh said he agreed to the misdemeanor plea because of the former national security adviser's willingness to cooperate with walsh's investigation and his ``undisguised expressions of remorse after the false testimony.''
he tried to correct his testimony and actually imposed injury upon himself in a fit of depression,'' walsh said of mcfarlane's suicide attempt
walsh called mcfarlane's guilty plea a ``very important'' development in his 14-month investigation. in the coming weeks, the investigation is expected to yield a round of indictments against north and others, including rear adm. john m. poindexter, who was mcfarlane's successor as national security adviser
it furthers the work of the office of independent counsel because he has agreed to cooperate fully with our office in the pursuit of the remainder of our investigation,'' walsh said
mcfarlane told reporters, ``i did indeed withhold information from the congress. i believe strongly that, throughout, my actions were motivated by what i believed to be in the foreign policy interest of the united states.''
after the iran-contra affair unraveled in late 1986, mcfarlane said ``i believed profoundly that it was my personal obligation to testify voluntarily and fully to those bodies formally established to investigate this matter.''
the charges involve statements that mcfarlane made in three 1985 letters to house committees and in testimony before the house foreign affairs committee on dec. 8, 1986, when he denied knowing about solicitations of donations to the contras from an unidentified foreign country
the charges involve assurances to congress that nsc staffers, specifically north, were not involved in private efforts to help the contras and that mcfarlane knew of no foreign donations to the rebels
mcfarlane admitted withholding information from the house permanent select committee on intelligence in letters he wrote on sept. 5, 1985, and on oct. 7, 1985, in response to queries about reports that his staff was secretly helping the contras in violation of the 1984 boland amendment's ban on direct or indirect military aid to the rebels
in the oct. 7 letter, mcfarlane wrote that ``lieutenant colonel north did not use his influence to facilitate the movement of supplies to the resistance.''
he further assured the panel in the letter that there was ``no official or unofficial relationship with any member of the nsc staff regarding fund-raising for the nicaraguan democratic opposition.''
this includes the alleged relationship with general singlaub,'' mcfarlane said
the letter was misleading, the charge said, because mcfarlane knew that north ``had used his influence to facilitate the movement of certain supplies to the contras'' and he knew that ``a member of the nsc staff had had contact with retired maj. gen. john k. singlaub regarding fund-raising for the contras.''
in the sept. 5 letter, mcfarlane told the panel ``i can state with deep personal conviction that at no time did i or any member of the national security council staff violate the letter or the spirit of the law.''
we did not solicit funds or other support for military or paramilitary activities either from americans or third parties,'' he wrote
he made a similar assurance in a sept. 12, 1985, letter to former rep. michael barnes, d-md., who then headed the house foreign affairs subcommittee on western hemisphere affairs
the fourth charge relates to dec. 8, 1986, testimony in which mcfarlane told the house foreign affairs committee that he was not aware of any third country or citizens of a foreign nation helping the contras
the concrete character of that is beyond my ken,'' mcfarlane told the committee
the charge noted that mcfarlane was withholding the fact he was aware that citizens of the unidentified country had been donating millions of dollars to the contras. mcfarlane also withheld the fact that he had provided a representative of the country with the number of a secret bank account where the funds could be deposited, the charge said
mcfarlane told the congressional iran-contra committees that as early as may of 1984, he had met with the ambassador from what was called country 2, which later was learned to be bandar bin sultan of saudi arabia
the ambassador offered to provide $1 million a month to sustain the contras at a time their money was running out. mcfarlane told the panels he had not solicited the money, but that it had been offered as a gift after he bemoaned the likelihood of the reagan administration winning additional contra support from congress. u 14th `six of'</note>
it was 50 years friday that the nazis annexed this country. austrians honored the dead and demonstrated against president kurt waldheim, who was made a silent spectator by his questionable wartime past
conservative and socialist politicans emphasized that some austrians committed atrocities in the nazi era, challenging the long-held view that the nation was a victim of the nazis. huge crowds cheered adolf hitler's troops when they marched into his homeland march 11, 1938
a minute of silence drew little response friday on the streets of vienna and few people turned out in the early morning to watch political leaders lay wreaths at monuments to fallen soldiers and victims of the nazis
shops, businesses and schools were open
about 300 protesters gathered outside the presidential offices in the imperial hofburg palace, demanding that waldheim resign, and dozens vowed to hold a three-day vigil. waldheim has said he will not leave office until his term expires in 1992
at a memorial ceremony in the hofburg, foreign minister alois mock praised waldheim as having given austria ``prestige in the world'' in his decade as u.n. secretary-general, which ended in 1982
mock heads the conservative people's party, which backed waldheim for president in 1986. he was the only official to mention him directly at friday's ceremonies marking the annexation, or anschluss
waldheim was forced to cancel a speech at the ceremony because of unresolved questions about whether he committed war crimes while serving as a german army lieutanant in the balkans in 1942-45. some prominent austrians had said they would not attend if he spoke
franz vranitzky, the socialist chancellor, told a special cabinet session austrians must ``recognize the fact of historical guilt (and) draw lessons from the past failures of society.''
he dismissed the idea that austria was just a victim of the nazis
many austrians unwillingly donned german uniforms, he said, but others ``did not see a shameful coercion in this, but a simple test of strength in which _ for the most varied reasons _ they fulfilled their assigned duties.''
addressing about 900 students later, he urged young austrians not to ``make blanket accusations against an older generation or to reproach them ... after the fact with moral mistakes, blindness, bias and a lack of will to defend themselves.''
he said one of the terrible aspects of nazism was that it arose in countries that regarded themselves as cradles of culture and guarantors of western traditions
six of the seven parliamentary deputies of the small greens party walked out as soon as waldheim entered a special session of parliament. the greens invited austrians to join them in marking the anniversary at the site of a former concentration camp
in a leaflet, they said they boycotted the parliamentary ceremony because waldheim was there
on this particular day, the presence ... of a guest who `like hundreds of thousands of others only did his duty,' is not representative of the austria we want to remember,'' the leaflet said
the flier was referring to waldheim's repeated declarations that he was only doing his duty during the war
waldheim kept his war past a secret until march 1986, when it surfaced during his presidential campaign. a panel of historians concluded last month that waldheim was in close proximity to nazi war crimes but did nothing to prevent them
the report left open the question of waldheim's guilt or innocence in atrocities, and waldheim has always denied wrongdoing, but he has come under increased pressure to resign
dozens of anti-waldheim protesters chanted ``we do not accept waldheim, resistance is our duty!'' as survivors of nazi concentration camps and resistance fighters met on the square where the feared gestapo had its vienna headquarters
speaking in front of a monument to the victims of nazism, the socialist minister of social affairs, alfred dallinger, stressed that ``not only those who can be clearly identified as perpetrators were guilty.''
guilt was also shared by the many who allowed what was carried out by others: those who ran along, who concurred, who adapted themselves or looked away,'' he said, to loud applause
