the new york post will add some panache to its blue-collar image built on sex and crime, the tabloid's new publisher promised friday
we don't want to emasculate the new york post,'' peter o. price told the city club, a civic group. but he added: ``our challenge is to make the new york post noticed for the right reasons and not for the wrong reasons.''
the improved post, he said, will aim for depth in its writing, a manhattan focus, an even beefier sports section and more positive stories about education and race relations. it might also launch a sunday edition, he said
the post, the nation's oldest continuously published daily newspaper, officially became the property of developer peter kalikow on monday
australian-born newspaper baron rupert murdoch, who had owned it since 1976, sold the money-losing tabloid to comply with federal regulations barring ownership of a tv station and a newspaper in the same city. murdoch owns wnyw
murdoch's post was loud, lively and controversial. his british tabloid style relied heavily upon sex, crime and violence,'' price said. ``many advertisers ... refused to place ads in the newspaper, which they considered out of step with the image they were trying to portray.''
price said the emphasis on what some regard as ``terribly lurid things'' is ``perhaps not so bad as people may think.''
the pulse of journalism in the new york post is that sense of the city, that savvy, provocative, bold quality that's very often talked about pejoratively because of rupert murdoch,'' he said
it very often gets people upset. but it certainly does not go unnoticed. our challenge is to make the new york post noticed for the right reasons and not for the wrong reasons.''
kalikow paid $37.6 million for the paper, which has been losing money and circulation for years. it was founded in 1801 by alexander hamilton
kalikow acquired the post only after the paper's 10 unions agreed to a $22 million package of concessions, including a last-minute gift of $3 million from murdoch
the canadian mortgage and housing corp. has refused to revise building codes that have effectively barred american manufactured plywood from being used in canada, the commerce department said friday
a change in the canadian building codes is a key part of the plywood provisions in the proposed u.s.-canada free trade agreement and rep. ron wyden, d-ore, said that congress will have to get tough with the canadians in writing provisions to implement the agreement
rep. don bonker, d-wash., said he was disappointed in the canadian decision and that while he thought the overall free trade agreement was a ``excellent package, on this provision our negotiators got taken to the cleaners.''
claire buchanan, a commerce department spokeswoman, declined comment but said the decision was under review
the reagan administration had linked the elimination of plywood tariffs on both sides of the border to a revision in construction regulations by the cmhc, a government-controlled mortgage authority
canadians insist american plywood is not sturdy enough to withstand the harsh climate of canada, a claim officials of the american plywood industry say is unfounded
rep. peter defazio, d-ore., called the canadian refusal ``protectionism plain and simple.''
if the administration gives into this, they are just confirming it will be one-way free trade and that will be a disaster for the northwest plywood industry,'' defazio said
while construction sponsored by chmc accounts for only 10 percent of canada's construction plywood market, administration officials had hoped it would be a ``foot in the door'' for american plywood manufacturers and that changes would eventually be made in other building codes that have restricted u.s. imports
the door got slammed today,'' wyden said. ``this represents a major inequity in the free trade agreement and it is just more fodder for our position that we need tough enabling legislation.''
oregon is the top plywood producing state in the nation
wyden, defazio and other northwest congressmen, at a house subcommittee hearing earlier this week, had warned that the free trade agreement would do little to open the canadian market to american-maufactured plywood while at the same time it would give canadian plywood manufactuers unrestricted access to american markets
the agreement calls for the total elimination of the 20 percent u.s. tariff on canadian plywood and the 15 percent canadian tariff on u.s. plywood over 10 years
wyden and others have suggested that a provision be inserted in the treaty's implementing language that would call for a review of american access to the canadian market before u.s. tariffs are totally eliminated
it looks like that's the way we will have to go,'' wyden said. be scattered on cricket field; picks up 4th graf pvs, ``charles, his ...inserts 3 grafs after 16th: ``at this point... with charles going to windsor.</note>
prince charles flew home friday with the body of a friend who was killed by a swiss avalanche that nearly engulfed the future king as it roared down a mountain in a ``terrifying matter of seconds.''
with maj. hugh lindsay's pregnant widow, sarah, the prince watched as six soldiers from his dead friend's royal lancers regiment bore the flag-draped coffin from the red and white jet of the queen's flight
the 39-year-old heir to the throne was praised for helping save the life of another skier in his party but called foolhardy for skiing perilous slopes off the main trails of the klosters resort
a private funeral service in devon was being arranged for lindsay, but no date was announced. independent television news reported that lindsay, an avid cricket player, had said he wanted his ashes to be scattered on the cricket ground in his home town of budleigh salterton
charles, his wife, princess diana, and sister-in-law, sarah, the duchess of york, all dressed in black, walked under leaden skies from the jet at northolt air base near london
they were met by mrs. lindsay, 34, a buckingham palace press officer who had helped answer inquiries about thursday's accident before discovering her husband had died
she and lindsay, also 34, were married last summer and she expects a baby in may. he was a former aide to queen elizabeth ii, the prince's mother
in a handwritten statement read to reporters at the zurich airport after the royal party left, charles said he and five companions were skiing ``at our risk and we all accepted ... that mountains have to be treated with the greatest respect and not treated lightly.''
when the avalanche started ``with a trememdous roaring'' he and three others skied out of its path, charles said
then, ``to my horror, maj. hugh lindsay and mrs. palmer-tomkinson just failed to ski clear and were swept away in a whirling maelstrom as the whole mountainside seemed to hurtle past us to the valley below. it was all over in a terrifying matter of seconds.''
he described helping dig patricia palmer-tomkinson out of the snow with a shovel, then with his hands. both of her legs were broken and she is hospitalized in switzerland
the royal party cut the skiiing holiday short. it began tuesday and ended tragically at 2:45 p.m. thursday when the avalanche hurtled down the mountain toward charles; mrs. palmer-tomkinson; her husband, charles; lindsay; swiss guide bruno sprecher; and a swiss policeman
they were skiing off the main track between the treacherous gotschnawang and drostobel trails at an altitude of about 5,800 feet when the snowslide began about 300 feet above them. officials had warned of avalanche danger at 5,200 feet and higher
herr sprecher acted with incredible speed and total professionalism,'' the prince said. ``he skied down as fast as possible, having told the swiss policeman to radio for assistance.''
sprecher located mrs. palmer-tomkinson by a beeper on her body
mr. palmer-tomkinson and i skied down and just arrived as herr sprecher had reached mrs. palmer-tomkinson's head,'' the statement said. ``he gave her mouth-to-mouth resuscitation and revived her. he gave me the shovel to dig her out and i tried using my hands as well
at this point i sat with mrs. palmer-tomkinson while he (sprecher) quickly went to try and locate maj. lindsay. he found him about 15 yards above mrs. palmer-tomkinson, but tragically he had been killed outright during the fall.''
mrs. lindsay left the northolt base with her father. she was carrying a bag apparently containing some of her husband's belongings that the duchess of york had given to her
prince charles departed for windsor castle, 20 miles away, to see the queen and diana and the duchess of york went to kensington palace
thereafter their movements for the weekend are private,'' buckingham palace said
the accident highlighted the sometimes risky behavior of britain's royals
hours before the avalanche, the duchess of york, 28 and four months pregnant, took a bad fall skiing
that night, the royal navy ship on which her husband, prince andrew, is serving lost a helicopter with two crewmen off portugal. andrew, younger brother of charles, was not involved but he is a helicopter pilot
the avalanche was the worst accident for the royal family since prince william of gloucester, a cousin of the queen, died in a crash during an air race in 1972
newspapers clamored on friday for charles and other members of the royal family to give up dangerous pursuits
why was he there?'' the tabloid sun asked. ``charles has consistently risked his life by going on increasingly deadly slopes.''
charles is an ardent polo player who has taken many falls, and had a near-collision while flying a plane. on his first parachute jump he snarled the rigging and fell several thousand feet before untangling it
the police department rolled out its fabled battering ram after a two-year absence to break into two fortified houses where crack allegedly was being sold
civil-rights lawyers who in 1986 forced police to garage the ram expressed satisfaction with the way the use of the armored vehicle was authorized under new guidelines but promised to keep a close watch on future deployments
in a thursday night raid, police used the vehicle with a 14-foot metal pole to smash into a house in south central los angeles. officers arrested five suspected drug dealers and seized drugs, weapons and hundreds of dollars in cash
police also raided four other houses without the ram in the same operation and took more than 25 people taken into custody
on wednesday night, police seized about $10,000 worth of cocaine and about $500 in marijuana after ramming into another south central house where rock cocaine, a crystalline form of the drug also called crack, allegedly was being sold
it was the most heavily fortified rock house we've seen in a couple of years,'' said police spokesman cmdr. william booth. the house was reinforced with gun turrets, metal bars and steel mesh, he said
police chief daryl gates, who arrived after the thursday night raid, pointed out the security measures used by the suspected drug dealers
see how the bolts come all the way through?'' gates said, pointing to a steel-barred window. ``there's no way you can pull those bars off. you need a ram.''
police said they had not used the ram in drug raids since february 1986. they wheeled it out in october when an armed man barricaded himself in a house, but did not use it
joan howarth, an attorney for the american civil liberties union who had challenged the police department's use of the ram and forced its suspension, said she was satisfied with the way it was used
the judge told the lapd it could not use the ram until they did a surveillance of the locale to make sure there were no children present,'' she said
ms. howarth had represented a woman whose house was the first target of the ram, in 1985. the ram burst into a room only moments after the woman's 5-year-old son and two other children left it
as a result of that case, the state supreme court ruled that police must get a judge's certification and a search warrant before using the ram, a ruling the u.s. supreme court upheld in october
booth said obtaining judicial approval for use of the ram this week was not difficult
we just don't run up and use it. part of our tactics is to make a purchase just minutes before entering,'' which enables undercover officers to look inside the house, he said
the ram has become a featured part of tv shows and films. in last summer's ``dragnet'' movie, it was used to raid a suspected drug factory that turned out to be a dairy processing plant. up 7th graf pvs, the letter ...</note>
the united nations issued a strong protest at the u.s. decision friday to go ahead with closing the palestine liberation organization's observer mission
the plo called it a ``stab in the back'' to the middle east peace process
u.s. ambassador herbert okun informed secretary-general javier perez de cuellar of the justice department decision friday morning, said u.n. spokesman francois giuliani
he said perez de cuellar ``strongly protested this violation of the headquarters agreement,'' the 1947 treaty under which new york became home to the united nations
the u.s. state department also has said closing the plo mission would violate the pact, and even america's closest allies have denounced the closure. giuliani said perez de cuellar's legal staff is studying several options. he refused to elaborate, but one possibility would be a legal challenge when the justice department seeks a court order closing the mission
zehdi labib terzi, the plo's united nations observer, said the plo would not challenge the justice department move in court
we will not go into american court. we will have nothing to do with american courts,'' he told reporters after meeting with u.n. legal advisers. ``this is a matter between the united states and the united nations.''
he said the plo would ask arab nations to request a meeting of the general assembly to consider whether u.n. headquarters should remain in new york
calling the u.s. decision a ``stab in the back'' to mideast peace efforts, terzi asked, ``how could the united states really look like a peace broker when they want to throw out the representative of the palestinian people, which is the principle party to the conflict?''
the letter okun handed perez de cuellar said the justice department will initiate legal action to close the mission around march 21. it said the united states will not try to shut the offices until the litigation ends
the mission is located in a four-story townhouse the plo owns on manhattan's fashionable upper east side
the united nations released copies of okun's letter at a briefing
the united states has refused binding arbitration of the dispute, its worst with united nations
at a special meeting last week, the 159-nation general assembly asked the world court in the hague to rule on whether the united states must agree to arbitration. arguments before the court are set for april 11
congress passed an anti-terrorism law in december ordering the mission closed by march 21
u.n. officials and many diplomats regard the threat to the plo mission as a challenge to the independence of the united nations
it's a very serious development,'' said norwegian ambassador tom eric vraalsen. ``it goes beyond the plo because it violates the headquarters agreement.''
several arab diplomats have suggested moving the general assembly to geneva if the mission is shuttered. other diplomats say western nations probably would block such a step
last year, the state department closed down the only other plo office in the united states, a washington information office, in an attempt to head off legislation to close the u.n. mission
the united states and israel consider the plo a terrorist organization. the united nations recognizes it as the only legitimate representative for palestinians. 03-11 0853</first> crash</head> update with comment by ntsb chemist. inserts 3 grafs after 15th graf bgng: schwartz said ... to update with comment from pilot's employer. picks up 16th graf pvs bgng: the air ..., editing to tighten.</note>
the pilot of the continental express commuter plane that crashed near durango, colo. in january, killing nine people, had traces of cocaine in his urine and evidence of the drug's by-products in his blood, the national transportation safety board said friday
it appeared to be the first such accident involving u.s. commercial airlines in which evidence of drug use by the pilots had been found, aviation authorities said
the board did not characterize the finding as a cause of the accident or indicate whether the pilot might have been impaired. investigators have not determined whether the pilot or co-pilot was flying the airplane at the time of the accident
nine people, including both crew members, perished in the jan. 19 crash. the eight survivors were rescued after one of them, peter schauer, trudged 1{ miles over a snowy mountainside to a house
dr. merrit m. birky, an ntsb chemist, said the cocaine found in the pilot's body ``is a small amount,'' but he declined to comment further
dr. sorell l. schwartz, a pharmacology professor at georgetown university, said that based on the amounts of the traces found, the pilot was not under the influence of cocaine at the time of the accident
schwartz also said it was unlikely that a habitual user of the drug would feel any lingering effects from the amounts of cocaine detected in the pilot's body
there can be impairments,'' he said. ``there can be impaired mental function, but that's not usual.''
the potential impairments could include a sense of well-being, he said
safety board spokesman alan pollock declined to characterize the findings
this investigation continues, and has quite a long way to go,'' he said. ``we don't expect to find a probable cause for a number of months.''
he noted that investigators have not determined whether the pilot, steven s. silver, 36, of denver, was operating the twin-engine turboprop aircraft when it plummeted into a mountainous part of southeastern colorado about 10 miles east of durango
test results on the co-pilot, ralph harvey, 42, of denver, are expected within the next two weeks, pollock said
the tests showed that silver's blood contained 22 nanograms per milliliter of benzoylecgonine, a by-product of the body's breakdown of cocaine. a nanogram is one-billionth of a gram
silver's urine contained the same amount of cocaine, and 1,800 nanograms per milliliter of the by-product. no other drugs were detected
schwartz said cocaine leaves the body quite quickly, with half of it being removed every 45 minutes. he said that based on the information, he could not estimate how much cocaine had been used or when
silver was an employee of trans-colorado airlines inc. of colorado springs, which leases planes and crews to rocky mountain airways, a continental airlines subsidiary that operates in colorado as continental express
bill white, a denver attorney speaking for trans-colorado, said the company was ``obviously surprised. we're concerned.'' white said he did not know how long silver had been a pilot for trans-colorado
there is certainly no way the company would condone anything like that (cocaine use),'' he said. ``if there had been any indication, he (silver) would not have been on the payroll. it's not the type of thing you do more than one time and get another chance.''
the air line pilots association said it was ``deeply disturbed'' by the report and added that ``this would be the first instance where drug use by a pilot was shown to be the cause of an accident at a u.s.-scheduled airline.''
the association, which represents the pilots of the nation's major airlines, said, however, the report ``leaves unanswered more questions that it resolves.''
before we draw any conclusions, we must determine the accuracy of the report, eliminate the possibility of a false positive reading, determine the quantity and recency of the dosage, determine whether the pilot was actually impaired at the time of the accident, and then demonstrate that the impairment, if any, played a role in the accident,'' said alpa president henry duffy
george james, president of airline economics inc., a washington consulting firm to the airline industry, said he was not aware of another commercial airline accident in which drug use had been involved
just thursday, the department of transportation proposed a drug testing program for more than a half million airline employees
in a statement released by his office, transportation secretary james burnley called the incident ``a tragic reminder that not even commercial aviation is exempt from the drug abuse problem which plagues our society.''
the fairchild-swearingen metroliner crashed at about 7:30 p.m. in light snow as it was approaching laplata county airport in durango. the flight originated in denver
wyoming on friday became the last state to raise its drinking age to 21
gov. mike sullivan signed into law a bill raising the age from 19 effective july 1
when this becomes effective, we will no longer be an island,'' he said. ``it is in the best interests of the state, the country and, foremost, in the best interests of the young people of this state.''
the signing marks the end of several years of debate on the issue in the legislature, which has been unable to pass such legislation largely because of arguments that wyoming should not give in to ``federal blackmail.''
wyoming stood to lose $8.2 million in federal highway funds immediately if the increase were not in place in july
the government would continue to withhold funds until the state adopted the increase, which was called for in a 1984 federal law
albert gore jr., calling himself the candidate with campaign momentum that will eventually carry him to the presidency, said friday he expects to do extremely well in south carolina's democratic caucuses saturday
the tennessee senator, campaigning in the state's largest cities on caucus eve, told a crowd of a few hundred supporters at the statehouse that his strong super tuesday showing, when he won six of the 21 democratic events, surprised everyone
i believe that momentum is going to continue right through the convention in atlanta and right through november,'' he said. ``i'm excited about the possibility of victory.''
gore is expected to finish a strong second to jesse jackson in the south carolina caucuses
asked what state in the north he could win to prove he is not just a southern regional favorite, gore refused to be specific, saying only that he figured he would do well in illinois and michigan
gore said he has been in south carolina more than any of the other candidates and his campaign has bought the most television ads in the days before the caucus sessions
we have worked very hard in this state and i think we have an opportunity to extremely well here,'' gore said
gore noted that he supported legislation to restrict the growth of textile imports. such imports have caused plant closings and job losses in the state's largest industry
current textile trade agreements are being ``brazenly violated,'' gore said, adding that as president he would be sure that agreements are enforced
in the upstate friday, gore spoke to textile employees in lyman where he said the reagan administration is aiding the wealthy in the hope that others will eventually benefit
rather than asking what's best for those who are already well off, i want to ask what is best for the man and the woman who work in the textile mills, who work in the apparel industry, the person who is behind the typewriter, the small businessperson, the small farmer, and the person at the grass roots,'' he said. affair</head> with mcfarlane sidestepping issue of pardon. picks up 21st graf pvs bgng: the charges ...</note>
former presidential aide robert c. mcfarlane pleaded guilty friday to misdemeanor charges that he misled congress by assuring lawmakers the reagan administration was not helping arm nicaraguan rebels during a ban on u.s. military aid
president reagan's former national security adviser pleaded guilty to four counts of withholding information from congress when questioned about news reports that members of his staff, particularly lt. col. oliver l. north, were helping to raise money and ship arms to the contra rebels
mcfarlane, who agreed to cooperate fully with independent counsel lawrence e. walsh's investigation, could be sentenced to up to four years imprisonment and fined as much as $400,000 for the guilty pleas he entered before u.s. district judge aubrey e. robinson jr
robinson released mcfarlane on his own recognizance and did not schedule a sentencing date. mcfarlane was subdued and spoke in a soft voice when responding to questions posed by the judge
you understand that imprisonment could be consecutive?'' robinson said, referring to the option of making the four one-year terms concurrent or consecutive
i understand that,'' mcfarlane said without showing any emotion
the judge later asked, ``do you know any reason i should not accept the plea?''
no,'' mcfarlane said
mcfarlane played a major role in the iran-contra affair, even after he resigned as national security adviser in december 1985. the following may, he led a secret mission to tehran to open contact with so-called moderate iranians who were thought to hold influence with kidnappers of american hostages. he brought with him a cake and a bible signed by president reagan
mcfarlane attempted suicide in february 1987 by taking an overdose of a tranquilizer the day before he was scheduled to testify before a presidential commission investigating the affair
president reagan, leaving the white house friday afternoon for a helicopter trip to camp david, md., refused to comment on mcfarlane's plea
it's in the court,'' he shouted to reporters
north, who is expected to be indicted for his role in the iran-contra affair, was asked by cbs news about mcfarlane. ``i wouldn't comment about mr. mcfarlane,'' north said. ``but as i think i told you once before, this marine is never going to plead guilty to any charge and i'll fight this or any other allegations of misconduct forever.''
earlier, in an impromptu news conference following the hearing, walsh acknowledged that mcfarlane could have been charged with perjury, a felony that carries a five-year sentence for each charge
but walsh said he agreed to the misdemeanor plea because of the former national security adviser's willingness to cooperate with walsh's investigation and his ``undisguised expressions of remorse after the false testimony.''
he tried to correct his testimony and actually imposed injury upon himself in a fit of depression,'' walsh said of mcfarlane's suicide attempt
walsh called mcfarlane's guilty plea a ``very important'' development in his 14-month investigation. in the coming weeks, the investigation is expected to yield a round of indictments against north and others, including rear adm. john m. poindexter, who was mcfarlane's successor as national security adviser
it furthers the work of the office of independent counsel because he has agreed to cooperate fully with our office in the pursuit of the remainder of our investigation,'' walsh said
mcfarlane told reporters, ``i did indeed withhold information from the congress. i believe strongly that, throughout, my actions were motivated by what i believed to be in the foreign policy interest of the united states.''
after the iran-contra affair unraveled in late 1986, mcfarlane said ``i believed profoundly that it was my personal obligation to testify voluntarily and fully to those bodies formally established to investigate this matter.''
in an interview later with nbc news, mcfarlane sidestepped a question as to whether he thought president reagan might pardon him
that's not for me _ and i don't think it ought to be for the american people _ the issue. i guess that's really my central concern (is) ... why this really happened, and to see if we can't correct the way we do business between the president and the congress so that this kind of thing doesn't happen again,'' mcfarlane said
the charges involve statements that mcfarlane made in three 1985 letters to house committees and in testimony before the house foreign affairs committee on dec. 8, 1986, when he denied knowing about solicitations of donations to the contras from an unidentified foreign country
the charges involve assurances to congress that nsc staffers, specifically north, were not involved in private efforts to help the contras and that mcfarlane knew of no foreign donations to the rebels
mcfarlane admitted withholding information from the house permanent select committee on intelligence in letters he wrote on sept. 5, 1985, and on oct. 7, 1985, in response to queries about reports that his staff was secretly helping the contras in violation of the 1984 boland amendment's ban on direct or indirect military aid to the rebels
in the oct. 7 letter, mcfarlane wrote that ``lieutenant colonel north did not use his influence to facilitate the movement of supplies to the resistance.''
he further assured the panel in the letter that there was ``no official or unofficial relationship with any member of the nsc staff regarding fund-raising for the nicaraguan democratic opposition.''
this includes the alleged relationship with general singlaub,'' mcfarlane said
the letter was misleading, the charge said, because mcfarlane knew that north ``had used his influence to facilitate the movement of certain supplies to the contras'' and he knew that ``a member of the nsc staff had had contact with retired maj. gen. john k. singlaub regarding fund-raising for the contras.''
in the sept. 5 letter, mcfarlane told the panel ``i can state with deep personal conviction that at no time did i or any member of the national security council staff violate the letter or the spirit of the law.''
we did not solicit funds or other support for military or paramilitary activities either from americans or third parties,'' he wrote
he made a similar assurance in a sept. 12, 1985, letter to former rep. michael barnes, d-md., who then headed the house foreign affairs subcommittee on western hemisphere affairs
the fourth charge relates to dec. 8, 1986, testimony in which mcfarlane told the house foreign affairs committee that he was not aware of any third country or citizens of a foreign nation helping the contras
the concrete character of that is beyond my ken,'' mcfarlane told the committee
the charge noted that mcfarlane was withholding the fact he was aware that citizens of the unidentified country had been donating millions of dollars to the contras. mcfarlane also withheld the fact that he had provided a representative of the country with the number of a secret bank account where the funds could be deposited, the charge said
mcfarlane told the congressional iran-contra committees that as early as may of 1984, he had met with the ambassador from what was called country 2, which later was learned to be bandar bin sultan of saudi arabia
the ambassador offered to provide $1 million a month to sustain the contras at a time their money was running out. mcfarlane told the panels he had not solicited the money, but that it had been offered as a gift after he bemoaned the likelihood of the reagan administration winning additional contra support from congress. election</head>
president augusto pinochet on friday rejected an opposition demand to allow more than one candidate to run for president, saying it would create ``chaos and anarchy.''
pinochet, the army commander who has ruled chile since a 1973 coup, vowed to carry out the government's plan for a single candidate in a yes-or-no plebiscite sometime this year
pinochet made the remarks in an address to the nation to mark the seventh anniversary of the military-drafted constitution, which the opposition wants amended
in a pre-dawn attack before pinochet's speech, leftist guerrillas fired submachine guns and at least two rocket grenades at a suburban santiago police station, wounding two officers and three civilians, officials reported
they said several ``extremists'' in two cars carried out the attack and one of the injured policemen was in serious condition
officials reported three other guerrilla attacks early friday in the santiago area, but no casualties
another police station and a patrol car were fired at, they said, and at least four electric-power pylons were damaged by bombs, blacking out some neighborhoods
army patrols in combat gear were deployed in this capital city of 4.5 million people before pinochet's speech, which was broadcast on national radio and television
according to the constitution, the commanders in chief of the army, navy and air force and the head of the national police will pick a single presidential candidate for a yes-or-no vote
pinochet, 72, is allowed by the constitution to seek election for the 1989-97 term, and appears to be seeking the nomination. he led the coup that ousted the elected government of marxist president salvador allende in september 1973
no date has been set for the plebiscite, but government officials have said it will be in the second half of this year
in his 35-minute speech, pinochet made no reference to his candidacy but said the next president ``must identify himself'' with the constitution imposed by the military
if the government granted the opposition demand to amend the constitution and block the government's election plan, ``a situation of public unrest and serious uncertanties would follow,'' he said
according to the constitution, if voters reject the military candidate in the plebiscite this year, an open presidential election must be called in 1990 with pinochet remaining in power until then
several thousand people gathered in front of a government building in downtown santiago as pinochet, in a general's uniform, arrived to make his speech. some said they were government employees and had been ordered to go there
police said there were scattered scuffles in santiago between government supporters and dissidents after pinochet's speech. portrayed...</note>
the usually tame soviet media provided sensational coverage friday of the hijacking of an aeroflot jetliner by a family of jazz musicians, digging up details about the private lives of the air pirates
interrupted flight,'' read the headline of sovietskaya rossiya. ``combat aboard a plane,'' screamed the labor newspaper trud
the simeons throw off their mask'' proclaimed pravda, the official voice of the communist party, referring to the name of the jazz ensemble
nine people died in the attack, including five of the 11 hijackers
the reports included dirt on the musical family from siberia and described in detail how they were duped into thinking they had landed in finland
even under soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's campaign for glasnost, or openness, the reports offered a rare account of an act of terrorism in the soviet union
the hijackers were all members of the ovechkin family, a siberian jazz ensemble from irkutsk that went by the name ``seven simeons.''
armed with a bomb and shotguns, they boarded the leningrad-bound tupolev-154 in irkutsk, and after a refueling stop in kurgan demanded that they be taken to london, the newspapers said
but the pilot set the plane down on a small airfield near leningrad. five of the hijackers, including the ``hero-mother,'' described as the ringleader, three passengers and a stewardess were killed in an ensuing shootout
the newspapers covering the story didn't rely on dispatches from the official news agency tass; they assigned their own correspondents
trud said the group, which was named after a russian fairy tale about a large family of farmers, was a hit in irkutsk and was gaining popularity nationwide
the ensemble visited japan in november. their pictures appeared in the local press frequently and they were the subject of a documentary film
the group had been scheduled to play a concert march 4-6 in irkutsk, but canceled because one of the brothers was ill, according to trud. the real reason for the cancellation, the paper suggested, was that they were preparing to flee the country
at that time they were selling all their household goods,'' trud reported
pravda said the trip to japan swelled their heads
the boundless praise apparently made their heads spin; the ovechkins began to dream about the `good life' abroad,'' it said, without citing a source
it said the family members had everything going for them. they had jobs and profited nicely from a private farm plot. but pravda said there was a dark side
the mother, ninel ovechkin, continued to deal in vodka, even after her husband died a few years ago from excessive drinking
the media reports indicated that mrs. ovechkin, described as a plump, well-dressed woman of over 50, had at least 11 children
before setting out for the irkutsk airport, the ovechkins left a note on their apartment door saying they were going to another siberian city and would return friday, according to pravda
all members of the family but the eldest sister boarded the flight, trud said
they carried only hand baggage, mainly musical instruments, according to pravda. everything was searched except for the string bass, which wouldn't fit in the x-ray machine, pravda said. the ovechkins refused to allow the bass to be checked into the baggage compartment, and nothing suspicious was found in a visual inspection, pravda said
tass said thursday the weapons used in the hijacking had been smuggled aboard the plane in the instruments

the newspapers portrayed stewardess tamara zharkaya as a martyr who negotiated calmly with the hijackers, who were armed with 16-gauge, sawed-off shotguns

this girl took a tremendous responsibility upon herself,'' pravda said. ``she succeeded in psychological victory over the bandits.''
sovietskaya rossiya quoted pilot first class valentin kupriyanov as saying the crew decided to accept the demand because the hijackers were becoming dangerous
to avoid placing the passengers at risk, we decided to fulfill the demands of the bandits and fly abroad,'' kupriyanov recalled. ``the ground (flight controllers) approved our action. but the closer we got to leningrad, the clearer it became that we would not reach even nearby finnish or swedish airports.''
izvestia said the flight crew contacted the ground, and a plan was worked out to dupe the hijackers into thinking they were landing in finland
an assault team was waiting when the tu-154 touched down, media said
the attack was over in minutes. with possible asylum countries for noriega. picks up 9th graf pvs bgng: the administration ...</note>
president reagan imposed new sanctions friday against panama, trying to weaken military strongman manuel antonio noriega's grip on power and end ``the illegitimate noriega regime.''
in a written statement, reagan said, ``i believe that general noriega would best serve his country by complying with the instruction of president (eric arturo) delvalle to relinquish his post.''
delvalle, the civilian figurehead president regarded as the legitimate constitutional authority by the united states, has been in hiding since feb. 26 when he tried unsuccessfully to fire noriega as commander of the panama defense forces. noriega is under indictment in the united states on drug-smuggling and racketeering charges
reagan ordered that u.s. government payments due panama be put in escrow until constitutional rule is restored in panama. a $6.6 million payment is due next tuesday for operations relating to the panama canal
he also suspended trade preferences panama receives under a special system for third world countries and the caribbean basin initiative. secretary of state george p. shultz said $96 million worth of goods would be affected annually
in addition, reagan ordered stepped up scrutiny of panama by u.s. immigration and customs service officials ``to apprehend drug traffickers and money launderers.''
panamanian ambassador juan b. sosa told a news conference he was pleased with reagan's announcement. he said that by themselves sanctions will not be enough to bring down noriega but that this goal will be achieved when combined with the actions of the panamanian people
based on information he refused to disclose, sosa said he was ``very optimistic'' that noriega intends to depart panama shortly
abc news quoted diplomatic sources as saying the government of spain was prepared to offer asylum to noriega
the two countries most mentioned by opposition leaders as possible asylum sites are paraguay and the dominican republic. opposition leaders say they have sounded out the dominican republic and that noriega sent two military colleagues to paraguay this past week, possibly to discuss asylum prospects
the administration is trying to force noriega's ouster and weaken the military-dominated government by increasing the cash-squeeze in panama. measures already taken with u.s. support have caused a severe cash shortage, prompting the government to suspend many banking operations, crippling panama's economy
u.s. military and economic aid to panama was cut off last year following the initial popular uprisings against noriega in june. last week, the united states ruled that panama was not cooperating in efforts to control drug trafficking
under the finding, the united states was required to stop military and economic assistance _ which already had been done _ and to oppose panamanian requests for assistance in international lending institutions
reagan said noriega's resignation ``would contribute very substantially to reducing political tensions and set the stage for a prompt transition to democracy in panama
until such a time as democratic government is restored in panama, the u.s. cannot proceed on a business-as-usual basis,'' the president said. ``today, therefore, i have taken a number of steps against the illegitimate noriega regime that will contribute significantly to the goal of a democratic, stable and prosperous panama.''
underscoring reagan's use of the word ``illegitimate,'' shultz told a news conference, ``that's a very strong word
what we think should happen is that he should leave panama, and we want to see a return to civilian democratic rule, and we also expect to see the panamanian defense forces resume an honorable and proper role'' in a constitutional government
he said noriega ``has to get out of the way.''
shultz said there was no need to impose an additional sanction to cut off fees panama receives from alaskan oil shipments which are transferred to u.s. east coast ports through a panamanian pipeline. he said that money already has been frozen under a temporary restraining order from a u.s. court. a source speaking only on condition of an/nymity said later that the order was issued by a court in massachussetts and ran until friday
the first national bank of boston agreed to freeze activity on panamanian government accounts until the state department lifts sanctions against the nation, according to a settlement filed in u.s. district court there. the action stemmed from a civil suit filed earlier this week by sosa
a federal judge tuesday issued a temporary injunction against payments to any panamanian government agency from accounts at bank of boston and four florida-based banks. in addition, a restraining order was issued friday by a federal judge in new york against the bank of boston international, which holds a panama government clearing account
shultz accused noriega of trying to impose a military coup in panama by deposing delvalle
shultz said the u.s. actions will escalate panama's cash shortage. ``that does have some effect on the economy but it also has an effect ... on the immediate ability to manage things.''
he said the united states did not impose a broad trade embargo against panama because ``we don't want to punish the panamanian people.'' instead, he said, ``we're anxious to see general noriega get out of there.''
shultz added, ``we're trying to very carefully and deliberately but strongly take actions that are focused in on things that we think will make a difference.''
three men convicted in a scheme to create more than $350 million in bogus tax deductions for celebrities such as andy warhol, lorne green and sidney poitier drew sentences friday ranging from probation to two years in prison
irs officials believe the scheme was the largest tax-fraud case in u.s. history, said assitant u.s. attorney stuart abrams said late last year
the three promoters of the scheme were indicted in 1987 on charges of creating more than $1.3 billion in fraudulent losses and interest expenses while trading in treasury bill futures and other government securities
those losses generated bogus tax deductions for investors such as actor michael landon, former postmaster general preston r. tisch, tisch's brother, cbs president laurence a. tisch, the late lorne greene and tv producer norman lear
the investors are not accused of wrongdoing but will have to square accounts with the irs. they had expected to receive $4 in tax deductions for every $1 invested
charles agee atkins, 33, of amelia island plantation, fla., was sentenced by u.s. district judge morris lasker to two years in prison, four years' probation and 500 hours a year of community service
atkins is the son of former ashland oil co. chairman orin e. atkins
william hack, 62, of new york city was sentenced to four months in prison, four years, eight months' probation, and 1,000 hours a year in community service. he was fined $25,000
ernest grunebaum, 52, of chappaqua, n.y., was placed on probation for five years and ordered to do 400 hours of community service a year
the three were convicted in december of conspiring to defraud the internal revenue service; they could have received five years in prison on that count alone. atkins and hack were also convicted of numerous tax offenses
soviet citizens are engaged in ``heated discussions'' about whether a new criminal code now being written should retain capital punishment, tass said friday
in a report from riga, capital of latvia, the official soviet news agency said a final decision will be made after nationwide discussion. defendants sentenced to death in the soviet union are executed by firing squads
heated discussions are going on over the problem of capital punishment,'' tass said. ``some people insist that it should be repealed altogether, while others insist that it should be preserved for some special cases. the latter view predominates at the moment.''
the state-run media occasionally report executions of people convicted of such crimes as treason, murder and wide-scale bribery and corruption. the reports have not indicated how frequently the death penalty is imposed
in an interview with igor karpets, a latvian law professor, tass said the revised code will contain a new section covering punishments for ``crimes against peace and humanity.''
what behavior that section is intended to discourage was not clear, but one possibility is terrorism
soviet officials have referred frequently to the review of the 28-year-old criminal code, but have not said when the draft will be completed
twenty-one children forced to take refuge at two farms when a late-season blizzard waylaid their two school buses settled in for a second night of campstove meals and makeshift bedding friday
one of the farms had no electricity
the storm hit a little faster than we thought,'' said bus driver sharon grubbs, who had eight children with her when the storm bore down thursday afternoon, with heavy snow and winds up to 55 mph reducing visibility to zero
she said she and fellow driver linda barrett, who had 13 children on her bus, were in radio contact when they decided to find shelter rather than continue taking children home from the banner county school in harrisburg
ms. grubbs' crew landed at jack and karen holt's farm about 17 miles west of harrisburg. holt was snowed in elsewhere
the storm knocked out electricity at the farm late thursday and things were still chilly friday afternoon as the wind buffeted the farmhouse, said ms. grubbs
ms. grubbs and mrs. holt used a camping stove to cook meals as children huddled in their coats and under blankets. ``we're kind of hurting,'' said ms. grubbs. ``we've tried to fix one hot thing for every meal.''
the three boys and five girls, ages 7 to 13, have been playing games and listening to a battery-operated radio. they telephoned their parents to let them know they were safe, said ms. grubbs, a 10-year veteran bus driver
they've been super for us,'' she said. ``they've cooperated so well, but they ride the bus together every day.''
mrs. barrett and her 13 passengers found refuge at agnes wynne's farm, about 20 miles from harrisburg
mrs. wynne, who lives alone, said she was worried the food won't last. ``we've managed so far,'' she said. ``i guess we just take each day as it comes.''
menus so far have included chili and homemade noodles, mrs. barrett said. children were sleeping wall-to-wall in the two-bedroom farmhouse, said mrs. wynne
the children have been playing games and even doing homework, since many had their school and library books, mrs. barrett said
the kids have been really good,'' she said. ``we have one kindergartner and i don't think he's ever been away from home before.''
mrs. barrett said the youngest spoke with his parents on the phone and seemed to be coping well
mikhail s. gorbachev is to visit belgrade next week and sign a new guarantee of yugoslavia's independence, which the late president tito declared forcefully in 1948 by breaking with the soviet union
senior yugoslav officials said friday the declaration also appears to indicate the future course of soviet relations with other nations
gorbachev is scheduled to arrive monday and stay four days on the first official visit to this nonaligned communist country by a soviet leader since 1976
the new document will update previous declarations of 1955 and 1956 and ``further confirm principles of non-interference on the basis of equality and sovereignty,'' ilija djukic, the deputy foreign minister, told reporters
the late leonid i. brezhnev was the last kremlin leader to pay an official visit to yugoslavia, which broke with the soviet bloc over ideological issues in 1948 but maintained economic and political links
brezhnev attended tito's funeral in may 1980. tito had visited moscow in 1979
the declaration calls for ``non-interference of any kind in the internal matters of the two countries,'' a senior official said on condition of anonymity
he said the document also appears to represent a message about a general change in soviet policy under gorbachev
the declaration, to be made public during the visit, is said to call for cooperation with all nations and parties ``regardless of ideological differences'' and ``full and principled implementation of human rights in the whole world,'' the official said
