a truck driver barged into his estranged wife's home and blasted away inside with a shotgun friday, then jackknifed his rig on a busy freeway and held officers at bay for five hours, police said
ronald stone, 34, put down his double-barreled shotgun and surrendered at 7:20 a.m. after threatening to shoot anyone who approached, police said. no serious injuries were reported
stone, who had engaged police in an armed standoff a decade ago, was taken to the solano county jail and booked for investigation of attempted murder, said police chief gary tatum
the standoff closed interstate 80, the east-west artery between san francisco and sacramento, forcing miles of backed-up traffic onto bypass routes
stone's brother, jim, 38, of grass valley, said stone went to his wife's house, ``thinking everything was all right again. but she said, `get out of here.' that's when he wigged.''
stone's wife, jackie, said: ``i thought i was going to die.''
tatum said stone's wife had called police at 12:46 a.m. to report that her husband, from whom she had been separated for about a month, was at the door and appeared drunk. by the time officers arrived, he was gone
tatum said they received a second call about half an hour later from one of stone's children saying stone had returned
lt. gary mallory said stone kicked his way into the house where mrs. stone, their three young children, and mrs. stone's mother were staying. according to mallory, stone told the children, ``it's time for your mother and i to die.''
stone's mother-in-law and the children fled as stone went upstairs, found mrs. stone, who had been hiding, and attacked her, mallory said
she escaped, but stone fired four blasts from a 12-gauge shotgun inside the house, then two more from the porch after she ran outside, said mallory
when police arrived, stone threatened to kill himself, mallory said. then he leaped into his tractor-trailer and drove for an hour at speeds of up to 90 mph, with police pursuing
on the freeway, he jackknifed the empty truck, apparently on purpose, mallory said. police closed the freeway in both directions. stone sat in the vehicle with ``lots of ammunition,'' said mallory
police talked with stone, first by cb radio and then via a military-style field telephone tossed into the cab. ``he was distraught and felt as though his marriage was on the rocks. he no longer wanted to live,'' said tatum
stone gave up after five hours, firing a final blast out the truck window. he suffered minor powder burns but was otherwise unhurt
in 1978 in vacaville, stone held off police with a gun in a domestic dispute, tatum said. no shots were fired and no one was injured, according to police, who had no further details. relatives said he spent some time in jail as a result. electricity</head>
nine mile point 2 went into permanent commercial operation friday after 11 years of delays and cost overruns that have made it the nation's most expensive nuclear plant at a cost of $6.3 billion
the 1,080-megawatt plant, which was to have been completed in 1977 for $423 million, went on line at 3 p.m., providing electricity to more than 9 million new yorkers, said niagara mohawk power corp. spokesman william romano
it becomes the 105th nuclear plant operating commercially in the united states
i feel great,'' said niagara mohawk president william donlon. ``it's been a difficult period, it's been difficult on the company. but we did succeed. we did not fail where others have.''
nine mile 2, on the lake ontario shoreline north of oswego, will generate enough electricity to replace about 6 million to 8 million barrels of oil per year, said romano
besides niagara mohawk, four other utilities own the boiling-water reactor _ new york state electric and gas, long island lighting co., rochester gas &amp; electric corp., and central hudson gas &amp; electric corp
nine mile 2, which already has produced 250 million kilowatt hours of commercial electricity during testing, will be brought up to 100 percent operating capacity over the next several days, romano said
niagara mohawk was granted its construction permit for nine mile 2 in 1974, and began construction a year later. work was not completed until june 1986
niagara mohawk has attributed the cost overruns and delays on upgraded safety standards and plant design changes required by the nrc. critics have blamed mismanagement, inefficient procurement practices and union corruption
