a federal appeals court on friday upheld the reagan administration's refusal to release $180 million in revenue sharing funds that had been withheld two years ago under the gramm-rudman deficit-reduction law
the ruling, by a three-judge panel of the u.s. court of appeals for the district of columbia circuit, reverses a lower court which had ordered treasury secretary james a. baker iii to release the money
an attorney for three associations representing local governments said an appeal of the latest decision was ``virtually certain.''
my sense is the court did not fully comprehend the nature of our legal arguments. ... i think it's virtually certain we'll ask the court to reconsider its decision,'' said david c. vladek, a lawyer for the national association of counties, the national league of cities, the u.s. conference of mayors and 10 city and county governments
the dispute involves president reagan's feb. 1, 1986 order under the gramm-rudman law that set aside 4.3 percent of budget items, including $180 million from that year's $4.2 billion appropriation to the revenue sharing trust fund
the local governments argued that the law provided that sequestered 1986 budget money should remain in government trust funds and be paid out in 1987. they argued that even though congress had abolished revenue sharing after 1986, it intended that any money remaining in the trust fund be distributed
revenue sharing, begun under the nixon administration, provided nearly all local governments with unrestricted federal grants
u.s. district judge joyce hens green, in a ruling last july 28, found in favor of the local governments, and said baker had illegally transferred the revenue sharing money from the trust fund to the general fund
however, judge john r. gibson, who wrote the appeals panel's decision reversing judge green, said congress' intent with the gramm-rudman law was clearly to reduce the federal budget deficit
merely freezing (the monies in 1986) and resuscitating them (in 1987) would not result in any meaningful deficit reduction and could be characterized by critics to be a sham,'' said gibson, who was joined by judges patricia m. wald and david santelle
the result in this case may be harsh, but we believe it is consistent with congressional intent,'' wrote gibson, who was designated to the case from the u.s. court of appeals for the eighth circuit in st. louis
among the plaintiffs are new york city, kansas city, mo.; milwaukee county, wis., and cuyahoga county, ohio, which includes cleveland
the u.s. conference of mayors, at the time of the original district court decision last summer, had estimated that new york would receive $10 million; chicago, $2.6 million; los angeles, $2.2 million, and detroit $1.3 million of the money
other estimates were $606,000 for new orleans, $554,000 for indianapolis, $677,000 for washington, d.c., $440,000 for denver and $104,000 for des moines. estimates for other cities were not provided
