a british air force transport that made an emergency landing en route to the falkland islands left thursday after britain agreed it would return to ascension island, uruguayan officials said
the hercules c-130, carrying a crew of seven and a cargo of tires, cylinders of oxygen and munitions, left carrasco international airport outside montevideo at nearly two days after landing here, airport authorities said
the plane developed an oil leak while flying from its base on ascension to mount stanley in the falklands, british ambassador eric vines said
officials said the return to ascension was a condition set by uruguaya's foreign minister, luis barrios tassano, the former ambassador to argentina
argentine authorities claimed the landing was no accident but part of the controversial military manuevers that britain began monday in the falklands
argentina and britain fought in 1982 over sovereignty of the remote south atlantic islands. the 74-day war, won by britain, killed 712 argentines and 256 britons
argentine foreign minister dante caputo said the emergency landing was actually a test to find out how uruguay would react in case of actual need during a similar wartime situation
vines denied it
a kenyan millionaire developer and arms dealer was acquitted thursday of conspiring with five other africans, including a nephew of kenya's first president, to import 1,900 tons of marijuana into the united states
stephen mwangi, 49, was found innocent by a federal jury in its fifth day of deliberations. mwangi testified that he had come to this country with one of the accused men to speak to potential investors in a land deal
he was arrested in october with a ugandan and four other kenyans, including samuel muigai, 36, a former kenyan army officer. muigai's uncle was jomo kenyatta, kenya's first president
muigai and the four others have pleaded guilty and face terms of up to 20 years in prison at sentencing later this month
all six were arrested after being driven by a customs agent posing as a drug buyer to the port in gloucester city, where $1 million worth of marijuana was seized
the deal was arranged in long-distance calls between an informant and defendants other than mwangi. the calls were taped, along with a conversation in the car when the agent was driving the men from philadelphia to new jersey
assistant u.s. attorney james patton alleged that mwangi was a silent backer of the deal, which was ultimately to involve three tons of marijuana. spat' ^eds: leads with 16 grafs to update with ex-aide saying he advised mecham that alleged threat was a `little spat.' adds background on mormon beliefs. picks up 6th graf pvs, `asked by ...'; subs 17th graf pvs, `mecham faces ...' to conform.</head>
a former aide to gov. evan mecham said friday he looked into an alleged death threat and assured the governor it was a ``little spat'' between employees that would ``probably go away by itself.''
max hawkins, former department of administration chief, took the stand for the defense at mecham's senate trial, where the governor is accused among other things of trying to thwart an investigation of the alleged threat against a witness testifying before a grand jury investigating mecham's finances
hawkins said he confronted his employee, prison construction chief lee watkins, who was accused of making the threat against donna carlson, and got a different version of the story first reported by mecham aide peggy griffith
mrs. griffith has testified that watkins warned that her friend carlson should stop talking or she might ``go on a long boat ride.''
but hawkins said watkins told him: ``i told peggy she should tell donna she should keep her mouth shut and stop running down the governor in the press.' he said, `there are a lot of people out there who are excitable and some harm may come to her.'''
hawkins said that mrs. griffith told a smiliar story and that he did not think this constituted a threat
asked what he told the governor, hawkins said: ``it was a matter that would probably go away by itself. that it was a little spat, a frivolous matter, probably lee blowing off steam and peggy reacting to it and to leave it alone and it would go away.''
hawkins was fired by acting gov. rose mofford, who took office after the 63-year-old mecham was impeached by the house on feb. 5
mecham, who took office in january 1987, is the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades
besides being accused of ordering an aide not to cooperate with the state attorney general's investigation of the alleged threat, mecham was charged by the house with concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and loaning $80,000 in state money to his auto dealership
in earlier testimony friday, one of mecham's closest aides said the governor believed he was ``divinely guided'' in making executive decisions
sam steiger, a special assistant who was forced out of office by his own indictment on political extortion charges, also described a bitter battle between mecham and the state's attorney general, whom steiger blamed for mecham's downfall
i had the feeling that the governor did and does feel he is divinely guided,'' steiger said in response to a question by sen. john mawhinney, a republican like mecham
mawhinney asked if there was truth to rumors that mecham, a devout mormon, ``could and would make decisions on specific pieces of legislation through, he believed, some divine inspiration.''
yes, the governor believes his motives are divinely inspired,'' said steiger, ``at least adhering to principles that are divinely inspired
mormon doctrine holds that faithful christians may receive guidance from god regarding wordly endeavors, including their occupations. church leaders also teach that god inspired the political principles in the u.s. constitution, and that it is god's will that government adhere to them
asked by the associated press about steiger's comment on divine guidance, mecham would say only: ``sam, he's a little off the wall in some of his comments, too.''
although steiger's defense testimony only peripherally addressed the charge, he held senators riveted with his blunt, colorful descriptions of the mecham administration
steiger blamed the governor's troubles at least partially on his fierce battle with fellow republican attorney general robert corbin
that fight, he said, stemmed from mecham's resentment that he ``took an inordinate public beating'' over eliminating the state's martin luther king holiday for executive branch workers when it was really the attorney general's idea
corbin had advised all 1986 gubernatorial candidates that the holiday had been illegally declared that year by then-gov. bruce babbitt and that corbin would have to sue the governor if it was observed
in the most vitriolic comments of the trial's two weeks, steiger described corbin as ``not very bright but politically adept'' and suggested he manipulated legislators
he (corbin) has deluded many of you into thinking he is a competent person,'' he told the senators
he declared that corbin had turned the attorney general's office into ``one of the most expensive in the country'' and disliked mecham's cost-cutting policies
i believe those people are capable of setting up anybody,'' he said of corbin and his staff, ``but i have no knowledge they did.''
contacted for comment on steiger's remarks, corbin said: ``oh well, you know sam. just remember the position he is in with regard to our office and you can draw your own conclusions.''
steiger is being prosecuted by corbin's office on charges that he tried to extort a vote from a parole board member
mecham faces a criminal charge brought by corbin's office alleging that he concealed the $350,000 campaign loan
he also faces a recall election may 22, but that could change if he is convicted by the senate. a two-thirds vote of senators could remove him from office, and a second two-thirds vote could bar him from holding any state office again. later libyan report</note>
panicked soccer fans fled knife-wielding ruffians and triggered the collapse of a sports stadium in libya, killing at least 20 people, according to news reports friday
malta's state radio said two libyans were arrested in tripoli, the libyan capital, after the collapse
newspapers in belgrade, yugoslavia, quoting a report from the yugoslav state news agency tanjug from tripoli, said at least 20 people were killed and hundreds injured when a stadium dividing wall fell thursday during a match between malta and libya
but the libyan news agency jana said two spectators were killed. the jana report, monitored in london, said some people had been treated and released and 16 were hospitalized
joe sacco, the general secretary of the maltese football association who was in tripoli with the maltese team, said friday there was speculation in the libyan capital that the death toll could be higher
jana said a row of seats collapsed at the ``june 11'' stadium. the stadium reportedly has a capacity of 70,000. it was not immediately known how many people were at the game
the times of malta said panic occurred when someone in the stands brandished a weapon and the spectators rushed to get out
politika ekspres, a belgrade daily, said the incident began when several fans pulled out knives during a quarrel
some spectators returning to malta told reporters at the airport the same story while others quoted people in the stadium as saying a man was terrorizing the crowd with a snake
politika ekspres said spectators seeking safety toppled an iron fence. at the same time, a six-foot thick, 15-foot long wall dividing the second from the third level of the stadium also crashed down
it is hard to believe that anyone under it could have remained alive,'' politika ekspres said, quoting eyewitnesses
several hundred people reportedly were injured when the crowd from the third level surged down, creating panic that soon spread to other parts of the stadium
people rushed to exits, and that caused more injuries, the paper said
finally, about 5,000 fans in the field started chasing the culprits. one of them was captured but police managed to drag him free from the hands of the crowd, politika ekspres said
malta's department of information said the foreign ministry was informed that no maltese nationals were involved in the accident
the libyans were leading 1-0 in the exhibition game between the two national teams. the game was stopped and did not resume
prime minister edward fench adami of malta sent a message friday to libya's leader, col. moammar gadhafi, extending ``our condolences and deepest sympathies to the familes of the bereaved and to all those hit by this tragedy.''
the people of malta join me in sharing your profound grief at this unhappy moment during the sports festival,'' fenech adami said in the message. picks up 5th graf pvs, three journalists ...</note>
panama's military-backed government ordered cuts in public services friday as new u.s. sanctions compounded a financial crisis. police firing tear gas broke up an opposition rally
the beleaguered government of strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega reportedly also was considering delaying or reducing paychecks due early next week to nearly 150,000 public employees. a spokesman said no decision was made on those steps
several businessmen said they were warned their stores could be expropriated if they refused to cash public employees' paychecks
a planned demonstration by government opponents in the central banking district was broken up friday afternoon by riot police firing tear gas grenades and spraying the stinging, acrid liquid from portable canisters
large numbers of police prevented any sustained gathering of demonstrators. small groups gathered and then ran, setting a few fires. an associated press photographer at the scene reported more journalists on hand than police, spectators and demonstrators
at one site there were about 60 journalists and fewer than 20 protesters, who loudly chanted ``justice!'' and taunted the police
three journalists were injured when police sprayed gas in their faces at close range. they were: lucia annunziata, a reporter with la repubblica of rome; david walters, a photographer with the miami herald; and manolo iscala, a cameraman for spanish television
the nation's new chief executive, manuel solis palma, ordered his cabinet into emergency session after president reagan imposed several new sanctions, including putting some panama canal fees in escrow
a spokesman for solis palma characterized reagan's action as ``a state of war.''
the cabinet ordered working hours in all government offices slashed from eight to six hours daily
it also told government agencies and departments to cut their use of electricity, fuel and telephones, and asked employees to take vacations due them immediately
treasury minister hector alexander was quoted by a panama city newspaper as saying upcoming paydays of public employees ``are going to have to be deferred'' because of a growing cash shortage
the newspaper la estrella said the treasury minister did not elaborate on his remark about delaying paychecks, which was carried in a brief, three-paragraph story friday morning
a source close to panama's government said the cabinet also contemplated delaying paychecks to government workers, reducing their pay temporarily and giving them partial payment in food instead of cash
the u.s. sanctions were announced on the 10th day of a bank closure forced by a cash shortage in panama. the country uses the american dollar as its currency and its central bank normally receives transfers from the u.s. federal reserve
the united states halted those transfers last week and attorneys for ousted president eric arturo delvalle have tied up an estimated $50 million in official panamanian funds in private u.s. banks
directors of six supermarket and one pharmacy chains said mario rognoni, the trade and industries minister, told them the government could expropriate the chains if they did not cash public employees' paychecks
they said in a statement they would consider a general strike if the government followed through on its ``veiled threat.''
if they cashed the checks, they would have no money to operate ``in less than 24 hours,'' the directors said
rognoni denied he made any threat and said he only wanted to advance the idea of having chains give food to employees and deduct the value from the paychecks
panama's most recent problems began in february when noriega was indicted in florida on u.s. drug-trafficking and money laundering chages
on feb. 25, president delvalle tried to remove noriega as chief of the defense forces. instead, noriega arranged for the legislature to dismiss delvalle, and a political and economic crisis ensued
washington responded by imposing economic sanctions on panama and declaring its support for delvalle, who went into hiding
on friday, reagan stepped up u.s. economic pressure by ordering that a $6.5 million canal payment due tuesday be put into escrow
reagan ordered several other measures and called on noriega to resign
in boston, the first national bank of boston agreed to freeze panamanian government accounts until the state department lifts sanctions against the nation, according to a settlement filed in u.s. district court
the panamanian government normally disburses about $33 million in paychecks every two weeks, but its cash reserves are said by diplomatic sources and private economists to be approaching zero
the government managed to pay its 15,000 soldiers thursday, but must meet a bi-monthly payroll for the nation's 20,000 public school teachers on monday and thousands of other government workers on tuesday
the school teachers form a powerful lobby that brought down a civilian president in 1979 over a pay dispute
public employees in general are considered to be among the few remaining backers of noriega. livestock</head> minnesota, pickup 2nd graf pvs, `students heading ...'; subs 8th graf `up to ...' to update snowfall totals; inserts 1 graf after 16th, `wind gusting...' with motel roof blown off; inserts 1 graf after 19th, `the men ...' with cattle industry spokesman's comment.</note>
a blizzard plastered the northern plains with deep snow driven by wind up to 65 mph friday, endangering newborn calves and stranding travelers along hundreds of miles of blocked highways in colorado, nebraska, wyoming and the dakotas
the storm barreled into minnesota on friday night. blizzard warnings were issued for the northwestern part of the state, and wet snow and 35 mph wind made driving hazardous
students heading home aboard two school buses were caught by the storm thursday and were spending their second night as guests at two farms, one of which had no electricity
we feel it is in the best interest of the public to not, not go out on the highway,'' said capt. pius ternes of the north dakota highway patrol. ``we don't want someone getting stranded. it's just a very dangerous situation.''
we've mostly had people sliding off the road. we're not even pulling them out. we're just getting people out of the vehicles,'' nebraska state patrol dispatcher alex haberkorn said in scottsbluff
several hundred pupils in colorado spent the night in their schools. some travelers tried to sleep on the floors of a courthouse. north dakota capitol workers were sent home friday about an hour after they arrived
there were numerous minor accidents as vehicles slid on ice and snow, and many schools closed. snow plows could not keep up with blowing, drifting snow in many areas. wyoming state offices were closed, although the legislature met
hard-hit nebraska was not expected to get relief until late friday or early saturday. the storm was expected to track across minnesota and wisconsin
up to 40 inches of snow fell in two days in the mountains of utah at the alta ski resort, with 37 inches at snowbird. three to 4 feet had fallen around lead and deadwood, on the edges of south dakota's black hills. visibility in areas was down to zero
school bus driver linda barret and her 13 riders took refuge thursday at a farm some 20 miles from harrisburg, neb., when the storm cut visibility, and bus driver sharon grubbs and her eight riders, ages 7 to 13, wound up at a farm 17 miles from harrisburg, in far western nebraska
they were still there friday and planned to spend a second night. the electricity had been out at the second farm, owned by jack and karen holt, since late thursday
it's kind of like the old days,'' ms. grubbs said. she and mrs. holt used a camping stove to cook meals while the children huddled under blankets
outside scottsbluff, neb., jim and elizabeth davis of hot springs, wyo., spent about 15 hours stuck in their car before they were rescued friday. davis, 68, said he and his 67-year-old wife had apples and candy, plenty of blankets and a full gas tank
for one resort, the storm was too much of a good thing
we must have close to 4 foot. even the ski slopes are closed,'' said bob ekeren, manager of the terry peak lodge in the black hills. snow buried cars at the lodge and would-be skiers stayed inside friday morning, he said
right now you can't hardly see your hand in front of your face,'' ekeren said. ``i've never seen this much snow in my life. it's just unbelievable.''
wind gusting to 60 mph was reported friday morning at fort morgan, colo., and to 65 mph at rapid city, s.d. western nebraska had gusts to 50 mph
the wind blew off a 20-by-30 foot section of roof at a rapid city hotel, and it landed on three cars. no one was hurt. ``if there would have been someone down there, it would have killed them for sure,'' said manager gregory lester
friday was the 100th anniversary of the start of the four-day great blizzard of 1888 in the east. that storm claimed 400 lives
the weather threatened thousands of newborn calves, and ranchers in the nebraska sandhills region worked around the clock to get animals to shelter
the men are just exhausted. ... we worked all night long,'' said marianne beel. ``we had 300 calves born yesterday. we're dragging them in, separating them from their mothers.''
dick kjerstad, chairman of the south dakota beef checkoff campaign committee, said friday the storm could be a severe blow to the state's cattle industry. ``if it lasts another day, there could sure be some big losses,'' he said
in the nebraska panhandle, all roads in and out of kimball were closed and civil defense director dan jenson estimated 600 travelers spent the night in the town of 3,800 residents
hotels and motels were filled, and residents opened their homes, he said. but many spent the night at the kimball county courthouse, and about 200 truckers slept in their trucks
i've never seen so many gosh-dang people,'' jenson said
interstate 80 was closed for more than 300 miles, from walcott, wyo., to rock springs, neb., because of snowdrifts and low visibility. many other roads also were closed in eastern wyoming, including almost 140 miles of interstate 25, and in western nebraska
the closing of roads into laramie, wyo., marooned skiers at the snowy range ski area, which has no overnight accommodations. co-owner terri collins said about 180 people spent the night on the floor and tables and most were too tired friday morning to go skiing on 12 inches of fresh snow
we've got all the roads closed. people have to stay home,'' said kathy moan of the wyoming highway patrol. she said roads in and out of cheyenne and gillette were closed and the eastern part of the state was immobilized friday morning
about 100 miles of interstate 90 was closed overnight in western south dakota, and sections of i-94 were closed in north dakota. several northeastern colorado highways also were closed, including sections of interstates 25 and 70, the state patrol said
in northern colorado, 250 to 300 of the 1,200 students in the weld county school district spent the night in schools because buses couldn't get them home thursday, said superintendent bob gudka
the kids are having a ball,'' gudka said. as for the teachers, he joked, ``we may have to get psychological help for them later on.''
he said parents in four-wheel-drive vehicles fetched some students friday morning and a few were sent home on a convoy of buses accompanied by other four-wheel-drives
dennis day, a tenor who appeared on jack benny's tv and radio shows and recorded ``danny boy'' and other irish ballads, was hospitalized in critical and unstable condition, a hospital spokesman said friday
the 71-year-old singer whose trademark line was a sprightly ``gee, mr. benny!'' was brought to the emergency room wednesday after a fall at his home, said armen markarian, a spokesman at st.john's hospital and health center
while in the emergency room, day complained of a severe headache. a scan showed bleeding in the brain and he was rushed into surgery, markarian said. ``he's been in critical condition since then,'' the hospital spokesman added
in july, day's spokesman announced that he had been diagnosed with amyotropic lateral sclerosis, a degenerative nerve disease also known as lou gehrig's disease. however, markarian said day's condition did not appear to be related
day was born eugene denis mcnulty in new york city. his singing career began in 1939 as a naive kid with a golden voice on jack benny's radio show
he recorded such songs as ``peg of my heart'' and ``clancy lowered the boom,'' and appeared in several films, including ``buck benny rides again,'' ``music in manhattan,'' ``one sunday afternoon'' and ``the girl next door.'' news digest: chicago _ pm-political rdp, a0486; bloomington, ill, _ pm-dole, a0477; denver _ pm-hart, a0438; washington _ pm-us-panama, a0421; jerusalem _ pm-israel, a0446; washington _ pm-stubborn israeli, a0412; vienna, austria _ pm-austria-anschluss, a0495; new york _ pm-stocks-collar, a0448</note>
the military regime of gen. manuel antonio noriega made its army payroll, but panama's deposed president and economists predicted it will not be able to pay civil servants next week
that could further erode support for the general, chief of the 15,000-strong panama defense forces and considered the real power behind panama's civilian government
the government had to withdraw substantial funds from the central national bank of panama and divert receipts from state-owned utilities in order to back the army payroll thursday, diplomatic sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity
two former pentagon officials and the general accounting office are sharply criticizing a pact with japan for the retrieval of plutonium from u.s. nuclear wastes
critics of the nuclear cooperation agreement said thursday they may move to kill the accord next week in congress
the former officials, richard n. perle and frank j. gaffney jr., said the defense department was not given a significant role in negotiations and considers the agreement ``seriously flawed.''
elisabeth ann zinser resigned today as president of gallaudet university in a victory for students demanding a hearing-impaired president for the nation's only liberal arts college for the deaf
the university, which was shut down by protests over zinser's appointment five days ago, never has had a deaf president in its 124-year history
my decision to resign was reached with great difficulty as i came to understand how deeply some see the social stature of deaf persons reflected in the presidency of this university,'' zinser, who has normal hearing and doesn't know sign language, said in a statement early today
a 15-year-old boy convicted of killing a classmate with a baseball bat ``to know what it was like'' has been sentenced to life in prison, becoming the state's youngest prison inmate
rod matthews could be paroled in 15 years under the mandatory sentence he received thursday after being found guilty of second-degree murder in the nov. 20, 1986, slaying of 14-year-old shaun ouillette
two former friends of matthews testified he told them of planning the killing and took them to see ouillette's body, which police did not find until nearly four weeks later in woods in canton, a suburb 15 miles south of boston
prince charles was reported found trembling and weeping after an avalanche swept two close friends in his skiing party down a steep, unmarked alpine slope, killing one and breaking the other's legs
charles, the prince of wales and heir to the british throne, escaped unhurt
the loose snow cascaded down as charles, 39, and five companions were skiing thursday at about 5,800 feet in an area of the swiss alps that authorities earlier in the day warned was prone to avalanches. the area was off the main skiing trails
gov. evan mecham's defense lawyer angered senators by accusing the senate majority leader of showing ``overwhelming'' bias against the governor during his impeachment trial
jerris leonard lashed out thursday at majority leader bob usdane when the republican lawmaker questioned whether the impeached governor's new lawyers erred when they said weeks ago they were ready to defend mecham
usdane ``ought to show a little more impartiality,'' said leonard. ``his bias and prejudice are overwhelming,'' and under normal trial circumstances he should be disqualified, the attorney said
frederic remington, the painter and sculptor best known for his depiction of the wild west, deserves recognition as an american master, say the curators of a traveling exhibit of his work that opens here today
remington has been seen superficially,'' said michael edward shapiro, chief curator at the st. louis art museum. ``he's been stereotyped as a cowboy artist when he was a very sophisticated new yorker who drew from a lot of sources and created his own style, which has astonishingly imprinted itself on the conscience of our country.''
shapiro and peter h. hassrick, director of the buffalo bill historical center in cody, wyo., organized ``frederic remington: the masterworks,'' the first major traveling exhibit of remington's work. news digest: washington _ am-us-panama; panama city, panama _ am-panama; undated _ am-political rdp; boston _ am-polish seamen; london _ am-drake expenses.</note>
former presidential aide robert c. mcfarlane pleaded guilty friday to misdemeanor charges that he misled congress by assuring lawmakers the reagan administration was not helping arm nicaraguan rebels during a ban on u.s. military aid
president reagan's former national security adviser pleaded guilty to four counts of withholding information from congress when questioned about news reports that members of his staff, particularly lt. col. oliver l. north, were helping to raise money and ship arms to the contra rebels
mcfarlane, who agreed to cooperate fully with independent counsel lawrence e. walsh's investigation, could be sentenced to up to four years imprisonment and fined as much as $400,000 for the guilty pleas he entered before u.s. district judge aubrey e. robinson jr
gary hart, declaring ``i got a fair hearing and the people decided,'' quit the 1988 presidential campaign for good friday, three months after rejoining a race from which he had been driven by revelations about his personal life
hart, the one-time democratic front-runner who had been drubbed in every contest since re-entering the campaign, advised the five surviving candidates to debate more and attack each other less
asked if he would ever seek the white house again, he said lightly, ``not this year; twice in one year is enough.''
a blizzard plastered the northern plains with deep snow driven by wind up to 65 mph friday, endangering newborn calves and stranding travelers along hundreds of miles of blocked highways in colorado, nebraska, wyoming and the dakotas
students heading home aboard two school buses were caught by the storm thursday and were spending their second night as guests at two farms, one of which had no electricity
we feel it is in the best interest of the public to not, not go out on the highway,'' said capt. pius ternes of the north dakota highway patrol. ``we don't want someone getting stranded. it's just a very dangerous situation.''
half the arab policemen in the west bank resigned by plo order friday and israeli soldiers closed the main gaza mosque on the moslem sabbath for the first time worshipers could remember
the al amari mosque in gaza city has been a rallying point for protest since riots began dec. 8 in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, with prayer leaders sometimes calling over its loudspeakers for resistance to the army
israeli troopers shot and wounded nine palestinians during street battles after friday prayers at other mosques in the occupied territories. the army demolished the homes of four arabs accused of attacking either israelis or palestinians accused of collaborating with them
prime minister yitzhak shamir on friday attacked u.s. peace proposals for the first time in public, charging that they were ``fraught with danger'' and incapable of bringing peace to the region
u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz shuttled through the region last week to urge arab and israeli acceptance of the plan
the only word i agree with in the u.s. plan is the name shultz,'' shamir was quoted as saying by the israeli daily newspaper haaretz
the government said friday that retail sales edged up 0.6 percent in february, bolstered by strong demand for autos, but economists expressed worries that sales in january were much weaker than previously believed
in good news on the inflation front, wholesale prices fell 0.2 percent in february, pushed down by drops in both food and energy costs
for the first two months of the year, the labor department said prices have been rising at an annual rate of 1.1 percent, half the modest 2.2 percent increase in 1987. analysts said inflation should remain moderate for the rest of the year
iran and iraq stopped nearly two weeks of attacks on each other's cities friday, but the iraqis said they got in the last volley with 11 missiles fired before their afternoon truce deadline
hundreds of civilians have been killed or wounded since the exchange began feb. 29
eight rockets were aimed at tehran on friday and three at the iranian holy city of qom, the official iraqi news agency reported. it said the last missile left its launcher at 3:44 p.m., just 16 minutes before time iraq said it would stop shooting
prince charles flew home friday with the body of a friend who was swept off a swiss mountain by an avalanche that nearly engulfed the future king as it roared down the slope in a ``terrifying matter of seconds.''
with maj. hugh lindsay's pregnant widow, sarah, the prince watched as six soldiers from his dead friend's royal lancers regiment bore the flag-draped coffin from the red and white jet of the queen's flight
the 39-year-old heir to the throne was praised for helping save the life of another skier but called foolhardy for skiing perilous slopes off the main trails of the klosters resort
austria on friday marked the 50th anniversary of its annexation by nazi germany with solemn memorials to the dead and demonstrations against president kurt waldheim, whose wartime past relegated him to silent spectator at official ceremonies
conservative and socialist politicans emphasized that some austrians were perpetrators in the nazi era, challenging the long-held view that austria was simply a victim of adolf hitler when he sent his troops into the alpine nation on march 11, 1938
a minute of silence drew little response on vienna streets, and few viennese turned out in the early morning to watch political leaders lay wreaths at monuments to nazi victims and fallen soldiers
about 2,500 gallaudet university students and supporters claimed victory in a capitol hill rally friday after elisabeth ann zinser resigned as president of their school for the deaf, but they vowed to continue their protests until their other demands are met
zinser, who is not deaf and does not know sign language, was named to the post last sunday but announced her resignation early friday morning after protesters virtually halted all classes this week. zinser said she had stepped down in response ``to this extraordinary social movement of deaf people.''
students and activists marched across the capitol lawn friday bearing signs and banners and chanting ``deaf president now,'' ``no hearing president'' and ``deaf power.''
gov. evan mecham believed he was ``divinely guided'' in making executive decisions, one of his closest aides testified friday at mecham's impeachment trial
sam steiger, a special assistant who was forced out of office by his own indictment on political extortion charges, also described a bitter battle between mecham and the state's attorney general, whom steiger blamed for mecham's downfall
i had the feeling that the governor did and does feel he is divinely guided,'' steiger said in response to a question by sen. john mawhinney, a republican like mecham
lyndon larouche's attorneys demanded access friday to information a prosecutor relied on when he said a top fbi official conferred with a key figure in the iran-contra scandal about an effort to collect information against larouche
the attorneys said the information might help them prove their contention that former white house aide oliver north asked the fbi and cia to infiltrate larouche groups because they were interfering with north's private contra-resupply effort
also friday, the trial judge again delayed the resumption of testimony in the fraud and conspiracy case against larouche, six aides and five organizations because of pending searches of government records, including those of the white house and vice president george bush, for any evidence suggesting infiltration of larouche groups
with help from a u.s.-led aid program, a rundown site dividing roman catholic and protestant areas of belfast is being transformed into an industrial park for fledgling businessmen
it is one of about 40 projects that have been promised money from the multimillion-dollar international fund for ireland, the most tangible outgrowth of the anglo-irish agreement of 1985 that aims to help reconcile feuding catholics and protestants in northern ireland
the $1.6 million-townsend enterprise park will create space for 45 new businesses near the towering ``peace wall'' dividing the protestant shankill road district from the catholic falls road
frank murphy, the project head, said it would not have gone forward without the fund's $440,000 contribution
but just as the fund is getting off the ground, its future has been put in question following an announcement that the u.s. state department is dropping the fund from its 1989 allocations. of the fund's present kitty of $86.8 million, $85 million has come from washington with $35 million more due this year
the rationale behind the fund is that in a province with a 17-percent unemployment rate and the collapse of its traditional heavy industries, only economic revival can eliminate slums, joblessness and resentment
another project helped by the fund aims at turning the first-century ruin of navan fort in county armagh into a tourist site. another has given $4,500 to frank o'donnell, a 24-year-old londonderry catholic unemployed for two years, to open his own business selling hand-carved fireplace mantels
when the fund was set up in 1986, the u.s. congress approved $120 million over three years to stimulate economic regeneration and foster catholic-protestant reconciliation. seventy-five percent was earmarked for northern ireland and 25 percent for border counties in the irish republic to the south
some protestants are suspicious, since the anglo-irish agreement grants the irish republican government in dublin a say in their affairs. the rev. ian paisley, the northern irish protestant hardliner, called the fund ``yankee blood money'' and urged a boycott of its projects
the european economic community, which had been expected to make a major donation, has held back because london and dublin can't agree on a joint application for funds. canada is contributing $10 million spread over 10 years, and new zealand has given a one-time $300,000 payment
bob myers, u.s. consul general in belfast, said in an interview the united states wants more countries to contribute to the fund
but concern rose in ireland in february when u.s. deputy secretary of state john whitehead said the united states ``does not receive a real return'' on its contribution to the fund and was dropping it from the state department's 1989 foreign aid allocations
in its present state, the fund would die without the u.s. donation, and irish-american congressmen, such as sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., say they are confident congress will continue to support the international fund
the fund's board has so far allocated only 20 percent of its money, about $16 million, to some 40 projects. it says about 2,000 applications have come from both catholics and protestants, despite paisley's call for a boycott, and hopes to have distributed the whole amount within 18 months
i would have liked to see quicker progress. ... but i'm absolutely certain if we plunged in, spending money like drunken sailors, it would have been disastrous,'' said charles e.b. brett, the lawyer and former public official who chairs the fund's seven-member board
the board gives priority to job-creation programs, tourism and venture capital companies. one idea never tried before is the joint marketing of irish goods from both north and south
the board has also approved projects to help universities develop marketable products and more than half a dozen programs to launch entrepreneurs like o'donnell in londonderry
danny morrison, publicity director for sinn fein, the outlawed irish republican army's legal political wing, and the rev. matthew wallace, a catholic priest on the townsend park board in belfast, complained that the fund was putting too little into catholic areas where unemployment is 2{ times higher than in protestant areas
wallace said he preferred to see american companies investing in northern ireland and creating real jobs
that's more important than the money itself from the fund _ the money will do nothing,'' the priest said
i don't think we can expect violence to end unless we do something about unemployment,'' said franklin adair, a banker who heads the youth enterprise scheme _ yes. the fund's first grant of $88,500 went to yes, which is helping hundreds of people under 25 to start businesses
we must give young people something to hold on to,'' adair said. ``otherwise, what do they have to lose? that's where i think the american funds can be best used _ in positive creation of employment. that's the way to achieve peace.''
the government has rejected proposals for cease-fire talks under the central american peace plan and the guatemalan military has gone on the offensive against leftist rebel strongholds in the countryside
president vinicio cerezo turned down guerrilla proposals for talks as ``a good-for-nothing petition.'' a few days before he did that, the roman catholic archbishop, prospero penados del barrio, accepted a request from the rebels to mediate between the two sides
the rebels, the church and most political parties have urged the resumption of talks between the government and rebels in madrid, spain, last october _ the first in the 27-year-old war
but gen. hector gramajo, the defense minister, repeated the military's insistence that the rebels abandon their weapons first
the army is very close to achieving a total victory,'' he said
a few days before the october talks began in madrid with the guatemalan national revolutionary union, the umbrella for three guerrilla forces, the army announced new operations in the rebel-controlled northern part of quiche province and on the southern side of lake atitlan, where the rebels have been most entrenched
establishing a cease-fire is one of the commitments guatemala agreed to in signing the central american peace plan last aug. 7 along with nicaragua, el salvador, costa rica and honduras
gramajo maintained, however, that with an amnesty that requires rebels to disarm and participate in the political process, ``there is no need for talks.''
the rebels refute gramajo's claims that they have only 500 to 700 now under arms, down from 2,500 to 3,000 in 1986, and that the military offensive is a success. in the early 1980s, rebel strength was estimated at 4,000 to 6,000 combatants
there is a flareup in the war in guatemala, basically because of the army offensive,'' said one of the guerrilla respresentatives who went to madrid in october, speaking on condition of anonymity. he called the army's current offensive the ``biggest ever in strictly military terms.''
the army has thrown most of its strength of 43,000 personnel, including air support, into the effort, mainly focused on quiche
the guerrilla organization claims 3,500 combatants in its three armies _ the guerrilla army of the poor, the group fighting in quiche, a northwestern province; the organization of the people in arms, generally in the lake atitlan area and west to san marcos, and the rebel armed forces in the northern peten panhandle province
gramajo placed the army's casualties from september to mid-february at 83, while the rebel source put them at 700 from october through december. neither side gave rebel casualties, which generally are lower because guerrillas use ambushes and other tactics that avoid direct combat
one of the army's main targets is what it considers the rebel support population in northern quiche _ thousands of campesinos, most of them indians, who have hidden from the army for as long as seven years
they remained behind when thousands of others fled into neighboring mexico or cities in the early 1980s, when more than 400 villages were destroyed and tens of thousands of civilians killed in the northwest highlands
highlands residents, diplomats and human rights groups claim the army did most of the killing. the army blames the guerrillas
the rebels say they are fighting for what they call real democracy and national sovereignty and against social injustice and poverty
the most visible effect of the offensive in northern quiche around the area of nebaj is the hundreds of refugees being brought to the army base there. gramajo says a sign of the army's success is its ``rescue'' of 2,200 of the 4,000 peasants in the area
although the army is allowing them to return to a few villages near nebaj where it has re-established permanent posts and is putting in roads, the refugees must first receive three months of army ``re-education'' in ``patriotism and nationalism,'' officers said
villagers farther north remain closed to them
right now they can't return to those places,'' the civilian affairs officer at the base said. ``the army is going to have more success the fewer the people who are there.''
one refugee identifying himself only as diego said some refugees are captured by the army and others turn themselves in when soldiers appear
we saw, well, that there was no way out because the army was covering all the points,'' he said in a whisper outside a wood-plank army barracks at nebaj
even in the 100-degree heat of midday, the niger valley echoes with the sounds of the women beating their wash against the stones on the river bank
their back-breaking day's work will earn them an average of 250 west african francs (88 cents)
the women, their hard work and low pay epitomize the problems facing this west african nation shackled by constant drought and the economic difficulties that arise from it. the world bank ranks mali as one of the five poorest countries in the world, with a per capita income of $148 a year
the washerwomen, all from the dogon tribe, were driven out of their homes in the north to bamako four years ago by the devastating sahelian drought. they remain excellent vegetable farmers and the river banks behind them bloom with radishes, tomatoes and strawberries
but they live in isolation, on the outskirts of this city of 1 million. they do not speak french, mali's official language, nor do they know bambara, the lingua franca of the region
they are tolerated by their countrymen because, for the moment, there is no other room for them and there is still residual sympathy for the suffering they endured in the drought of 1983 and 1984. but another dry spell could quickly make them unwanted, another burden on a country already unable to feed itself
average rainfall varies from 47.2 inches in the south, to the desert north with less than 8 inches
the next drought will mean the loss of more farm land and even more people will be forced south, toward bamako, to compete for the scant resources
this huge, largely desert or semidesert country, with its 8.4 million people spread across an area larger than california and texas combined has never known prosperity. according to the economic-trends report from the u.s. embassy, it will need continued foreign help for the forseeable future
despite a national commitment to economic reform and relatively good soils in the south, cereal production has fallen in recent years,'' the report said. ``over the past 10 years the climate throughout mali, particularly the great inland delta of the niger, has become drier. this has resulted in serious losses of crops and cattle, declining agricultural productivity, and increased reliance upon donations of grains from the west.''
the report says mali has made serious attempts at mending its ailing economy, forcing retirements and imposing staff cutbacks in the public sector, but 70,000 government employees remain on the roles, three-fourths of all salaried workers in the country
in 1986, while under the squeeze of economic reform, the bottom fell out. the price of cotton, the country's chief export, plummeted. the government discontinued much of an austerity package that formed the basis for loans from the international monetary fund and world bank, but the imf money stoppoed coming because the government gave up on the austerity commitment
now mali is broke
teachers, on strike since mid-february for salaries three months in arrears, have been joined by students demanding that scholarship payments be brought up to date
president moussa traore said recently he hoped the 18-month-long ``misunderstanding'' with the imf could be cleared up and loans would be coming again
we have said that we favor the structural adjustment program, but we also favor the preservation of our human dignity, and despite our difficulties, the world economic situation, and drought _ which we do not control _ we want people to understand us,'' he told a news conference
structural adjustment does not mean throwing workers into the streets without compensation. nor does it mean dismantling the economy of a country or destroying the basis of an economy. we are still expecting help from our partners.''
march is salsa star ruben blades' month: his new album is being released and his latest movie, ``the milagro beanfield war,'' opens
blades, who writes most of his songs, also has a master's degree in law from harvard university. how does he find time to do so much?
the answer is that i am very well organized,'' he said in a recent interview. ``i select chunks of time based on my interest, i block that time and when it arrives i do only what that time has been devoted for
i begin to plan things usually a year or two before the event occurs. even if at the time the event doesn`t seem like its going to happen, i begin to plan for that event
my interests are so diverse,'' he added, ``that i keep surprising everybody by literally jumping from one thing to another and yet to another. for instance, when i went to harvard to do my master's, i didn't perform. during those two years, 1984 and 1985, i devoted my time to studying. i wrote some songs on the side, so to speak, but i didn't perform at all.''
after getting his degree, blades went to new mexico to shoot ``the milagro beanfield war,'' directed by robert redford, in 1986. it was his first screen appearence since teaming up with whoopi goldberg in ``fatal beauty,'' which was released that same year
the year 1985 saw the release of ``crossover dreams,'' a controversial film of dashed hopes and hot salsa in el barrio, starring blades and directed by the cuban-american filmmaker leon ichaso
ichaso has a very good eye for the absurd, which i think is a tremendous asset for anyone,'' blades said, talking about his work with various directors. ``redford, being an actor himself, is a very patient director, very protective. they both make actors feel very comfortable,'' he said
the milagro beanfield war'' will open in new york and los angeles march 18, and nationwide on april 1. blades' lp, ``nothing but the truth,'' will be released also on march 18, according to elektra records
the 39-year-old blades, who was born in panama and moved to the united states in 1974, described ``the milagro beanfield war'' as ``a comedy with a very serious point.''
the movie, based on the novel of the same title by john nicholson, is about the frictions and disputes between outside developers and local residents of a little, fictional town in new mexico called milagro
blades portrays bernabe montoya. ``he is the man in the middle. he is part of the community, but he has been appointed as a sheriff by the developers. ... he is the only one that has a genuine, independent outlook of both sides.''
blades said latin actors have more opportunity for film work today than 15 or 20 years ago. ``i think that because of the rising interest of the anglo public toward the latin culture and because of the impact of the political realities in central and south america, new opportunities are given now to latin actors and also latin directors,'' blades said
and i think this is a trend that will continue.''
sweet auburn,'' long the lifeline of black atlanta's business community, has lost its luster, and revitalization plans are hobbled by disagreement over what should be done in the district where martin luther king jr. preached and louis armstrong played
the city's auburn avenue area was a child of segregation. for years, a soaring black middle and professional class was allowed to do business or offer services nowhere else. in 1956, fortune magazine called auburn avenue the richest black business district in america
the avenue was a cradle of the civil rights movement. but it was the movement's success that eventually disseminated the middle classes to other parts of atlanta and started sweet auburn on its decline
whether it can be renovated without its few remaining businesses being ``gentrified,'' and whether the old flavor can or should be restored, are issues along the avenue
whatever is proposed, the older people in the area seem to disagree with it,'' said gordon joiner, a former chairman of the martin luther king historical district development corp. ``they all seem to agree that the area needs to be revitalized, but that's where the agreement stops.''
king's ebenezer baptist church, his birthplace and his tomb are on auburn avenue, and some redevelopment proposals center on that
the development corporation envisions reverting part of the avenue to the way it was when king was young. others want to revitalize the entire district into an area where people again will come to do business, using its past as a tourist draw
atlanta has budgeted $2.4 million this year for auburn avenue-area landscaping, improvements on the still-functioning municipal market building and historic facade renovation. the city also hopes to get some help from the national trust for historic preservation
most grant money for the auburn district has gone to the east end where the martin luther king jr. center for nonviolent social change sits and not to the dilapidated commercial sector
nearly 500,000 visitors a year travel the two-mile-long avenue from downtown atlanta to the king center
en route, visitors pass a few remaining bars, beauty shops, small restaurants and boarded-up businesses. they pass a four-story brick shell of a building with the names of lawyers, dentists, accountants and doctors in peeling paint on the remaining shards of windows
prostitution and drug deals flourish along the avenue, a high-crime area at night
the poor and the prostitutes were always there
the rev. william borders, 82, who just finished his 50th year as pastor at the wheat street baptist church, remembers being propositioned years ago. ``they used to make a pass at me and i would say, `don't you know who i am? i'm the preacher,' and they would say, `i don't care who you are. do you want to date me or not?'''
borders came to the avenue in the 1920s. ``it was a lot rougher out there then than it is now,'' he said
my mother used to tell us we were born too late to be in slavery and too early to be out of slavery.''
borders was instrumental in getting some substandard housing replaced by projects
atlanta's most prestigious black churches are still there, along with the national offices of the southern christian leadership conference; black fraternal lodges; one of the nation's first black-owned radio stations, werd; and the atlanta daily world, the nation's oldest black-owned daily newspaper
the masonic building, built by blacks in the early years of the century, sits atop an underground river. ``i'm proud to say we built it, and proud to say we ain't seen a drop of water yet,'' said x.l. neal, the grand master
old-line atlantans remember the area for some of the best food in town, and an alluring smoky pungence from the auburn avenue rib shack is comforting assurance that not everything has changed
over time, the region became known as ``sweet auburn.'' in the 1930s and '40s cab calloway, louis armstrong and others packed patrons into the top hat club, now long closed
the royal peacock hosted another generation of black entertainers such as otis redding and ray charles. it hung on for 25 years until it closed in 1973
the peacock has been leased by two white entrepreneurs who plan to reopen the second-story walkup as a blues and rock showcase
what visitors see of (black) atlanta is a poor reflection of what the auburn avenue area was all about,'' said daniel moore, director of apex, a privately funded organization building a permanent display of atlanta's black history on the avenue
for a number of years there have been plans for auburn avenue but no one has taken the task seriously,'' he said. he said a recent study about what might be done cost $240,000 and was one of a half-dozen over the past 10 years, all of them expensive
i don't see much chance of anything major being done before the (democratic national) convention,'' scheduled for atlanta in july, he said
politically, more has been said than done about the area, and no unified leadership has emerged
there are a number of factions on the avenue, and the avenue does not have a czar to speak for all factions,'' said portia scott, whose family has published the daily world since 1928. ``there are a whole lot of themes here, not just martin luther king.''
ben e. smith, a lifelong auburn avenue area resident and nightclub owner, agrees
of a move to put city funds from a defunct project into the area, smith said recently, ``i'll make sure the king center doesn't get everything. everything can't go to the gravesite.''
smith, who heads the sweet auburn merchants and professionals association, is urging unity among the remaining businesses to assure their interests are covered in any revitalization plans
smith, ms. scott and others fought hard against plans to tear out seven businesses on the avenue to make room for a black studies library and research center. fulton county officials have agreed to try to find an existing vacant building for the center instead
there is a diehard need for restoration that does not displace the merchants,'' smith said, adding that it is equally important to ``keep the history and character of sweet auburn,'' a street described by many atlantans as one of the few in town with any character left
cbs is beefing up its schedule with four new comedies, but from the looks of the first three, the shows themselves will need some beefing up before they will help cbs
because of its hour-drama-heavy schedule, the network wants more half-hour sitcoms. thus ``eisenhower &amp; lutz'' premieres tonight in two half hours, before and after ``newhart.'' its regular time period will be monday in place of ``frank's place,'' which moves to tuesday
trial and error'' and ``coming of age'' make their debuts tuesday. a fourth comedy, ``the dictator,'' also was to have premiered tuesday, but it has been delayed by the writers' strike. in the meantime, cbs will bring back ``my sister sam.''
the most promising of the three new comedies is ``trial and error.'' it falters occasionally in the premiere half hour, but mostly lands on its feet, thanks to the comic abilities of its two stars, eddie velez and paul rodriguez
velez plays john hernandez, a clean-cut young lawyer just hired by a big los angeles law firm. his childhood friend and now roommate, tony rivera (rodriguez), is a t-shirt entrepreneur
rodriguez, a stand-up comic, delivers the one-liners with professional aplomb. he takes his buddy to a fancy restaurant to celebrate his new job. the waiter lists the specials, including goat cheese, $8: ``goat cheese eight dollars?'' complains rivera. ``i got a buddy in alhambra who'll sell me the whole goat for four.''
velez's forte is physical comedy. acting cool in his new office with his modular phone, he whips the receiver around on its elasticized wire, but ends up having to hide from it when it gets out of control
the show doesn't make any heavy social points, but does manage a meaningful plotline when hernandez faces the fact that he was hired by the law firm because he is hispanic. the senior partner dismisses his protests by telling him there was a time he would have been rejected because of it. at rivera's urging, he decides to take the break for what it's worth
eisenhower &amp; lutz'' also shows promise with occasionally crisp writing and a likable star, scott bakula, playing a palm springs shyster who's practicing alone but thought eisenhower on the firm's name sounded prestigious
his secretary quits over her pay. ``remember two months ago when i interviewed for a job and we discussed salary and i said, yes, i wanted one?''
so his girlfriend (delane matthews), a cocktail waitress, fills in, typing up his resume before his meeting with a big law firm he thinks might hire him. he notes she included his alma mater, southeast school of law. ``i thought we were going to dress that up a little,'' says he. says she, ``i took `and acupuncture' off.''
the series is from mtm productions and executive producer allan burns, an emmy-winning writer formerly with ``the mary tyler moore show.'' the lines are smart enough, but the series needs to develop some heart
coming of age'' was apparently meant to be kind of a co-ed ``golden girls.'' it stars paul dooley as dick hale, a wise-cracking former airline pilot from pittsburgh reluctantly relocated to a sunny retirement village in the southwest with his wife, ginny (phyllis newman)
the comedy in the premiere episode is broad and sluggish, though dooley can almost pull it off. ``that's 27,'' he says, gazing out the window as his wife unpacks. ``what are you counting?'' she asks. ``gray heads,'' he says
alan young and glynis johns play neighbors ed and trudie pepper, who come over bearing a welcome pie. turns out ed baked the pie
so, basically, ed,'' says dick, ``you retired and became a woman.''
even dooley can't manage for long with material like this
the fourth comedy, ``the dictator,'' features christopher lloyd, best known to tv audiences as rev. jim on ``taxi,'' as joseph domino, supreme ruler of the south sea island nation of bando. after the overthrow of his government, he is exiled to rego park, queens. the premise sounds great, but it's a bad sign if the series has to be halted because there are too few scripts for even a limited spring run. when the series does premiere, look forward to seeing bob elliott of the comedy team bob and ray as guest star
elsewhere in television:
phil fills in _ phil donahue will fill in for bryant gumbel on the ``today'' show the week of april 4. gumbel is taking off time in preparation for his anchor duties when nbc broadcasts the olympics from seoul later this summer. gumbel will also be off the week of april 18, and former ``today'' host jim hartz will fill in that week. ..
no nukes _ ``crime story'' is filming a climactic, three-part season finale in acapulco, mexico. the occasion for the locale is a plotline that has torello and his strike force chasing villain ray luca and his crime empire to a small latin american country. in last year's season finale, luca was caught in a nuclear blast
fifty years after the nazis closed the world's first museum of jewish art in vienna, a private exhibit of jewish ritual objects has been drawing large crowds of visitors
some 800 items displayed at the ``judentum in wien'' (``jews in vienna'') exhibit housed by the museum of the history of vienna are all loans from a private judaica collection, regarded by art historians as one the most important private collections of jewish life
according to max berger, owner of the collection, most of the drawings, paintings, sculptures, medals, coins, manuscripts and handicraft on show were in danger of being destroyed or lost after austria's annexation by nazi germany in 1938
berger, a viennese businessman who survived a nazi concentration camp, pieced together his collection over years and this is the first time it has been shown in public
the exhibit displays mementoes of jewish life from the early 18th century until present, focusing on vienna as an important center in the history of european jewry. museum officials said it is the first step toward opening a permanent jewish museum here in the next two or three years
about 6,000 jews live in vienna today, compared with 200,000 who helped make this city a capital of science, culture and the arts before world war ii. they included sigmund freud, gustav mahler, stefan zweig, arnold schoenberg and hundreds of others
some 65,000 austrian jews perished in nazi concentration and death camps during the war
the exhibit is divided into eight sections, including ritual objects and hebrew writings, the jewish year and life, the history of the viennese jews, zionism, anti-semitism and persecution and jewish contributions to art and culture
it's the first time that the most important private judaica collection in europe is displayed for the austrian public after the war,'' karl-albrecht weinberger, a curator who helped set up the display, said in an interview
by march 3, the exhibit had been visited by some 30,000 people
on saturdays and sundays we have up to 500 visitors a day,'' weinberger said, adding that recently austrian school authorities advised schools to come and see the exhibit as part of their history classes
more young austrians gradually have been educated about the nazi past and the holocaust in the two years since the first disclosures that president kurt waldheim had covered up his wartime past as a german army lieutenant in the balkans
weinberger said the exhibit was planned before waldheim became president
the most valuable objects displayed are a silver-and-gold torah crown made in austria in 1810 and a torah plaque made in 1806 of gold-covered silver
the oldest display is a torah curtain made around 1700 of red velvet laced with silver threads
weinberger said the first jewish museum in the world opened in vienna in 1895, with a very big collection of jewish art
the nazis dismantled it in 1938. while some items were lost or destroyed, others were taken by the germans to prague where they planned to open a big anti-semitic jewish museum. the museum never materialized but some objects have remained in the prague jewish museum which opened after the war
asked if the austrians ever asked the czechs to return the items held by the vienna museum, weinberger said they never did
it's difficult to prove what objects belonged to the jewish vienna museum as all catalog were destroyed during the war,'' he said
your eyelids freeze, it's dark much of the time, polar bears stroll the streets every so often, and a heat wave is when the temperature goes above 40 degrees in the summer. not many outsiders go to the world's northernmost city, but a moscow-based associated press correspondent did and wrote this story when she thawed out. it is one of a series of periodic ap reports on life and culture in the byways of the world
igor perlovsky is a big man in dickson. he runs the only bar in town. he owns the only vcr
and for the 5,000 soviets who inhabit the world's northernmost city on the ice-bound kara sea, drinks and movies at perlovsky's ``coupole'' lounge are a cherished escape from the 10 months of winter when temperatures plunge to 75 degrees below zero and the wind freezes the moisture in the corners of people's eyes
outdoor sports are out of the question on the desolate ice desert that stretches more than 300 miles from here to the south. even for those hardy enough to play outdoors, it's hard to see a soccer ball during the three-month polar night. nor is there swimming during the two-month ``summer,'' when the mercury climbs to an average high of 40
there used to be an automobile in dickson, which is reachable only by air and sea, but the novelty of driving on the city's three or four roads wore off, and the 11-year-old moskvich subcompact has been garaged with only 70 kilometers (44 miles) on the odometer
every few weeks, a resident sights a polar bear lumbering along the moguled ice paths that pass for streets, and telling tales of narrow escapes from the arctic's natural inhabitants is a popular pasttime
police sometimes are summoned to chase the bears away by firing rifles into the air, but they are forbidden to shoot the beasts except in life-threatening situations: polar bears are protected by the soviet red book, the endangered species list
at first glance, dickson appears uninhabited. the plume from a single smokestack atop the city's steam-generating plant provides the first sign of life. on closer inspection, a few fur-hatted pedestrians can be seen bobbing between the snowbanks. the silence is broken by the roar of a jeep or the thrashing of a tracked ``vezdekhod'' _ the refitted armored personnel carriers that serve as dickson's police cars, ambulances and buses
the city, which lies 500 miles inside the arctic circle and 1,100 miles below the north pole, is named for oskar dickson, a swedish brewer and financier who bankrolled the international expedition that discovered the port in 1875. dickson's retention of his name through a century of political tumult in russia is evidence of its isolation from moscow and the official penchant for renaming places for soviet heroes
the first settlers arrived in dickson in 1915 to operate a radio transmitter at the port. by world war ii, a few hundred were living here to handle shipping on the yenisei river that flows into the kara just to the south
today, dickson's port is the gateway to the northern sea route that provides europe's only direct sealink to the pacific ocean
gennady m. svetkov, deputy chief of the city's governing council, said the port, which is the only major enterprise in dickson, generates revenues of 6 million rubles ($10 million) a year. that figure could skyrocket if the soviet union reopens the northern sea route as communist party chief mikhail s. gorbachev proposed last october. it has been closed to all but soviet vessels since 1964
in winter, supply ships, shepherded by icebreakers, make their way into the frozen port every month or so. but in july and august the waterfront bustles as soviet cargo ships ply the arctic ocean with goods bound for japan, china and points south
increased ship traffic and the arrival of foreign crews could change this arctic outpost, but dickson's city fathers regard an international port as a distant prospect
such decisions are in the hands of the mainlanders,'' said svetkov, referring to those who live beyond the tundra
for now, dickson's residents appear content to bear with the hardships to keep the sea lanes open and gather data from eight weather research stations drifting in the arctic ocean
it's not so cold here,'' said 20-year-old marina rovenska. ``it's just boring.'' miss rovenska, a clerk at dickson's shopping center, came here with her parents from the ukraine eight years ago
she and a friend, yelena cherevik, said young workers flock to perlovsky's bar several times a week for the best dickson has in social life
perlovsky, a 36-year-old native who returned after a few years as a seaman in odessa on the black sea, where it's warm, is a respected businessman among dickson's youth, who are paid double salaries for working under hardship. perlovsky bought a german-made video deck last year for a 10,000 rubles ($16,000) _ two years' his salary as a state bartender _ from a friend of a friend of a diplomat. his tapes, recorded from finnish television or soviet film libraries, have been collected through a farflung network of friends and connections. his library of about 100 titles cost him about 100 rubles ($160) each 
while perlovsky is a state bartender, he is a private video operator at the ``coupole,'' a wood-paneled anteroom of cafeteria no. 1. he operates in part ``na levo'' (literally, on the left), a russian expression for doing things outside the law. but his video bar exemplifies the freer hand soviets have in remote communities to bend the rules to make their system work
for 1.50 rubles ($2.50), or three times the price of a movie ticket elsewhere in the soviet union, a dickson resident can settle down at perlovsky's bar and watch a soviet film classic or western rock video _ once everyone has agreed on the night's selection. liquor appears to be in greater supply here than in most areas of the soviet union, again illustrating a concession from moscow, where gorbachev's tough anti-drinking crusade has made alcohol both expensive and hard to find
some guys come in here and drink themselves into such a state that they have to be helped home,'' said perlovsky, who as a former national rowing champion is equal to the task of bouncer. ``but i wouldn't say we have an acute problem with drunkenness, at least not like in central russia where guys will drink up their last kopek. most people just want a place where they can gather.''
older residents cite its advantages over other areas of the country. crime rates are low, they say, because thieves can't flee the city and stolen goods are hard to hide in housing that is mostly communal
the north is like a sifter,'' observed gennady ilchenko, the director of the weather station who has lived in dickson for 37 years. ``those who are weak or lazy or untalented fall out quickly.''
schoolteacher larissa duvinets, a 28-year resident, says children are taught in the city's two schools to value the northern lifestyle and plan for futures in their parents' footsteps
but city officials concede that at least 20 percent of dickson's population turns over each year
i don't think i'll stay here after school days,'' said 13-year-old sergei lutsenko as he led visitors on a tour of the city's three-room museum. ``i feel it's cut off from the outside world.''
he and his friends said they long for big-city life with subways and buses _ and the simple pleasures of summer, like swimming and going barefoot
the texas hill country seemed an odd backdrop to talk with a man who ruled louisiana much like a king when he wasn't rolling dice in monte carlo and las vegas, flirting with beautiful women or fighting off racketeering charges
but gov. edwin edwards is preparing to leave office monday, and his texas ranch has been a hideaway used more frequently by the governor who became the most propular official in the bayou state since huey long _ until he was undone by the collapse of oil and questions about his honesty that wouldn't go away
in a recent interview at the ranch overlooking the greenish waters of the south llano river, edwards spoke softly about his political career and about leaving it all behind
the 1,400-acre ranch is dotted with scrub oaks stunted by the scant rainfall, a far cry from edwards' louisiana estate, with its massive moss-covered oaks and enough green grass in the yard to more than feed the 60 head of cattle barely surviving on what they can find here
still, the texas spread is far from the swirl of politics and controversy that has been his life
edwards' brother once said, ``he's an introvert trying to be an extrovert.''
that's accurate,'' said edwards, gently rocking and fiddling with the bottom button of a down jacket. ``it's almost ludicrous to say that but i've done a good job in overcoming it. i have a basic tendency to get away. that's why i have this ranch.''
the ranch is not so much a place to relax for edwards, who at 60, still doesn't know how to take it easy
if he's not hunting, he's on that tractor or using a bushhog,'' an aide told a reporter
the reporter recalled a comment years ago by edwards' brother-in-law: ``he's not relaxed like a normal frenchman.''
maybe that's because he's ambitious,'' said edwards' mother-in-law
edwards sprouted from impoverished south louisiana, the son of a sharecropper. education was the only escape route
at 21 he had finished law school, and six years later, in 1954, he was elected to the crowley city council. from there he was elected to the state senate, to congress and finally to the governor's office in 1972 and again in 1976
he never lost an election
he was adored by the people because he brought ``les bons temps'' _ good times _ by prodding the legislature to tax oil at a percentage of value in 1973 just before prices soared. government was on easy street and the economy was beautiful
people were tolerant, even proud, of his candor when edwards commented that ``gambling turns me on.'' they smiled when he flirted openly with women
he left office after serving two consecutive terms, the most allowed by law, but returned in 1984 for an unprecedented third term, overwhelming one-term republican dave treen
edwards was so powerful that while the republican served, the populist cajun opened an unofficial governor's office and began collecting $13 million for a campaign that kept treen looking over his shoulder
edwards won with nearly 63 percent of the vote despite unfavorable publicity during his first two terms:
_ he had acknowledged receiving $20,000 from a south korean whose dealings with congressmen and others led to the ``koreagate'' investigations
_ he had shrugged off a book written by a former aide who accused edwards of selling state jobs and conquering legions of women
_ he was investigated by the internal revenue service after all of the publicity about his gambling
_ he was investigated during the fbi ``brilab'' probe that led to the conviction of a top aide
edwards survived it all
but in these last four years, the king was felled by the collapse of oil prices, which devastated the state's economy, and continued attacks on his honesty
louisiana has one of the highest unemployment rates in the nation and the government is nearly bankrupt
his answer to economic woes this term was a lottery and casino gambling, something lawmakers would not buy. edwards lost control of the legislature partly because of his two federal racketeering trials
he went on trial in 1985, accused of brokering hospital permits obtained while in and out of office. the jury was hung with all but two voting for acquittal
in 1986, a second jury acquitted edwards and all other co-defendants, including his brother, marion, and several friends and aides
i was shunned by the legislature during and between trials,'' edwards said, planting his boots on the ground to stop the rocking chair. ``they saw how u.s. attorney john volz used the federal grand juries. they were scared. `if they can do that to you, i don't want to be close to you.' there was an aura of fear in louisiana. if volz and the other republicans could do that to me, what could they do to legislators? that was the feeling.''
the polls showed that the people went along with the lottery idea and feeling the masses were still behind him, edwards tried last year for a fourth term
as a 44-year-old congressman, he had first swept into the governor's office on a reform platform. at age 60, he was beaten by buddy roemer, a 44-year-old congressman who used a reform platform, complaining that edwards had given louisiana a banana republic image
there's always been a mania to knock the man from the top of the mountain,'' said edwards. ``but it took them a lot of years. it's been a costly journey to the top
in the last four years, it's been even worse. my family has suffered. my net worth has gone down considerably. i've paid an awesome price, onslaughts on my integrity from unfair investigations, indictments. but i think i've faced it realistically and altruistically.''
in a 1979 interview, edwards was reminded that he said that what he would like more than anything else ``is to convince people i'm honest.''
i guess that is more what i would like to do now than ever, but it seems like it is something that is going to escape me,'' he said
but i remind the people that despite all of the money spent, all of the efforts made by people over the years, they've yet to prove anything.''
what's going to happen now? can edwards relax?
for about four days,'' he said, grinning. ``i guess the phones will continue ringing, people will still come to see me. i feel nothing is going to happen with a new administration. if that's true, i will be sought out. if not, i'll try to accept that.''
in the meantime, edwards will practice law with one of his sons and offer himself to the nation's universities as a lecturer for $5,000 per appearance. he'll talk about legalized gambling and his career
he'll also hunt, gamble and, yes, flirt
i don't believe i've mellowed with age,'' he said
spring has come to central alabama: the redbuds are blooming, the fire ants are pushing up fresh mounds of earth and jesse jackson is the people's choice in dallas county, where the infamous ``bloody sunday'' attack at the edmund pettus bridge shocked the nation 23 years ago
jackson overwhelmed the presidential primary field here tuesday, 23 years and one day after alabama state troopers savagely beat black voting rights advocates attempting to march from selma to montgomery. the episode, shown on national television, helped galvanize congress to pass the federal voting rights act later that year
on tuesday, jackson carried alabama by a narrow margin. but he held better than a 5-to-1 edge over his nearest democratic challenger in dallas county, where blacks constitute 55 percent of the 50,000 residents
the official county tally showed jackson with 4,872 votes to 923 for the runner-up, sen. albert gore of tennessee. vice president george bush easily won the republican race with 1,282 votes
selma mayor joe smitherman, who was serving his first term when bloody sunday took place, said he thinks a lot of white democrats didn't vote but would have gone for bush if they'd been able to cross over. however, he acknowledges that blacks gave jackson an undeniably smashing victory in selma and dallas county
the black community really turned out for jesse. he was here a week before the election, and i accompanied him as he walked through a poor, black section of town,'' said smitherman, who admits he was a segregationist back when it was fashionable
you had to be a segregationist to be elected in the south when i was starting out,'' said the 58-year-old mayor. ``but we've matured, i've matured. we were wrong to try and deny people their right to vote, and i'm sorry for what we did.''
given the changes that have occurred in selma, smitherman said, it's really no surprise jackson did so well
however, the man who led the bloody sunday march, rep. john lewis, d-ga., professed amazement that a black could score such a victory in dallas county
to me it is simply unbelievable,'' said lewis, when contacted at his washington, d.c., office. ``when hosea williams and i led that march back in 1965, only 2.1 percent of dallas county's black residents were registered to vote.''
since then, smitherman points out, a lot of the alabama river has flowed beneath the edmund pettus bridge
when i was first elected mayor in 1964 only 50 percent of our streets were paved and less than half of our homes were connected to the sewage system. but after 1965 we started taking advantage of the federal programs and grants that existed at the time. now, every street is paved and the sewage system is all over town
also, we now have an appointed black county school superintendent who makes more damned money than i do. half of the city council is black and the assistant police chief is black. blacks probably have made more progress in selma than in any other white-controlled city in the alabama.''
the rev. joseph rembert, pastor of brown's chapel where the bloody sunday march began, acknowledges there have been changes in selma. but he adds that whites still hold most of the power and that many of the changes have come about as the result of federal court actions initiated by blacks
attitudes are slowly changing in selma,'' he said. ``but, like most places, we've still got a long way to go. what we really need here, desperately, is jobs; our county unemployment rate runs about 16 percent and it's probably as high as 25 percent for blacks.''
rembert adds, though, that he would rather be one of selma's 27,000 residents than live in a big, northern city like new york
we don't have a utopia here but at least when we stage a protest these days nobody gets hurt. blacks and whites may fight to the bone over an issue but when it's over they also may go off and have lunch together, and that's a big change from the past.''
edwin moss, one of the city's three black city councilmen, said he has seen many changes during the 73 years he has lived in selma
we've made some big political strides in this county, and we've made social progress, too,'' said moss, who founded and manages a federal credit union with a largely black membership
now,'' he added, ``we need economic progress. we need jobs. we need financing for black-owned businesses.''
smitherman, in the midst of his sixth four-year term, agrees selma needs more jobs, but he's obviously proud of his city, with its wide main street and gracious neighborhoods. he points out he couldn't be mayor without the support of both blacks and whites and is quick to show visitors his accomplishments in integrating government and improving the local standard of living
that's why i, personally, like jesse jackson's message,'' he said. ``he's talking about the same things i deal with as mayor. he's talking about jobs, about the problems of working people, about the homeless and the poor.''
you know,'' he said, ``jesse reminds me a lot of george wallace, 20 years ago. they're both populists.''
yet, he said, neither he nor most other local whites voted for jackson last tuesday
it's funny, but you'll hear a group of whites talking politics and somebody will say, `jesse makes more sense than any of them.' then he'll up and add that he's voting for bush or gore. a black's just not going to get many white votes around here, not yet at least,'' smitherman said. ``i don't know why i didn't vote for jesse, maybe it's because i don't think he can win.''
at present, there is only one elected black county official in dallas county, which is under a federal court mandate to create four voting districts _ two predominantly white and two predominantly black _ by the fall election
that one black official is district judge nathaniel walker, who left selma and got his law degree at fordham university, then returned home. walker, the first black to hold countywide office here, said he is heartened by the changes he has seen in his hometown
i was among the marchers who were attacked on bloody sunday,'' he said. ``back then, the courthouse was off limits for blacks, it was a place to be feared
but jesse's victory is an example of what we were fighting for. last tuesday's election shows that the people recognize just how dear is their right to vote and that they're determined to exercise their franchise.''
john lewis, who was hospitalized for two days with injuries he received on bloody sunday, said much the same thing
that's what the civil rights movement was all about,'' lewis said. ``we were trying to build a bi-racial democracy in alabama and throughout the south. jesse jackson's overwhelming victory in a place like selma proves this is possible.''
strat douthat is the ap southeast regional reporter, based in atlanta
canadian liquor giant seagram co. ltd. has proposed buying orange juice producer tropicana products inc. for $1.2 billion to expand seagram's share of the beverage market
the canadian liquor-and-beverage giant's acquisition of tropicana from beatrice u.s. food corp. marks a ``diversification and an expansion'' of seagram's product line, seagram chairman edgar m. bronfman said thursday
securities analysts said the move into the juice business was a logical step for seagram, which has limited growth potential from its liquor products
investor marvin davis has made an unsolicited $780.3 million offer for loss-plagued lorimar telepictures corp
lorimar, based in this los angeles suburb, said thursday that davis made the $17-a-share cash offer in a letter asking that takeover negotiations be arranged between him and lorimar's management
the announcement came just three days after lorimar disclosed it was holding preliminary talks on the possibility of being acquired by new york-based entertainment giant warner communications inc
farmers group inc., a leading insurer, says its board unanimously has rejected an unsolicited $63 per share, or $4.4 billion, tender offer from the u.s. subsidiary of britain's bat industries plc
farmers also said thursday it was urging shareholders to reject the offer
farmers consistently has spurned bat's overtures since the british company proposed a friendly $60-per-share merger in january
batus had no comment on the rejection by farmers
colt industries inc., a large defense contractor, has accepted a $526.6 million cash buyout offer from a group led by senior management and a unit of morgan stanley group inc
the $17-a-share bid for all of colt's nearly 31 million common shares outstanding was approved by the company's board of directors and is expected to begin within the next five days, a spokesman said thursday
an investment partnership which previously indicated it would top a $940 million buyout bid for afg industries inc. has decided against making an offer for the glassmaking concern
forstmann little &amp; co. said thursday it decided against making an offer based on its review of afg's internal records and its own ``adherence to strict acquisition criteria.'' it declined to elaborate
a group led by afg's founder and chairman, r.d. hubbard, said from afg's headquarters in irvine, calif., that it intended to proceed with its earlier offer to take afg private in buyout valued at $33 a share
investor burt sugarman says two companies he controls had boosted their stake in media general inc. to 10 percent from 9.8 percent and would seek a shareholder vote on his $1.75 billion takeover offer
however, virginia-based media general disputed sugarman's contentions thursday on how the company's two classifications of stock would be allowed to vote on a merger
world oil-producing nations, aware that they cannot afford another 1986-style market collapse, probably will succeed in bringing an end to the recent erosion of prices _ at least temporarily, analysts say
after three months of declines, hopes of a turnaround stirred with a report from paris that officials of the organization of petroleum exporting countries were studying a plan to shave 5 percent off the production of all 13 members except iraq
analysts said the report sent oil futures broadly higher thursday on the new york mercantile exchange, even though it later was denied by opec officials
more than 2.4 million jobs are expected to be created in the united states this year, fewer than the 3 million created in 1987 but ``still a very healthy number,'' a business research company says
manufacturers and companies with fewer than 20 employees again will be leaders in creating jobs, according to dun &amp; bradstreet corp
the company on thursday announced the results of its annual survey of employment expectations at 5,000 companies
the union representing 6,700 flight attendants for northwest airlines says the contract the airline plans to impose april 1 is unacceptable and warned travelers about the possibility of a strike during spring break
but dennis quinn, the teamsters' national strike coordinator, stopped short thursday of saying flight attendants actually would strike
this is a continuation of the threat the union has made since a feb. 26 strike deadline passed, he said. since then, the attendants have been free to strike but have not done so, and the airline had been free to impose its latest contract offer
meanwhile, union members at a rally in philadelphia accused eastern airline's parent company of trying to financially cripple the air carrier to win wage concessions
the united auto workers union has agreed to early contract negotiations with chrysler corp. and the two sides soon will set a date for the start of talks, uaw president owen bieber said
bieber said thursday the talks could begin by mid-april
the union's main reason for granting chrysler's request for early talks is that the contract expiring sept. 14 doesn't contain protections negotiated last year at ford motor co., bieber said
case ih, a worldwide maker of agriculture and construction equipment, says it will reduce employment this year by 3,000 workers, or approximately 10 percent
the company, a subsidiary of houston-based tenneco inc., said thursday the reductions would occur through layoffs of hourly and salaried workers, retirements, attrition, termination of temporary employees and a hiring freeze
the stock market fell sharply thursday, as the dow jones average of 30 industrials tumbled 48.24 to 2,026.03
bond prices fell as energy and precious metals prices rose
the dollar was mixed in foreign exchange trading
grain and soybean prices retreated and livestock and meat futures were mixed
united auto workers president owen bieber says he is optimistic that early contract negotiations with chrysler corp. will produce an early settlement and soothe chrysler's bruised labor relations
the uaw's 140-member national chrysler bargaining council, representing 71,700 chrysler workers, voted thursday to grant chrysler's request for early talks
if i was overly pessimistic, i doubt that we would have called the meeting today or taken the action that we did,'' said bieber, who along with uaw vice president marc stepp had urged the council approve the request
no date has been set for the talks aimed at replacing the existing three-year contract that expires sept. 14, but they could begin as soon as late april. talks usually begin in midsummer
there will be no strike deadline, but the two sides will set a target date for a settlement when they decide a starting date for the talks
the company is hopeful that a new contract that is equitable to both sides can be reached expeditiously,'' said chrysler spokesman lloyd northard
bieber said the union will seek a two-year contract so that in 1990, all big three automakers' contracts can be negotiated together for the first time since the union reopened its chrysler contract in 1979 to make concessions needed by the company
last fall, the union negotiated a job-protecting industry pattern contract at ford motor co. the contract quickly was accepted at gm, leaving only chrysler workers without its protections this year
the union would not have agreed to early talks if chrysler had not indicated it was willing to accept the pattern as a basis for negotiations, giving chrysler workers
the relationship between the uaw and chrysler has been badly injured in the past few months by chrysler's abortive attempt to sell its 28,000-worker acustar inc. parts subsidiary
to block the plan, which the union said was a threat to companywide job security, angry workers prepared for a series of crippling plant-by-plant strikes and stopped participating in critical union-manangement programs for improving productivity and quality
last week, chrysler backed down and stepp moved quickly to settle a dispute at a key stamping plant in sterling heights, where the first strike was to occur. weekend talks brought a settlement early monday morning
but stepp didn't tell workers to renew participation the joint programs until the thursday meeting, after he received a written promise that top chrysler executives will resume monthly meetings with top union officials
in the past two years the chrysler-uaw ``round table,'' where union and company officials had consulted on major decisions since its creation in 1979, met only once, stepp said
stepp said the lack of round table meetings indicated chrysler had changed its attitude toward its workers for the worse
with the agreement of chrysler chief negotiator anthony st. john to resume the meetings, stepp said he believes workers' anger will ease
the two sides still must work out an acustar-related sore point. chrysler said it will close four acustar plants if it can't sell them within 18 months. the uaw wants to protect the plants' 2,000 workers
during the week of march 20, national union officials and the elected 10-member rank-and-file chrysler negotiating team will draw up their demands and strategies for fitting established auto industry contracts to chrysler
the gm and ford contracts prohibit plant closings unless production is cut because of slow sales, make the transfer of work to outside suppliers more difficult and slow the rate of attrition
they also contain a profit-sharing formula based on the companies' u.s. performance. at ford, workers reaped average profit-sharing checks of more than $3,700 apiece from ford's record $4.6 billion profit
chrysler workers have no profit-sharing formula and instead receive a $500 bonus annually regardless of their company's performance
interest rates on 52-week treasury bills have risen in the latest auction to the highest level since january
the treasury department sold $9.03 billion of the bills thursday at an average discount rate of 6.3 percent, up from 6.18 percent at the last auction on feb. 11
the rates were the highest since jan. 14 when the one-year bills sold for 6.67 percent. the new discount rate understates the actual return to investors _ 6.71 percent with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,363.00
companies making computer hardware and communications equipment may be growing rapidly, but a private survey released today finds many have been less profitable than the general run of american companies during recent years
intense competition from japan and other foreign rivals is one reason for the profit squeeze on those companies, according to harvey poppel, a partner in broadview associates of fort lee, n.j., the investment banking firm that conducted the survey
a broadview survey of 269 u.s.-based hardware and equipment companies found they had a median return on equity of 6.5 percent in 1987, with a large number of poorly performing small companies dragging down the results
poppel said the median return on equity for major american companies is typically about 11 or 12 percent
return on equity is a widely used measure of a company's performance. it is the company's profit as a percentage of its shareholders' equity, or net worth
when the survey results were adjusted to give the heaviest weight to the companies with the biggest stock market values, such as highly profitable international business machines corp., the average return on equity was 10.7 percent, roughly in line with the average for american business
broadview associates specializes in mergers and acquisitions in the computer software and services industry. poppel said a survey of nearly 200 of those companies found their return on equity was above average _ about 18.6 percent last year
poppel cited several reasons for the difficulties of the computer hardware and communications equipment companies:
_japan and other aggressive competitors are willing to accept lower profit margins to gain shares of the world market
_many nations protect their home markets and domestic companies, especially in the case of western europe with telecommunications equipment
_products have short life cycles, giving companies only a short time to recoup their heavy investments
_it is easy for new companies to enter the market, especially at the low end, because the basic components such as computer chips are readily available
in contrast, poppel said the information services companies have higher return on equity because their offerings cannot easily be rendered obsolete with new technology and are protected by high barriers to entry of new competitors
prices of products such as software and database services can be kept relatively high and companies have fewer expensive assets such as factories, poppel noted
it was a marketing phenomenon that turned into the focus of an international battle with multibillion-dollar implications
within a year of introducing its $4,500 pony subcompact to north america in 1984, hyundai corp. of south korea captured 7 percent of the canadian market. it then invaded the united states and sold 168,182 of its excels in just 10 months
but were the koreans exploiting a market void or unfairly dumping the autos at below-cost prices in order to grab a share of the lucrative market?
the canadian import tribunal is considering evidence from four weeks of hearings that concluded thursday over claims by domestic automakers such as general motors corp. and ford motor co. of unfair pricing by hyundai. hyundai could be slapped with a 26 percent duty if found to be dumping cars
the case has worldwide implications as america's car giants compete against asian rivals who've grabbed more than 25 percent of their auto market
a ruling is expected march 23 and both sides have the right to appeal
in anti-dumping hearings held in ottawa, gm and ford subsidiaries in canada accused hyundai of purposely setting below-cost prices to grab a niche in the competitive small-car market
the carmakers asked the canadian import tribunal to uphold revenue canada's preliminary finding last november that hyundai has been dumping pony, excel and stellar hatchbacks and sedans in canada at an average 26 percent cheaper than they cost in south korea
a 26-percent duty would add more than $1,000 to the price of hyundais in 182 showrooms across canada and could lead to similar cases against other foreign makes
gm and ford told the tribunal they were forced to slash prices and offer cash rebates in order to compete with hyundai's bargain-basement approach
future injury is going to take the form of reduced production, reduced employment and reduced utilization of productive capacity,'' penny bonner, legal counsel for the two companies, testified thursday
hyundai acknowledged using canada as a spearhead to penetrate the american market, but argued that it never hurt gm or ford because the rear-wheel-drive pony had no direct competition at the bottom end of the market
the pony was swept along because in a real sense there was no competition,'' said hyundai lawyer richard gottlieb. he termed the success of the ``nice little car'' a fluke, coming right at the end of a recession when american carmakers virtually had given up on the sub-compact market
in surprising testimony on thursday, lawyers for the canadian government's consumer affairs department supported hyundai. they said the korean company answered a need ignored by north american manufacturers, thereby helping consumers
hyundai zoomed to a 21 percent share of the small-car market in canada in 1985 with sales of 79,072 ponies and stellars
but since the preliminary anti-dumping ruling, the canadian subsidiary has been in a tailspin and some dealers have resigned, according to company spokesman greg young
it destroyed us in the marketplace in terms of public perception and confidence in the product,'' young said
while still the third-ranked import behind honda and toyota, hyundai expects to sell just 45,000 cars this year, led by the excel, which starts at $5,835
people may say, `i like the honda civic but before making up my mind i'm going to take a look at the excel.' but the honda salesman just says, `why bother?' because of the possible duties,'' young said
but he said the bad publicity has not reached the united states, and american hyundai sales are still climbing after reaching 263,610 cars last year
to save the day in canada, hyundai has launched a ``here to stay and proud of it'' tv and newspaper advertising campaign
it pledged to proceed with a $259 million manufacturing plant in bromont, quebec, and $16 million parts factory in newmarket, ontario. scheduled to open later this year, the plants will create 1,300 jobs and give hyundai the capacity to make 100,000 new-model compacts a year
the plants will expand a canadian car industry that grew out of the milestone 1965 auto pact with the united states which permits vehicles and parts to move duty-free across the border. dominated by gm, ford and chrysler subsidiaries, the canadian car and truck plants employ 140,000 workers with another 400,000 related jobs
young said hyundai will remain in business here, but may be forced to reassess operations if anti-dumping duties are imposed
it may be step one against all import car companies, against all competition,'' he said
investor marvin davis is seeking to get back into the entertainment business by making an unsolicited $770.1 million offer for troubled lorimar telepictures corp. and has indicated he may be willing to go even higher
davis' $17-per-share cash buyout offer was disclosed thursday, only three days after lorimar announced it was holding preliminary talks about a possible acquisition by new york-based entertainment conglomerate warner communications inc
a source close to the situation indicated davis, the former owner of 20th century fox film corp., was ``very serious'' about acquiring lorimar, the culver city-based entertainment concern best known as the producer of such television programs as `dallas'' and ``knots landing.''
lorimar appeared to give short shrift to the proposal, stating that it ``would bear davis' letter in mind.''
lorimar stock rose $1 to close at $15.37{ on the american stock exchange after the announcement of davis' offer. the company has 45.3 million common shares outstanding
davis made his offer in a letter to lorimar management
on monday, lorimar and warner announced they had entered preliminary merger talks over the weekend
analysts have suggested lorimar's stock is worth between $14 and $20 per share
lorimar is a leading producer of original television programming, but in recent years has been troubled as its ambitious plans to expand into other areas disintegrated, sometimes causing the company to incur losses or heavy costs that depressed earnings
for the first nine months of its current fiscal year, lorimar posted a loss of $82.6 million on revenue of $616.8 million. the deficit included $45 million in writedowns on five movies and $22 million in reserves for possible future losses in its home-video unit
the company replaced managements of both the movie and home-video units
for the fiscal year ended last march 31, the company lost $58.6 million, mostly because of restructuring costs, on revenue of $766.2 million
davis has been seeking to get back into the entertainment industry since selling fox to media magnate rupert murdoch in 1985 for $575 million. davis had owned fox for four years, but the company was beset by persistent losses
last year, he made an unsuccessful $321.9 million bid for the 90.6 percent he didn't already own of texas-based spectradyne inc., the nation's largest supplier of cable television and pay-per-view movies for hotels
on wednesday, four disgruntled shareholders filed a class action lawsuit against lorimar in federal court alleging the company overstated its income and net worth and did not reveal problems with its home-video unit, thereby causing investors to pay more for stock then they believed they should have
afg industries inc. is left with a single suitor following an investment partnership's decision not to top the $940 million buyout bid the glassmaker already has accepted from its chairman
forstmann little &amp; co., which previously indicated it might be willing to make a higher offer, said thursday it decided against making an offer based on its review of afg's internal records and its ``adherence to strict acquisition criteria.''
a company led by afg's founder and chairman, r.d. hubbard, stated from afg headquarters in irvine, calif., that it intended to proceed with its earlier offer to take afg private in buyout valued at $33 a share
afg's stock finished down $5 a share at $31.62{ in trading on the new york stock exchange
larry selwitz, a securities analyst for the investment firm bateman eichler, hill richards in los angeles, said the odds favored hubbard's bid for the company. ``i would be really hard-pressed to see who might come into it now,'' he said
another analyst, donald pattison of cyrus j. lawrence, morgan grenfell in new york, said forstmann probably decided against proceeding because of the strong possibility that hubbard would leave the company. ``he'd go off with his own company and probably eat their lunch,'' pattison said
forstmann little announced march 2 that it proposed paying more than $33 a share in cash for all of afg's common stock, subject to a review of afg's internal corporate information and meeting with afg management
on thursday, forstmann little said it had completed the review, that afg had promptly furnished requested confidential information and that afg management had cooperated fully in the review
based on this review and forstmann little's adherence to strict acquisition criteria, it has determined that it will not make an offer to acquire afg,'' the new york-based leveraged buyout specialist said
the firm declined to elaborate
afg announced feb. 25 that it had agreed to a buyout by a new company headed by hubbard that would pay $33 a share in cash for 94 percent of afg's common stock and $33 per share in preferred stock or a combination of cash and stock for the rest of the shares
afg has 28.5 million common shares outstanding
afg is one of the leading manufacturers of window glass and has a range of specialty glass products
hubbard's offer is being made by hubbard's clarity industries corp., which is offering to buy up to 26.8 million afg common shares
meantime, clarity said two afg shareholders had filed class-action complaints in delaware seeking to block its tender offer
clarity said the shareholders alleged the agreement between clarity and afg to take the company private constitutes self-dealing, deception and unfair dealing and breaches the fiduciary duties owed afg shareholders. takeover bid</head>
an impending battle for media general inc. is heating up, with television producer burt sugarman boosting his stake in the company and signaling a fight to force a shareholder vote on his $1.75 billion buyout bid
sugarman said thursday that two companies he controls boosted their stake in media general, the virginia-based broadcasting and publishing corporation to 10 percent from 9.8 percent
sugarman also repeated his contention that media general's board of directors was legally bound to put his buyout plan to a shareholder vote
however, media general disputed sugarman's contentions on how the company's two classifications of stock would be allowed to vote on a merger
media general has 28 million shares of class a common stock entitled to one vote each and 559,168 class b shares that have disproportionate voting rights and elect seven of the company's 10 directors
the family of media general's chairman, d. tennant bryan, owns 71 percent of the company's class b stock
shortly after sugarman made his $61.50-per-share takeover offer late last month, the bryan family said it wasn't interested in selling the company
in a letter sent thursday to media general's president and chief executive officer, james s. evans, sugarman contended that under media general's charter all shareholders should have equal voting rights in deciding on a proposed acquisition of the company by someone holding at least 10 percent of its stock
in all other cases, the class b stock would retain its special voting rights, sugarman contended
sugarman reiterated that if media general directors failed to put the proposed merger before shareholders, they ``will be breaching their fiduciary duty.''
media general disputed sugarman's claims, saying ``company counsel found sugarman's legal reasoning incorrect.''
media general said that under its charter any merger would require the vote of two-thirds of each class of stock. in addition to the charter requirement, the company said, virginia law requires that a merger be approved by more than two-thirds of the class b stock
media general owns a number of daily papers, including the richmond (va.) times-dispatch and news leader, the winston-salem (n.c.) journal and the tampa (fla.) tribune, plus 32 weeklie in southern california and a 40 percent interest in garden state newspapers inc., which owns 18 dailies and four weeklies in eight states. it also owns television stations, including wcbd-tv in charleston, s.c., wjks-tv in jacksonville, fla., and wxfl-tv in tampa, fla
sugarman is making his takeover bid through two companies he controls _ barris industries inc., the creator of tv programs such as ``the dating game,'' ``the newlywed game'' and ``the gong show,'' and giant group ltd., the parent of keystone cement co. and giant cement co. with units in pennsylvania and south carolina
take one liquor company, add one orange juice company, and the resulting mix could be a satisfying corporate cocktail _ at least that's how some industry experts characterized seagram co. ltd.'s plans to buy tropicana products inc
the $1.2 billion deal announced thursday will expand seagram's share of the beverage market and could result in a wider line of tropicana products, said robert s. reitzes, who follows seagram for the investment firm mabon, nugent &amp; co. in new york
it's a good fit,'' reitzes said ``it makes sense in their business.''
the canadian liquor-and-beverage giant's acquisition of tropicana from beatrice u.s. food corp. marks a diversification and expansion of seagram's product lines, seagram chairman edgar m. bronfman stated in announcing the deal
we have already broadened our base with seagram's (wine) coolers, and tropicana is another step in this direction,'' bronfman said
analysts said the move into the juice business was a logical step for seagram, which faced limited growth potential from its liquor business
they understand the business, and it's growing unlike most of their liquor products,'' said ian osler, an analyst with prudential-bache securities inc. in toronto
seagram will finance the acquisition _ to be made through the company's u.s. subsidiary, joseph e. seagram &amp; sons inc. _ initially with a combination of bank loans and short-term borrowings, seagram said
montreal-based seagram, best known for its distilled spirits and wines, in recent years moved into production of wine coolers and the sale of mixers such as tonic and ginger ale under the seagram name
seagram also is in the process of acquiring french cognac producer martell &amp; co. in a deal valued at $930 million. it also owns a 23 percent stake in du pont co
tropicana, headquartered in bradenton, fla., is a leading manufacturer and distributor of ready-to-serve orange juice and frozen concentrate. it had sales of about $750 million in its last fiscal year, which ended feb. 29, said marcelline thomson, a seagram spokeswoman in new york
seagram had net income of nearly $423.5 billion on sales of $3.3 billion in the fiscal year ended jan. 31, 1987. it reported a profit of more than $402.4 million on sales of $2.6 billion for the nine months ended oct. 31
chicago-based beatrice u.s. food corp. is a division of closely-held beatrice co., which put itself up for sale last september. the company also is considering the sale of its hunt-wesson operations, which produce vegetable oils, ketchup and la choy brand chinese food
beatrice co.'s predecessor, beatrice cos., was taken private in 1986 in a $6.2 billion leveraged buyout led by kohlberg kravis roberts &amp; co. since then it has sold most of its major assets, including avis car rental, international playtex inc. and its international foods business
a number of beatrice's consumer products businesses were spun off as e-ii holdings inc., which last month agreed to be acquired by american brands inc. after making a brief takeover move against the company
beatrice chairman donald kelly, who also is chairman of e-ii, had hoped to sell beatrice whole but could not find a buyer at his asking price, reportedly $4.5 billion
the credo of banana republic's new travel magazine is simple _ people shouldn't travel halfway around the world only to find the same hamburger joints they've got back home
we are on the brink of becoming mcglobe,'' warns mel ziegler, president of the san francisco-based clothier and editor-in-chief of trips, a quarterly launched nationwide this week
ziegler says 300,000 customers already have expressed interest in $10-a-year subscriptions to the magazine, which promises to ``lead you down the back alleys of cairo, onto forbidden islands or through your own hometown, in search of stories that will transcend the distinctions between traveler and fantasist...''
we wanted to publish the world's first honest travel magazine,'' he said in a recent interview. ``if you read most travel magazines, you get the idea travel is painless, nothing ever goes wrong. we all know nobody ever takes a trip like that.''
trips, which takes an iconoclastic approach to globe-trotting, is aimed at the same affluent urbanites who made such a success of the 10-year-old adventure-wear company, which was sold to the gap clothing chain for an undisclosed sum in 1983
it also attempts to latch onto a recent boom in travel magazines that has seen a handful of new publications in recent months
the inaugural issue is a trek into the offbeat and bizarre
articles include a journey through the apartheid world of south africa, bicycling with the 400-pound king of tonga in the south pacific and sneaking onto a secret hawaiian island
an interview with rod nordland, a correspondent-at-large for newsweek magazine, is billed as ``a palm-greasing primer'' on the art of baksheesh, the arabic word for petty bribery
but the advice doesn't just center on money: the article advises that a pack of cigarettes may convince a taxi driver in angola to get you to the airport and a bottle of liquor or contact points for a '57 chevy can get you just about anything in burma
also included is a section where world-weary travelers pass on tips to surviving off the beaten path
these include suggestions to carry a golf ball in your luggage, because many of the world's hotels don't have drain plugs, and to carry a roll of toilet paper not only for obvious uses but also for insulating boots, wrapping wounds, and serving as barter
trips is entering a rapidly expanding market. in 1986, the most recent year for which figures are available, americans spent $257 billion on domestic travel and $24.5 billion overseas, according to the new york times
as a result, travel magazines are enjoying a renaissance. the newhouse media conglomerate in september began publishing conde nast's traveler which, like trips, promises not to whitewash getaway spots. fairchild publications' travel today, a weekly tabloid, hit newsstands in january
ziegler says many americans he meets traveling these days are not on ``tour packages seeing foreign ports from a bubble, nor are they backpackers...
these are working people who have saved some money who like to enjoy cultures fully by immersing themselves in it.'' `unacceptable'</head>
the union representing 6,700 northwest airlines flight attendants is warning travelers about the possibility of a strike during the busy spring break
as the travel increases over spring break and easter, it is to our advantage to keep ready for a strike,'' dennis quinn, the teamsters' national strike coordinator, told a news conference thursday
however, he added, ``we have not set a firm strike deadline at this time.''
quinn's comments came as the union termed unacceptable the contract which northwest plans to impose april 1
the minneapolis airline has been free to impose the contract since a feb. 26 strike deadline passed and the union has been free to strike
terry erskine, northwest's vice president of law and labor relations, said he would not rule out making changes in the contract before april 1 if the union comes forward with suggestions
but quinn said, ``northwest intends to force a strike. it is moving into a situation where there are no other alternatives but a work stoppage, and that it is a very good reason for you to indicate, yes, we are serious.''
northwest spokesman redmond tyler denounced the teamster announcement as ``rhetoric'' and said spring travelers would encounter no problems even in the event of a strike
continue to plan your travel because we anticipate no disruption in service,'' tyler said. ``we regret any attempt to intimidate ... we are disappointed our employees would take this tactic to confuse their company's customers.''
meanwhile, a taped message on a teamsters hotline for flight attendants criticized the contract and said the company's move did not end the union's right to strike
northwest assumes you will accept this substandard contract. please show them how wrong they are,'' dottie malinsky, president of teamsters local 2747, which represents the minneapolis unit, told attendants on the taped message
this company action will backfire on them. nickel and diming the employees is not going to change the bad management at northwest,'' she said
teamsters have called a strategy meeting monday in washington, d.c., for local union officers and strike captains at northwest. leaders of the unions representing northwest ground workers and pilots are expected to attend that meeting, malinsky said
claudia bushbaum, secretary-treasurer for teamsters local 2747, said the airline's offer to negotiate on the contract was meaningless. northwest is unwilling to bend on the issue of when to elevate lower-paid employees, who are on what the company and union call a b pay scale, to higher pay scales, she said
if the company does not come back to the table and negotiate and move off of their position of the extended b pay scale, there is all likelihood we will strike when the time is right,'' bushbaum said. ``they're willing to sit across the table from you and say they're going to negotiate, but sitting across the table from you and saying `no' is not negotiations. and that is exactly the way northwest negotiates when we talk about the b pay scale.''
under the new contract, northwest says union membership would no longer be a condition of employment. bushbaum, who called that a ``union-busting tactic,'' said teamsters' attorneys were reviewing the legality of this action
erskine said wednesday that if attendants decide to strike now, the airline is prepared to hire permanent replacements. picks up 3rd graf pvs, the subcommittee ... a version moving on general news wires.</note>
labor secretary ann mclaughlin today said a proposal to raise the federal minimum wage to $5.05 an hour over the next four years may sound ``like the right thing to do'' but it actually would cause a loss of jobs
mrs. mclaughlin said the proposed increase, likely to be approved next week by the house education and labor committee, would be particularly hard on young people with no skills who are seeking their first jobs
this is a tough one. $5.05 an hour, i'm afraid would make almost any economist have some jitters,'' mrs. mclaughlin said in an interview on nbc-tv's ``today'' show. ``the body of economic thinking is that the increase in the minimum wage, while well-intentioned and it sounds like the right thing to do, actually will cause a loss of jobs, particularly impacting on young people who need to get into the workforce.''
education and labor committee chairman augustus f. hawkins, d-calif., scheduled a session next wednesday for final action on the minimum wage bill. the panel had been unable on thursday to address all the amendments to a proposal that was approved by the house labor standards subcommittee a week ago
the subcommittee approved an increase from $3.35 to $4.65 an hour over a three-year period, with a 50-cent raise in 1989 and a 40-cent jump in both 1990 and 1991
during the full committee's hearing, rep. carl c. perkins, d-ky., proposed an amendment for an increase of another 40 cents in 1992 in an effort to keep the federal minimum at approximately one half of the nation's average wage
the committee approved the perkins amendment on a vote of 18-14 with only two democrats, reps. austin j. murphy of pennsylvania and timothy j. penny of minnesota, joining republicans in opposing the proposal
murphy, chairman of the labor standards subcommittee, said his panel had fashioned a measure which would be acceptable to the full house and the senate and possibly the white house
we don't know what impact the fourth year will have on the loss of jobs,'' murphy said
rep. stephen j. solarz, d-n.y., however, read from a letter written to hawkins by labor secretary ann mclaughlin who said senior white house advisers would recommend to president reagan that he veto any legislation increasing the minimum wage
it doesn't matter what we do; the executive will be against it,'' he said
rep. dick armey, r-tex., who opposes any increase, proposed an amendment to the perkins measure to raise the base to $20 an hour, but withdrew it after hawkins called it absurd
the committee approved 20-13 an amendment by rep. tommy f. robinson, d-ark., to increase the ``tip credit'' for restaurant employers
current law allows employers of workers who regularly receive tips _ such as waiters and waitresses _ to count the tips as earned wages equivalent to 40 percent of the minimum wage
thus, a restaurant owner could pay a worker $2.01 an hour, with the remaining $1.34 _ 40 percent of today's $3.35-an-hour minimum wage _ supposed to come from tips
the robinson proposal would increase the credit to 50 percent
the senate has a companion bill, sponsored by sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., chairman of the labor and human resources committee, which raises the minimum wage to $4.65 an hour over a three-year period. news wires.</note>
retail sales, boosted by strength in autos, rose 0.6 percent in february, following a january decline, the government reported today
the commerce department said that retail sales rose a seasonally adjusted $714 million to $127.99 billion last month
while the february increase was generally in line with expectations, the government revised the january report to show a small decline of 0.2 percent, instead of an originally reported increase of 0.5 percent
even with the january decline, analysts said the retail sales report generally reflected that the october stock market crash has had little effect on consumer buying plans
ever since the record 508-point drop in stock prices which occurred on oct. 19, economists have been closely watching to see whether the consumer sector would weaken
since consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of overall economic activity, any significant faltering in this area could topple the country into a recession
continued strong gains in employment growth have apparently calmed initial jitters over the stock market. many economists have recently revised up their growth forecasts for 1988
the february report said that retail sales rose to the highest monthly total since august 1987
much of the strength came from a 1.6 percent rise in auto sales, which followed an even stronger 2 percent increase in new car sales in january
without the gain in autos, which accounted for almost one-fourth of total sales last month, retail sales would have risen a smaller 0.3 percent in february
the important general merchandise category, which includes department store sales, suffered a 1.6 percent decline in sales in february following a small 0.1 percent drop in january sales
sales of all durable goods, items expected to last three or more years, were up 1.6 percent in february while sales of non-durable goods edged down 0.1 percent
in the durable goods category, sales at building materials and hardware stores jumped a sharp 2.3 percent
sales at furniture and appliance stores were up 0.3 percent in february following an even stronger 2.7 percent january increase
sales at specialty clothing stores climbed 0.6 percent in february, only a partial rebound following a giant 3.3 percent january decline
sales at gasoline stations fell 1.6 percent in february while sales at restaurants edged up 0.1 percent and sales at drug stores posted a 0.6 percent increase
sales at grocery stores enjoyed a 0.7 percent rise in sales in february, reversing a 0.6 percent january decline. options and expenses, and total outstanding shares.</note>
colt industries inc., a major defense contractor and industrial concern, has agreed to be taken private in a $660 million leveraged buyout led by senior management and the investment firm morgan stanley group inc
the board of colt, whose name may be best known from its firearms business, approved an offer of $17 a share for all of its approximately 31.65 million common shares outstanding late wednesday and announced the plan on thursday. the price of colt stock options and expenses was included in the total price of the buyout
the offer was subject to several conditions, including a majority of the shares being tendered
colt shares surged $4.87{ to $18.12{ on the new york stock exchange on thursday, indicating some speculators believed an offer higher than the group's $17 a share bid would emerge
under the transaction, colt would become a wholly-owned subsidiary of colt holdings inc., a new company formed by the management team and morgan stanley leveraged equity fund ii, colt stated. about $1.4 billion of colt debt would remain outstanding, it said
the morgan stanley leveraged equity fund ii is a limited partnership that invests in leveraged buyouts, or deals in which a company is acquired largely with borrowed funds repaid through the target company's profits or sale of its assets
colt said morgan stanley and its equity fund unit have agreed to provide $460 million in short-term bridge financing for colt holdings, which would be repaid through a public or private offering of long-term debt
investors in colt holdings would put up another $200 million, colt said
colt chairman david i. margolis said the merger agreement would give colt ``the opportunity to establish and implement a more aggressive business program, including acquisition, than we could have undertaken alone.''
colt is a leading supplier of aerospace, automotive and industrial products. it employs about 22,000 people
