oil prices may be headed higher again, after months of declines amid swelling inventories and lackluster demand
analysts say prospects of good summer demand and indications that major producers might take action to help curb the recent slide should help boost prices in coming months
unconfirmed reports that the organization of petroleum exporting countries was studying a plan to shave 850,000 barrels from its daily production sent futures contracts soaring on thursday, and that rally continued today
near midday on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, stood at $16.19 per 42-gallon barrel, up 19 cents from thursday, when the price closed up 51 cents at $16.00
refined products also built on thursday's strong advance. wholesale heating oil, up 0.90 cent thursday, stood at 44.44 cents per gallon, up another 0.51 cent. wholesale unleaded gasoline stood at 45.55 cents per gallon, up 0.41 cent after leaping 1.14 cents per gallon to close at 45.14 cents thursday
james steel, an analyst at refco inc. commodities, said traders were encouraged by reports that opec was considering cutbacks, even though cartel officials later denied that the purported idea of 5 percent output cuts for all 13 members except iraq was getting serious consideration
the organization of petroleum exporting countries also indicated that its pricing committee was unlikely to meet soon, despite calls by member venezuela for a meeting
but steel said futures traders pushed prices higher because the reports suggested the cartel was at least taking some action to deal with the declines before they started getting out of hand
in the persian gulf, for example, crude recently has been selling at levels between $13 and $14 per barrel _ far below opec's $18-per-barrel target _ while in the united states, west texas intermediate has been bouncing in the $15-to-$16 range after selling near $18 in january
analysts have blamed the slump on sluggish worldwide demand and swelling inventories, worsened by an unusually warm winter in europe
some opec members, desperate to preserve their market shares, have aggravated the decline by discounting prices to lure customers away from opec competitors and ``nopec'' countries, such as mexico, britain, norway and a host of other smaller nations
dillard spriggs, president of the petroleum analysis ltd. consulting firm, said crude prices could fall another dollar in two weeks if world production does not slow down quickly
in a worst-case scenario, buyers might then disappear to wait for even lower prices, heightening downward price pressure
but chances are probably pretty good they'll rein it in,'' spriggs said, citing prospects for increased summer demand. ``i think we're in this cycle of up-and-down that will go on until about 1990.''
analysts said opec's problem was that the production quotas the cartel set at its december meeting simply were too high
since december, opec's official aggregate quota has stood at 17.5 million barrels a day. spriggs said the cartel would have to cut production to about 16.8 million barrels daily to match demand and bring prices back to its $18-per-barrel target
as a result, cartel members had to discount the extra barrels to sell them, said ed krapels, of the washington-based energy security analysis inc. consulting firm
still, krapels said, ``the worst is over,'' because demand should pick up during the summer driving season
we expect the situation to be a little easier for opec to handle in the next three months than in the last three,'' he said
at the oppenheimer &amp; co. securities firm, oil analyst paul ting said he also believed oil prices will head higher, continuing in a cycle of ``strengths and weakness.''
opec is all too aware of the billions of dollars of income it lost by casting off production constraints in 1986, he said
back in 1985, nobody in his right mind would have thought oil could drop below $18 a barrel. they got quite a surprise when it got down to $8. i think they're not likely to repeat that again,'' ting said
i think they're going to get their acts together (because) they really can't live at prices significantly below $18 for a long time,'' he said
the stock market lost more ground today, extending thursday's sharp decline
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, down 48.24 points on thursday, dropped 3.65 to 2,022.38 by 11 a.m. today on wall street
losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 6 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 604 up, 693 down and 506 unchanged
volume on the big board came to 93.71 million shares at midmorning
a big chunk of that activity came in the stock of mfs intermediate income trust, which traded at 10 after a 200 million-share initial offering at that price
the debut of the closed-end investment company specializing in interest-bearing securities of 10 years or less marked the largest initial public stock offering ever in the u.s. market
otherwise, analysts said traders were a bit unnerved by thursday's drop, which was the largest in more than two months
stocks drew some support, however from falling interest rates in the credit markets, where prices of long-term treasury bonds rose as much as $5 for each $1,000 in face value
the bond market got a lift from news of an unexpected 0.2 percent decline in the producer price index last month and a relatively modest 0.6 percent rise in retail sales for the same period
among actively traded blue chips, general electric dropped \ to 42}; american express { to 26|; international business machines [ to 113|, and dow chemical 1\ to 85]
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost .08 to 148.84. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was down .27 at 295.73
while the market for new stocks has turned chilly since black monday last oct. 19, wall street has found strong demand for one category of new issue _ closed-end bond funds
in the first two months of 1988, standard &amp; poor's reports, investors snapped up more than $3.5 billion in shares of these investments
on friday, massachusetts financial services of boston added $2 billion more to the total with the debut of its mfs intermediate income trust, in what stands as the largest initial public stock offering ever
the attraction of these funds is not the hope of spectacular growth or quick trading profits, but rather yields as high as the 10 percent to 11{ percent range
there is no denying the appeal of such returns, especially in a period when interest rates have been generally declining, pushing the yield available on long-term government bonds below 8.5 percent
but some analysts wonder whether all the eager buyers look beyond the yield to gain a full understanding of this particular breed of security and how it has often behaved in the past
a closed-end fund operates very much like a mutual fund, with one very important difference
mutual funds stand continuously ready to sell new shares and redeem old ones, at a price that is determined by the net asset value of their portfolios on any given day
shares of closed-end funds, by contrast, are traded like any other stock on an exchange or in the over-the-counter market
the number of shares remains fixed, except for special occasions on which the fund might decide to increase it with a new offering or reduce it by buying in some of its stock
so while the operating performance of a mutual fund is the sole determinant of its price, a closed-end fund's price is also influenced by supply and demand forces in the open market
its shares can trade at a premium above net asset value, or a discount below net asset value
during periods of strength in fixed-income markets, such as at present, some bond funds may temporarily sell at a premium to nav,'' standard &amp; poor's analysts observe in the firm's weekly publication the outlook
if history is any guide, however, the premiums tend to shrink and give way to discounts once interest rates begin to rise.''
closed-end funds of all types have enjoyed a revival of interest in the past few years. fund managers say they like the format because it allows them to pursue their investment strategies undisturbed by the ebb and flow of money that can occur in mutual funds
in theory at least, a popular mutual fund may have to make bigger or riskier bets than it would like when money pours into its coffers. conversely, it may have to sell securities it would rather keep when redemptions increase
the recent evidence lends some support to this view. s&amp;p quotes statistics from lipper analytical services showing an average total return of 85 percent over the last five years for closed-end bond funds
in the same period, a comparable group of fixed-income mutual funds averaged a total return of 72 percent
nevertheless, veteran observers of closed-end funds say, when you are approached by a broker recommending a new fund, it makes sense to look at the similar alternatives that may be available in existing funds
says s&amp;p: ``consider acquiring a closed-end fund in the after-market, when premiums often shrink after a few months and you need pay only a normal brokerage commission and not a built-in initial underwriting fee of about 7 percent.''
campeau corp. says it has moved closer to completing the financing for its $6.18 billion tender offer for federated department stores inc
campeau is fighting a competing $6.1 billion offer by r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. to buy federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailing company. seeking support for its bid, campeau has announced each step in its efforts to win financing as they have been reached
campeau said thursday that citibank of new york and the new york branch of sumitomo of japan have agreed to provide $1.5 billion of a $2.66 billion secured loan that would be used in connection with purchase of federated shares
the toronto-based retailer said in a statement the two banks were confident the remaining $1.16 billion needed for the loan could be obtained through a syndicate of banks
campeau also said citibank would provide $1 billion and sumitomo $500 million of $3.13 billion in long term financing for the federated acquisition after the tender offer
campeau has offered to pay $75 a share in cash for 80 percent of federated's stock and $44 a share in cash for the remaining 20 percent
the macy proposal, which is backed by federated management and the company's board of directors, would pay $74.50 a share in cash for 80 percent of federated's shares and stock in the merged company, macy's-federated inc., for the remaining 20 percent
campeau earlier announced $1.5 billion in bridge financing from first boston corp., its financial adviser, and $1.4 billion in equity to put into the federated acquisition
the equity includes a $480 million loan from youngstown developer edward j. debartolo, $500 million in secured bank loans, $260 million in debentures from olympia &amp; york developments ltd., and a portion of the $770 million campeau expects to realize from the proposed sale of the brooks brothers division of its allied stores corp
besides the $3.13 billion in bank financing, campeau has agreed to sell federated's filene's stores in boston and foley's in houston to st. louis-based may department stores inc. for between $1.3 billion and $1.5 billion in cash and notes
campeau and macy have both indicated they would sell federated's non-department store holdings, which include ralphs supermarkets, gold circle discount stores and children's place and main street specialty retailers
in a filing this week with the securities and exchange commission, macy indicated $2.9 billion in federated assets would be sold if its bid is successful. macy said the non-department store divisions would be put up for sale as well as ``certain other assets.''
analysts believe macy would sell two department store divisions, abraham &amp; straus and rich's, which directly compete with macy stores
