fred w. o'green will retire at the end of this month after a 26-year career with the litton industries inc., the last seven as chairman, the company said friday
o'green, 66, will be succeeded as chairman by orion l. hoch, 59, who will retain his post as litton's chief executive
litton is a technology-based conglomerate involved in advanced electronics and defense systems, industrial automation and geophysical services
former merchant banker lord patrick spens was freed on $920,000 bail raised by two friends after appearing in court friday to hear charges related to the guinness financial scandal
spens, a former managing director of merchant bankers henry ansbacher and co. ltd, was arrested and charged thursday for his alleged role in one of britain's largest financial scandals
he was ordered to appear in court again april 12 along with four others charged so far in the affair, surrender his passport to police and not to contact employees from the ansbacher group
two business friends _ alan lewis, the chairman of a textiles company, and charles longbottom, former chairman of an ansbacher subsidiary _ paid spens' bail, the british domestic news agency press association reported
police are investigating guinness' tactics during its $4 billion 1986 takeover of distillers co. plc, a scotch whisky and gin maker, in what was then britain's biggest acquisition ever
spens, 45, resigned from henry ansbacher in january 1987 under pressure from the bank of england, and told reporters his alleged role in the guinness affair was perceived as an error of judgment
he was subsequently charged in two counts with involvement in the improper payment of an interest-free loan of $14 million from guinness to ansbachers to fund the buying of more than 2 million shares in the brewing giant
two other counts allege falsification of a document for ansbachers and conspiracy to create a false or misleading impression of the market value of guinness shares
guinness has admitted arranging the allegedly illegal repurchase of its stock in an apparent effort to boost the price and make its cash and stock offer for distillers more attractive than a rival bid from argyll group plc, a supermarket operator.  
here are the major business events and economic events scheduled for the coming week (some dates are tentative):

cleveland _ a federal judge has scheduled a hearing to review the constitutionality of ohio's anti-takeover law, filed by the italian tiremaker pirelli in an attempt to prevent firestone tire &amp; rubber co. from using the law to thwart pirelli's $1.86 billion buyout bid
washington _ business inventories for january will be released at 10 a.m. by the commerce department

washington _ the current account report covering trade in merchandise and services, for fourth quarter 1987, will be released at 10 a.m. by the commerce department
detroit _ the nation's automakers will release auto sales for first 10 days of march
london _ chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson presents the british budget to parliament

washington _ housing starts for february will be released at 8:30 a.m. by the commerce department; industrial production for february will be released at 9:15 a.m. by the federal reserve
washington _ the house labor committee has scheduled a final vote on legislation increasing the federal minimum wage to $5.05 an hour over next four years
richmond _ a bankrupcty hearing is scheduled to review latest version of a.h. robins co. reorganization plan

washington _ merchandise trade for january will be released at 8:30 a.m. by the commerce department; factory use for february, release time uncertain, by the federal reserve
