analysts said traders were a bit unnerved by thursday's drop in stock prices, which was the largest in more than two months
but a midsession slide gave way to buying as the dow jones industrial average dropped to near the 2,000 level
stocks drew some support from falling interest rates in the credit markets, where prices of long-term treasury bonds rose more than $5 for each $1,000 in face value
the bond market got a lift from news of an unexpected 0.2 percent decline in the producer price index last month and a relatively modest 0.6 percent rise in retail sales for the same period
why do americans have different beers for different times of the day, asked a visiting soviet public relations executive who was confused by some u.s. advertising techniques and wound up confusing his hosts
valentin v. kozitsyn, who is traveling with a soviet cultural exhibit now at cincinnati's union terminal center, had some questions for members of the cincinnati public relations company he visited thursday
employees at smith kaufman public relations were confused by his beer question
they understood when kozitsyn explained that he had seen a television commercial saying ``the night belongs to michelob.''
and another thing: ``why is k mart america's favorite store?'' he asked
any advertising or public relations effort in the soviet union is ``done very slowly, with much care and deliberation,'' kozitsyn said. he described the american media as fast, colorful and timely
there is much to learn about the methods here,'' he said
much of thursday's informal discussion was spent explaining to kozitsyn the distinctions between u.s. advertising, public relations and journalism
in our country, it isn't so important to explain everything,'' he said
kozitsyn said interest in public relations methodology is increasing in the soviet union because the country, under communist party leader mikhail gorbachev, is taking a hard look at its traditions
we have not only successes _ we have mistakes,'' kozitsyn said. ``there is a need for us to explain our mistakes in history and modern life. ... there is the need to understand truths.''
there is much we need to teach our own people, and much to learn about accomplishing that,'' kozitsyn said
lora l. doerr, an account supervisor with smith kaufman, said the cincinnati firm first came in contact with kozitsyn while arranging publicity for the exhibit
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, down more than 20 points at midafternoon, closed with a gain of 8.95 at 2,034.98. for the week the average lost 22.88 points
advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 5 on the new york stock exchange, with 864 up, 658 down and 458 unchanged
big board volume totaled 200.02 million shares, against 197.26 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index rose .53 to 149.45
crude oil prices moved deeper into $16-a-barrel territory friday, but analysts disagreed as to whether fundamental or technical factors were responsible for the two-day breakout above the $15 range
some said traders were anticipating new moves by oil producing countries to trim their excessive output, bringing world supply and demand closer into balance. others, noting that continuous profit-taking had dampened the rally friday, suggested that it lacked strong conviction
contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, closed 29 cents higher at $16.29 per 42-gallon barrel on the new york mercantile exchange, adding to thursday's strong 51-cent gain
refined products also built on thursday's robust advance. wholesale heating oil settled at 44.69 cents a gallon, up 0.76 cent after thursday's 0.90 cent gain. wholesale unleaded gasoline closed at 45.59 cents a gallon, up 0.45 cent after leaping 1.14 cents thursday
there's a growing confidence that, by whatever means it might take, our oil-exporting friends will contain the discounting and get prices moving up,'' said bob baker, an analyst for prudential-bache securities inc
since late last year, sluggish demand and growing surpluses have put downward pressure on oil prices. that weakness was aggravated by discounting on the part of members of the organization of petroleum exporting countries
analysts said the 13-nation cartel has been sticking to its aggregate quota of 17.5 million barrels a day, but that the total goal, set in december, was simply too high for the world's needs
as a result, by early this week prices had eroded to levels between $13 and $14 per barrel in the persian gulf _ far short of opec's $18 target _ and to $15.37 per barrel on the new york merc, $2 to $3 cheaper than january levels
indications that worried opec and non-member countries were attempting to find ways to boost those prices sent the market strongly higher thursday _ although crude had picked up 12 cents in light trading on tuesday and wednesday
while crude continued to gain ground in friday's session, however, product prices did not ``put in all that good a showing,'' said jayne ball, an analyst at the dean witter reynolds inc. securities firm
at this point, it's unclear whether this is just a technical correction ... or whether it's a serious recovery,'' she said
the first national bank of boston agreed friday to freeze activity on panamanian government accounts until the state department lifts sanctions against the nation
the action stems from a civil suit filed earlier this week by panama's u.s. ambassador, juan b. sosa, the recognized representative of the government of deposed president eric arturo delvalle
a federal judge tuesday issued a temporary injunction against payments to any panamanian government agency from accounts at bank of boston and four florida-based banks. in addition, a restraining order was issued friday by a federal judge in new york against the bank of boston international, which holds a panama government clearing account
under a settlement filed in u.s. district court in boston, the bank of boston prohibits transactions against any account of the republic of panama, banco nationale de panama or petroterminale de panama, unless approved by sosa
bank of boston, however, can transfer up to $4 million a month to petroterminale from its panama branch to cover salaries and operating expenses for the company, which runs a ship fuel pipeline alongside the panama canal
the settlement, presented to district judge edward harrington, was reached following talks between lawyers representing the bank and the delvalle government, overthrown in late february by gen. manuel antonio noriega
attorney michael gardener, representing the delvalle government, estimated the bank of boston handles ``several million dollars'' in panamanian government assets
bank spokesman wayne taylor declined to estimate a figure, but said the bank's settlement may set a precedent for sosa's suit against the florida banks
defendants in that suit are the citizens and southern international bank, republic national bank of miami, barnett bank of florida and the bank of new england international
a federal judge in miami has scheduled a march 16 hearing for the suit
on march 7, a federal judge in new york added 10 days to a restraining order preventing marine midland and bankers trust from transferring an estimated $50 million to the banco nationale de panama
irving trust was dropped from that order after agreeing not to transfer any money to the panama bank. last wednesday, another defendant, republic national bank of new york, was dropped when it agreed to transfer $10 million in panamanian funds to the federal reserve bank
delvalle is still recognized by the u.s. government as the legitimate head of panama
two u.s. grand juries in florida indicted noriega on drug charges feb. 4. delvalle sought to dismiss noriega feb. 25, but was ousted the next day by noriega supporters and went into hiding
a former defense industry official was sentenced friday to three years in prison and fined $5,000 for his part in a scheme that overcharged the government nearly $9 million in military contracts
roland edward fisher, 57, of suburban drexel hill, former vice president and general manager of litton systems, inc., pleaded unsuccessfully for leniency through his attorney before u.s. district judge robert kelly
litton was earlier fined $6.3 million for its part in the price-rigging conspiracy
assistant u.s. attorney nicholas harbest, in seeking lengthy incarceration, said ``fisher was entrusted with the taxpayer's funds and abused that trust. a prison sentence will send a ringing message to other defense industry executives that this type of conduct will no longer go unnoticed and unpunished.''
harbest told the judge that fisher, between january 1975 and december 1984, set prices for the goverment contracts litton obtained that were well above the real costs to produce the item and that other individual defendants participated in the scheme
specifically, fisher was found guilty of racketeering, obstruction of a government agency's proceedings, making false statements and mail fraud
two other litton employees were sentenced earlier in the case
michael millspaugh, 35, a former controller from buffalo grove, ill., received one year and a $10,000 fine, while joseph diliberto, 69, a former materials manager, of levittown, pa., received 5 years' probation and a $10,000 fine
both had pleaded guilty. problems</head>
the new york stock exchange's 5-week-old ``collar'' on computerized trading appears to be an effective therapy for easing volatility in the post-crash market and luring back frightened investors, analysts say
but the restriction also makes the market less attractive to investors who thrive on risk, which could drive them overseas
and some market experts even argue that the restriction would do little to squelch another panic
the collar, as nyse officials call it, has played a role in blunting runaway moves in the dow jones industrial average since it was enacted feb. 4, judging from the market's behavior since then
it works by banning use of the exchange's computers for a trading technique known as index arbitrage when the dow average moves 50 points from the previous close. an earlier, voluntary restraint was triggered by a 75-point change
since the 50-point collar was announced, it has never been breached. the dow average approached it three times, moving up 47.58 on feb. 10, up 48.41 on feb. 29, and down 48.24 on thursday
i think it's got to be more than coincidence that it doesn't get to 50,'' said richard wholey, a broker-analyst at the wayne hummer &amp; co. investment firm in chicago. ``i would say there's got to be a very strong connection.''
by comparison, in pre-collar days the dow average jumped 76.42 points jan. 4, fell 140.58 points jan. 8 and fell 57.20 points jan. 20. it exceeded a 50-point swing six times in december and four times in november
last october, when the market suffered the worst decline since the great crash of 1929, the dow average careened over 50 points 12 times, capped by the unprecedented 508 point plunge on black monday, oct. 19
some wall street strategists knowledgeable about index arbitrage believe the collar directly influences market behavior. when index arbitrage traders see the dow average moving 40 or more points beyond the previous close, they turn off the computers that run the automatic trading programs
the limit is a definite factor,'' said leigh stevens, stock index futures strategist at painewebber inc. in new york. ``the traders will see they are near it. they'll stop at that point, because if it's going to touch 50, they'd be forbidden to use it for the rest of the day.''
index arbitrage enables investors to sell massive volumes of stock in new york and simultaneously buy the equivalent stock-index futures traded in chicago, or vice versa, in an attempt to profit from price differences
the technique has been blamed for playing a role in the wall street crash and subsequent price swings that frightened millions of ordinary investors
several prominent wall street firms, concerned they were killing their own business and arousing congressional hostility, have since abandoned index arbitrage for their own accounts
i don't see anything under the surface that's detrimental about the new york stock exchange's limitation,'' said john a. conlon jr., executive vice president and director of institutional equity research at nikko securities co. international in new york. ``any step toward attempting to quell the kind of volatility we saw is an intelligent posture.''
others agreed but said the limit was discouraging speculators who thrive on the risky futures markets. this has helped cause a drop in the futures business and raised fears that less restrictive foreign markets will benefit
i consider the collar a stabilizer, and from the point of view of the country or market as a whole, it's very positive,'' said haskel b. benishay, an economics professor and market expert at northwestern university's kellogg graduate business school
but of course it's less exciting and creates less opportunities for index arbitrage program traders to make money,'' he said
some futures experts believe the nyse's move reflects a broader failure by the securities business to take coordinated steps aimed at averting another market collapse, a key recommendation of a presidential commission
the critics say the nyse's collar won't mesh with the circuit-breaking mechanisms imposed in the futures market since the crash
new price limits established to regulate stock index futures trading on chicago exchanges could theoretically paralyze those markets in response to a sharp decline in prices. in such a case, traders would rush to dump stocks on the nyse, which would be prevented by its collar from relieving the pressure
if we should have a sharp market break, the markets would unlink automatically,'' alger b. chapman, chairman of the chicago board options exchange, told an annual futures industry meeting in florida earlier this week. ``it would be worse than in october.'' 
the dollar declined in quiet trading friday as foreign-exchange markets awaited next week's release of u.s. trade figures for january
gold prices slipped after soaring as much as $7 a troy ounce on thursday. republic national bank of new york quoted a late bid price of $441.25 for an ounce of gold, down from $442.50 late thursday
currency dealers said the dollar opened lower in new york, reaching trading levels set in overseas activity, but moved little the rest of the day
volume was light in advance of the weekend. there was more interest in trading in the other major currencies, which dominated the markets for much of the week
earl i. johnson, assistant vice president with harris trust and savings bank in chicago, said the market was waiting for two announcements expected next week: the british budget, to be unveiled on tuesday, and u.s. trade figures for january, to be released thursday
the trade figures have set off wide swings in the dollar in recent months, and johnson said that trend may continue next week
traders are focusing on the british budget because the pound surged earlier this week in response to higher interest rates and continued economic strength in that country
the british pound continued to climb against the dollar friday, trading in london at $1.8535, up from $1.8435 late thursday. in later new york trading, the pound rose to $1.8562 from $1.8462 late thursday
the pound has leaped by 4 percent in value against the dollar this week. but traders said the rally appeared to be running out of steam on a statement thursday by chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson that sterling would be unable to sustain a further advance
in tokyo, the dollar closed at 127.80 japanese yen, down from thursday's close of 128.20 yen. later in london, it fell to 127.80 yen and in new york, it slipped to 127.295 yen from 127.955 yen late thursday
