prices for may and july delivery of cotton surged friday on a combination of technical factors, bargain hunting and concerns about a drop in supplies, analysts said
on other markets, livestock and meat futures finished mostly higher in a volatile session; precious metals were mixed; grains and soybeans were mixed; energy futures advanced; and stock-index futures moved higher
strong technical buying boosted near-month cotton futures prices on the new york cotton exchange, but fundamental factors also played a role in the rally, said ernest simon, cotton specialist in new york for prudential-bache securities inc
from a fundamental point of view, the futures market is the cheapest market around for u.s. cotton,'' simon said
with futures priced three to five cents below cash, cotton users who do not need supplies immediately can buy cotton at a bargain on the futures market
but the buying interest also tends to raise futures prices, effectively bringing the futures markets more in line with cash prices
simon also noted some ``decertifications'' of deliverable stocks, indicating a company with obligations to deliver cotton planned to make those shipments using the type of cotton traded on the cotton exchange
cotton settled .60 cent to 1.45 cents higher with the contract for delivery in may at 63.20 cents a pound
cattle futures ended higher on the chicago mercantile exchange in a volatile session marked by a failed attempt to rally the live cattle market above its previous highs
traders bid the april contract up to 73.50 cents a pound, just .05 cent shy of the contract's lifetime high. but buying interest disappeared at that point and the april contract dropped to 72.67 cents on profit-taking late in the day, said philip stanley, an analyst with thomson mckinnon securities inc. in chicago. prices rebounded before the close, however
hog futures contracts advanced despite the week's slaughter of nearly 1.68 million head, the largest weekly slaughter of the spring. frozen pork bellies settled mostly lower on indications of growing supplies
live cattle settled .13 cent to .40 cent higher with april at 73.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .45 cent higher with march at 82 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower to .10 cent higher with april at 43.25 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .45 cent lower to .70 cent higher with march at 51.20 cents a pound
