the general services administration on friday extended by one month the deadline for bids on a new, multi-billion dollar government telephone system to give us sprint communications co. more time to draft its proposal
the gsa said it was ``reluctantly'' extending the deadline to april 29, but said it was doing so ``to insure the fullest possible competition'' for the contract, one of the biggest ever let by the government
besides sprint, only two other teams of companies are bidding on the project, the work for which will be split 60-40 between two vendors
the other bidders are a team led by american telephone &amp; telegraph co. and another headed by martin marietta corp. with mci communications corp
us sprint, a joint venture of gte corp. and united telecommunications inc., will team with gte government systems, according to industry sources who spoke on condition they not be identified by name
the contract for the new telecommunications system, called fts-2000, is valued at as much as $25 billion over 10 years. the winners will replace the government's 25-year-old phone system with a state-of-the-art network for voice, data, video conferencing and other communications services
the extension is the fifth time the bid deadline has been postponed since the contract was opened to bidding in january 1987. last fall, under pressure from congress, the gsa revised the contract to split the award between two vendors instead of giving it all to one bidder
us sprint originally had teamed with electronic data systems to bid on the project, but they withdrew, citing confusion in the procurement process. however, after the contract was revised us sprint decided to re-enter the bidding
us sprint officials declined to comment on the company's request for the extension, but the gsa said us sprint needed the additional time ``to address many functions and aspects of the procurement they had previously assigned to eds'' in the original joint venture
gsa administrator terence c. golden said the agency determined that ``us sprint is indeed committed to competing for fts-2000 and has in place the necessary resources to live up to its commitment to submit a proposal by april 29.''
bond prices rose friday in reaction to news of a decline in wholesale prices and slower-than-expected retail spending
the treasury's bellwether 30-year bond rose 21-32 point, or about $6.56 per $1,000 in face amount, as its yield fell to 8.50 percent from 8.55 percent late thursday
the government reports were interpreted as bullish for bond prices, said elizabeth g. reiners, vice president for money-market research at the investment firm dean witter reynolds inc
the labor department reported that wholesale prices fell 0.2 percent in february, following a 0.4 percent rise in january. bond traders were heartened by the slowing in inflation, ms. reiners said
the bond market fears inflation because it erodes the value of fixed-income securities
also friday, the commerce department reported retail sales rose 0.6 percent in february. but the department also revised its january figures to reflect a drop in consumer spending that month
consumer spending accounts for two-thirds of overall economic activity, so any dropoff heightens concern about a possible recession. but bond traders respond bullishly to such negative statistics because the federal reserve board is considered unlikely to rein in credit by raising interest rates if the economy is sluggish
bond prices and interest rates move in opposite directions, so lower interest rates mean bonds would be worth more
partially offsetting the favorable news from the government was an increase in oil prices and a small decline in the value of the dollar
in the secondary market for treasury bonds, prices of short-term government issues ranged 1-16 point to 3-32 point higher, intermediate maturities rose between 5-32 point and 13-32 point and 20-year issues rose 23-32 point, according to figures provided by telerate inc., a financial information service
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the price of a bond with a $1,000 face value
the shearson lehman daily treasury bond index, which measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with maturities of a year or longer, rose 2.39 to 1,181.83
in corporate trading, industrial and utility issues rose { point in moderate trading, according to the investment firm salomon brothers inc
moody's investment grade corporate bond index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.93 to 284.23
in the municipal bond market, the bond buyer index of 40 actively traded general-obligation and revenue bonds rose 5-32 point to 89 9-16 as of 3 p.m. est. the average yield fell to 8.04 percent from 8.06 percent
yields on three-month treasury bills fell 1 basis point to 5.73 percent. a basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. six-month bills fell 1 basis point to 5.83 percent and one-year bills dropped 5 basis points to 6.24 percent
the federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was quoted late in the day at 6 9-16 percent, unchanged from late thursday. fe</head>
a delaware chancery court judge friday denied henley group inc.'s request for a preliminary injunction against santa fe southern pacific corp., clearing the way for santa fe's restructuring plan to proceed
the legal action is the latest in a series of manuevers involving santa fe and a pair of companies _ henley and olympia &amp; york of toronto, canada _ vying to take over the chicago-based railroad and energy conglomerate
the court's denial means santa fe will immediately begin issuing debentures of $5 per share to stockholders who already received a special cash dividend of $25 per share, santa fe spokesman bob gehrt said
the debentures, at 16 percent interest, come due in 2004. the payments are part of a restructuring plan aimed at thwarting a hostile takeover bid from henley of la jolla, calif
henley had filed a lawsuit seeking an injunction to block issuance of the debentures
the lawsuit also asked the court to declare santa fe's recently enacted shareholder-rights plan invalid, to rescind the appointment of two olympia &amp; york executives to the santa fe board, and to allow henley to propose an amendment that would make it possible for henley to elect a majority of directors at the santa fe's annual meeting may 24
vice chancellor jack b. jacobs denied all four requests
we're studying the ruling and considering our alternatives,'' said henley spokesman norman ritter
olympia &amp; york, controlled by the canada's reichmann family, had launched a tender offer to boost its own holdings in santa fe, but agreed to support the restructuring in exchange for board representation. hospital</head>
wall street speculator john mulheren, accused of plotting to kill convicted financier ivan boesky and a former boesky aide, arrived at a private psychiatric hospital thursday after a federal appeals court lifted an order preventing his release from prison detention
mulheren went to the carrier foundation in belle mead, n.j., following the morning ruling by the 2nd u.s. circuit court of appeals in manhattan
the family and john are delighted with the results and look forward to the day when john can be home with them,'' said one of mulheren's attorneys, otto obermaier
the court denied the government's motion to continue holding mulheren in the metropolitan correctional center, saying evidence provided by a psychiatrist showed the speculator presented no danger
the government had argued that the private facility was not secure enough to house mulheren, the senior partner at jamie securities co. and a former friend of boesky, central figure in an insider trading scandal
mulheren, carrying a loaded assault rifle, was arrested feb. 18 by the police outside his rumson, n.j., home
he was charged with threatening to kill boesky and michael davidoff, boesky's former head trader. the men reportedly have implicated mulheren in possible securities law violations
mulheren's lawyers argue that he is a manic depressive who had failed to take a drug used to control impulses. tax fraud</head>
charles agee atkins, the convicted promoter of a billion-dollar tax scheme that attracted celebrities, was sentenced friday to two years in prison and four years' probation
atkins told u.s. district judge morris lasker that he felt ``deep remorse and i accept the responsibility for what occurred.''
lasker told atkins that he felt the defendant was the ``most culpable'' of the three defendants, but noted that he had received hundreds of letters on his behalf
a co-defendant, william hack, was sentenced to four months in prison, four years, eight months on probation and fined $25,000. the judge ordered him to perform 1,000 hours a year in community service during probation
the third co-defendant, ernest grunebaum, was given a six-month suspended sentence, probation of five years and ordered to do 400 hours of community service a year during probation
they remained free on bail and their sentences were stayed by the judge pending the outcome of their appeals, according to james a. moss, atkins' attorney
a 31-count indictment in march 1987 accused the three of creating more than $1.3 billion in fraudulent losses and interest expenses while trading in treasury bill futures and other government securities
those losses generated more than $350 million in bogus tax deductions for the investors, among them actor michael landon, the late andy warhol and postmaster general preston r. tisch
others include tisch's brother, cbs president and chief executive laurence a. tisch, the late lorne greene, television producer norman lear and actor sidney poitier
lasker also sentenced atkins to spend the first six months of probation at a community center and then do 500 hours a year of community service for the remaining time. moss said the center is a halfway house for those getting out of prison
the three were convicted in december of conspiring to defraud the internal revenue service; they could have received five years in prison on that count alone
atkins, of amelia island plantation, fla., also was convicted of 27 other tax-related counts; hack, of new york city, was convicted of three; grunebaum, of chappaqua, n.y., was convicted on 13 more counts. grunebaum was acquitted on two counts
those who invested are not accused of wrongdoing but will have to square accounts with the irs about back taxes on the $4 in tax deductions they were supposed to get for every $1 invested. shareholders</head>
a federal judge in nevada on friday ordered insurer farmers group inc. to put a merger proposal from unwanted suitor batus inc. before shareholders at farmers' annual meeting may 20
the court also ordered farmers to make its shareholder lists available to batus by next wednesday so batus can effectively solicit proxies for its proposal
however, the judge did instruct that the non-binding proposal be revised to recommend only that farmers' board reconsider its decision not to negotiate with louisville, ky.-based batus, the u.s. subsidiary of bat industries plc of britain
as initially drafted, batus' proposal recommended that farmers immediately enter negotiations with batus
earlier this month, batus began a hostile $63-a-share, or $4.4 billion, tender offer after its initial friendly overtures were spurned by farmers. the offer expires march 30
batus said it was ``very pleased'' with the court action, which requires farmers to include batus' negotiation proposal in farmers' proxy cards being sent to shareholders for the annual meeting
in a separate statement, farmers didn't go beyond outlining the decision and reiterating its opposition to batus' takeover effort
farmers, based in los angeles, filed suit in nevada because that is where it is incorporated
the judge's decision came just one day after farmers' board of directors unanimously rejected the batus offer as inadequate and urged its shareholders to do likewise
farmers said thursday it was exploring a variety of alternatives to a batus takeover, including restructuring or merging with another company, adding that it has held discussions with an unidentified third party about a possible leveraged buyout
batus has asked repeatedly to meet with farmers management to discuss all conditions of its takeover bid including price, but farmers has said it is not interested in such a meeting and believes batus' offer is substantially less than the company is worth
farmers is the nation's third-largest home and auto insurer after state farm and allstate and is the seventh-largest property and casualty insurer
nasa reductions in shuttle redesign efforts have been blamed for morton thiokol inc.'s layoff of more than 100 workers from its space division
morton thiokol spokesman rocky raab said friday that another 100 employees have been transferred from the division to other jobs in the company's wasatch operations
the space division has a work force of more than 2,600
raab said the layoffs came after the company learned nasa is going to limit some small-scale tests and other analyses in the shuttle redesign efforts
however, none of the large-scale tests will be cut, he said
the company has been working on a redesigned shuttle booster rocket since the jan. 28, 1986, challenger disaster. a presidential commission blamed a leaking rocket seal for igniting the explosion that destroyed the shuttle and killed its seven-member crew
meantime, morton thiokol also is reorganizing management in its strategic division to improve safety control and efficiency, raab said
two other divisions under the aerospace group, tactical and automotive products, won't be affected by the changes, he said
raab offered few details of the management restructuring, but the standard-examiner reported friday that a morton thiokol employee, who asked to remain anonymous, said the move was at least partially due to the dec. 29, 1987, fire at an mx missile motor plant that killed five workers
i think that put the icing on the cake,'' said the employee
the nation must take ``bold controversial actions'' to control federal spending in order to reduce the huge budget deficit, federal reserve chairman alan greenspan said thursday
greenspan also indicated the fed would continue making the battle against high inflation the cornerstone of its long-term monetary policy
greenspan, at a luncheon of the federal reserve's 12th district banks, emphasized that future federal budget cuts _ not tax increases _ would be a major factor in bringing down the massive deficit
hiking taxes ``carries with it the risk that expenditures also will be raised, and that the resulting deficit improvement will be small,'' greenspan said
he referred to the tax resistance movement of the 1970s, chiefly triggered by california's successful tax-limiting proposition 13 ballot initiative
greenspan _ who previously has called for slashing the budget deficit _ reiterated the federal reserve's recent report to congress that gross national product was expected to grow by 2.5 percent in 1988, while time prices were expected to climb between 3 percent and 4 percent
the nation could not count on continued foreign capital inflows to help finance the deficit, greenspan said, calling such a trend ``neither a satisfactory nor a sustainable solution over the long run.''
greenspan also said that keeping inflation pressures under control was critical to continued progress in reducing the deficit
in this regard, monetary policy must maintain, as a long-run objective, establishing reasonable price stability,'' he said
greenspan praised what he said was the public's alertness to the dangers of inflation, and said he sensed ``there is still a deep reservoir of support for policies to keep inflation in check.''
